<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>About NHS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image73.gif" WIDTH="271" HEIGHT="63" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="image109.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
The <STRONG>National Honor Society</STRONG> is the front runner of organizations
and societies that promote appropriate recognition for students who reflect
outstanding accomplishments in the areas of scholarship, character, leadership
and service. Thousands of high schools are chartered and their chapters
are following the NHS constitution.<BR>
<BR>
Similarly, National Junior Honor Societies exist in junior high / middle
schools to promote the same ideals: scholarship, character, leadership,
service and citizenship. <BR>
<BR>
Sponsored by the <A HREF="http://www.nassp.org/">National Association of
Secondary School Principals</A><A HREF="../../TASSP%20docs/nhs.htm/www.nassp.org">,</A>
the NHS and NJHS organizations are administered by the Department of Student
Activities at the NASSP office in Reston, Virginia. <BR>
<BR>
Membership in local chapters is an honor <STRONG>bestowed </STRONG>upon
a student. Selection for membership is by a faculty council and is based
on outstanding scholarship, character, leadership and service (and citizenship
for NJHS selection.) Once selected, students are expected to continue to
demonstrate these qualities.<BR>
<BR>
For specific questions about your school's National Honor Society or National
Junior Honor Society, contact the campus principal. For questions about
national standards for chapters, insignia, or printed materials, contact
the <A HREF="mailto:nhsnjhs@nassp.org">Department of Student Activities
</A>at NASSP. 
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
