<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Session 1 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <STRONG>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
SET I -- SATURDAY, OCTOBER 26, 9:00 - 10:15 a.m.<BR>
<BR>
1. A Multiple Intelligence Approach<BR>
Independence<BR>
Helen Darilek [512-444-3243], Austin ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants will be provided with a demonstration of the utilization of
the multiple intelligence methodology on a campus and in the classroom as
an attempt to reach all learners.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> eddie salinas, corpus christi
isd<BR>
<BR>
2. Jump Start<BR>
Lone Star<BR>
Gary McCain [903-395-2111], Dana Scott, Lydia Tom, Dixie McClain, Larry
Trapp & Judy Wilson, Cooper ISD</STRONG><BR>
Students are invited for a very positive but mandatory experience following
TAAS failure. Experienced teachers are used. Everyone loves the atmosphere.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> sue barker, whitesboro isd<BR>
<BR>
3. The C.I.A. -- Cavazos Interdisciplinary Academy<BR>
Lavaca<BR>
Henry Galindo [806-766-6600], Curtis Cogswell, Bill Caney, Chris Borland,
Dana Brown & Joe Porras, Lubbock ISD</STRONG><BR>
This School-Within-A-School design incorporates real world learning and
application through interdisciplinary units culminating in projects and
presentations which earn the students integrated speech credit at the middle
level.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> linda snook, new caney isd<BR>
<BR>
4. Alliance Schools: Parent Involvement of the Future<BR>
Cedar<BR>
Cynthia Castillo [210-977-1610], Martha Avalos, Janie Benavides, Sandra
Carlton & Pearline Miller, Harlandale ISD</STRONG><BR>
Presenters will briefly establish the need for parent, school and community
teamwork. ALLIANCE will be defined. Stonewall-Flanders Elementary's journey
with hurdles and successes will be described. The school's future vision
with Alliance and Communities Organized for Public Service (COPS) will be
shared. Time for a question and answer period will be included at the end.
Participants will receive a handout that will serve as a resource.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> elvira barela, plainview isd<BR>
<BR>
5. Strategies to Effect Change with Minimum Stress & Maximum Success<BR>
Mulberry<BR>
Linda Holman [915-566-2929], El Paso ISD</STRONG><BR>
Appropriate for all leadership levels, this program will provide the participant
with tools and strategies that can make change a positive focus on one's
campus or in one's district. As schools and school districts introduce innovative
programs and school renewal activities, change can either cause a group
to lose its focus or revitalize it. <BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> brenda barney, copperas cove
isd<BR>
<BR>
6. You Want More of My Time?!<BR>
Red River/Neches<BR>
Sally Keener [214-349-6348] & Jeff Oldham, Richardson ISD</STRONG><BR>
Avoid in-services on your time by developing an Instructional Specialist
for a collegial approach to staff development for effective and efficient
in-house, ongoing training and support. See how to mentor all staff members
in a united, goal-oriented structure.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> susan kincannon, temple isd<BR>
<BR>
7. Keeping the &quot;Tools&quot; from Rusting<BR>
Brazos<BR>
Diana Macon Bernshausen [713-774-4500], University of Houston; Claude Cunningham,
Mansfield ISD</STRONG><BR>
This presentation addresses the idea that pre-service teachers enter the
teaching field with a &quot;tool box&quot; of teaching strategies; but,
for some reason, the tools are left behind to rust. Participants will be
actively involved in strategies to explore &quot;self talk&quot; as a way
to keep the tools in use and help bridge the gap between individual learner
needs and goal attainment.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> sandra billodeau, como-pickton
isd<BR>
<BR>
8. The Professional Development School: Establishing a Successful Partnership
for Professional Development<BR>
Cypress<BR>
Donna Cooner [409-845-6427], Terresa Kah, Jane Burrows & Jane Rankin, College
Station ISD; Teresa Fluth, Round Rock ISD</STRONG><BR>
The South Knoll-Texas A&M University Partnership is the winner of the Department
of Education's grant for innovation in education. South Knoll utilizes over
300 university students per week in an instructional program that includes
teacher participation at every level. The structure and evaluation of the
program will be discussed.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> virginia bolton, north lamar
isd<BR>
<BR>
9. Parent Education and Involvement: Reconnecting Families, Schools and
Communities<BR>
Freedom<BR>
Judy Farmer [512-467-0222], Practical Parent Education Consultant, Texas
Association of School Boards</STRONG><BR>
Educators, school board trustees and community members throughout the state
and nation have identified parental involvement as a key issue in education.
This session explores opportunities for parents, schools and community organizations
to work together to develop effective strategies for parent involvement
and to encourage effective communication with the school community.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> bob carter, round rock isd<BR>
<BR>
10. Solving the &quot;504&quot; Puzzle<BR>
Colorado<BR>
Karen McDonald [214-519-8600], Penny Hale & Michael Hughes, Plano ISD</STRONG><BR>
The Campus Assessment Team is Plano East Senior High's research-based response
to the challenge of 504/at-risk/special needs students. The team of campus
professionals has implemented a successful intervention process which provides
for assessment of needs, delivery of services and follow-up for secondary-level
students.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> janet covington, itasca isd<BR>
<BR>
11. Magic of Mentoring<BR>
Live Oak<BR>
Evelyn Narrell [806-371-5538], Amarillo ISD</STRONG><BR>
A mentoring program produced a magical increase in the number of Caprock
High School's Superintendent's Scholars in only four years when nothing
had worked before. A second mentoring program to work with ninth graders
who are in danger of not being promoted to the tenth grade has also shown
significant gains. This presentation will give you a practical step-by-step
plan for implementing a mentoring program for helping students at your school.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> malcolm dennis, round rock
isd<BR>
<BR>
12. ISS (In School Suspension) A Decision Making Model<BR>
Ash<BR>
Sandi Thomas [903-856-6432], Pittsburg ISD; Cheryl Hassman, Temple ISD</STRONG><BR>
Learn how to implement a decision-making curriculum for those students placed
in &quot;in-house&quot; suspension, with a focus on responsibility, not
busy work. Presentation will include development of units as well as overview
of implementation in grades six to eight.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> shirley nichols, north east
isd<BR>
<BR>
13. Teaming to Align and Integrate Instruction<BR>
Trinity/San Jacinto<BR>
Ann Sandoval [713-948-4222] & Debbie Barrett, Pasadena ISD</STRONG><BR>
Implement an easy-to-look-at format for planning, teaming and &quot;closing
the gaps&quot; when aligning TEKS and curriculum, which address vertical
and horizontal alignment. We developed and have used this positive system
schoolwide for six years.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> sara fogg, round rock isd<BR>
<BR>
14. The Literacy Learning Process: A Balanced Approach to Reading Instruction<BR>
Hickory<BR>
Mary Ann Whitfield [512-846-2111], Kristen Epstein & Ben Carson, Hutto ISD</STRONG><BR>
This presentation will give the audience an overview of a balanced, structured
approach to Literacy Development being implemented at Hutto Elementary.
Developed in New Zealand over the last 25 years, it has resulted in their
children scoring at the top of international literacy evaluations, one of
the highest literacy rates in the world and their instructional methodologies
being sought worldwide.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> teri fowler, texarkana isd<BR>
<BR>
15. Book and Brain Reading<BR>
Pine<BR>
Nancy Linden [214-265-8300], Dallas</STRONG><BR>
Educators will learn how to &quot;divide and conquer&quot; the TAAS reading
test into two categories: book questions and brain questions. This skill
used for TAAS can then be applied as a life skill in all content areas of
reading.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> gilbert galvan, weslaco isd<BR>
<BR>
16. Project K.I.T.E. - Kindergarten Integrating Technology into Education<BR>
Water<BR>
Vicki Rockett [903-845-2254] & Brendan Williams, Gladewater ISD</STRONG><BR>
Kindergarten students at Gladewater ISD use modern technology to learn skills.
By publishing original stories on the World Wide Web and developing e-mail
correspondence around the world, these students increased their global awareness
while learning essential elements and developing basic technology skills.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> pat mcdonald, aransas county
isd<BR>
<BR>
17. Effective Primary Math Instruction<BR>
Pecan<BR>
Dinah Chancellor [817-251-5517], Grapevine-Colleyville ISD</STRONG><BR>
The mathematics classroom is changing to better meet the needs of students
in the modern world. This is described in the TEKS Mathematics and exemplified
in the TexTeam Mathematics Institute. This session shows examples of how
a mathematics classroom might look. Come see examples of the practices to
encourage and support, as well as learn about the resources available in
mathematics professional development.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> john grasshoff, round rock
isd<BR>
<BR>
18. Sustaining Technology Integration -- A Model<BR>
Sabine<BR>
Sharon Clark [409-857-3336] & Trina Davis, Waller ISD</STRONG><BR>
A teacher/technologist and principal will identify key components of a model
for successful and continued integration of technology in a school. The
model produces a high level of use of technology by students and teachers
and can be replicated in other schools of any level.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> nancy harwell, corpus christi
isd<BR>
<BR>
</STRONG>
