<P>1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE<BR>
<BR>
from <STRONG>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
SET II -- SATURDAY, OCTOBER 26, 10:30 - 11:45 a.m.<BR>
<BR>
19. Technology Planning for the 21st Century<BR>
Brazos<BR>
Wes Schultz [801-371-5500], Nicki Wilcoxson, John Holman & Becky Harrison,
Amarillo ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants will hear an overview of a five-year technology plan from the
planning stage process to the current third year of the plan. The &quot;how-to's&quot;
of developing a technology plan will be presented.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> ray alvarez, south san antonio
isd<BR>
<BR>
20. Grant Writing -- Dream Team Visions Come to Life<BR>
Trinity/San Jacinto<BR>
Carol Ann Bonds [817-642-3802], Katie Ryan, Brenda Marek & Cindy Gunn, Rogers
ISD; students, Holland & Rogers ISDs</STRONG><BR>
A grant writing team from Rogers and Holland ISDs will share their procedures
which have resulted in $ 2.8 million of grant funds. A multi-age student
team will present a multimedia presentation which demonstrates the accomplishment
of the ultimate goal from several grants. It's clearly worth the long nights
and weekends of writing!<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> ginger henry, victoria isd<BR>
<BR>
21. Beyond the Dream<BR>
Cedar<BR>
Phyllis Hamilton [713-897-4720], Jodie Smith, Dawn Triska, Jane Tipps & Tom
Danish, Cypress-Fairbanks ISD</STRONG><BR>
We are now in our third year of Vertical Teaming, and we've gone beyond
our original dream. We're now in the thick of collaboration with 1) goal
setting, 2) vertical staff development, 3) student-led conferences from
prekindergarten through grade 12 and 4) vertical discipline -- Boys' Town
Training.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> lucie dowe, north east isd<BR>
<BR>
22. A Framework: Understanding the Hidden Rules of Poverty<BR>
Ballroom C<BR>
Ruby Payne [713-424-9151], RFT Publishing, Baytown</STRONG><BR>
The hidden rules of generational poverty, analysis of resources and techniques
for discipline and instruction will be discussed.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> linda schmeltekopf, hays cisd<BR>
<BR>
23. Looking at Inclusion Through Rose-Colored Glasses -- A Success Story<BR>
Freedom<BR>
Kay Jefferies [806-285-2535] & Ricky Karr, Olton ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session highlights the successes of an elementary life skills class
designed for children who are physically, mentally or emotionally challenged.
Participants will receive handouts and an outline of the curriculum. A slide
show will be presented and questions answered. This is a pilot program.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> judith herbst, willis isd<BR>
<BR>
24. Middle School Transition Program<BR>
Colorado<BR>
Sue Humphrey [512-918-3170], Austin ISD</STRONG><BR>
This presentation is about a program for fifth graders and their transition
to sixth grade in a middle school. Participants will hear about effective
strategies for making a positive move to the middle level.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> martha pruse, galena park isd<BR>
<BR>
25. Interventions: Collaborative Planning for Students At Risk<BR>
Hickory<BR>
Mickey Garrison [541-672-5145], Educational Support Services, Roseburg,
Oregon</STRONG><BR>
Do students with chronic behavior and motivational problems sometimes have
you stumped? This session will examine a process for staff to develop a
proactive plan for helping the student learn to behave more responsibly.
An overview of 16 interventions will be provided, with information on how
to select and implement the interventions that will &quot;best fit the problem.&quot;<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> virginia aguilar, harlandale
isd<BR>
<BR>
26. Good Intentions Get You Nowhere!<BR>
Live Oak<BR>
Stephen Russell [903-342-5002], New Leadership Training Programs, Winnsboro
ISD; Michael T. Smith, Whitharral ISD</STRONG><BR>
A national award-winning program, New Focus empowers teachers with the tools
to teach students to be accountable and responsible for their own learning
and behavior. The presentation will offer practical, creative strategies
on how to implement a successful, organized approach to teaching students
accountability and responsibility.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> annette johnson, round rock
isd<BR>
<BR>
27. Authentic Learning/Curriculum: Developing Curriculum with Concepts<BR>
Independence<BR>
Carol Mendenhall [210-804-7185], North East ISD</STRONG><BR>
Connecting students to what is being taught is essential if learning is
going to have a chance. This session will focus on a series of questions
you should ask yourself as you design curriculum that will connect to students'
lives, to other curriculums and to authentic assessments.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> mary ann moody, region xii
esc, waco<BR>
<BR>
28. A Model for Using Curriculum Alignment to Improve TAAS Scores<BR>
Water<BR>
Margaret Kilgo [713-453-3360], Houston</STRONG><BR>
A Curriculum Alignment model which can be used to determine the match between
instructional materials, textbooks, curriculum documents, and the higher-level
thinking and logical reasoning required for student success on the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) will be presented.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> lynette king, mineral wells
isd<BR>
<BR>
29. The Three Critical Features of Effective Literacy Programs -- K-12<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
Richard Allington [518-442-5103], The University of Albany - SUNY, Glenmont,
New York</STRONG><BR>
The education profession routinely engages in debates about the most effective
curriculum for teaching children to read and write. These debates are often
contentious, volatile and disruptive to the educational process, as well
as largely meaningless since there is little evidence that the nature of
curriculum materials much affects the way teachers actually teach. Largely
ignored in the debates are the truly critical features of effective classroom
literacy instruction. This session focuses on those factors.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> lynda carter, round rock isd<BR>
<BR>
30. Using Children's Writing to Help Readers Learn to Read -- All Ages<BR>
Red River/Neches<BR>
Elizabeth Hamilton [512-846-2111], Lisa Hamilton & Brenda Westerman, Hutto
ISD</STRONG><BR>
The audience will receive an overview of how to use a child's own writing
to help him learn to read, including the supporting research, steps to implementation
and sharing of personal experiences.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> barbara moore, round rock isd<BR>
<BR>
31. &quot;Tricks of the Trade&quot; That Are Results Driven!<BR>
Lone Star<BR>
Jeanette Bradley [713-487-9259], Pasadena</STRONG><BR>
Activities show how to make an elementary class/school plan and easy techniques
to teach students in a manner that is results-driven. &quot;Tricks of the
trade&quot; that help students comprehend, retain and retrieve academic
concepts for long-term successes will be presented with fun and free ideas.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> jeanette moore, tcta<BR>
<BR>
32. Developmentally Appropriate What?!<BR>
Lavaca<BR>
Elizabeth Langley [512-362-6040] & Cynthia Richey, Beeville ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session for early childhood through elementary grades emphasizes the
philosophy, classroom design, curriculum materials needed, purpose assessments
and other information to acquaint the audience to developmentally appropriate
practices. This workshop is very interactive.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> sue moran, schertz-cibolo-universal
city isd<BR>
<BR>
33. School-To-Work/Tech Prep: Innovation in Action<BR>
Cypress<BR>
Diana Landrum [409-361-5394], Sylvia Luera, Debbie Garringer & Dennis Herlihy,
Bryan ISD</STRONG><BR>
Innovative School-To-Work/Tech Prep partnerships have been established in
many areas of society. This presentation includes an overview of the partnerships
and implementation of the Career Academies, the role of the counselor, the
fifth through twelfth grade graduation portfolio and the selection of career
graduation plans. School-to-Work business/industry representatives, elementary,
secondary and university representatives are leading the way.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> ken sawin, lockhart isd<BR>
<BR>
34. Thinking in Three's<BR>
Pine<BR>
Nancy Linden [214-265-8300], Dallas</STRONG><BR>
Educators will learn how to look at our world in a different manner &shyp;
the pattern of three's. This new point of view will help students to have
success in TAAS writing and in other areas where critical thinking is needed.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> yesenia pardo, plainview isd<BR>
<BR>
35. Developing Partnerships for Success<BR>
Pecan<BR>
Linda Anderson [817-831-5786], Birdville ISD</STRONG><BR>
Birdville ISD has formed a dynamic School-to-Work Coalition including partnerships
with business, industry and post secondary institutions. A Framework for
School-to-Work was developed which has been used as a model. Innovative
instructional partnerships of academic and career technology teachers in
grades K-12 are the key to this successful program.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> john hancock, temple isd<BR>
<BR>
36. Working Together: Reading and Mathematics<BR>
Mulberry<BR>
Janice Bradley [512-719-5893], Austin ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session will focus on the difficulties associated with the reading
of mathematics and how reading strategies can be used to enhance mathematical
understanding.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> bob brundrett, statewide initiatives/region
xiii esc<BR>
<BR>
37. Making a Personal Connection: Kids and Content<BR>
Ash<BR>
Susan Bigelow [713-634-3446], Ft. Bend ISD</STRONG><BR>
&quot;First you've got to reach them, then you can teach them.&quot; Connect
students to their learning through the utilization of personal experiences.
This presentation will provide activities to enhance student self-esteem
and increase retention of skills and concepts.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> janie pollard, aubury isd<BR>
<BR>
38. Snap, Crackle, Pop! Connecting the Circuits of Learning<BR>
Sabine<BR>
Emily O'Connor [903-737-2820], Diane Stegall, Sandy Bolton & Jane Keith,
Chisum ISD</STRONG><BR>
Presenters will share strategies for making connections for kids incorporating
literacy learning and technology resulting in authentic student learning
experiences where curriculum, instruction and assessment come together to
create a seamless system.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> pamela pond, tcta<BR>
<BR>
