<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Session III </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <STRONG>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
SET III -- SATURDAY, OCTOBER 26, 3:30 - 5:00 p.m.<BR>
<BR>
39. The Mentor School Connection<BR>
Red River/Neches<BR>
Tam Jones [512-919-5313], Bob Brundrett & Pat Pickles, Office of Statewide
Initiatives, ESC Region XIII, Austin</STRONG><BR>
Elementary, middle and high school state coordinators will provide an update
on the direction of the &quot;New Texas Mentor Network Initiative.&quot;
Participants will understand the purpose of the network, benefits of belonging
and the roles and responsibilities of mentor schools and other state support
systems.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> roseta reynolds, angleton isd<BR>
<BR>
40. Innovative Changes Through Creative Scheduling at the Middle Level<BR>
Trinity/San Jacinto<BR>
Tom Leyden, Plano ISD [214-519-8885], Bob Caudle, San Marcos ISD; George
Kale & Charlie Franklin, Henderson ISD; </STRONG><BR>
This presentation will begin with an overview of the reason to block schedule
at the middle school. Three examples of creative scheduling will be introduced,
followed by a small group discussion on the schedule of the participant's
choice.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> carol mckenzie, eanes isd<BR>
<BR>
41. Technology Update: Educational Change Through Connectivity<BR>
Colorado<BR>
Bob Digneo [512-870-2103], Southwestern Bell Telephone Company; Keith Mitchell,
Apple Computer, Austin</STRONG><BR>
This session will help educators and administrators raise their awareness
and take advantage of new technology resources for the classroom. The session
will focus on current educational applications, computing technology and
the opportunities available to schools to acquire certain telecommunications
services at reduced rates through HB 2128.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> bill shatford, hurst-euless-bedford
isd<BR>
<BR>
42. Roots and Wings: Universal Excellence for Elementary Schools<BR>
Hickory<BR>
Robert Slavin [410-516-8809], Center for Research on the Education of Students
Placed at Risk, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, Maryland </STRONG><BR>
&quot;Roots and Wings&quot; is a design for total restructuring of elementary
schools intended to place a high floor under the achievement of all students
while allowing all to gain such higher-order skills as problem solving,
creative writing and use of scientific method. The program incorporates
elements derived from the extensively researched &quot;Success for All&quot;
program's effective approaches to reading, pre-kindergarten and kindergarten,
tutoring for at-risk primary students and family support. To these it adds
&quot;Math Wings,&quot; a practical constructivist math curriculum and &quot;World
Lab,&quot; an integrated approach to social studies and science emphasizing
simulations and group investigations. Research on &quot;Roots and Wings&quot;
has found substantial gains on performance measures of reading, writing,
language arts, social studies and science.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> lillie beth wilson, alief isd<BR>
<BR>
43. Dream Masters<BR>
Cypress<BR>
Emily Cole [713-226-4900], Katie Ekstrom, Georgia McGlasson & Roberto Gonzales,
Houston ISD</STRONG><BR>
Learn about the Davis Vertical Team approach to comprehensive instructional
and social program of working together in a pre-kindergarten through twelfth
grade cohesive team. The result? The highly successful Project GRAD! <BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> bill lawson, houston isd<BR>
<BR>
44. Instructional Interventions for Students from Poverty<BR>
Ballroom C<BR>
Ruby Payne [713-424-9151], RFT Publishing, Baytown</STRONG><BR>
Building learning structures inside the head is necessary for student achievement.
What are these structures? How are they built?<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> alex williams, corsicana isd<BR>
<BR>
45. Crisis, Grief and Loss...and How to Help Your Students Through It<BR>
Mezzanine 8<BR>
Sharon Johnson [800-414-5844], SCORE, Orange County Department of Education,
Costa Mesa, California</STRONG><BR>
The grief process and some principles for helping will be covered in this
presentation. Participants will understand the grief process and how it
affects students and learn principles and techniques for facilitating learning
when students are in crisis. Presenter will use interactive visuals to illustrate
the grief process in the classroom, based on Kubler-Ross research, and a
curricular bibliography for dealing with loss.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> susan smith, esc region xvi,
amarillo<BR>
<BR>
46. Circles of Power: An Affective Dropout Reduction Plan<BR>
Mezzanine 6<BR>
Mike Bennett [806-766-0660], Kay Reat, Larry Hess, Becky Lowe & Debbie Rowan,
Lubbock ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants will explore a dropout reduction plan that has been effectively
implemented at Monterey High School. Teachers, administrators, parents,
students and community members have been involved in shared decision-making
activities that have drastically reduced the dropout rate at Monterey.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> tim turner, eastland isd<BR>
<BR>
47. Essential Education: Putting School In a Child's World<BR>
Lone Star<BR>
Debbie Clouatre [903-845-5419] & Suzie Lambert, Gladewater ISD</STRONG><BR>
Real power consists of creating a situation where it need not be exercised.
Create a classroom of intrinsically motivated students who produce quality
work without coercion. Find out how we can begin to create a place for students
to meet their needs so that they want to learn.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> bertie standley, esc region
v, beaumont<BR>
<BR>
48. Solutions to Classroom Discipline -- K-5<BR>
Mulberry<BR>
Randy Sprick [541-345-1442], Teaching Strategies, Eugene, Oregon</STRONG><BR>
Discipline problems are some of the most difficult challenges facing schools
today. You will learn how to design and implement plans for chronic classroom
misbehaviors. The focus is on providing practical strategies you can implement
in your classroom immediately. You will be given tools for solving 100 classroom
problems and will learn how to apply research-based strategies to any behavioral/motivational
problem.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> david moore, round rock isd<BR>
<BR>
49. The EFG Curriculum Collaborative<BR>
Ballroom A<BR>
Barbara Barnes [800-692-2847] & Joel Barker, Infinity Unlimited, St. Paul,
Minnesota & EFG Curriculum Collaborative, Scottsdale, Arizona</STRONG><BR>
Joel Barker and Barbara Barnes have collaborated with international teams
of educators, business and community leaders to design and implement an
integrated curriculum that is relevant to the real world in the 21st century.
This Curriculum Collaborative is located in the U.S., Canada, U.K. and New
Zealand and utilizes the latest in technology to communicate worldwide.
The specifics of the E (Ecological Education), F (Futures Education) and
G (Global Education) will be presented with actual school implementation
examples shared.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> linda robinson, alvin isd<BR>
<BR>
50. Thoughtful Literacy, Grades 7-12<BR>
Water<BR>
Richard Allington [518-442-5103], The University of Albany - SUNY, Glenmont,
New York</STRONG><BR>
A key feature of the movement to raise academic standards in American schools
is the emphasis on developing thoughtful literacy in virtually all students.
Unfortunately, most school programs are not designed to achieve this goal.
It will require some substantial restructuring of 1) the school day, 2)
the nature of schoolwork kids complete, and 3) evaluation schemes (both
those for evaluating children's literacy development and those focused on
evaluating school effectiveness).<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> chris hines, hays cisd<BR>
<BR>
51. Foundation for Success in the Learning Community: Early Literacy<BR>
Ash<BR>
Pam Campbell [806-796-7239], Elizabeth Brown & Stacey Wright, Lubbock ISD</STRONG><BR>
The Early Literacy Framework, as developed by Dr. Gay Su Pinnell and others
at Ohio State University, uses the works of Marie Clay to develop this language/literature-based
procedure for the early learner. Well-known educator, Regie Routman, writes
about and utilizes this method. We will provide you with classroom strategies
based on this philosophy.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> jackie thornton, rockdale isd<BR>
<BR>
52. Reading with Empowered Comprehension: Directed Thinking Program<BR>
Mezzanine 5<BR>
Judith Story [903-425-7222], Dianne Shaffer & Wesley Story, Eustace ISD</STRONG><BR>
Students who fail TAAS Reading often call words correctly, but do not respond
to the &quot;meaning getting&quot; nature of reading. These students must
be trained to apply strategies that will assist them in understanding what
they have read. The Directed Thinking Program is a method of instruction
which addresses phonics, comprehension skills and application of comprehension
skills, with an emphasis on self-directed thinking.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> lydia villescas, pharr-san
juan-alamo isd<BR>
<BR>
53. &quot;Hands-On&quot; Reading Strategies that Have Yielded Phenomenal
Gains on TAAS with Middle Level & High School Students<BR>
Mezzanine 7<BR>
Kelly Daggett [817-383-3981], Texas Woman's University, Denton; Cheryl Cox,
Garland ISD</STRONG><BR>
High yield reading strategies for maximizing student achievement will be
shared in this session. These strategies have proven highly successful in
obtaining phenomenal gains on the TAAS reading test, especially with at-risk
students. A heavy emphasis will be placed on higher order thinking skills
and &quot;hands-on&quot; activities.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> wendell dunlap, plainview isd<BR>
<BR>
54. Authentic Assessment: The Critical Piece in the Restructuring Process<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
Kay Burke [800-348-4474], IRI/Skylight Training & Publishing, Arlington
Heights, Illinois</STRONG><BR>
Creating authentic assessments to measure standards and goals is essential
if we are to measure students' growth and development in meeting these goals.
This session will provide an overview of the key elements of the assessment
process, the curriculum changes that are needed and the importance of establishing
criteria and clear guidelines for assessing students' performances.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> annette scott, victoria isd<BR>
<BR>
55. Einstein!<BR>
Freedom<BR>
Jerry Brown [719-576-8000], U.S. Space Foundation, Colorado Springs, Colorado
</STRONG><BR>
Meet Albert Einstein in person! This session, provided through the U.S.
Space Foundation, will explore the world's thinking prior to Einstein and
review his legacy and its effect on the 21st Century.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> james murphy, birdville isd<BR>
<BR>
56. Authentic Learning/Instruction: Creating Context for Students<BR>
Independence<BR>
Carol Mendenhall [210-804-7185], North East ISD</STRONG><BR>
If learning experiences are contextual in nature, students have a better
chance of &quot;getting it.&quot; This session will focus on how to create
those experiences through a variety of instructional strategies.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> sheila maher, carrollton-farmers
branch isd<BR>
<BR>
57. Service Learning: Fostering Student Achievement through Authentic Pedagogy<BR>
Brazos<BR>
James & Pamela Toole [612-787-0409], Compass Institute, St. Paul, Minnesota</STRONG><BR>
While many students are not engaged in their own education, authentic pedagogy
like service learning have the potential to reignite a passion for learning
and deepen the intellectual life of schools. How can service learning strategies
foster student achievement? This workshop will present a research-based
model and many examples of how service tasks can be designed to improve
scores on TAAS and success in performance-based 21st century roles.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> chrissy hester, college station
isd<BR>
<BR>
58. Connecting Algebraic Thinking from Elementary to High School<BR>
Lavaca<BR>
Norma Jost [512-719-5893], Austin ISD & Tere Ralston, Pflugerville ISD</STRONG><BR>
Yes -- algebraic thinking begins in elementary school! This hands-on session
will involve participants in activities that develop algebraic thinking
across the grade levels.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> debbie crenwelge, fredricksburg
isd<BR>
<BR>
59. Implementing a Work-Based Hospitality Services Program<BR>
Live Oak<BR>
Leta Durrett [214-720-5339] & Daniel L. Salinas, Dallas ISD; David Conway,
Sr. Vice President, Hilton Hotel International., Dallas</STRONG><BR>
Learn the tools you need to organize a successful hospitality services program
in your high school. An introduction to the Texas High Schools for Hospitality
program will get the ball rolling in education and create interest for your
students in future career opportunities within the hospitality industry.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> roberto hein, zapata county
isd<BR>
<BR>
60. Mission Impossible: An Interdisciplinary Unit for High School<BR>
Cedar<BR>
Sharon McGlaun [713-396-6750], Christi Sullivan & Barbara Pryor, Katy ISD</STRONG><BR>
Getting high school teachers from all content areas to work collaboratively
on an instructional unit is a challenging endeavor. Here is a success story
that describes the &quot;how-to&quot; and the rewards of interdisciplinary
teaching.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> leticia gonzalez, alice isd<BR>
<BR>
61. Revitalizing High Schools: What Can the School-to-Careers Movement Contribute?<BR>
Pine<BR>
Richard Kazis [617-742-5995], Jobs for the Future, Boston, Massachusetts</STRONG><BR>
Across the nation, high schools and districts are turning to school-to-career
approaches to change pedagogy, organize instruction more effectively and
make high schools more vibrant for students of all abilities. Come learn
about school-to-careers: what it is and isn't; why many believe it has the
potential for making high schools better places for learning; and what leading
districts are learning about design and implementation.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> jerry kirby, mansfield isd<BR>
<BR>
62. Effective Middle Level Math Instruction <BR>
Pecan<BR>
Elizabeth Boehm [210-433-8035], Edgewood ISD</STRONG><BR>
The mathematics classroom is changing to better meet the needs of students
in the modern world. This is described in the TEKS in Mathematics and exemplified
in the TexTeam Mathematics Institute. This session shows examples of how
a mathematics classroom might look. Come see examples of the practices to
encourage and support, as well as learn about the resources available in
mathematics professional development.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> linda humphrey, lewisville
isd<BR>
<BR>
63. Best Practice Model at the Elementary School Level: KAPOW (Kids and
the Power of Work)<BR>
Mezzanine 1<BR>
Jeffrey Newman [212-840-1801], President, National Child Labor Committee;
George Pedraza, Vice President, Public Finance Group, Texas Commerce Bank</STRONG><BR>
KAPOW is an elementary level program designed to teach young people about
the world of work. It utilizes the business, school and intermediary partnership
model set out in the School-to-Work Opportunities Act. Grounded in the best
of child development theory and educational pedagogy, KAPOW is child-centered,
multi-sensory and stresses experiences connected to a child's world.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> joan harding, spring isd<BR>
<BR>
64. What? We Chose Physics<BR>
Mezzanine 2<BR>
Marilyn Cook [512-749-5256], Jane Thompson & Guy Burleson, Port Aransas
ISD; Denise Nutt, Reynolds Metal Company</STRONG><BR>
What happens when pre-kindergarten through grade nine teachers and the elementary
principal kick off their shoes, grab the chart paper and markers and put
their district's science curriculum under the microscope? Physics comes
into focus to give students a lively week of integrated hands-on lessons
and activities involving community/business resources, all three district
campuses and an action research component. At Port Aransas ISD, physics
is no longer on that shelf in the lab or an afterthought in the unit plans
but a foundation for science concepts that enables students to link classroom
learning to their everyday lives. Yes, we did choose physics, learned and
had FUN!<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> kenny sanders, north lamar
isd<BR>
<BR>
65. The Distance Learning Classroom: Educating Everyone<BR>
Sabine<BR>
Suzie Lambert [903-845-5448] & Blake Gordon Gladewater ISD; Kay Gode & Kelvin
Woodfin, Winnsboro ISD; Jill Brown, Quitman ISD</STRONG><BR>
Learn about Distance Learning: the implementation and application of telecommunication
in the secondary classroom, addressing the needs of traditional and non-traditional
students, communities, and providing for all avenues of higher education.<BR>
<I><STRONG>facilitator:</STRONG></I><STRONG> joe westmoreland, crane isd<BR>
<BR>
</STRONG>
