<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Session IV</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <STRONG>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
SET IV -- SUNDAY, OCTOBER 27, 8:30 - 10:00 a.m.<BR>
<BR>
</STRONG>66. SCORE: Success in the CORE for Everyone!<BR>
Lone Star<BR>
Sharon Johnson [800-414-5844], SCORE, Orange County Department of Education,
Costa
Mesa, California<BR>
In this awareness workshop, participants will learn the elements necessary
in designing a successful
partnership program to reinforce student achievement in the classroom, an
understanding of the
concept of acceleration as opposed to remediation as an effective strategy
for increasing the
achievement of high-risk youth, the keys to program success and the strategies
for improving
academic achievement using study skills across the curriculum. With these
keys, school districts
and schools can facilitate effective institutional change, create learning
environments, build
partnerships and develop lifelong learners.
facilitator: james kelch, socorro isd<BR>
<BR>
67. Breaking Ranks: Changing an American Institution<BR>
Colorado<BR>
Dave Hottenstein [215-674-5038], Director of Secondary Ed/Principal, Educational
Impact
Associate, Hatsboro, Pennsylvania <BR>
This session will include an overview of the process followed in producing
the national
commission report on high school restructuring for the 21st century. The
commission, made up
solely of practitioners, included principals, an assistant principal, parents,
students, teachers and
representatives from higher education. Ernest Boyer and the Carnegie Foundation
for the
Advancement of Teaching joined with Tim Dyer and NASSP to develop a blueprint
for the high
school of the future. Emphasis was placed on the importance of the &quot;how
to&quot; component of the
change process which educators could understand and implement. Mr. Hottenstein,
a member of
the Commission, will highlight key sections of the report and discuss several
recommendations
critical to the change process.
facilitator: richard mc reavy, waller isd<BR>
<BR>
68. Year-Round Education: The 21st Century Calendar<BR>
Mezzanine 1<BR>
Sue Shook [915-860-3429], Socorro ISD<BR>
A far-west Texas district located on the Rio Grande River with 20,000 students
has found the
answer to improved student performance: Year-Round Education. In Socorro
ISD, test scores have
soared, drop-out rates have plummeted and the community has embraced the
district's new
calendar. Come get the facts about year-round education: the advantages,
the challenges and the<
results.<BR>
facilitator: linda richey, garland isd<BR>
<BR>
69. We Measure Success One Student At a Time<BR>
Mezzanine 5<BR>
Sandra Sellers [713-331-1690] &amp; Sherry Goen, Alvin ISD<BR>
Discover the components of a unique alternative middle school program for
over-age students that
accelerates learning, strengthens skills and redirects negative behaviors
before they go to high
school.
facilitator: kathy owen, texarkana isd<BR>
<BR>
70. Collaborative Teaming<BR>
Independence<BR>
Richard Villa [802-878-8957], Bayridge Educational Consortium, Colchester,
Vermont <BR>
Participants will become familiar with the five critical elements of an
effective collaborative team,
stages of group development and a recommended team meeting agenda format.<BR>
facilitator: sally blewett, beaumont isd<BR>
<BR>
71. Teacher Portfolio Assessment: How This Process Improves Instruction<BR>
Brazos<BR>
Rosalyn Bratcher [409-756-7751], Conroe ISD
Professional portfolios guide individuals toward personalized improvement.
The portfolio is highly
individualized and meets the unique needs of all teachers regardless of
previous skill level and
experience. How administrators and teachers collaboratively develop a vision,
set goals, reflect on
pedagogical practices and document accomplishments will be shared. The development
of a
personal vision statement is the core activity used to initiate the portfolio
process. Reflection of how
current teaching practices may be improved is accomplished by personal journalizing
and
introspective reading of professional writings, with additional collection
of artifacts and authentic
demonstrations of performance added in subsequent years.<BR>
facilitator: carolyn hitt, hays cisd<BR>
<BR>
72. NEA Learning Lab -- A National Initiative to Give Teachers a New Sense
of Power to
Control Their Own Profession and Determine the Future<BR>
Cedar<BR>
Marilyn Butcher [512-414-4495], Will Wall, Holly Brandt, Sue Gizelbach &amp;
Denise Graham,
Austin ISD<BR>
Participants will explore the process for transforming their school into
a Learning Lab where
&quot;Action Research&quot; provides a new way of teacher evaluation and
gives teachers the opportunity to
find answers to the questions that matter in education today.<BR>
facilitator: sarah hodges, grapevine-colleyville isd<BR>
<BR>
73. A New Understanding -- Obtaining Excellence in Education in Urban America<BR>
Mulberry<BR>
Kay Lovelace [313-494-7143], Detroit Public Schools Professional Development
Academy,
Detroit, Michigan<BR>
We are all aware that the more information we have regarding how children
learn, the more
successful we will be in developing their academic achievement. Think about
the power of opening
minds based on a new understanding of students' preferred learning styles
that stems from who
they are, where they come from and what they value. During this fast paced,
cutting edge
presentation, Dr. Lovelace will inspire participants to put in place a new
understanding and
appreciation for research findings and successful practices based on learning
differences that stem
from cultural backgrounds.<BR>
facilitator: manuel rodriguez, pasadena isd<BR>
<BR>
74. Merit Marks -- Closing the Gap<BR>
Live Oak<BR>
Kristi Hawkins [903-667-2328], Maleia Burkett &amp; Nina Rhea, DeKalb ISD<BR>
Merit Marks, a multi-age instruction arrangement at the elementary level
creates an environment
that fosters a good self-concept and positive self esteem which invites
students' academic success.<BR>
Topics of discussion include developmentally appropriate instruction, positive
parental/student
involvement, town meetings and a &quot;pull-in&quot; Title 1 program.<BR>
facilitator: key amundson, white oak isd<BR>
<BR>
75. On the Job -- Job Corps<BR>
Mezzanine 7<BR>
Kay Engler [210-372-5430] &amp; Cindy Vernon, Seguin ISD<BR>
On the Job -- Job Corps received an innovative award in 1993 and has been
replicated in eight
districts across Texas. This no cost pre-referral elementary program is
designed to reduce disruptive
behaviors. Students are given opportunities to earn special &quot;jobs.&quot;<BR>
facilitator: howard baggs, burkburnett isd<BR>
<BR>
76. &quot;Tots to TEENS&quot; -- Parent Education for Infants, Toddlers
and Teen Parents<BR>
Cypress<BR>
Kathy Hughes [817-294-8958], Ft. Worth ISD<BR>
This session will focus on the importance of parent education in a community
setting, as well as on
innovative sessions presented to pregnant and parenting teens in a school
setting. Handouts will be
provided.<BR>
facilitator: beverly kirk, lewisville isd<BR>
<BR>
77. Sugar and Spice and Technical Advice -- A Program for Girls Facing the
21st Century
Workplace<BR>
Mezzanine 6<BR>
Renee Wells [409-729-7644 x103], Pat Briggs, Jane Convery, Mary Jane Moore,
Erma
Richter &amp; Nancy Thompson, Port Neches-Groves ISD<BR>
Utilizing resources within the community, the Pathfinders mentorship/leadership
project is a cost
effective means of providing opportunities for girls to explore the educational,
professional and
personal experiences that contribute to the success of women in business
and industry. Those
attending this session will be able to replicate this highly successful
leadership program.<BR>
facilitator: melissa porche, victoria isd<BR>
<BR>
78. Schoolwide Discipline Policies that Prevent Misbehavior<BR>
Lavaca<BR>
Mickey Garrison [541-672-5145], Educational Support Services, Roseburg,
Oregon<BR>
Are you concerned about discipline and motivation in your schools? Are you
interested in reducing<BR>
office referrals, increasing staff consistency, increasing student motivation
to learn and improving<BR>
the school climate? This session will provide procedures and tools for evaluating
current discipline<BR>
policies and teach a process to develop or revise a discipline policy that
teaches responsible student<BR>
behavior.<BR>
facilitator: mark roberts, pleasant grove isd<BR>
<BR>
79. Educational Architecture for Learning in the 21st Century<BR>
Trinity/San Jacinto<BR>
Barbara Barnes [800-692-2847], EFG Curriculum Collaborative, Scottsdale,
Arizona<BR>
Five Key areas will be presented: 1) integrated curriculum that is relevant
to the real world and
connected to participants around the world - the EFG; 2) authentic performance
based assessments
and portfolio systems including TQM tools and techniques for continuous
improvement; 3)
partnerships and collaborations with the global community: parents, families,
business,
corporations, community organizations and higher education; 4) technology
and communication
tools including World Wide Web sites; and 5) organizational strategies for
the learning community
including multi-age instruction, alternate schedules and year-long calendars.<BR>
facilitator: mary deike, fredericksburg isd<BR>
<BR>
80. Worksheets Be Gone<BR>
Ash<BR>
Pamela Fry [903-784-8973], North Lamar ISD<BR>
Implement reading strategies and techniques in the regular elementary classroom
using leveled
books, Reading Response journals and workstations. Base grading, on authentic
individual
assessments which are student-driven products rather than worksheets will
be shared.<BR>
facilitator: linda little, north lamar isd<BR>
<BR>
81. Thoughtful Literacy Grades K-5<BR>
Ballroom A<BR>
Richard Allington [518-442-5103], The University of Albany - SUNY, Glenmont,
New York<BR>
A key feature of the movement to raise academic standards in American schools
is the emphasis on
developing thoughtful literacy in virtually all students. Unfortunately,
most school programs are not
designed to achieve this goal. It will require some substantial restructuring
of 1) the school day, 2)
the nature of schoolwork kids complete, and 3) evaluation schemes (both
for evaluating children's
literacy development and for evaluating school effectiveness).<BR>
facilitator: cynthia fairall, north east isd<BR>
<BR>
82. Performance Assessments As Classroom Learning Tools<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
Tom Guskey [606-257-8666], University of Kentucky, Lexington, Kentucky<BR>
Performance assessments lead to improvements in student learning only when
they are used as part
of the instructional process at the classroom level. This session will focus
on the steps necessary to
ensure that performance assessments become a regular part of students' learning
experiences and
serve as valuable tools to facilitate learning.<BR>
facilitator: jerry cox, conroe isd<BR>
<BR>
83. Bridging the Gap Between Essential Elements and Authentic Learning:
Aligning<BR>
Curriculum, Instruction and Assessment Around Quality Learning Actions<BR>
Ballroom C<BR>
Kit Marshall [800-738-5294], Action Learning Systems, Inc., Cameron Park,
California<BR>
Learn to communicate about quality performance expectations and assessment
through The
Learning Actions. Celebrated for their capacity to clarify and integrate
content across subject
disciplines and grade levels, the five components of The Learning Actions
System clarify and
strengthen all current models and approaches to school improvement. Students
learn how to &quot;show
what they know&quot; to parents, students and community members through
learning performances that
apply rigorous criteria and standards in a process of continuous improvement.
Dr. Marshall's work
with alignment of curriculum, instruction and assessment is consistently
proving its power
throughout the United States and Canada as a definitive approach to increasing
K-12 learning
performance while deepening basic academic skills and workplace basics across
all grade levels.
Whether you are searching for strategies to raise the performance level
of the students in your
discipline or seeking a rigorous and relevant approach to an entire K-12
system of schooling, this
session will be a critical turning point in the success of your efforts.<BR>
facilitator: debbie easom, mansfield isd<BR>
<BR>
84. Space &amp; The Future<BR>
Freedom<BR>
Jerry Brown [719-576-8000], U.S. Space Foundation, Colorado Springs, Colorado<BR>
Don't you and your students wonder about the future of America's space endeavors?
Dr. Brown
will enlighten the audience as to the biological effects of spaceflight
on humans and will share both
what we know about Mars and what we suspect about future travel to Mars.<BR>
facilitator: phil trice, north lamar isd<BR>
<BR>
85. Authentic Learning/Assessment: Creating Assessment Packages That Foster
Learning<BR>
Red River/Neches<BR>
Carol Mendenhall [210-804-7185], North East ISD<BR>
Assessment is an attitude before it is a method. Creating a balanced approach
to assessment, one
that includes traditional assessments as well as performance and portfolio
assessment, will be the
focus of this session<BR>
facilitator: gwen poteet, texarkana isd<BR>
<BR>
86. Literacy Assessment: Techniques that Work FOR Kids<BR>
Water<BR>
Elizabeth Hamilton [512-846-2111], Lisa Kridner, Michelle Bischoffberger,
Tammi Kasper<BR>
&amp; Ben Carson, Hutto ISD<BR>
The audience will learn about assessment procedures (including running records,
observation notes,
conferencing, spelling assessment and writing evaluation), evaluation of
results and application to
early childhood, elementary and middle level instruction.<BR>
facilitator: paula de la guardia, laporte isd<BR>
<BR>
87. Work-Based Learning: What Does it Mean? How Do You Do It?<BR>
Pine<BR>
Richard Kazis [617-742-5995], Jobs for the Future, Boston, Massachusettes<BR>
Many secondary schools are experimenting with ways to get students out of
the classroom and use
local workplaces as learning opportunities. This session will combine an
overview of work-based
learning approaches with an interactive exercise in designing quality work-based
learning
experiences.<BR>
facilitator: clint mc mahon, caddo mills isd<BR>
<BR>
88. Algebra, Part I (Part II scheduled at 10:30 a.m., Session #118)<BR>
Pecan<BR>
Pam Chandler [713-634-1000] &amp; Basia Rinesmith-Hall, Fort Bend ISD<BR>
The mathematics classroom is changing to better meet the needs of students
in the modern world.<BR>
This is described in the TEKS Mathematics and exemplified in the TexTeam
Mathematics Institute.
This session shows examples of how an algebra classroom might look. Come
see examples of the
practices to encourage and support, as well as learn about the resources
available in mathematics
professional development.<BR>
facilitator: greg mc intyre, college station isd<BR>
<BR>
89. Ability Grouping and Alternatives in Middle and High Schools<BR>
Hickory<BR>
Robert Slavin [410-516-8809], Center for Research on the Education of Students
Placed at<BR>
Risk, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, Maryland <BR>
Despite decades of research finding few benefits for the practice, between-class
ability grouping is
still prevalent in middle and high schools. Ability grouping has not been
found to benefit high,
average or low achievers, and often causes within-school segregation, low
expectations for students
in low groups and unnecessary divisions among students. This presentation
will review research on
ability grouping and will discuss alternatives focusing on maintaining high-track
expectations for all
while using teaching methods capable of succeeding with a wide range of
students and providing
targeted assistance to students having difficulty with a high-expectations
curriculum.
facilitator: ann hoover, esc region xi, fort worth<BR>
<BR>
90. Leap into Learning Styles<BR>
Mezzanine 2<BR>
Kenn Franklin [903-963-8623], Donna Wallace, Brad Crawford, Judy Fincher
&amp; Tom<BR>
Parks, Van ISD<BR>
Students at Van High School leap into learning styles through a centrally
located learning lab that
serves all levels of learning. Data banks of information provide &quot;above
and beyond&quot; opportunities
of exploration of new learning pathways. A variety of settings in the lab
provide opportunities to
explore individual learning styles through eight areas: Math, Science, English,
Social Studies,
Reading, Spanish, TAAS and SAT Prep.<BR>
facilitator: claudio salinas, brooks isd<BR>
<BR>
91. Connecting School and Work: The Role of an Intermediary<BR>
Mezzanine 8<BR>
Jessie Teddlie [817-565-4109] &amp; Pat McLeod, University of North Texas,
Denton; Bill<BR>
Watkins, West Central Texas Consortium, Abilene; Larry Kolb, ESC Region
XIII, Austin<BR>
This presentation will assist administrators, district personnel/partnerships
in meeting the needs of
students and reaching the goals and requirements of Senate Bill 1 and school-to-work
via skill
standards and the coordinator or intermediary.<BR>
facilitator: donna hill, college station isd<BR>
<BR>
92. Road Map to a Successful Math Program<BR>
Sabine<BR>
Cheryl Cox [214-414-4930], Garland ISD; Kelly Daggett, Texas Woman's University,<BR>
Denton<BR>
In this session, information on how to build a strong math program will
be presented. With the
implementation of this plan, students will be far more likely to be successful
on the TAAS math
test. Powerful strategies for at-risk students will also be shared.<BR>
facilitator: annette dunn, texarkana isd
<UL><CENTER><A HREF="../mainmenu.htm"><IMG SRC="../image230.gif" WIDTH=
