<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Session V</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <STRONG>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR></strong>
<STRONG>SET V -- SUNDAY, OCTOBER 27, 10:30 a.m. - Noon</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>93.  Why Do Kids Love School?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lone Star</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>H. Jerome Freiberg [713-743-4953], University of Houston </STRONG><BR>
Jerome Freiberg revised Carl Rogers' classic text, Freedom to Learn.  For the book, he traveled to five cities, interviewing both inner-city and rural middle and high school students about their lives in school. The schools were preselected for their efforts and accomplishments over a 20-year period with person-centered approaches to learning. The findings are surprisingly consistent across the nation. Implications for schools for a new millennium will be discussed.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> diane brazell, waller isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>94.  Intensive Scheduling: Restructuring Through Time Management</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Colorado</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Dave Hottenstein [215-674-5038], Director of Secondary Ed/Principal, Educational Impact Associate, Hatsboro, Pennsylvania</STRONG><BR>
Reworking the school day to better accommodate teaching and learning is a great concept at work in high schools across the globe.  Intensive Scheduling at Hatboro-Horsham High School in Pennsylvania is an outgrowth of a two and a half year process of restructuring to change the curriculum delivery system and improve the academic environment as well as student achievement.  Join this session for a review of the process and the impressive results after four years of restructuring efforts.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> nancy mack, dallas isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>95.  Synergy: A Fully Integrated High School Curriculum</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Live Oak</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Art Shaw [915-857-4400], Mimi Wallace, Debbie McDonald, Monica Herrera, Carolyn Wittrup & Bob Dierdorf, Socorro ISD</STRONG><BR>
The teaching staff of Montwood's interdisciplinary, fully integrated synergy "school within a school" program will present their innovative, successful approach to learning and discuss the successes and lessons of the first year of implementation. A Fine Arts segment has also been included in this year's synergy programs.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gloria nuckles, copperas cove isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>96.  U Can 'ACE' It</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 6</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Dottie Chiles [512-643-6566] & Joe Thedford, Gregory-Portland ISD</STRONG><BR>
The "ACE" (Alternative Center for Education) has been a very successful new program. Using uniforms and unusual daily progress reports to parents, most students are successful in changing attitudes and behavior. The academic and counseling components are interdisciplinary in design.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> sharon ward, jasper isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>97.  Utilizing Campus Organizational Health Feedback Data to Enhance Leadership Effectiveness</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Freedom</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>John Taylor [409-760-7723] & Rosalyn Bratcher, Conroe ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants in this session will leave with a good understanding of how Conroe Independent School District systematically implemented, over a three year period, a process for creating healthy work environments by diagnosing the health of campuses and central office units and utilizing the diagnostic data for providing ongoing support for leadership development.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> ileen foley, victoria isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>98.  You Deserve A Break Today: Head to McDonald's for An Order of Fresh Tutoring</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Red River/Neches</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Leah Rae Marchand [409-744-1721], Galveston ISD; Debbie Brown, McDonald's Company, Galveston</STRONG><BR>
Students who want free tutoring can head over to the Golden Arches every Monday and Tuesday night. Students enrolled in the Bridging the Educational Scene for Teachers of Tomorrow program at Ball High will provide tutoring free of charge in any academic subject to students in second through eighth grade. McDonald's is the business sponsor of the B.E.S.T.T. program at Ball High School in Galveston. To date, over 2,400 students have attended B.E.S.T.T. Tutoring at McDonald's, while the B.E.S.T.T. students have given 1,500 hours providing the tutoring. This presentation will explore avenues for the business and school communities to work together for the educational benefit of all students.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> joe martinez, college station isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>99.  Making Connections</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 5</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Michele M. Pola [713-942-1460] & Lili McRae, Houston ISD</STRONG><BR>
This workshop will provide participants with activities between elementary classes, schools and central administrative staff through teachers. Mathematics is used to create the link for the critical connection to improve TAAS scores.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> marilyn jacobs, abilene isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>100.  Discipline Interventions for Students From Poverty</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom A</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ruby Payne [713-424-9151], RFT Publishing, Baytown</STRONG><BR>
Many students from generational poverty bring a different set of behavioral rules to school. What are successful behavioral interventions for these students?<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> annette nash, new waverly isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>101.  The Inclusion Puzzle: Fitting the Pieces Together</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Independence</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Richard Villa [802-878-8957], Bayridge Educational Consortium, Colchester, Vermont</STRONG><BR>
Participants will become familiar with the accomplishments of special education, characteristics of inclusionary or heterogeneous schools, multiple rationale for change, transition learnings, reasons why change is difficult, organizational and instructional strategies supportive of inclusionary schooling, beliefs operating in heterogeneous schools and successful examples from elementary, middle and high school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> sharon azar, silsbee isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>102.  Successful Practices in Developing Bi-Literacy in Second Language Learners</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cypress</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Oralia Rios [210-580-5042], Judy de la Garza, Alda Benavides & Becky Villarreal, La Joya ISD</STRONG><BR>
Studies have shown that a strong cognitive and academic preparation in the first language strongly influences success in the second language. Presenters will share the La Joya ISD instructional process which delineates procedures and criteria for placement, certification and movement of students from Spanish to English literacy.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> margaret jefferson, houston isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>103.  A Little Fish in a Big Pond</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 1</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>James Johnson [713-453-7183] & Joe Zuniga, Galena Park ISD</STRONG><BR>
The transition from middle school to high school is a difficult undertaking for many freshmen. In order to create a positive first-year experience for students, an orientation class may be the key to shaping and developing the positive mental attitudes needed to deal with the rigors of high school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> paul pasqua, fort stockton isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>104.  Solutions to Classroom Discipline, Grades 6-12</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mulberry</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Randy Sprick [541-345-1442], Teaching Strategies, Eugene, Oregon</STRONG><BR>
Discipline problems are some of the most difficult challenges facing schools today. You will learn how to design and implement plans for chronic classroom misbehaviors. The focus is on providing practical strategies you can implement in your classroom immediately. You will be given tools for solving 100 classroom problems and will learn how to apply research-based strategies to any behavioral/motivational problem.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> ronny nash, silsbee isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>105.  Develop Students' Character... Or Else!</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 7</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Young Jay Mulkey [800-284-0499], Character Education Institute; Brenda Kay Fowler, Austin ISD</STRONG><BR>
Teaching strategies designed to instill universal values, develop critical thinking skills and build self-esteem in pre-kindergarten through the ninth grade will be demonstrated. Participants will engage in lesson activities that demonstrate how to develop students' character. A former principal will describe the effects of developing students' character in an elementary school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> jackie jones, texarkana isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>106.  Educational Architecture for Learning in the 21st Century</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Trinity/San Jacinto</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Barbara Barnes [800-692-2847], EFG Curriculum Collaborative, Scottsdale, Arizona</STRONG><BR>
Five Key areas will be presented: 1) integrated curriculum that is relevant to the real world and connected to participants around the world - the EFG; 2) authentic performance based assessments and portfolio systems including TQM tools and techniques for continuous improvement; 3) partnerships and collaborations with the global community: parents, families, business, corporations, community organizations and higher education; 4) technology and communication tools including World Wide Web sites; and 5) organizational strategies for the learning community including multi-age instruction, alternate schedules and year-long calendars.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gary wuest, schertz-cibolo-universal city isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>107.  Success for All: Every Child a Reader</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Hickory</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Robert Slavin [410-516-8809], Center for Research on the Education of Students Placed at Risk, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, Maryland</STRONG><BR>
"Success for All" is a comprehensive program designed to ensure that every child is successful in reading from the beginning of their time in school. It provides research-based curricula and extensive professional development for  pre-kindergarten to grade six, one-to-one tutoring for primary students experiencing difficulties, family support and other services. A Spanish version of "Success for All" is used in bilingual schools. Research has found substantial and lasting positive effects of "Success for All" on reading in English as well as Spanish. The program is used in more than 100 Texas schools and more than 400 schools nationwide.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> greg gibson, graham isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>108.  A Multi-Year, Thematic Approach to Teaching AP English</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 2</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kay Reat [806-766-0662], Pam Mills, Amanda Cargile, Becky Lowe & Melinda Parsons, Lubbock ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants will explore a different approach to teaching AP English that incorporates team teaching and multi-age teaching. Junior and senior AP students attend class and study works of English through a thematic approach rather than by examining American literature the eleventh grade year and British Literature the twelfth grade year. This two-year approach helps better prepare students to take the AP exam.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> linsae snider, esc region xvii, lubbock</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>109.  7 Steps to Cognition -- European Cognitive Education Methodology to Teach Content, K-12</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Water</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Iles Lee Hannel [602-253-2402] & Marion Veronica Hannel, Educational Consultant/Psychologists, Phoenix, Arizona</STRONG><BR>
A demonstration lesson involving attendees to this presentation will occur. Ninety percent of all problem solving is subtly switched to students; therefore, students can do the work most teachers attempt to do for students. Participants will learn how to get students to solve problems themselves, making them internally competent, not dependent.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> tommy hill, rockwall isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>110.  Grading & Reporting Student Learning</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom B</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Tom Guskey [606-257-8666], University of Kentucky, Lexington, Kentucky</STRONG><BR>
Developing an effective grading and reporting system is more a challenge in thoughtful communication than a simple process of documenting student achievement. This session will review current research on grading and reporting and offer practical guidelines for developing systems that enhance teaching and learning.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> tam jones, statewide initiatives, region xiii esc, austin</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>111.  Applying the "Learning Actions" to K-12 Essential Elements</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom C</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kit Marshall [800-738-5294], Action Learning Systems, Inc., Cameron Park, California</STRONG><BR>
Work with international school restructuring expert Kit Marshall as she teaches and demonstrates using The Learning Actions. This powerful and clear process for designing courses, integrated units and aligning K-12 curriculum, instruction and assessment around high academic standards will enable you to immediately improve your students' performance. Starting points, classroom material samples and practical strategies for engaging stakeholder groups and building ownership across your learning community will be included in this fast moving, hands-on session.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> david chavez, tcta</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>112.  Service Learning: Fostering Student Reflective Thinking Through Authentic Pedagogy</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Brazos</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>James & Pamela Toole [612-787-0409], Compass Institute, St. Paul, Minnesota</STRONG><BR>
In a culture that encourages impulsiveness and offers constant entertainment, how do we create schools in which youth become powerful reflective thinkers? Reflection is a critical tool because it is at the heart of being a self-directed and lifelong learner. It requires a cluster of skills and habits of mind, including patience, sustained curiosity, self-discovery, depth, intellectual integrity and critical and creative thinking. This workshop will demonstrate how to design powerful classroom strategies through service learning, as a form of authentic pedagogy, to cultivate reflective thinking.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> linda smiles, carroll isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>113.  Creating a Multiple Intelligences Portfolio (K-12)</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lavaca</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kay Burke [800-348-4474], IRI/Skylight Training & Publishing, Palatine, Illinois</STRONG><BR>
Portfolios play an important part in the assessment process. Participants in this session will work in small groups to create either a subject area or integrated portfolio unit that includes learning experiences and authentic assessments from all of Howard Gardner's Multiple Intelligences. They will also develop a rubric to grade the portfolio.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> michelle french, paris isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>114.  Vertical Alignment to Create Mathematically Functioning Students</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cedar</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jon Hartgraves [817-796-2186], Kim Shumake, LeeAnn Turner & Jessie Uptergrove, Hico ISD</STRONG><BR>
Learn about mathematical vertical alignment from pre-kindergarten through grade twelve that really works and how experimental course-combining, creative scheduling and open communication can create an environment for greatest learning potential.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> greg whitman, whitehouse isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>115.  Work-Based Learning: What Does It Mean? How Do You Do It?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Richard Kazis [617-742-5995], Jobs for the Future, Boston, Massachusetts</STRONG><BR>
Many schools are experimenting with ways to get students out of the classroom and use local workplaces as learning opportunities. This session will combine an overview of work-based learning approaches with an interactive exercise in designing quality work-based learning experiences.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> kelly rodgers, pleasant grove isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>116.  It Works for Us</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ash</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jerry Kirby [817-473-5660], Linda Jobe, Kay Prosser, Cheryl Barksdale, Dana White, Kelly Willingham & Jennifer Giddings, Mansfield ISD</STRONG><BR>
This presentation will include an overview of materials and procedures used in the Algebra I/Extended Algebra classes to prepare students for the end of course exam.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> dirk callison, anna isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>117.  Meeting School-to-Work, Career Pathways and Work-Based Learning Through a Comprehensive Career Guidance Program</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 8</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jessie Teddlie [817-565-4109] & Pat McLeod, University of North Texas, Denton; Bill Watkins, West Central Texas Consortium, Abilene; Larry Kolb, ESC Region XIII, Austin </STRONG><BR>
This presentation will assist administrators, district personnel/partnerships in meeting the needs of students and reaching the goals and requirements of Senate Bill 1, Section 33, concerning school-to-work.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> mary adams, temple isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>118.  Algebra, Part II (this is a continuation of session #88)</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pecan</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pam Chandler [] & Basia Rinesmith-Hall, Fort Bend ISD</STRONG><BR>
The mathematics classroom is changing to better meet the needs of students in the modern world. This is described in the TEKS Mathematics and exemplified in the TexTeam Mathematics Institute. This session shows examples of how an algebra classroom might look. Come see examples of the practices to encourage and support, as well as learn about the resources available in mathematics professional development.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> susan higgins, cypress fairbanks isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>119.  Motivating Through Multimedia</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sabine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Nicki Wilcoxson [806-371-5518], Amarillo ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session will focus on the process of involving teachers and students in the construction of multimedia products, techniques for classroom management during construction of multimedia products and the equipment needed for establishing a portable multimedia lab in middle and high schools.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> joe kelley, aransas pass isd</STRONG><BR>

