"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <strOng>1996 National Conference of Texas Program<BR></STRONG>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>SET VI -- SUNDAY, OCTOBER 27, 3:00 - 4:30 p.m.</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>120.  Instructional Long-Range Planning: 1988-2010</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sabine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Beverly Rodgers [817-565-4433], Texas Center for Educational Technology; Delia Duffey & Anita Given, Texas Education Agency; Lucy Cochranc, Texas Task Force for Educational Technologies</STRONG><BR>
TCET was asked to conduct research on the impact of technology in Texas schools. This panel discussion will examine findings. Learn about plans and trends in many Texas districts. This session will also involve a focus on aligning existing curriculum to the new TEKS (Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills) in both content areas and in "Applications of Technology".<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> archie mcafee, plano isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>121.  The Charter School: A Concept Whose Time Has Come</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Trinity/San Jacinto</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kit Marshall [800-738-5294], Action Learning Systems, Inc., Cameron Park, California</STRONG><BR>
This session is grounded on the current state-of-the art in charter schools throughout the United States. This powerful movement is sweeping the country and represents a growing mindset around accountability, action academics, authenticity, and assessment. Whether you are moving in the direction of charter schools or anxious about what this shift in the school restructuring agenda may mean, you need to become informed about what is so clearly on the horizon beyond site-based schools and systemic restructuring.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> james mc swain, texarkana isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>122.  How to Teach in a Longer Time Block</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Colorado</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Dave Hottenstein [215-674-5038], Hatsboro, Pennsylvania</STRONG><BR>
The key to successful restructuring is to create a time configuration that works for your school.  It must provide teachers and students with a better learning environment.  More importantly, teacher and student behavior inside the classroom must change positively to improve teacher and student performance.  Join this session for a look at effective instructional strategies which can be used during longer time blocks in high school classrooms for improved academic performance.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> denise mattson, lubbock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>123.  Common Sense in School Renewal: Lessons From The Basic School Network</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Water</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mary Ellen Bafumo [540-568-7098], James Madison University, Harrisonburg, Virginia & Shari Albright, Southwestern Bell Telephone Company, San Antonio</STRONG><BR>
As the Basic School National Network enters its third year of implementation, many lessons have emerged about the process of school renewal in this diverse demonstration project. The voices of teachers, students, parents and administrators share the successes, challenges and the future faced by schools organizing for excellence around Ernest L. Boyer's four priorities for renewal: community, curriculum, climate and character.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> pat hanks, atpe</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>124.  Quest High School: The Future Is Now</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cedar</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lynn Parsons [713-540-5003], Linda Wodka & Carol Ann Caveny, Humble ISD</STRONG><BR>
Participants will receive detailed information about the design and implementation of a high-tech break-the-mold magnet alternative high school in a property poor suburban district. You will leave with a design process that you can replicate in your own district and specific examples of curriculum, staffing patterns, program design and funding.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> lary reap, spring branch isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>125.  Effective Staff Development</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Freedom</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Tom Guskey [606-257-8666], University of Kentucky, Lexington, Kentucky </STRONG><BR>
Learn about the factors that contribute to the effectiveness of staff development and make it a valuable experience for all who take part. This session will describe essential planning, implementation and follow-up activities, and offer a series of practical guidelines for more effective practice.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> jim phillips, burkburnett isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>126.  Working with the News Media</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Brazos</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Steve Knagg [214-494-8485], Garland ISD</STRONG><BR>
Effective communication is an important part of every educator's job. Local, state and national news coverage of educational issues is growing. The presenter, a past president of the National School Public Relations Association, will share strategies on working with the news media that he has developed over the last 20 years in the communications department of the Garland ISD<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> rudy duran, clear creek isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>127.  Communication: The Key To Successful Leadership</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 8</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kelly Rodgers [903-832-8006], Paula Hawkins, Linda Bruce & Shana Cheney, Pleasant Grove ISD, Texarkana</STRONG><BR>
This workshop promises to provide the participants with techniques on effective communication with teachers, parents, students and the community. This presentation is guaranteed to be entertaining and informative. Techniques will be demonstrated and handouts provided.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> alex alexander, lufkin isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>128.  A New Understanding: Obtaining Excellence in Education in Urban America</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mulberry</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kay Lovelace [313-494-7143], Detroit Public Schools' Professional Development Academy, Detroit, Michigan</STRONG><BR>
We are all aware that the more information we have regarding how children learn, the more successful we will be in developing their academic achievement. Think about the power of opening minds based on a new understanding of students' preferred learning styles that stems from who they are, where they come from and what they value. During this fast-paced cutting edge presentation, Dr. Lovelace will inspire participants to put in place a new understanding and appreciation for research findings and successful practices based on learning differences that stem from cultural backgrounds.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> freddye kelly, katy isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>129.  Methodology which Targets the Obstacles to Learning for At-Risk, Bilingual, Special Ed and Dyslexic Students</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Hickory</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ben Rodriguez [817-751-1188] & Jane Wilkinson, Creative Education Institute, Waco</STRONG><BR>
Students of all ages and abilities can learn, but learning follows different neurological pathways for each individual. By focusing at the cause of learning failure rather than the symptoms, students' lives can be dramatically improved.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> cheryl  kosta, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>130.  The Yellow Rose Parenting Program</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 2</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Gilbert Garcia [210-622-5301], Jada Pitman, Lisa McConoghy & Gloria Valdez, Southwest ISD</STRONG><BR>
"It is by believing in roses that we bring them to bloom." Gather strategies and techniques to implement a focused, well-targeted high impact program addressing special needs. The Yellow Rose Parenting Program provides comprehensive services to school-age parents utilizing a holistic and educational approach serving both female and male students.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> steve fleming, nederland isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>131.  Consistency Management & Cooperative Discipline: From Tourist to Citizen</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lone Star</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>H. Jerome Freiberg [713-743-4953], University of Houston</STRONG><BR>
Consistency Management & Cooperative Discipline (CMCD), combines instructional effectiveness through consistency of organization with cooperative discipline developed collaboratively with students. The CMCD program, used with more than 10,000 kindergarten through twelfth grade students and teachers from inner-cities to rural schools, gives teachers and administrators a plan to improve the quality of instruction and learning environments. The CMCD program is not a packaged discipline program, but a framework that evolves to incorporate five themes: prevention, caring, cooperation, organization and community.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> bruce cunningham, frenship isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>132.  Student Leadership: An Extended Education </STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 1</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Brenda Gilmore [817-460-2541], Arlington ISD; Dodie Kasper, Plano ISD</STRONG><BR>
Based on the belief that all students are leaders, this session will look at models for high school leadership classes and will include activities and suggestions for implementing these techniques and processes in any classroom.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> charlotte risinger, fort worth isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>133.  Interdisciplinary Curriculum: Playdough for the Mind</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Red River/Neches</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Dawn Campagna [806-766-0988], Canzada Bray & Mary Jane Potts, Lubbock ISD</STRONG><BR>
Nat Williams Elementary teachers will discuss basic steps that will help you mold your curriculum and shape it into the "Big Idea." Learn to use broadbased themes (the big idea) to make connections among all content areas and real life situations, stretching minds into higher levels of thinking.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> donna martinez, la joya isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>134.  Community Economic Development as a Curriculum Reform Catalyst</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cypress</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Gene Schatz [817-694-3457], Whitney ISD; Larry Dyer, School to Work Consortium; Bill Woods, Quality Work Force Planning Commission, Waco</STRONG><BR>
One model for school and community unity in economic development will be given and other ideas will be shared among attendees. Labor force development will be the number one factor in attracting industry.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> marvin agnew, moody isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>135.  Opening Windows to Literacy Success</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ash</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Deanna Scully Smith [210-379-2675], Leticia Villarreal, Sally Keddal, Becky Helms & Jane Wells, Seguin ISD</STRONG><BR>
Emergent readers thrive in an environment where learners are actively involved in meaningful literacy experiences. Participants will open the windows to a balanced literacy program from fine arts to the classroom to the playground.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> debbie maxey, tatum isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>136.  Individualized Reading in the Junior High or "Hey, Reading Really Is Cool"</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 7</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Marjorie Jennings [512-858-4155], Hays CISD</STRONG><BR>
This individualized reading program in junior high allows all students to read, discuss and answer high-level thinking questions on novels selected to match their reading ability level.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> leslie faught, calallen isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>137.  Reaching Fluency in Reading with Dignity</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Independence</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sandra Love [903-531-3755], Becky Monroe, Linda Malone, Sindy Oldham & Candy DuBose, Tyler ISD</STRONG><BR>
Meeting the needs of all learners in elementary school is attainable through balanced literacy. This session will include the use of shared reading, read-alouds, focus poetry, guided reading and vertical planning. An investigation of nonfiction and suggested follow-up responses will also be shared.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> debra mayfield, harlandale isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>138.  Creative Responses to Students Experiencing Behavioral and Emotional Challenges: From Risk to Resilience</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom A</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Richard Villa [802-878-8957], Bayridge Educational Consortium, Colchester, Vermont </STRONG><BR>
Participants will distinguish between punishment and discipline and a continuum of placement and a continuum of services. Assumptions underlying discipline systems will be explored. The relationship between theories of motivation, communication and student behavior will be discussed. A constellation of supports and services for meeting the needs of learners experiencing behavioral and emotional challenges will be highlighted.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> art shaw, socorro isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>139.  What New Brain Research Tells Us About Authentic Learning</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom B</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Eric Jensen [619-546-7555], UCSD, San Diego, California</STRONG><BR>
This exciting and upbeat session explores the links between new brain research and learning strategies. You'll learn what neuroscientists tell us that boosts motivation, attention, learning, meaning, recall and application. Presentation includes handouts with specific practical strategies that all K-12 educators will enjoy.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> julia lyda, grapevine-colleyville isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>140.  A Dialogue With Sandra McBrayer</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom C</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sandra McBrayer, San Diego, California </STRONG><BR>
Participants will have a chance to follow up with Sandra on her keynote address in a more intimate setting, following the Second General Session. The 1994 Teacher of the Year will take time to answer questions and speak openly about her own experiences as a top educator.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> shari emmons, birdville isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>141.  Caprock Accelerated Program: Service Drives the Learning</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Live Oak</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Rebecca Harrison [806-371-5500], Gwen Treat, Judith Johnson & students, Amarillo ISD; Andrae England, ESC Region XIV, Abilene</STRONG><BR>
Strong community partnerships have contributed to four successful years for the Caprock Accelerated Program. Students and teachers from this award-winning high school will illustrate how weekly service is an integral part of the academic curriculum. Examples of interdisciplinary tasks, performance assessments and service components will be presented. Additionally, an overview of service learning across Texas will be included. Handouts will be provided for participants.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> kay berry, olney isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>142.  Rubrics: The Heart of Authentic Assessment (K-12)</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lavaca</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kay Burke [800-348-4474], IRI/Skylight Training & Publishing, Palatine, Illinois </STRONG><BR>
"Any student can hit a target that he or she can see and that is held still." This quote by Stiggins and Conklin (1992) supports the importance of setting clear expectations for students and working with them to create criteria to measure student achievement and growth. This session will focus on creating user-friendly scoring rubrics to assess students' projects, performances and portfolios.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gladys gibbs, northside isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>143.  Center Approach to Teaching</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Joy Lott [817-249-7100], Sandra Jenkins & Cathy Conlin, Ft. Worth ISD</STRONG><BR>
Three teachers of multi-grade, center-oriented primary classes will share ideas on classroom management and organization of centers. Examples of activities to be used in centers will be given.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> sally mcbee, north east isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>144.  Contemporary Mathematics in Context -- Core Plus Curriculum</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pecan</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Tommy Eads [903-737-2010], Barbara Eatherly, Kathy Stewart & Jimmie Stripland, North Lamar ISD</STRONG><BR>
The Core-Plus Mathematics Project is an integrated mathematics program for all secondary students that provides relevant learning situations in algebra, geometry, statistics, trigonometry and discrete mathematics topics. Come prepared to participate in active mathematics learning just the way students learn in the CPMP classroom.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> larry lee, junction isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>145.  Career Education - Not Business as Usual</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 5</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Steve Johnson [409-764-5465] & Judy McLeod, College Station ISD</STRONG><BR>
PreK-12 educators will obtain insight into the often confusing state of career education in our schools. The presenters will focus on how new processes and new partnerships can and will be forged to provide career education for all students. Handouts with specific examples will be available.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> tony dominguez, karnes city isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>146.  Outstanding in Their F.I.E.L.D (Fun-Filled Integrated Educational Learning Destinations</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 6</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kathyna Hatla [409-361-9600], Stefaine Bestor, Kathyna Hatla & Dawn Bishop, Bryan ISD</STRONG><BR>
Join a step-by-step explanation and hear examples of ways to create, plan and implement an extended integrated field trip. These activities are designed for middle school students in Texas.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gail krohn, nederland isd</STRONG><BR>

