<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <strong>1996 National Conference of Texas Program</strong><p><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>SET VII -- MONDAY, OCTOBER 28, 9:40 - 10:40 a.m.</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>147.  Envisioning the Basic School at the High School Level</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Red River/Neches</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Shari Albright [210-736-7597], Southwestern Bell Telephone Company, San Antonio & Mary Ellen Bafumo, James Madison University, Harrisonburg, Virginia</STRONG><BR>
The Basic School Project, an initiative of Ernest L. Boyer, president of the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, was originally conceived as the first in a trilogy of school renewal efforts that began with the elementary grades and continued through middle and high school. This workshop offers a guide to implementation of the basic school's highly integrated teaching approach and its student-centered philosophy into the middle and high school setting.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> edward seifert, southwest texas state university, san marcos</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>148.  Summer + Bored Children = Trouble: We Have A Better Equation!</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Brazos</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Fran Gasch [210-334-5043] & Lee Ann Ray, Pearsall ISD</STRONG><BR>
What is there to do in a small, poor rural South Texas community of 6,000 with growing gang and drug activity? Since our town has had very little in the way of organized recreation and is quite vulnerable to the influx of negative influences, it was imperative that our adult community present a unified, cohesive front as we combatted the infiltration of vice. The elementary principals organized a Youth Task Force made up of leaders of the community to design a state-recognized summer recreational program for 300-400 at-risk students.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> steve fuller, pflugerville isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>149.  School Reform: Genesis of Schoolwide Projects</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lavaca</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Robert Lopez [210-684-8180], Albert Cortez & Abelardo Villarreal, Intercultural Development Research Association, San Antonio; Joe Johnson, Dana Center, Austin; Barry Rutheford, RMC, Denver, Colorado</STRONG><BR>
This session will provide participants with information to assess their planning and implementation of schoolwide projects. Project personnel will share a vision of Title I, requirements of schoolwide projects and funding projections. In addition to the STAR presentation, administrators will share experiences in implementing successful schoolwide projects. A schedule of technical assistance activities for the 1996-87 school year will be shared with participants.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> pam ainsworth, crockett isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>150.  Proactive Connections for Student Success</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Water</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Molly Bradford [512-664-0126], Christi Townsend, Jerry Trevino, Veronica Alfaro & Mary Lou Guerra, Alice ISD</STRONG><BR>
At Alice High School, Academic Teaming is being enhanced by connections with social skills training, peer mediation and special education inclusion. This proactive approach positively impacts attendance, discipline and failure rate and leads to increased success for students and staff<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> blanca hernandez, brownsville isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>151.  Stacking Innovations: When Too Much Is Too Much</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ash</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Claude Cunningham [817-473-5600], Mansfield ISD; Diana Macon Bernshausen, University of Houston; Danny Stribling, College Station ISD</STRONG><BR>
As site-based teams plan for school improvement, there is a tendency to address a wide array of needs. We are trained to try to address the needs of each individual. Such an approach may be counterproductive. Possible outcomes of stacking many changes are explored and possible alternative strategies are offered.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> beth gay, beaumont isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>152.  Step to Success: Accelerating Learning Through An Extended-Year Program</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 6</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Fran Rhodes [210-706-8640], Wanda Mann, Kathy Richards, Heather Williams & Lisa Walls, Northside ISD</STRONG><BR>
A diagnostic-prescriptive program to reduce retentions and accelerate learning for kindergarten through eighth grade will be described. This program can be used for year-round intersessions, extended day programs and traditional summer school programs.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> allison gadbois, atpe</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>153.  Information on the Telecommuni-cations Infrastructure Fund</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 7</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Arnold Viramontes [512-475-3156], Telecommunications Infrastructure Fund, Austin</STRONG><BR>
Now in its initial planning phase, the TIF is a $150 million grant program to be administered over ten years. It will facilitate the deployment and use of advanced telecommunications technologies in Texas public schools, hospitals, libraries and other public institutions. Join the TIF executive director for an overview of the Fund and general information about grants, which will be awarded beginning late this year.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gretchen goetz, atpe</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>154.  Maintaining the Momentum of the Improvement Process</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Freedom</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Stephanie Hirsh [214-661-2924], National Staff Development Council, Richardson</STRONG><BR>
Examine the beliefs and assumptions that guide effective staff development and school improvement planning. Practice strategies for pushing the thinking of your colleagues to the "edge." Specific processes (i.e. study groups, banishment, reframing, effective meetings) for focusing the improvement efforts on student learning will be shared. Gather new resources to assist with your change efforts. Opportunities for discussion, question and answer and networking will be provided.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> jan aragon, houston</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>155.  Professional Portfolios -- A Reflective Assessment Tool or Just Another Gimmick for "Dog and Pony Shows"</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kathy Harwell [817-851-5510] & Julia Lyda, Grapevine-Colleyville ISD</STRONG><BR>
Review the critical attributes of the professional portfolio for teachers and administrators. What are the most important questions to ask about their use? Learn about and see examples of this tool for reflective professional growth and student achievement.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> linda gossett, mart isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>156.  Vertical Team -- Starting Small for the Success of All Students in Mathematics</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Hickory</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Larry Sigler [214-539-1591], Julie Altom, Lynn Feaster, Kathy McCool & Debbie Rochester, Lewisville ISD</STRONG><BR>
During this session, all-level math teachers and administrators will see how a plan was developed for curriculum alignment through a Vertical Team to improve TAAS math scores and to enrich pre-advanced placement and advanced placement classes. Handouts and suggestions will be shared.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> bill parry, esc region i, edinburg</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>157.  Beyond Rhetoric: Understanding and Building on the Community of Diversity</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 8</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sandra Nolan [409-295-9161] & Greg Heuberger, Education Service Center Region VI, Huntsville</STRONG><BR>
Teachers and administrators from middle schools and high schools will experience an interactive, meaningful session explaining a process for developing communities within diversity of students, teachers and administrators. Participants will practice a process for infusion of inclusive, multicultural concepts into all aspects of the school culture.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> celina russell, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>158.  Changing Times for General Education Teachers</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sabine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Randy Soffer [512-454-6694], Inclusion Works!, Austin & Four State Teacher Association Representatives</STRONG><BR>
Different from the recent past, today's general educators are expected to meet the instructional needs of diverse learners, principally, mainstreamed or fully included special education students. To experience success, teachers need preparation and supports. To find out what is needed and, importantly, how to ensure that you get what you need, come to this session.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> tom mandeville, southwest texas state university, san marcos</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>159.  Success Through Support for ADHD</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mulberry</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Diane Van Cleve [512-788-9587] & Harriet Becker, Victoria ISD</STRONG><BR>
A parenting program that really works!! Strategies and resources on initiating a support group for parents of children with Attention Deficit Disorder and Attention Deficit Disorder with Hyperactivity will be presented. Meeting the needs of parents of ADD/ADHD children has proven to be a successful parenting program in VISD.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> debbie jinkins, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>160.  Counselors on Wheels</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 2</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Edward Valent [210-548-8601], Nora Johnson & Ray West, Brownsville ISD</STRONG><BR>
The Counselors on Wheels project is funded through a community grant designed to prevent/reduce juvenile crime. Families who are unable, too busy or uncomfortable visiting a secondary/elementary campus to discuss matters with counselors are visited after working hours by selected counselors to address the needs of the students and their family members. The project is intended to develop intrafamily bonding, provide individual counseling, present parenting sessions in the neighborhood and prevent drug abuse and gang involvement.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> norma kinchen, johnson city isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>161.  International Baccalaureate -- A Model for the Distinguished Achievement Program Goals</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Independence</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cynthia Smith [512-778-5631], Liberty Hill ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session will review the components of the Distinguished Achievement Program (DAP) as they are actualized in one model -- the IB program. It will take a practical look at the philosophy and functional goals of the DAP and how they are fully achieved by students pursuing the IB Diploma.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> eddie parsley, judson isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>162.  SCORE "Use Me Now!" Study Skills</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cedar</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sharon Johnson [800-444-5844], SCORE, Orange County Department of Education, Costa Mesa, California</STRONG><BR>
When students are successful in content areas and when students master content rather than going through motions, they are more motivated. They are easier to teach, and teachers enjoy teaching more. This workshop will provide participants with strategies to increase student retention, enhance student interest and create an atmosphere conducive to learning. Participants in this session will receive handouts on learning theories, communication, whole-brain note taking techniques and authentic assessment strategies. Presenters will use transparencies and handouts which are interactive and conducive to discussion.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> matt matthys, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>163.  The Texan Tribunal -- Making Student Courts Work</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine I</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lynn Bridges [512-994-0934] & Bruce Scott, Corpus Christi ISD</STRONG><BR>
The Texan Tribunal, implemented through a communication course, helps high school students who are in danger of failing because of attendance problems. Students learn communication and citizenship skills and then assume legal roles where they make decisions and provide options for troubled students. It's about student empowerment and responsibility.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> alys brasfield, katy isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>164.  Status of Development of the Texas Essential Skills (TEKS)</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom A</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ann Smisko [512-463-8525], Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The TEKS have been under development since 1995 and will be adopted in 1997. This presentation will provide an overview of the process and discuss related issues, including implementation.  Dr. Smisko will also respond to questions.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> roseanne perez, calallen isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>165.  Creative Problem Solving: An Interdisciplinary, Schoolwide Approach</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Trinity/San Jacinto</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Chip Evans [817-571-3562], Marthajane Harrington King & Bettie Gimbert, Grapevine-Colleyville ISD</STRONG><BR>
Presenters will walk fifth through ninth grade teachers and campus administrators through the steps they developed while turning their middle level campus into an across-level, creative problem-solving campus. They will share ideas about the CPS process and ways they organized their campus, as well as give participants a how-to booklet. After this session, participants will be able to hold a problem-solving event on their own campus.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> charlie franklin, henderson isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>166.  Every Child a Reader: The Goals of the Governor's Reading Initiative</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom C</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Robin Gilchrist [512-463-9027], Texas Education Agency & Jean Osborn, University of Illinois</STRONG><BR>
This session will include an overview of the Governor's Reading Initiative, activities of the Texas Education Agency and a discussion on a balanced reading program for energizing readers.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> debra nelson, frisco isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>167.  What New Brain Research Tells Us About Authentic Learning</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom B</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Eric Jensen [619-546-7555], University of California, San Diego</STRONG><BR>
This exciting and upbeat session explores the links between new brain research and learning strategies. You'll learn what neuroscientists tell us that boosts motivation, attention, learning, meaning, recall and application. Presentation includes handouts with specific practical strategies that all educators will enjoy.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> mary ellen glaze, north east isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>168.  Diversity and Success...Using 4MAT to Address Both!</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lone Star</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>David Marshall [210-828-9797], San Antonio</STRONG><BR>
This session is designed to begin to give the participant tools to address the needs of all learners in their classrooms, grades pre-kindergarten through twelve. We will address how teachers can reach students who are unmotivated and disinterested and will provide answers on why some students succeed in school and others do not. In this hands-on workshop, educators will receive the latest information on learning preferences, brain hemisphericity, and how using the 4MAT learning cycle will address student diversity and create success.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> deanna scully-smith, seguin isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>169.  Authentic Teaching and Learning  Anything But Lecture</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Colorado</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Donna Tileston [903-342-3737], Winnsboro ISD</STRONG><BR>
What brain research tells us about "how" students learn could change classrooms forever. Based on the book by this presenter, ways to achieve optimum learning and higher test scores will be explored.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> dave shobe, east central isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>170. -- The School-To-Careers Connection: A Win-Win Opportunity</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Live Oak</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ward McCain [512-463-9734], Hank Madeley, Kirk Edney, Sally Wiedemann, Karen Batchelor, Gay Nell McGinnis, Richard Grimsley, Emmett Eary, Ann Pennington, Lana Perkins, Rebecca Patterson & Jim Laird, Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The Career and Technology Division staff discuss new initiatives, innovations and successes in the program content areas, provide updates on TEKS, Tech Prep and School To Work, clarify funding availability and describe components of the State Plan. Hear the goals for bringing Texas students into the 21st Century with competencies that will enable them to extend their education beyond high school and to expand opportunities for success in the workplace in high skill, high wage jobs whenever and wherever they seek employment!<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> ignacio salinas, san diego isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>171.  Connecting With the Real World Through Exciting Senior Internships</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cypress</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Nancy Hawk [806-358-3467], Amarillo ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session looks at internship programs that provide real work experiences for the senior student and an opportunity for career and college clarification and focus. This is a "how-to" session on implementing a professional internship program.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> robert jolly, highland park isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>172.  Effective Intermediate Math Instruction</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pecan</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>(Mathematics Institute Trainer)</STRONG><BR>
The mathematics classroom is changing to better meet the needs of students in the modern world. This is described in the TEKS in Mathematics and exemplified in the TexTeam Mathematics Institute. This session shows examples of how a mathematics classroom might look. Come see examples of the practices to encourage and support, as well as learn about the resources available in mathematics professional development.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> sydna hall, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>173.  8th Grade Community Service Learning in Action</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 5</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sandi Thomas [903-856-6432] & Glenda Maxwell, Pittsburg ISD</STRONG><BR>
An overview of our eighth grade, Community Service Learning Class will be presented. We will share how to prepare students and where to place them in the community.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> mauro vasquez, mercedes isd</STRONG><BR>

</STRONG>
