    <TITLE>Session VIII</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image43.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><STRONG><BR>
<BR>
1996 National Conference of Texas -- SESSIONS ONLINE</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>from <strong>1996 National Conference of Texas Program</strong><p><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>SET VIII -- MONDAY, OCTOBER 28, 10:50 - 11:50 a.m.</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>174.  Technology for the Entire District: Planning from Ground Zero</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Brazos</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Vickie De La Rosa [210-372-5771 x306] & Barbara Gettig, Seguin ISD</STRONG><BR>
The components of this presentation will include planning for the infrastructure and hardware to be used, software to be selected, staff development, curriculum integration and outlines on what to do and not do when designing a district's technology program.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> melinda welch, blue ridge isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>175.  Accelerated Block Scheduling in Secondary Schools</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Colorado</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Don Jefferies [817-325-6404], Clarence Holliman & Jeff Harris, Mineral Wells ISD</STRONG><BR>
Improve your students' academic and extracurricular performances through the use of accelerated block scheduling. Presented by practitioners with years of experience developing and implementing block programs and block schedules, very useful models will be shown.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> george kale, henderson isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>176.  Constructing Distance Learning Collaboratives That Work!</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cypress</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jerry Gantzer [817-565-4433], University of North Texas, Denton</STRONG><BR>
This presentation will focus on answers to the following types of questions...and more. What makes a distance learning collaborative successful? What are examples of working collaboratives? How do I get started?<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> judith williams, pasadena isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>177.  A Creative Way to Blend 'Choice' with 'Placed' in an Alternative School Setting</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kathy Gaines [409-277-6537], Brenham ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session is an overview of a rural school district's handling of an alternative school with three distinct programs: mastery-based high school diploma, in-school GED preparation, and AEP pre-expulsion discipline.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> bill carpenter, esc region ix, wichita falls</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>178.  NSDC's Standards for Staff Development</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Freedom</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Stephanie Hirsh [214-661-2924], National Staff Development Council, Dallas</STRONG><BR>
Eight national associations (NMSA, NSDC, NAESP, NASSP, NEA, ASCD, AASA, CCSSO) collaborated to develop and validate a set of national standards to guide the planning, implementation and evaluation of staff development programs in the elementary, middle and high school grades. Examine the staff development standards recommended if schools are to create programs that result in improved student learning. The standards address the area of school and district organization, staff development delivery strategies and content for staff development. Receive samples of the standards, suggestions for using the standards to strengthen your school or district staff development program and practical applications from districts currently applying the standards.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> janelle sanders, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>179.  A Successful Induction/Mentoring Model</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 7</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Robert K. Presley [512-268-2141] & Sherri White, Hays CISD</STRONG><BR>
Hays CISD, in an effort to promote student success by improving teaching performance and to ensure a rewarding and successful first-year teaching experience for teachers new to the district, has implemented a comprehensive, team-based Induction and Mentoring Program. This presentation will enable you to analyze the four key components of the Hays program and receive information and insights which will be useful in the development of a formal Induction/Mentoring Program in your school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> larry davis, connally isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>180.  Dealing with Displaced Hornets</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Hickory</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Steve Knagg [214-494-8485], Garland ISD</STRONG><BR>
Displaced hornets seem to be a regular occurrence in the school business. Educators must learn the strategies needed to deal with unhappy patrons, employees and pressure groups. The presenter, a past president of the National School Public Relations Association, will share his three-step plan for putting displaced hornets back into their nest. Come prepared to both learn and laugh!<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> dorian  martin, tepsa</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>181.  Making Connections to the Future: A School and University Partnership for School Improvement</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Live Oak</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Laurie Hawke [817-968-9814], Tarleton State University; Jerry Lewis & Tracie Truitt, Killeen ISD</STRONG><BR>
Palo Alto Middle School has initiated a major school restructuring effort in order to increase the number of students who are academically successful, to increase parent and community involvement, to establish and maintain a safe and inviting school environment, to integrate technology into instruction and to promote appropriate social interaction skills among students. Palo Alto Middle School and the Effective Schools Project of Tarleton State University have joined together in a unique partnership to facilitate, evaluate and ensure the success of the restructuring project.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> richard kouri, austin isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>182.  Family Nights -- Getting the Whole Family Involved </STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Pecan</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Marlene Powers [210-679-2780] & Mary Ann Horton, Northside ISD</STRONG><BR>
In order to increase parental involvement in the education of their children, the staff at Westwood Terrace Elementary School developed a series of family nights for reading, writing, research, science, geography, social studies and fitness as well as our popular back-to-school extravaganza. Westwood Terrace is a Partnerships school restructuring according to the Accelerated Schools model.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> sandra ellington, beaumont isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>183.  Building Rapport for Parent Involvement</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mulberry</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Miriam J. Georg [800-328-3757], Performance Learning Systems South Central, Arlington</STRONG><BR>
This workshop will identify the barriers that keep parents from the school campus. Participants will learn multiple strategies for engaging parent participation and improving the community's perception of the school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> peggy derousen, ricardo isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>184.  The Texas Tomorrow Fund -- Texas Prepaid High Education Tuition Program</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 2</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Melody Ellis [512-936-6135], Office of the Comptroller, Austin</STRONG><BR>
Learn how you can lock in the costs of tomorrow's tuition and fees today with a unique way to prepay a child's education in Texas. Find out how Texas is joining Alabama, Alaska, Florida, Massachusetts, Michigan, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Wyoming to ensure a prepared workforce in our state.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> mary lee glass, copperas cove isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>185.  Discover the Diversity</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 8</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jane F. Woodward [915-336-5241], Gwen Manchaca & Dianna Lannom, Ft. Stockton ISD</STRONG><BR>
Learn about an integrated unit of study for the middle school student on the physical and cultural diversity of Texas with performance-based tasks for the inclusive classroom. Many student examples and extensive hand-outs will be available.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> doug reed, columbia-brazoria isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>186.  Realities and Challenges -- Dealing Proactively with the Health Challenged Student</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 5</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Janet Railsback [817-897-2433], Gwen Mabery & Nancy Fisher, Glen Rose ISD</STRONG><BR>
Student achievement is significantly impacted by the chronic and/or terminal illness of a student. This presentation will provide methods/suggestions to help students, parents and staff deal directly, honestly and compassionately with the illness while maintaining success in school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> beth june, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>187.  Positive Classroom Management -- How to Keep Them Under Your Thumb with a Smile on Your Face</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Water</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Julia Robinson [817-370-8198], Aledo ISD</STRONG><BR>
This session gives an outline of major areas that the classroom teacher can change to have a positive impact on student behavior. The participants will re-examine their particular ideas and approaches to determine if they have an environment in which students feel comfortable and ready to learn.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> john parker, elgin isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>188.  Status Report of the English Language Arts/Reading TEKS</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom A</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cathy Davis [512-463-8525], Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The TEKS have been under development since 1995 and will be adopted in 1997. This session will provide a status report on the second draft of the TEKS in this content area, and Ms. Davis will respond to questions.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> connie kilday, irving isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>189.  Status Report of the Mathematics TEKS</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom B</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Bill Hopkins [512-463-8525], Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The TEKS have been under development since 1995 and will be adopted in 1997. This session will provide a status report on the second draft of the TEKS in this content area, and Mr. Hopkins will respond to questions.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> mindy long, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>190.  Status Report of the Social Studies TEKS</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Independence</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ann Rogers [512-463-8525], Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The TEKS have been under development since 1995 and will be adopted in 1997. This session will provide a status report on the second draft of the TEKS in this content area, and Ms. Rogers will respond to questions.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> don mcewen, seguin isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>191.  Status Report of the Science TEKS</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Trinity/San Jacinto</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Jim Collins [512-463-8525], Texas Education Agency</STRONG><BR>
The TEKS have been under development since 1995 and will be adopted in 1997. This session will provide a status report on the second draft of the TEKS in this content area, and Mr. Collins will respond to questions.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> barbara moore, spring branch isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>192.  ADD/ADHD: What's It All About?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lavaca</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Kitten Arthur [915-728-5581] & Kristi Hartwick, Colorado ISD</STRONG><BR>
Teachers, parents and administrators are frustrated as to how to meet the needs of ADD/ADHD students. This workshop will provide accurate, research-based information, teaching tips and behavior modification strategies for both parents and staff. Take this information back to your staff and inservice them in under one hour.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> emily o'conner, chisum isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>193.  Creating Reading Programs that Work</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ash</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Judy Mayne Wallis [713-498-8110 x5540], Alief ISD</STRONG><BR>
Successful reading programs don't happen by accident; they are carefully designed and nurtured. Learn components of a reading program that ensures successful instruction of all students.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> susan cichon, cypress-fairbanks isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>194.  Filling the "Hole" in Whole-Language: A Practical Teaching Model Designed to Build and Maintain Basic Skill Fluency</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine I</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ray Beck [303-651-2829], Project RIDE -- U.S. Dept. of Education, Longmont, Colorado</STRONG><BR>
This presentation will demonstrate an alternative approach to strictly whole-language. The model is based on a U.S. Department of Education-validated program designed to build and maintain basic skills through setting high expectation, curricula, slicing and one-minute practice sessions. It is for those who believe that practice and over-learning still have a place in skill building.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> steve ogle, del valle isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>195.  High Schools That Work -- A Catalyst for Change</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mezzanine 6</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Tom Harvey [409-283-3714], Carol Moffett & Pam Risinger, Woodville ISD</STRONG><BR>
A presentation of how the key practices of "High Schools That Work" have changed a Texas high school.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> donald pinson, northside isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>196.  Technological Education Addressing Multi-Level Students</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Red River/Neches</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Elaine Smith [409-764-5500], Bills Sands & Jami Bevans, College Station ISD</STRONG><BR>
Our presentation will train participants to develop interdisciplinary units including English, Science, Social Studies, Math and Art. Incorporation of various multimedia techniques will be demonstrated. Student scheduling to enable interdisciplinary success and to address individual student needs will be discussed.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> gene stokes, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>197.  Do You Want Your Kids Living With You Forever?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Cedar</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Don Travis [409-838-5555] & John Fluth, Education Service Center, Region V, Beaumont; Brenda Thames, Beaumont ISD</STRONG><BR>
Are you scared that you will graduate students who are unemployable? Experts in the field will tell you how you can use local employers to teach classes in the workplace so that students will graduate with "the skills required to be hired."<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> carolyn moore, texarkana</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>198.  Economic Realities: Preparing Students Today for Life Tomorrow</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Lone Star</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Mary Perry [512-251-5412], Bobby West, Jerry Ingham & Ernie Laurence, Hutto ISD</STRONG><BR>
Students often leave high school with all the content information they need to be successful in subsequent phases of their lives; however, many leave without any concept of imminent financial realities. This session focuses on Transitional Economics, a student-centered course that sends students into the community to gather data and plan for their futures.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> romeo rodriguez, laredo isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>199.  TAAS Interpretations and Accountability</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Ballroom C</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Marvin Veselka [512-929-1313] & Susan Barnes, ESC Region XIII, Austin</STRONG><BR>
This presentation will focus on state accountability updates, TAAS data analysis and TAAS interpretation. Emphasis will be placed on clear understandings of the TAAS system and the accountability policies.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> carolyn hood, round rock isd</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>200.  Digital Portfolios for Arts Students (Supported By a Grant From the Christa McAuliffe Foundation)</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Sabine</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>Nancy Mack [214-720-7300], Dallas ISD</STRONG><BR>
The use of interactive multimedia tools at the secondary level to create digital portfolios for performing and visual arts students will be presented.<BR>
<STRONG><i>facilitator:</i> kay todd, sweetwater isd</STRONG><BR>

