<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>TASC Constitution</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image57.gif" WIDTH="306" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<A HREF="tascmis.html"><IMG SRC="image104.gif" WIDTH="198" HEIGHT="44" 
ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="0"><BR>
</A></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>TEXAS ASSOCIATION OF STUDENT COUNCILS CONSTITUTION</CENTER>
</H3>
<H4><CENTER>PREAMBLE</CENTER>
</H4>
We, the member schools of the Texas Association of Student Councils, sponsored
by the Texas Association of Secondary School Principals, in order to instill
American ideals and develop citizenship among the youth of today, to encourage
student councils in the secondary schools of this State, do organize ourselves
to operate under the following constitution. 
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE I - NAME</CENTER>
</H4>
The name of this organization shall be the Texas Association of Student
Councils. 
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE II - MEMBERSHIP</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. The Charter Members: The Junior and Senior High Schools sending
delegates to the meeting called for April, 1937, at Highland Park High School,
Dallas, for the purpose of forming a State Organization, shall be recognized
as Charter Members of the Texas Association of Student Councils.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 2.</B> Any Junior High/Middle School or Senior High School, public,
parochial, or private, in the State of Texas, may become a member of this
organization, provided it pays the approved annual membership fees. 
<UL>
<LI>A. State and district membership dues shall be determined by the TASC
Board of Directors. 
<LI>B. State and district membership fees shall be paid to the state association.
<LI>C. Dues will be rebated by the state and forwarded to the district at
least twice a year (September and January). 
<LI>D. State and district participation is limited to paid members. 
</UL>
</UL>
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE III - OFFICERS</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. Student Officers of the Organization shall be: 
<UL>
<LI>A. Those elected by the official student delegates attending the Annual
TASC Conference 
  <OL>
  <LI>a President, 
  <LI>a Vice-President, 
  <LI>a Parliamentarian, 
  <LI>a Secretary. 
  </OL>
<LI>B. The Host School shall be selected two years in advance by the Executive
Director. 
<LI>C. The four student officers currently serving the Association shall
be voting members of the State Board of Directors. 
</UL>
<B>Section 2.</B> Also: 
<UL>
<LI>A. The person serving as State Executive Director of the TASSP shall
serve as the State Executive Director of the TASC. Said State Executive
Director shall be responsible to the TASC Board of Directors in all TASC
Work. 
<LI>B. A Board of Directors consisting of: 
  <OL>
  <LI>The Executive Director, 
  <LI>one student and the head sponsor of each of four officer schools currently
serving the Association, 
  <LI>three Senior High Faculty head sponsors, one elected during the meeting
of the sponsors each year to serve for a term of three years, 
  <LI>three members of the Texas Association of Secondary School Principals
to represent them on the Board of Directors of the Texas Association of
Student Councils, 
  <LI>two Junior High/Middle School faculty head sponsors, one to be elected
by Junior High/Middle School sponsors at a Junior High Regional Conference
each year that a three year term is completed, and 
  <LI>the sponsor of the Immediate Past President School . All sponsor elections
shall be by majority vote. The Principal of the school shall designate the
head sponsor of the student council. 
  </OL>
<LI>C. If an elected sponsor's school is elected to an officer school position,
the elected sponsor's position shall become vacant for the time the sponsor
serves on the Board of Directors as an officer sponsor. The Board of Directors
shall fill the vacant position. 
</UL>
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE IV - ELECTIONS</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. Qualifications for Candidate Schools: 
<UL>
<LI>A. Schools rather than individuals shall be candidates. Each Officer
School shall choose the student to fill the office. 
<LI>B. A Candidate School shall have been a member of the Association the
school year preceding its nomination and shall be a current member. 
<LI>C. A school may hold only one office at a time. Two full years shall
have elapsed between elections before a school may hold office again. 
<LI>D. A Candidate School shall file, with the Executive Director, a letter
of permission to run for an office from the Principal of that school. This
letter shall be submitted to the Executive Director at least sixty (60)
days prior to the opening date of the conference. 
</UL>
<B>Section 2.</B> Campaign Procedure: 
<UL>
<LI>A. Each Candidate School shall be responsible for securing from the
Executive Director a list of regulations governing the type and use of campaign
materials. 
<LI>B. A political rally, at which the Vice-President shall preside, shall
be held prior to the voting session. 
<LI>C. Each Candidate School shall be allotted only three minutes, during
which time nominating, seconding, and acceptance speeches may be made. 
</UL>
<B>Section 3.</B> Election Procedures: 
<UL>
<LI>A. Election of officer schools shall be held prior to the last general
session of the Annual Conference. 
<LI>B. Voting shall be by secret ballot, each member school having the same
number of votes as official student delegates present at the conference,
not to exceed five. Foreign or exchange students are not official delegates.
<LI>C. Preceding the opening of the last general session at the conference,
the run-off ballots, if needed, shall be marked, collected by the Vice-President
and given to the Chairman of the Tabulating Committee. The school having
a majority shall be declared the winner. 
<LI>D. Ballots shall be tabulated before the end of the last general session
of the conference and results of the election announced by the President.
<LI>E. All newly elected officer schools shall assume their responsibilities
at the conclusion of the last general session of the Annual Conference.
</UL>
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE V - CONFERENCES</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. The Annual Conference of the Association shall be held in the
Spring Term of each school year. The date of the meeting shall be set by
the Host School and State Executive Director. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 2.</B> 
<UL>
<LI>A. Attendance - The Board of Directors shall determine the number of
delegates each school may bring to the Annual Conference. 
<LI>B. Completed registration forms and fees shall be mailed to the State
Executive Secretary of the Association prior to the opening of the Annual
Conference. 
</UL>
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE VI - SPONSORS</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. The Association shall also include an organization of the Sponsors
from the member schools. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 2.</B> The Sponsors of the member schools represented at the
Annual Conference shall hold at least one scheduled meeting during the Conference.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 3.</B> The Chairman of this group shall be the State Executive
Director of the Association, who shall appoint a Secretary for the meeting.
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE VII- AMENDMENTS</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. Amendments may be proposed by any member school of the Association,
or by two-thirds vote of the State Board of Directors. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 2.</B> Amendments signed by the Principal and Sponsor shall be
submitted in writing to the State Executive Director of the Association
not later than March 1, each year, for consideration by the State Board
of Directors in regular session. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 3.</B> All proposed amendments shall be submitted in writing
(by the State Executive Director) to all member schools. Each school shall
vote by mail. Each ballot shall be signed by the Principal and Sponsor.
A majority of all votes cast shall be required for ratification. 
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE VIII - TASSP SPONSORSHIP</CENTER>
</H4>
The sponsorship of TASSP is given with the provision that any major action
or proposed action that changes the orderly operations, threatens the survival
or changes the balance of governing power may be referred by the President
of TASSP or the Executive Director to the TASSP Board of Directors for approval
prior to consideration by the TASC Board of Directors. 
<H4><CENTER>ARTICLE IX - RATIFICATION OF THE CONSTITUTION</CENTER>
</H4>
This constitution shall be presented by mail to the Principal of each member
school for ratification. Each ballot shall contain the signature of the
Principal and the Sponsor. The Constitution Committee shall canvass the
votes. Two-thirds of all votes cast shall be required for ratification.
If ratified, this constitution shall become effective immediately. 
<H4><CENTER>BY-LAWS</CENTER>
</H4>
Section 1. The President shall appoint a Credentials Committee composed
of the Vice-President, four students, each from a different school, and
one sponsor. This committee shall review the list of schools certified by
the State Executive Director and the Vice-President and prepare a list of
eligible candidate schools to be voted on at the Conference. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 2.</B> In the event no school signs up for an office, the President
shall appoint a Nominating Committee composed of five students, each from
a different school, and one sponsor. This committee shall recruit two (2)
or more schools for that office. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 3.</B> The President shall appoint a Tabulating Committee composed
of the Secretary, four students, each from a different school, and one sponsor.
This committee shall receive the marked ballots from the Vice-President,
tabulate the results, and present them to the President prior to the close
of the Annual Conference. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 4.</B> The Association may charge a Conference Registration Fee,
which shall be used to defray the expenses of the Conference. This fee shall
be collected from each delegate prior to the date set by the Executive Committee.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 5.</B> The amount of the registration fee may vary from year
to year with relation to the total expense of the Conference. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 6.</B> Duties of the student officers, State Executive Director,
Host School, Host Principal and State Board of Directors. 
<UL>
<LI>A. In conjunction with his or her sponsor, the President shall: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Give leadership to the Association throughout his term of office,
  <LI>Appoint committees; 
  <LI>Attend meetings of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Make arrangements for discussion groups at the Annual Conference suitable
for Senior High School students; 
  <LI>Give keynote address at the opening session of the Annual Conference;
and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>B. In conjunction with his or her sponsor, the Vice-President shall:
  <OL>
  <LI>Execute the duties of the President in case of the latter's absence;
  <LI>Attend the meetings of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Act as chairman of the Credentials Committee; 
  <LI>Act as Master of Ceremonies during the social sessions and political
rally at the Annual conference; 
  <LI>Spearhead state-wide projects accepted by the State Board of Directors;
  <LI>Provide, distribute, and collect ballots for the election of officers
at the Annual Conference; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>C. In conjunction with his or her sponsor, the Secretary shall: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Attend meetings of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Read minutes of the previous business meeting; 
  <LI>Furnish the State Executive Director with a copy of the minutes for
permanent filing; 
  <LI>Make arrangements for all activities at the Annual Conference suitable
for Senior High School delegates; 
  <LI>Act as Chairman of the Tabulating Committee; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>D. In conjunction with his or her sponsor, the Parliamentarian shall:
  <OL>
  <LI>Act as the final authority on questions of parliamentary procedure
at the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Serve as time-keeper at the political rally; 
  <LI>Promote and supervise the scrapbook contest; 
  <LI>Preside at the display of scrapbooks and be responsible for the judging
of same; 
  <LI>Attend meetings of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Furnish material and information on parliamentary procedure to member
schools upon request; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>E. The Host School shall: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Serve as Host School for the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Provide entertainment during the Annual Conference suitable for Senior
High School delegates; 
  <LI>Provide facilities for all activities at the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Have Sponsor and President Student serve as advisors to State Board
of Directors; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>F. Duties of the Principal of the Host School: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Coordinate school and community resources for the success of the Annual
Conference; 
  <LI>Bring greetings to the Conference delegates; 
  <LI>Attend meetings of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Approve facilities to be used at the Annual Conference; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties necessary to a successful completion of the Conference.
  </OL>
<LI>G. Duties of the State Executive Director: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Preside at all meetings of the State Board of Directors. Meetings
of the State Board of Directors will be called as follows: One meeting will
be called in the Fall and one meeting will be called at the Annual Conference.
A meeting must be called within 30 days at the request of any ten (10) members
of the State Board of Directors. 
  <LI>Secure platform speakers for the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Aid the President with all general sessions of the Annual Conference;
  <LI>Serve as Chairman of all business sessions of the Sponsors; 
  <LI>Receive membership fees and issue membership certificates; 
  <LI>Administer the funds of the Association with the consent of the State
Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Furnish the State Board of Directors a monthly report of income and
disbursements. An annual Financial Report will be prepared by the State
Executive Director audited by not less than three (3) Sponsors and Principals
of the State Board of Directors and presented to the State Board of Directors
at the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Collect materials of benefit to student councils and make them available
to all member schools upon request; 
  <LI>Encourage more schools to become active in the Association; 
  <LI>Organize summer workshops; 
  <LI>Prepare and distribute a minimum of four newsletters each year; 
  <LI>Select delegates to attend the Annual Conference of the National Association
of Student Councils with approval of the State Board of Directors; 
  <LI>Answer correspondence pertaining to student council activities in
Texas; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
<LI>H. Duties of the State Board of Directors: 
  <OL>
  <LI>Appoint persons to fill unexpired terms of the State Board of Directors
members; 
  <LI>Review and study the Annual Audit Report presented by the State Executive
Director; 
  <LI>Determine the date and place for the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Approve a program for the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Determine the registration fee for the Annual Conference; 
  <LI>Serve as a planning board of the promotion, growth, and continued
success of the Association; 
  <LI>Serve in an advisory capacity to the State Executive Director in all
matters pertaining to that office; and 
  <LI>Perform other duties as required. 
  </OL>
</UL>
<B>Section 7.</B> The By-Laws may be amended in the same manner as the Constitution.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Section 8.</B> &quot;Call to Order&quot;, published by the National Association
of Student Councils, 1904 Association Drive, Reston, Virginia 22091, shall
be the standard parliamentary text of the Association and shall govern all
cases not otherwise covered in the Constitution and By-Laws. <BR>
<BR>
<P><CENTER>Back to <A HREF="tascmis.html">About TASC.</A></CENTER>
</BODY>
