<H2>UP WITH KIDS</H2>
<H2>OLTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>

<p>Once upon a time in a town far away lived 53 student council members who believed they could make a difference in this world.  But what could 53 teenagers do, they asked, even with the help of a doddering old sponsor who cringes at the mention of another fund-raiser?  Happy, the president, reminded the merry band of their purpose - to foster well-rounded individuals.  Grumpy asked where they could start.  Lets start where we can really make a difference, yelled Dopey, in grade school.

<p>So a program called UP WITH KIDS was given birth, and it started in June.  Student council members spent one day each week for two months transporting 37 elementary children to exciting places for one hour.  The children studied the world of nature, watched The Bear, learned to do the Cotton-eyed Joe, met a real cowboy and read stories like Pecos Bill.  They were taken to a scientific world with bunsen burners and heard about Washington Carver; heard Indian stories read by someone in an Indian suit; and spent an afternoon with very quiet critters (baby rattlesnakes).  The summer reading program came to a close with a trip to Kidsville in Plainview, an appropriate culmination for a profitable two months.

<p>However, these energetic members did not want to stop here.  August rolled around, and they were just getting started.  Sleepy wanted to have a Little Buckaroo Rodeo (a rodeo arena is located north of town).  But well have to find goats and calves and stuff like that, Sneezy grimaced.  And they did!  Events were stick horse races, boot races, water bucket races, goat sacking, goat tying, goat dressing, two legged sack races, egg pitching and potato races.  Children 3-18 years could enter.  Drug free entertainment was stressed.  Following an evening of dust and true grit, the main street was blocked off and a street dance was held for children of all ages.  August gave way to Fall.

<p>In September, the Olton High School student council began their Buckle Up drive.  Wanting to stress safety and boost self-esteem, council members used the slogan, Buckle Me Up, Im Important.  Buttons with this message and coloring books were distributed.

<p>In October, Red Ribbon Week activities included a poster contest.  The winners of the contest were announced at a football game.  What would October be without Halloween? asked Doc.  The members worked weeks on safety sacks for each of the 445 elementary school students.  Candy and trick-or-treat tips were included.  A Halloween Carnival stressing drug-free entertainment boasted 15 booths, represented by eight different organizations, including a dunking booth, marriage booth, and fortune tellers tent to name a few.

<p>Christmas brought joy as well as sorrow.  Council members were told that 17 children might not have a visit from Santa.  Working diligently, the members made sure that each child would receive at least one new toy, coat, and food for Christmas dinner.

<p>The year is drawing to a close, and already the council is looking for new worlds to conquer, new roads to travel, and as in every fairy tale, they continue to hope that everyone can live happily ever after.
</DOC>
<DOC>
