<heading>educational</heading>

<H2>Aliefworld - Celebrating our Differences</H2>

1992-93 Top Ten Project - by the Student Council of
 Alief Hastings High School, Houston

<H3>Purpose:</H3>
<p>The Alief school district has a very unique community; students in our district represent over 70 difference nationalities.  This could be seen as a problem of communication and understanding among the different cultures, but we look on it as a unique opportunity to learn from each other and experience new things.  Aliefworld was a multicultural fair designed to educate us about each other.

<p>Description:
<P>We knew from the start it would take more than just the members of the council to produce a fair that everyone would enjoy and benefit from.  The first of the other groups enlisted were the language clubs at school.  The French and Spanish clubs, and the ESL group immediately started developing their booths and recruiting local groups to participate.  Many of the student council members and even some of our faculty are members of local ethnic organizations, which were asked to volunteer time and effort to present a good show for our community.

<p>We got a lot of help in advertising the event.  The school district allowed us to use the district mail to send flyers home to all the families of Hastings students.  A teacher who has a weekend talk show on an Indo-Pakistani radio station advertised the fair, and an advertisement was also placed in a local Chinese newspaper.

<p>May 1st finally arrived and council members spent the last period of the day setting up the booth areas in the cafeteria.  There were booths operated by students representing French, Hispanic, Indo-Pakistani, Chinese, Vietnamese, and African-American cultures.  There was even an American booth that included a frisbee, lawn chairs, coke bottles, and old 45s for musical entertainment.  Hari Krishnas from the community also set up a booth with literature about their group, and provided much discussion during the evening.  Many booths had video tapes playing that showed their country and some of the local traditions and celebrations.  Other booths played ethnic music.  The booth displays included flags, photographs, artwork, clothing, and even, in some cases, food.  Both the Vietnamese and Indo-Pakistani booths had a wide variety of food to sample.  But that wasnt the only food available.  A Mexican restaurant sold tacos and tamales.  The Bear Backers, our parent sports sponsor group, sold hot-dogs and cokes.  A local supermarket chain, Fiesta, brought a pianta and handed out balloons to the children; and a Hispanic radio station provided music for the cafeteria area and handed out bumper stickers and buttons.

<p>When people werent browsing around the booths, they could listen to a medley of multicultural songs sung by our Hastings choir, or watch a Kung Fu demonstration provided by a local academy.  From 3:30 p.m. to 8:00 p.m., a variety of presentations were made in our theater.  Members of the drama class ran the lights and music for each of the shows.  The shows included dancing, singing, and fashion shows.  There were Chinese, Vietnamese, Mexican, Colombian, Argentinean, Honduran, Czech, and Dutch dancers, and of course music to accompany all of them.  Fashions from ancient to modern Chinese attire were modeled, as well as a wide variety of Indian and Pakistani outfits.

<p>The fair was an incredible success.  At times all the seats in the theater were filled and all the food sold out.  There were no security problems.  Everyone got along wonderfully and learned a lot about other cultures that night.  We even had a visit from Harris County State Representative Talmadge Heflin.  The council had invited him to the fair, and he gladly accepted, viewing it as a unique opportunity to see many of the different people he represents in District 149.  The fair was enjoyed so much that in May of this year we are planning the Second Annual Multicultural Fair.
</DOC>
<DOC>
