</DOCHDR>
<H3>HUNTSVILLE HIGH SCHOOL</h3>


Name of Project:  "Election Awareness Campaign"<p>

Purpose:  During the month of October and the first several days of November, the HHS Student Council sponsored an election awareness campaign to not only make the student body more aware of the issues in the Presidential Campaign, but to also encourage students to take active control of their future and help reduce voter apathy.<p>

Description:  In cooperation with TIME/AASA (American Association of School Administrators), the Council planned and executed a project to encourage imaginative leadership and to expand students thinking about citizenship education and the importance of exercising the right to vote in a democracy.<p>
It was the Council's intent to engage as many adults, faculty and parents, as possible as well as draw from all of the diverse elements in our student body.  By offering a variety of activities, we hoped to provide something for everyone and thus get our entire school and our community involved.<p>

Our activities included the following:
<OL>
<li> Careful research of the program offered by the National Student/Parent Mock Election Committee
<li>An aggressive advertising campaign to attract students, faculty, administrators and our community into our project.
<li>A student debate in which two of our seniors spoke for the two national parties and answered questions for over an hour that were asked by a panel of adults consisting of two school board members and two faculty members.  The audience for this debate was made up of over 350 students from all four classes, clubs, school organizations, and volunteers,  Parents and representatives from both political parties in our community also attended.
<li> Our second event was to participate in the National Student/Parent Mock Election.  Council set up four polling places in the school; voters had to show proper student identification, have their name checked on class rolls and then sign prior to casting their vote.  These votes were tallied and called in to the Texas "Election Headquarters" at 4:45 p.m. on Thursday, November 3, 1988.
<li>  Our third and final activity was to hold a Mock Electoral Election on Monday, November 7th.  Again, we had several hundred students participating as members of the Electoral College.  The students were divided into states based on the same percentage as are on the Electoral College.  Student Council members acted as the chairperson for each state.  Our city Mayor, Jane Monday, gave the Keynote Address followed by student speeches on behalf of the two national candidates.  We allowed the students time to rally in support of their party using student council "whips."  It was at this event that we had the traditional roll call of states.
<li>To ensure actual learning was taking place, Council encouraged History and English teachers to give assignments that allowed students library time to research the issues that were being debated by the two national candidates and by our student candidates.  Following the debate, all of the participants were asked to fill-out a questionnaire and evaluate the responses of the debaters.  As a result, students were informed, and had opinions based on critical thinking and not on opinion or prejudice.
<li> The Council had earlier supported a voter registration campaign directed at our eighteen year olds and then provided a realistic voting situation for the entire student body.  We also published a newspaper of voter information.
</OL>
The culmination activity was to package everything we had done and submit it to Time Magazine and The American Association of School Administrators.  As a direct result of what the council had organized and because of the wide-ranging participation of our students and community our school district became eligible for national recognition.  Once our district Superintendent was able to substantiate that all of our schools had held election activities, Huntsville Independent School District was acknowledged as one of eight school districts in the nation to receive the Time Magazine/AASA Award.<p>

On March 16, 1989, our school district passed a resolution to recognize the "...members of the Huntsville High School Student Council...(for distinguishing)... themselves by developing political awareness among the HHS student body which brought about national recognition. . . "




</DOC>
