<heading>educational</heading>

<H2>STEPHEN F. AUSTIN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1715 West First Street, Austin, TX  78703

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Real World Approach to Student Elections</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3><OL>
	<LI>Make students more prepared for participating in the election process of 	the real world.
	<LI>Make students more aware of the candidates running for student offices 	and their platforms.
	<LI>Get more numbers of students interested and actively involved in the 	campaign-election process.
	<LI>Make student elections simulate real political elections.
	<LI>Teach students that voting is a privilege and a responsibility.
	<LI>Make candidates more prepared to run well-organized campaigns and 	better able to address their peers and act as student leaders.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>  
<p>The Austin High Spring Elections project, in which student council and senior class officers for the following year are selected, is composed of six main parts.

<H3>I.  INTRODUCTORY MEETING/PACKET</H3>
<p>After students sign up to run for office, they attend an introductory meeting in which campaign and election activities are introduced and students are given candidate packets composed of: 1) AHS elections code; 2) AHS elections philosophy; 3) student application to run for office; 4) question for personal statement response; 5) faculty petition to be completed; 6) pledge sheet; 7) elections timeline; 8) photo arrangement information.  Items number 3, 4, 5, and 6 must be completed before a student is considered as a candidate.  The video concept of the elections process is also introduced at this time.

<H3>II.  CANDIDATE WORKSHOPS</H3>
<p>A series of workshops are offered to candidates (and their campaign managers) to train them on campaigning techniques and to prepare them for making their video advertisement and/or appearing in the televised Presidential Broadcast.  The six workshops are held after school and run approximately 30 minutes.  Their topics are:  1) journalists role in elections, elections schedule and voting procedure, public relations, media introduction (how to make a video advertisement); 2) AHS media center tour; 3) introduction to field production-video making; 4) campaign ethics, planning video advertisements, signs, handouts, etc., group work with past candidates; 5) speechmaking, how to talk in front of a camera (an instructional film is shown), discussion and viewing of past advertisements and broadcasts (what works, what doesnt); 6) Presidential candidates workshop:  discussion of schedule of live broadcast, presidential candidates are given general idea of questions to be asked during the broadcast.

<H3>III.  NEWSPAPER COVERAGE</H3>
<p>During workshop #1, candidates are given optional questions to which they can write responses that will be published in the issue of the AHS newspaper the Maroon that comes out just prior to when video advertisements are shown.  They can also submit an activity list and have their picture taken; both of which will be published with their written response.  A press kit with election information is also prepared for the Austin American Statesman and the West Austin News.  The 1989 election, the first year this project was started, was also featured on a local television station.

<H3>IV.  SHOWING OF CANDIDATE VIDEOS/VOTE! SEGMENTS</H3>
<p>All candidates are invited to make a 1 to 1 1/2 minute video advertisement, all of which are shown in the cafeteria for three days prior to Election Day.  The videos allow students to get to know the candidates, find out about their ideas, and decide if they think the candidates would make good student leaders.  Videos can be made and edited with school equipment and with the assistance of the media club at no cost to the candidates.  Segments in which local personalities, politicians, and current student leaders encourage students to vote and get involved are shown along with candidates videos.  These Vote! segments are designed to get students attention and to stress the importance of voting; they also explain the voting process for students who have not previously voted.

<H3>V.  LIVE BROADCAST OF PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES</H3>
<p>On the day immediately before Election Day, a live broadcast of presidential candidates for Senior Class Officer and Student Council Officer is shown by means of the schools closed circuit television system.  The broadcast, which is filmed in the schools media center, is shown during class time and runs approximately twenty minutes.  The broadcast consists of a live question and answer session between three selected journalism students and the candidates.  Each candidate gets to answer a question first; journalism students can ask follow-up questions in which candidates can give a rebuttal.  The current student council president acts as a mediator and timekeeper.  The broadcast is organized and run totally by students from student council and the media club.

<H3>VI.  ELECTION DAY/VOTING BOOTHS</H3>
<p>Last year, the Student Council, along with other school organizations, raised money to purchase a set of voting booths.  The booths are open from 7:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. on Election Day and are monitored by a certified elections judge.  All city voting codes are followed.  The sign in tables are monitored by parent volunteers.  Students present a school ID/student number and take a ballot and help sheet from the table.  They proceed to a voting booth, make their selections, and place the ballot in an official ballot box.  It is up to the students to take the incentive to come and vote, however, teachers have the option of taking their students to the cafeteria to vote during class.  Winners and/or run-off candidates are announced the following day.

<H3>DESCRIPTION OF INVOLVEMENT WITH:</H3>
<p>A) STUDENT COUNCIL MEMBERS:  Representatives work to publicize their classes; the Election Committee coordinates times for candidates to make their videos and helps to organize the Live Broadcast, the Vote! segments, and the  workshops.
<p>B) OTHER STUDENTS:  The entire student body has a role in this project.  They watch the videos and broadcast, read about candidates in the newspaper and vote in the election.  Many students appear in candidate videos; past candidates work with current candidates.
<p>C) OTHER ORGANIZATIONS:  The media club helps film and edit videos and tapes the broadcast; journalism students appear in the broadcast and write about elections; other student leaders are asked to appear in Vote! segments (i.e. cheerleaders, senior boys, NHS President).
<p>D) FACULTY:  Speech and media teachers work with candidates; all teachers are invited to take their classes to vote as a learning experience; broadcast is shown during class.
<p>E) COMMUNITY:  Key figures of the community appear in Vote! segments; community is made aware of this project through newspaper articles/news coverage.  This year we also rented our voting booths to a local junior high for their student elections.
</DOC>
<DOC>
