<heading>fund-raising</heading>

<H2>Name of Project:  Seniors Serve Supper</H2>

<H3>Purpose and Objectives:  To raise money for Project Graduation</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Solicitation of funds from the community to go toward expenses of the annual 
 Project Graduation by people earning their money, not just asking for it.
<LI>To put an elegant event for seniors to showcase their talent and skills.
<LI>To facilitate more unity between the class government and the student council.
<LI>To create an annual event which will be supported by the community for years.

<H3>Description of Activities</H3>

<p>This year the WHS student council in partnership with the senior class sponsored Seniors Serve Supper.  This was a fund-raiser designed to bring in general funds for the student council, and money to be put toward Project Graduation, a safe-haven lock-in for seniors and their guests on graduation night.  Seniors Serve Supper grew from an idea presented in a five minute brainstorm session to an elaborate, detailed venture.  We wanted to hold a formal event that was totally student run.  The evening would include:  valet parking, coat checkers, matre d, waiters, baby sitters, memory makers (explained later), dinner music, and a talent show.  All these positions were filled by seniors.

<p>In several assemblies, the senior class was addressed by the executive committee on the status of the project.  As an incentive for participation, seniors will be given play money at the Vegas style tables at Project Graduation.  This play money will later be used to bid on prizes such as TVs, VCRs, etc.

<p>In the preliminary planning stages, the student council teamed up with senior parents to put tentative plans on paper, form committees, and delegate responsibilities.  The first task was to reserve the Civic Center for the event.  After that was accomplished, the details of the project were attended to.

<p>The public relations subcommittee was responsible for interaction with the press, sending out invitations to guests, and thank you letters.  Approximately three hundred invitations were sent through the mail, and over three hundred tickets were sold, at twenty dollars apiece.  After the event, thank you letters went out to all the guests, the Wharton-Journal-Spectator, WISD, and the parents involved.

<p>The valet parking subcommittee was responsible for devising a plan to park cars at the Civic Center, security during the event, and retrieving the cars after the supper.  This committee devised a system where parking slots were numbered, and numbered tags were put on keys, and given to the owners for receipt.

<p>The baby-sitting subcommittee was responsible for taking care of the guest children during the night.  Each member was instructed to bring a toy for the young ones to play with.  Also, McDonalds furnished Happy Meals at one dollar apiece for the children.

<p>The waiters/waitresses subcommittee was responsible for serving the guests the entree, refilling their drinks, and then serving dessert.  Each waiter or waitress was instructed to wear a white button-down shirt, black pants or skirt, and a bow tie.  The coat checkers were included in this committee also.  The matre d was a parent who met each guest at the door and introduced them to their waiter/waitress.  Memory makers also roamed the crowd with Polaroid cameras offering to take pictures for two dollars each.

<p>The talent show subcommittee was responsible for organizing student talent, holding rehearsals, and presenting a talent show after the meal.  This group included singers, pianists, guitarists, standup comedians, and dancers.

<p>The cutlery subcommittee had the responsibility of contacting senior mothers and soliciting the use of their dishes for use during dinner, ensuring the safety of those dishes, and returning the dishes afterwards.  Each donor was honored with a small card on the table that held their place setting.

<p>Additionally, the executive committee undertook several responsibilities.  Besides securing the Civic Center, they solicited a sound system for the show, oversaw the individual subcommittees, and collected all the money.  A few last minute ideas proved useful, too.  Street Musicians, talent show acts  improvising, lined the exits as the guests left, with hats in hand, of course.  The memory makers idea was also implemented the day before the supper.

<p>In one night we raised $6001 pure profit.  The majority came from ticket sales, but $1200 was made in tips.  Valet attendants, coat checkers, waiters/waitresses, and even talent show acts were tipped (they threw money at us).  Students were further pushed to ham it up because for every dollar they received, they got $1000 play money to use at Project Graduation.

<H3>Description of Involvement:</H3>

<p>The council--Student Council was integral in the leadership and organizational roles of Seniors Serve Supper.  For each subcommittee, a student council member was  teamed with a parent as a co-chair.  This student acted as a liaison between the parent and the student members of the subcommittee, and had responsibilities to the council to ensure the success of his/her task.

<p>Other students--Other students were the workers in this venture.  Not that StuCo members did not act as workers in their subcommittees, but the other students (mainly seniors) made the night successful.  They acted as the waiters/waitresses, valet attendants, etc.  They encouraged their parents to attend and spread the word.

<p>Other Organizations--Other student organizations as well as community organizations were integral parts in this venture.  Lion and Rotary Clubs both sponsored Seniors Serve Supper, and many of the members of both clubs attended as a result of their adoption of the project.

<p>Faculty--Teachers aided in the fund-raisers, too.  They were asked to inform their seventh period class of the event every day for a week and encourage them to attend.  Our principal allowed us to have assemblies as needed.

<p>Community--The community was the biggest piece of the puzzle in the success of Seniors Serve Supper.  They graciously attended our production and generously rewarded us  for our hard work and preparation.  Included here are the senior parents who took final responsibility for the tasks of the subcommittees.  Each parent who chaired a subcommittee helped make the evening possible through their resources, hard work, and perseverance.

</DOC>
