<heading>fund-raising</heading>

<H2>IMAGE
Fall Fashion Show
...by the Student Council of Kingwood High School</H2>

<H3>Name of Project:	Image--Fall Fashion Show</H3>

<H3>Purpose:</H3>
<p>To create a fresh project which incorporates a variety of students from all areas of our high school and to increase involvement with our immediate community in order to begin the school year with a high level of student and community enthusiasm for our education, activities, and school spirit.

<H3>Description</H3>

<p>For the first year in Kingwood High Schools history we decided to attempt to create a new fund-raiser for our school which would allow many different types of students to be involved who normally may not participate in school functions.  We decided that a fashion show would be an excellent way to achieve this goal.  In order to organize the production we first received permission from our administration and then researched the response of area retailers to our proposed project.  The response was overwhelming and we lined up the retailers who were interested in participating.  The next step was to hold auditions for models.  We publicized auditions and received a turnout of 72 students who wanted to participate.  Because of the vast variety of students who wanted to participate, we decided to allow all of the students to be models and we did not cut anyone who auditioned.  We assigned each model to a store and they were then fitted for the clothes they were to wear in the show.  Commentary for the outfits was written by the master and mistress of ceremonies and we held rehearsals in which the set design and runway choreography of the models were designed by student council members.  Complimentary tickets were given to participating retailers and all other tickets were sold for three dollars during lunch and at the door.  The show was held on a weeknight and the enthusiasm was outstanding!  Most of the retailers were extremely impressed with the outcome and volunteered their merchandise and services for next year and every student enjoyed their time to shine immensely!

<H3>Involvement</H3>

<p>We would first like to say that this project involved numerous people who make up the many different aspects of our school and community and it was a pleasure to see this project succeed.

<p>Student Council members:  Our members participated through the production and running of the show by being dressers and taking care of the clothes backstage, choreographing, constructing the set and runways, publicizing, attending and assisting at the stores for fittings, relations with the stores, running the house, and serving as commentators and technicians.  Approximately 30 student council members actively participated.

<p>Other Students:  Most importantly, SEVENTY-TWO students (who were not a part of student council) performed on stage as models in the program.  The schools Audio-Visual Department and AV Club helped to run and coordinate lighting and sound for the show.  Just about every organization was represented in our production from the football team to Future Farmers of America.

<p>Faculty:  The principal, teachers, and administration gave us the liberty to try this new and rather risky project (we dealt with over $38,000 worth of merchandise and twenty area retailers who were putting their full trust in us) and they encouraged students to participate.  They also assisted the night of the show by hiring and being security guards, helped with the clothing backstage, and were given jobs in the house.  Approximately seven faculty members participated.

<p>Community:  The participation from the community was overwhelming!  Over TWENTY area retailers participated in the project, they lent us over $38,000 in merchandise excluding the clothing racks and garment bags which they also loaned to us.  An area hair salon volunteered to style EACH models hair for the show and to also do all their make-up.  The salon brought their entire staff and supplies and they set up in a room to the side of the stage.  In addition to providing their services the night of the performance, the salon also provided free haircuts to all of the models the week prior to the show.  Students mothers also helped transport clothes for the show.  The community also helped publicize the event.  Approximately 100 members of the community actively participated.

<p>All proceeds from the show (approximately $500) went to our schools Jack C. Byrd Scholarship Fund which honors students in the senior class.  This project was extremely time consuming and was a large project for our council to take on considering the number of people involved, the responsibility to take care of the merchandise, and this was the first year this type of fund-raiser was attempted.  We handled the task professionally and with maturity and expect even greater participation from the students and community and increased attendance to show next year.  We would like to stress that our objective for this project was not only to raise money, but also to begin the school year with a high level of community backing for our school activities and awareness of our education and also to start off with a high level of school spirit.  These goals were most definitely accomplished!

<p>Kingwood High School expresses special thanks to Hanks High School in El Paso for sharing this idea.
</DOC>
