<H2>BOSWELL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
BOX 79160, FORT WORTH, TX  76179

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Kash for Kids Track Meet</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>After learning of some startling statistics concerning child abuse cases in Tarrant County, we felt a need to earn money to help combat this serious problem.  We decided to have a school-wide track meet and involve as many people as possible.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>Through public address announcements, posters displayed all over campus, and a school-wide handout, everyone was encouraged to enter a team.  The twelve-member coed teams were made up of six girls and six boys.  An entry fee of $2.00 per person was paid.  Each team member could enter 3 running and 2 field events or 2 running and 3 field events.  All the regular events of a track meet were included plus the 40 yard dash, 60 yard dash and softball throw.  Ribbons for 1st through 6th places were awarded in each event.  Team trophies were presented for 1st, 2nd, and 3rd place teams.

<p>To create interest in our track meet, we sold Lifesaver lollipops and Stop Child Abuse buttons during the week preceding the meet.  A billboard was displayed in Saginaw, and news coverage was provided by the Pioneer Press and the Northwest Sentinel.  A letter was mailed to all the other campuses in our district, the central administration office, and all school board members.  We appeared before the City Council of Saginaw to solicit their support and participation.  Local television and radio stations were notified.  Jars were placed in local businesses to collect donations.

<p>A total of 19 teams made up of 216 students entered the meet.  Each event was run by a faculty volunteer assisted by two Student Council members.  Faculty members also served as pickers and timers in the running events.  A total of 33 faculty members assisted in one way or another.

<p>The ribbons were donated by Coca-Cola and the trophies were donated by a local restaurant.  The mayor of Saginaw presented the ribbons and trophies.  A concession stand was manned by a community volunteer and student council members.  The announcer was also a community volunteer.

<p>Through donations, entry fees, admission charges, concessions, and lollipop and button sales  a total of $2,062.32 was raised.  A cashiers check for this amount was presented to the Tarrant County Department of Human Resources to be placed in the Kash for Kids fund.
</DOC>
