<heading>fund-raising</Heading>

<H2>WESTLAKE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4100 Westlake High Drive, Austin, TX  78746

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  The Tiny Tim Project</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3><OL>	
<LI>1.  To raise a minimum of $500 for the Brackenridge Foundation, which financially assists children who need medical care but have no means to pay for it.  These are children who cannot qualify for welfare, i.e. their parents have jobs but no insurance, etc.
<LI>2.  To increase community awareness and support of the various clubs and organizations on our campus.
<LI>3.  To unify the participating clubs and organizations for a common cause.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>The Tiny Tim Project began 42 years ago in Vineland, New Jersey.  The project started as a group of friends collecting money for a childs blood transfusion, but, over the years, has grown to be a popular Christmas activity in some eastern states.  The idea for the project was brought to the attention of the Student Council by an English teacher on our campus who is the niece of the lady who started the project in New Jersey.  The Student Council voted to adopt the project and put it into action during the 1988 Christmas season.

<p>The Tiny Tim Project preparation began in mid-October when an invitation to all clubs on campus was issued, inviting them to participate in Carol Night which was to be held on December 12, 1988.  On Carol Night each group would be assigned to carol in a particular neighborhood, going from house to house spreading Christmas cheer and asking for donations to the Brackenridge Foundation.  Eleven clubs answered the invitation and we were able to form fifteen choirs.  Approximately 200 students and 20 teachers participated.

<p>The Student Council began their organization of this project by selecting volunteers  to serve as chairmen of the committees.  The committees were Maps and Boundaries, Songbook, Publicity, Refreshments, Decorations, and Organization of Clubs.

<p>The Maps and Boundaries Committee obtained a map of the Eanes I.S.D. and divided it into sections to be assigned to the individual choirs.

<p>The Songbook Committee selected songs of both a religious and secular nature to be included in a songbook which was given to the members of each choir.  This committee also typed, xeroxed, and assembled the songbooks.

<p>The Publicity Committee had one of the biggest jobs since this was a new activity for our community, and community awareness was essential to a successful project.  The committee made posters to be hung throughout the school and the community.  They ran articles in the school, community, and city newspapers, and succeeded in reaching a local TV weatherman, who wore a T-shirt advertising our project on his show on the night of the project.  Approximately 2500 flyers were sent home with elementary school students in their report card envelopes.  Due to the hard work of this committee, most homes were aware of the Tiny Tim Project when carolers came to their doors.  Some people even called the school requesting that groups come to their neighborhoods to entertain for block parties.

<p>The Refreshments Committee had the responsibility for providing hot chocolate and cookies for the returning carolers.  The members of this committee solicited donations of the food and drinks served and of the cups and napkins used.

<p>The Decorations Committee created a holiday atmosphere in the lobby of the Fine Arts  Facility where the carolers gathered on Carol Night.

<p>Finally, the Organization Committee made sure that each choir received a folder on Carol Night which included their neighborhood map, songbooks, and an information sheet to hand to those people who were not familiar with the project and its purposes.  Each choir was also given a sealed collections can decorated with the projects logo which was used throughout the advertising campaign.

<p>On the big night, carolers met at 5:30 p.m., were given final instructions by the Student Council president, and practiced their songs for one last time.  At 6:00 p.m. everyone departed to their assigned neighborhoods and caroled until about 8:30 when they returned to the Fine Arts Facility to be warmed with hot chocolate and filled with cookies.  Donations were counted by the Student Council immediately.  Carolers could keep track on the totals by looking at a Christmas tree on which lights were turned on as each $25 was turned in.  The evening resulted in $1,100 being collected for the Brackenridge Foundation, and a great time was had by all.  Some clubs used the project as a kick-off or closing activity for their clubs Christmas party.  Several teachers enlisted students who were not members of organized clubs to form groups of their own, and the teachers sponsored them.  Next year we hope to increase student participation so that more areas can be covered.  We also will be sure to inform everyone to carry a flashlight.

<p>The culmination of the event for Student Council members was a trip to Brackenridge Childrens Hospital to present the money collected and to take a tour of the facilities where the collections will be used.  Student Council members will also appear on the Childrens Miracle Network Telethon in June.


</DOC>
