<heading>health/safety</heading>

<H2>Radiating Red Ribbon</H2>

<H2>A Top Ten Project by Taft Junior High School</H2>


<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>Our council initiates many Red Ribbon activities each year for our school.  We wanted the scope of the Red Ribbon message and involvement to radiate from many sources in our community.  Our objective was set to involve as many people as we could so that each person could use his or her own talent, resources and position to promote a drug-free environment.  The message needed to radiate from many to be effective

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>A month before Red Ribbon Week, personal visits, hand-written letters and telephone calls began.  We contacted many community leaders, individuals and organizations to help us radiate the Red Ribbon message.  We asked for specific favors, the use of special skills and talents or to perform unique jobs.

<p>Banks:  Bank presidents agreed to distribute our written messages with each bank transaction envelope throughout the week.  The 1 in. x 8 in. message was:  Taft Junior High School Student Council says: . .You can bank on a drug-free life.

<p>Grocery Store:  The grocer directed his checkers to place our 1 1/2 x 8 message, Drug-free Home, in each customers grocery bag.  The message was to be placed on doors or mail boxes.

<p>Churches:  All ministers and priests  received a hand-written letter asking them to use their influence to promote the Red Ribbon concept to their congregation, parishioners or study groups.

<p>Businesses:  Council members personally delivered red ribbons to each place of business for all employees and an invitation to participate in the Red Ribbon Finale Parade and Rally.

<p>School Organizations:  We encouraged our FHA and PAL organizations to join us in participating in the parade.  We distributed our personalized red ribbons with pins to parade spectators.

<p>City Officials:  The city gave us permission to hang hundred of red ribbons on the trees of the city park and to decorate the gazebo with red bows and garland for the rally.

<p>School Staff:  The faculty and principal worked with the council to execute a secret project that kept all junior high students in complete awe and wonderment until the final blow.  The secret project was  . . .Every 23 minutes.  Every 23 minutes of the school day, our principal announced over the public address system, Every 23 minutes someone dies because of drugs; someone just died.  One council member left the classroom after each announcement, painted his/her face white and completed the school day in complete silence.

<p>Law Enforcement:  The Taft City Police and the San Patricio sheriff arrested several of our student council members, handcuffed them and placed them in patrol cars while the unsuspecting student body watched.

<p>EMS and Funeral Home:  The local emergency medical team pretended to administer first aid to a council member who had over-dosed and a funeral home attendant along with a police officer wrapped another student in white sheets and placed her in the hearse.  Students were taken aback by the sight of what might have been.  Some were close to tears while others giggled nervously.

<p>Newspaper:  A Corpus Christi Caller-Times reporter and photographer came to our town to cover the Every 23 Minutes Project with the mock arrests and emergency team involvement.

<p>Television:  Two Corpus Christi television stations covered our Every 23 Minutes project.  Our principal, council sponsor and several student council members were interviewed.  One station televised in Spanish, the other in English.

<p>The Taft Junior High School Student Council achieved its goal of radiating the anti-drug message, but it did not merely radiate throughout our community.  Our message was seen and heard throughout South Texas.  The response of townspeople, school personnel and students was overwhelming.


</DOC>
