<heading>health/safety</heading>

<H2>S.T.A.R..S. - Students Taking All Responsibility Successfully</H2>

<H2>1993-94 Top Ten Project by the Student Council of Sam Houston High School, Arlington</H2>

<H3>Purpose:</H3>
<p>The STARS program is designed to educate elementary students about the dangers of drugs and alcohol and the need for safety awareness.  Students from Sam Houston High Schools Student Council stage skits, perform songs, and play games to relay the message that making wise decisions at a young age can result in a longer and more fulfilling life.

<H3>Description:</H3>
<p>Our Student Council has prepared a fun and interactive program which effectively communicates positive messages to young students.  Over twenty-two hundred third graders from twenty local schools have seen and participated in a fast-paced production that must not only educate, but hold their attention.  Anyone who has worked with third graders knows what an accomplishment that is.  The forty-five minute program is performed two times each week at different elementary schools in the district.

<p>STARS has been developed in its entirety by Sam Houston students who have written songs, created skits, and produced game shows that clearly present the message that being drug free is the way to be.  Part of the program includes a mock dating game called The Right Connection in which a boy from the audience is asked to choose a date from the three panelists:  one is a STAR and the other two are involved in drugs and alcohol abuse.  A skit called Dont Worry, Be Happy illustrates that a bad day cannot be made better through drug use.  Another funny and educational skit is based on the story of The Three Little Pigs.  In this version, however, two pigs go to a party instead of building their homes while the other one spends time making her home strong.  The story progresses and, as usual, ends with the message that the big, bad wolf is watching, so you better be responsible.  The third graders favorite game is called Trouble Dare, a take-off on Nickelodeons Double Dare.  It features two competing groups:  The Burnouts who were once bright but began using drugs and alcohol versus the Shining Stars who shine above the rest due to the good decisions they make.  Some of the songs include Drug Free sung to the tune of Green Acres, Drugs Arent for Me to the tune of Under the Sea from The Little Mermaid, and Just Dont Even Start to the tune of The Addams Family... The children enthusiastically sing along and clap their hands.  After the skits and songs, the children are split into small groups for a time of discussion with the high school students.  They receive a coloring book, a book mark and an Im a STAR sticker.

<p>Involvement:  An activity of this caliber requires the cooperation of a number of outside organizations as well as groups within the school.  The student council members enthusiastically perform the program repeatedly, and we are constantly looking for ways to improve it.  PTAs from the elementary schools have donated funds to help the program continue.

<p>We also sought the services of local community organizations to better prepare us in communicating with the young students.  This year an employee from Arlington Welcome House trained us to be stronger listeners and encouragers.

<p>We also performed the program for our Senior Skills Students who are physically and/or mentally handicapped, and they greatly enjoyed the songs, skits and interaction.  Faculty and staff also get involved through helping critique the program, providing resources and giving encouragement.

<p>STARS involves many facets of the community in that an impact is made not only on the third graders, but also their families.  Enthusiasm is contagious; therefore, the childrens attitude and excitement reach their parents and siblings when they return home wearing their sticker and relaying a positive message of being responsible.

<p>Besides the strong impact on the third graders, the STARS performers are also affected.  We realize our role as an adult in the eyes of the children carries with it responsibility.  In addition, our peers know that we are involved in STARS and we have a responsibility to be an example to them as well.

<p>Sam Houston is very proud of the STARS program and believes strongly in its message.  Our program has received rave reviews from the students, teachers, administrators, and parents in our local elementary schools.  We are fortunate to have the opportunity to bring such a positive and entertaining message to the children of our community.

</DOC>
