<H2>BLOOD ALLEY</H2>
Madisonville High School

<H3>PURPOSE AND OBJECTIVES</H3>
<p>The purpose of this project was to increase drug and alcohol awareness among people of all ages.  The main objectives were:  1) to illustrate the various degrees of drug and alcohol dependency, 2) to show the devastating consequences of driving under the influence of alcohol, 3) to combine students, administrators, community leaders, and citizens of Madisonville in a unified effort, 4) to achieve community-wide distribution of informative drug and alcohol pamphlets, and 5) to raise funds for a newly organized SADD chapter at Madisonville High School.

<p>In late 1991, the Madisonville High School Student Council conducted a blood alley on the high school grounds.  Blood Alley was a drive-through alleyway around the high school.  There were five scenarios and many road signs giving factual information on accidents and/or deaths resulting from driving under the influence of drugs or alcohol.  For example, upon entering the alley, participants read road signs giving data on our countys history of injuries and deaths due to driving under the influence.  The first scenario was a tailgate party where students were drinking and smoking; loud music roared from the speakers, and a good time was had by all.  The second scenario was a lone girl who was pulled over by a policeman.  Beer cans were strategically placed in the drivers car, and the policeman administered the breath analyzer test.  The third scenario was of a roll over accident where one teenager suffered from minor cuts and bruises.  The fourth scenario entailed one ambulance, two wrecked cars, two state trooper cars, and one police car.  Adorned with hard liquor bottles and beer cans, the two wrecked cars were placed facing each other.  Three students lay lifeless at the scene covered with blood, while one student cried, Bloody Murder! from within the ambulance.  The fifth scenario was of a funeral, complete with a casket and funeral tent and students serving as the mourners.  At the alleys end, several students distributed drug awareness packages to those who drove through and accepted donations.

<p>Blood Alley involved many people including all of the student council members and other students aided the council by donating flood lights for lighting (Blood Alley was held at night) and by helping to set up scenes and post road signs.  The Drama and Thespian Clubs prepared all Blood Alley actors and actresses with makeup and costumes.  Members of the faculty were involved in Blood Alley and helped with organizing, advertising and solicited media coverage of the event.  The greatest participation came from the community...Madison County Sheriffs Department, Madisonville Police, Maness Insurance Agency, Madison County EMS, Drakes Wrecker Service, Brazos County Department of Public Safety, Madison County Hospital, Madisonville Funeral Home, and the Madison County Department of Public Safety.

<p>Madisonville High School Student Councils Blood Alley was featured in the November issue of the Texas State Department of Highways magazine.  There were approximately 300 cars driven through the alleyway.  A substantial amount of money was raised and the council has now initiated SADD. 
</DOC>
<DOC>
