<heading>health and safety</heading>

<H2>DENVER CITY HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
601 Mustang Avenue, Denver City, Texas  79323

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  The Choice for Me - Drug Free</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>The Denver City High School Student Council wanted to make an impact on the fight against drugs and alcohol.  We coordinated many of our activities with a local drug and alcohol prevention committee during Red Ribbon Week in order to contact as many people as possible.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>The SMILE committee of our council is active each year fulfilling the requirements in the SMILE campaign as well as many additional projects.  This year, however, we decided to reach as many people in our community as possible by joining with a newly formed county organization, the Yoakum County Alcohol and Drug Prevention Committee.  Red Ribbon Week was designated by this local committee as October 23-30, and we attempted to saturate our school and community with information about the dangers of drugs and alcohol.  After receiving red ribbons from the local committee, the council distributed them to each school campus.  Every student in our community received a ribbon on Monday, October 24.  These ribbons  were worn to remind everyone to say no to drugs.

<p>During Red Ribbon Week, large red posters in the shape of red ribbons, original posters made by the SMILE committee members, and graphic posters ordered from the Readers Digest were placed in each school in our community.

<p>The SMILE committee manned a pledge table in the high school where students could pledge to not drink and drive.  Pamphlets about drug abuse and SADD contracts were distributed after students signed the pledge sheet.

<p>To emphasize myths about drinking, a mural was used which covered 21 feet of the junior hallway.  Cartoon figures and captions with famous myths decorated bright red paper.

<p>Crushed aluminum cans worn with yarn as necklaces signified that drinking and driving can crush a friendship.  We had our doubts about this one at first; however, it was so popular that we ran out of necklaces before lunch break.

<p>Announcements with music and slogans were made each day over the school intercom.  At the end of the week at the Friday night football game, our committee chairman made an announcement explaining Red Ribbon Week to the fans.  A table containing drug pamphlets  were erected by the stadium entrance.

<p>Various pamphlets and xeroxed information about drugs and alcohol were given to the drivers education, health, and home economics classes.  Also a display of pamphlets was placed in the library.

<p>Videos about drinking and driving were shown in various classes on the junior high and high school campuses.  Also, writing assignments were used in English classes on this subject.

<p>To involve some younger students, we had a poster contest for grades 4-6.  Prizes were awarded and the students pictures were published in the local newspaper.  To involve another campus, we had a coloring contest for grades 1-3.

<p>One of the most effective projects used was the gruesome display of a wrecked car.  A car which had been involved in a recent accident was placed in a marked off area in our high school parking lot.  Students and townspeople alike benefited from this sight.

<p>Alcohol and drug related projects were not just conducted during Red Ribbon Week.  During Homecoming Week, the SMILE committee made slogans  about drinking and driving and took them to the local florists to distribute with all corsages and boutonnieres delivered.  Before the Christmas holiday, slogans dealing with drinking and driving were tied to the outside rear view mirrors on all cars in the school parking lot.

<p>Drug and alcohol prevention programs are important to our council.  We hope in some way to make an impact on our student body and community.
</DOC>
