<h2>PROJECT SANTA BLOWS INTO NEW IBERIA</H2>

Helping Hurricane Victims with Christmas Gifts
by the Student Council of San Angelo Central High School

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Project Santa Blows into New Iberia</H3>

<H3>PURPOSES AND OBJECTIVES:</H3>
<p>To help hurricane victims with Christmas gifts to help make their lives a little better.  To encourage participation of the entire student body and community in a project to give to others less fortunate at Christmas.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>Annually, the CHS Student Council sponsors Project Santa to collect toys and clothes for needy children of San Angelo.  This year we were contacted by the Central High FHA and asked if we would be interested in a joint project for Christmas.  They had an outstanding idea, but they needed the organization that the Student Council already had established within the school and more people to help implement this project in a school of 2500.  The student Council Executive Board met with the FHA Executive Board, and a new cooperative dimension was added to our Project Santa.  The two executive boards decided to help Hurricane Andrew victims who had not yet recovered from the destruction and lacked the news coverage and donations to meet their needs.  When the idea was presented to the Student Council and FHA, it was overwhelmingly accepted.  With some searching and assistance from the Red Cross, we contacted New Iberia High School, New Iberia, Louisiana.  They said yes, they were in need of help and would locate children in their community that would not have a Christmas this year.

<p>While waiting for names of people to help from Louisiana, the Student Council elves contacted their homerooms and asked if each homeroom would like to participate.  (Each SC member is assigned 12 homerooms for the year as a way to communicate in person with the huge student body.)  Once we received 56 willing homerooms out of 72 and the names, ages, sex, sizes and Christmas wishes of the children from New Iberia, the Student Council elves set to work again.  The Activity Committee assigned the children to homerooms.  Each homeroom was given information on their child, a 20 gallon Santa bag, and a big red gift tag. The homerooms were given one and a half weeks to buy, make, or bring toys, clothes, and other gifts for the child.  Twice during this time, the Student Council elves checked on the progress of their homeroom and encouraged them to help this child have a great Christmas since what they gave was all the child would receive for Christmas.

<p>On the assigned date, the Student Council elves descended upon their homerooms to collect the Santa bags.  Only one problem developed.  The homerooms were so generous that many needed 2-3 Santa bags to contain their gifts.  After a quick trip to the store by the Activity chairmen, our problem was solved.  The Santa bags were collected in the rooms of the Student Council and FHA sponsors.  That afternoon, FHA students wrapped and evened out any bags that looked uneven.  Next, FHA students loaded the VERY FULL Santa bags onto a U-Haul trailer that was rented to us for a special price.  The FHA sponsor and her husband drove to Louisiana and personally delivered these gifts to New Iberia High School.  There they had a reception and a decorated tree awaiting them.  Willing students in New Iberia High School delivered the Santa bags from CHS students to the children in their community in time for these children to have a wonderful Christmas.  56 Children whose lives had been torn up by hurricane Andrew were able to have a Christmas that would have been forgotten this year if it were not for the foresight and planning of the CHS Student Council and FHA and the generous giving spirit of the CHS student body, faculty, and community.

<H3>Involvement:</H3>

<p>(a) Student Council members were involved in contacting the Red Cross, describing the project to their homerooms, assigning the children, encouraging student support, and collecting the gifts.  Several Student Council members were interviewed by the local TV station.

<p>(b) Other students were involved by choosing to participate in the project, and by bringing gifts for the children.  Students in Louisiana were involved in distributing the gifts to the children.

<p>(c) This was a joint project with the FHA, which was instrumental in thinking of the idea, helping to plan the project, assisting in gaining student body support, and wrapping and delivering the gifts to Louisiana.  Other organizations were involved in many ways.  Some organizations (National Honor Society and Business Professionals of America) also adopted children and brought them gifts.

<p>(d) The CHS faculty assisted by helping their homerooms choose appropriate gifts, encouraging their homerooms, and bringing gifts themselves.  The New Iberia faculty assisted by helping to find needy children and overseeing the distribution of gifts in Louisiana.

<p>(e) The community was also involved.  The Red Cross of San Angelo and Southern Louisiana helped locate children in need.  The Salvation Army gave us information and guidelines on gifts.  KLST News covered the project from the planning stage through completion.  One sponsor and two students were on a community news program.  The San Angelo Standard Times ran a story on the whole project and donated a copy of the picture from the story.  The CHS Campus Corral ran an article on the project.  Some community members contacted the school and brought gifts, donated money, or offered assistance.

<H3>Evaluation:</H3>

<p>There is no accurate way to measure the number of gifts given or the number of people who gave and received, but we believe that over $2,500 in toys, clothes, and other gifts were given for Project Santa.  That does not include the numerous hours spent by sponsors and students of both organizations in planning and implementing this project.  But that is not the issue.  We can only measure the success of our project in the smiles on childrens faces, thanks in the hearts of their parents, and satisfaction from helping someone less fortunate for Christmas.  We believe our project was a great success!

</DOC>
<DOC>
