<H2>ST THOMAS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4500 Memorial Drive, Houston, TX  77007

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Thanksgiving Food Drive</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>Each year the St. Thomas Council sponsors a food drive to help feed the needy families in our area during the Holiday Season.  Our main objective is to feed at least 24 families each year, then we give the remaining aid to St. Joseph Catholic Church which supplies us with the names of the needy.  Through this, we try to make the students realize that what they are doing is for the good of others and that through their efforts others are able to live.  This brings a sense of service throughout the school and instills a feeling of community and oneness within each student.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>The project began three weeks before Thanksgiving when the chairman of the project (Vice-President of Council) called St. Joseph Catholic Church and requested the names of thirty families that need food for the holidays.  After this, notices were made in each of the 24 homerooms that if they wanted to sponsor a family they had to raise about $100.  Each homeroom accepted the challenge.  Throughout the next two weeks, the students took collections in their homerooms.  After each homeroom period, the money would be put in the envelopes provided by Council and brought down to the main office to be counted and recorded by Council Reps.  A running total would be kept for each homeroom and all the money would be deposited with the business manager for safekeeping.  Also, students would bring non-perishable foods which would be deposited in five large barrels in front of the main office.

<p>During the last few days of collections, the homeroom teachers  really pushed the students to get involved in the project, especially if they had not contributed anything as of yet.  One the day before the food deliveries, the homeroom teachers made a list of each student and which food item he agreed to bring.  Some of these items included turkeys, hams, and various desserts.  This was also on a voluntary basis.  Three students were picked from each homeroom to accompany their Student Council Rep to the grocery store and to deliver the food to their family.  This occurred on Tuesday before Thanksgiving.  The students were able to get off school for two hours to deliver the food.  Before they left, they picked up the amount of money they brought in as a homeroom, and they collected some canned goods from the five full barrels.  At the store, each group selected food items such as flour, sugar, fruits, bread/cereals, corn meal, and other products such as detergents, paper plates, forks and spoons, and other paper goods.  Then the groups went to their respective families to deliver a Thanksgiving feast that would last at least two weeks.

<p>The good thing about a project such as this is that it gets the whole school involved for a single purpose.  The Student Council kept everything organized, but the project would not have been such a success without the intensity and generosity of the students and the determination of the faculty.  We fed a total of 30 families this year with the total of $2,204.  We have found that each homeroom is willing to share their collections with another family.  Each student who was not able to deliver the food was told about how the people smiled when they saw the food, and each student then knew that he had an integral part in each and every smile that had occurred.

</DOC>
<DOC>
