<H2>SHOES FOR KIDS FOR CHRISTMAS</H2>
<H2>SOUTH HOUSTON HIGH SCHOOL<?H2>
3820 SOUTH SHAVER, SOUTH HOUSTON, TX  77587


<h3>PURPOSE AND OBJECTIVES:</H3>
<p>Recognizing that there is a need within our community to help students less fortunate than ourselves, especially youngsters who are future South Houston High School students.  Trojan Council organized Shoes for Kids for Christmas.  Through this project Trojan Council members were paired with needy elementary students to spend a day buying school shoes.  The experience for both the Trojan Council members and the elementary students was overwhelmingly positive.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>  On the morning of December 16, the South Houston High School Trojan Council took eighty-five needy elementary school children to buy shoes and to have a pizza party.  In order for this to occur, the Community Committee of the Trojan Council spent months of advance planning and fund raising.

<p>During the summer, the Trojan Council raised almost $3,000 by running the intermediate summer school concession stand.  For six weeks, dedicated Trojan Council members came every morning of the week to serve the intermediate school students.

<p>This is the third year that Trojan Council members have worked very hard at fund raising in order to be able to buy shoes for these needy children at Christmas.  As in years past, we anticipated a successful day of reaching out in love and the spirit of giving to these little, future Trojans.

<p>We had asked the school nurses at four of the elementary feeder schools to help us by selecting twenty needy children from each school who could use new school shoes.  We picked up these eighty-five children (we were originally going to take a mere eighty-five children, but we had room for more) at their respective elementary schools at 8:30 a.m. and proceeded directly to the local Payless Shoe Source.  Each Trojan Council member helped their designated children select, size, and then purchase their new shoes.  In addition, we bought shoes for the several children unable to attend the outing.

<p>The Trojan Council members and the children, with their shoes in hand, went back to the high school where we purchased lunch for them.  With full tummies and new shoes, we all went to the students respective elementary schools, but not before we provided them with Free Willy posters, cupcakes, balloons, and lots of hugs.

<p>A few days after the drive, we began receiving letters of thanks from the children we assisted.

<H3>DESCRIPTION OF INVOLVEMENT:</H3>  

<p>Trojan Council Members:  Trojan Council members were involved, from the at-large members to the president.  Members were chosen according to the councils merit/demerit system.  Trojan Council members with the highest number of merits were allowed to take part in the shoe drive.

<p>Other Students:  Students from the National Honor Society took part in Shoes for Kids for Christmas and were also assigned children.  Representatives of the yearbook staff and the campus newspaper also came along with the original intent of taking pictures, but they had more fun playing with and helping the children.

<p>Other Organizations:  The National Honor Society contributed ninety pairs of socks to the shoe drive.  Creative Clowns provided three professional clowns who entertained us the entire outing.  Many teachers and students came out to say good-bye to the kids as the first lunch shift began and the buses rolled away.

<p>Faculty and Staff:  Many teachers donated money and shoes for our drive.  Our cafeteria workers donated over 15 pairs of shoes in addition to homemade cookies for the little guys.  These wonderful ladies prepared four lunch shifts instead of their regular hectic three lunches.

<p>Community:  Payless Shoe Source gave us a discount on the shoes, and the manager of the store paid for seven pairs of shoes out of his own pocket.  The day manager and her staff made 100 cupcakes and had candy canes for the kids.  One of the members of the Pasadena I.S.D. Board of Trustees met us at Payless and pitched right in with the selecting and sizing of the shoes.  Also lending a helping hand was the Secondary Superintendent who made sure every child had at least one pair of new socks and sometimes more (its hard to say no to a little one who says their brother at home needs some socks too).  The Pasadena Citizen came to record the event, as did the Houston Chronicle and television Channel 26.  Shoes for Kids for Christmas was front page in the Houston Chronicles This Week publication and the Pasadena Citizen.  Channel 26 aired our kids both at noon and on the evening news.




</DOC>
<DOC>
