<H2>HALLOWEEN PENNY CARNIVAL</H2>
Carnival provides safe, fun environment on holiday
...by the Student Council of West Mesquite High School

<H3>Name of Project:  Halloween Penny Carnival</H3>

<H3>Purposes and Objectives:</H3>
<p>Our neighborhoods are steadily becoming more and more dangerous, and, on Halloween especially, young children become prime targets for violent crimes.  The Halloween Penny Carnival was designed to provide a fun, yet safe and affordable Halloween activity that all the children of our community could enjoy.

<H3>Description of Activities</H3>
<p>The West Mesquite High School Student Council planned and initiated a Halloween carnival to benefit elementary school students and needy children of Mesquite.  Although many carnivals were hosted by community centers, churches, and schools, none were being held in the West Mesquite vicinity.  The council decided that by hosting a carnival, a fun and safe alternative to door-to-door trick-or-treating would be available.  It was decided that proceeds would be donated to Mesquite Social Services.

<p>All West Mesquite organizations were invited to participate in the carnival.  Fourteen campus groups became involved by sponsoring and working a game booth.

<p>Carnival tickets were provided for each student at the four elementary feeder schools; and Mesquite Social Services was provided with tickets also.  Over 3,000 tickets were sent to the schools and M.S.S.  The ticket allowed each child to enter the carnival free (no one was actually turned away), plus allowed each child to play 10 games free.  All games after the first 10 cost 1 each.  To make sure the carnival served the children of the community, persons over the age of 13 could only attend if accompanying a child with a ticket.  Extra tickets were provided to each school for children under school age.  The carnival was Saturday, October 30, in the WMHS gym.  It turned out to be a great success.  Over 2,000 people attended, and no child left the gym without a sack full of candy and prizes.

<H3>Description of Involvement</H3>

<P>a)  Student Council members:  The executive committee organized the event, recruited other organizations to get involved, and invited four elementary feeder schools to come enjoy the festivities.  Other members helped copy, cut, and count over 3,000 tickets that were sent out to the four participating schools.  Many members were involved with painting backdrops for the booths.  Several members came early to set up the booths and decorations and stayed late to clean up.  Student Council members worked some of the booths as well.

<P>b)  Other students:  several non-council members helped to set up the carnival and clean up afterwards.  Most of the booths were set up and worked by other students.

<p>c)  Organizations:  We relied on the participation of other campus organizations to make this carnival such a success.  Fourteen campus groups became involved by sponsoring and working a game booth.  Each group was responsible for planning the game, scheduling workers, setting up and taking down the booth.  Student Council was able to provide prizes for each booth.  Among the participating groups were Peer Tutors who sponsored the Costume Contest, Spanish Club who sponsored the Matador Game, Booster Club who handled the refreshments, the drill team who sponsored the Dart Throw, the basketball team who sponsored the Basketball Throw, Cultural Diversity Club who sponsored Musical Chairs, the Y.E.S. committee who sponsored the Ring Toss, the Sophomore Committee who sponsored the Hole in One Golf Game, Girls Athletics who sponsored Pick-A-Card, the cheerleaders who sponsored the Penny Toss, the French Club who sponsored the Pencil Drop Game, and P.T.A. who sponsored the Face Painting Booth.

<p>d)  Faculty:  Our principal was gracious enough to allow us use of the gymnasium for an entire day.  Many teachers helped to set up and work the booths.  Some teachers even brought their own children to enjoy the carnival.

<p>e)  Community:  Attendance at the carnival was recorded at over 2,000 people.  For most of the night young children and their parents completely filled the large gymnasium.  The entire event was geared towards benefiting the community.  We succeeded in providing a fun, safe and affordable Halloween alternative for the children in our area.  It was the smiles on the hundred of childrens faces that marked the true success of the project.  The proceeds of $150 were donated to the Mesquite Social Services for further use in the community.
</DOC>
