<H2>MUSTANGS</H2>

<H3>Mustangs Uniting Students Toward A No Gang Society..by the Student Council of Jefferson High School, San Antonio</H3>

<H3>Name of Project:  OPERATION MUSTANGS - Mustangs Uniting Students Toward A No Gang Society</H3>

<H3>Purposes and Objectives:</H3>  
<p>Recognizing the detrimental effects of gangs and their pervasive presence in our community, the Thomas Jefferson Student Council developed Operation M.U.S.T.A.N.G.S. for several reasons; to educate students about the problems of being in a gang, make students aware of the positive alternatives to gang involvement, and to give students who are presently involved in gangs hope and encouragement to get out of a gang.

<H3>Description</H3>
<p>Operation M.U.S.T.A.N.G.S. was a multifaceted project which involved students, administrators, teachers, and students from our feeder schools.  Vital to our success was the selection of Anti-Gang delegates.  These delegates were chosen by our Club and Organization sponsors to represent their respective clubs.  These students worked to develop and implement our projects.  Our project culminated with Gang Awareness Week which included a professional anti-gang play for the entire student body, a banner in the cafeteria on which students expressed their anti-gang sentiments, presentations by our school districts anti-gang unit, public address announcements, marquee announcements, information flyers for the teachers, a scavenger hunt, and an ongoing anti-gang/anti-drug/earth awareness program which is presented at our local elementary schools.  Another ongoing element of our project has been our participation in groups who work with local Home Owners Associations to paint over gang graffiti in our neighborhoods.

<H3>The Realities of Operation M.U.S.T.A.N.G.S.</H3>

<p>This project was conceived late last summer when our Council sat down to plan activities for the year.  One of our goals was to design a project that would have a community-wide anti-gang message.  At the time we had no idea what a monumental task we were undertaking!  As time went by, the project seemed to grow and grow.  The importance and urgency of this project was accentuated for us by the tragic death of one of our classmates who was an innocent victim of gang violence at the beginning of this year.  Although many wonderful people and activities affect out school life at Thomas Jefferson, this death put a very real face on a very grave problem facing our entire society, and particularly the society of our youth.

<H3>Elements of Operation M.U.S.T.A.N.G.S. -Anti-Gang Play, Los Fatherless</H3>
	
<p>The play Los Fatherless was presented by the Toviah Street Theater and contained an anti-gang message.  It touched many of the students since they felt they could relate to a gang type situation.  The play was presented to the entire student body and administrators.  Many students showed a positive response and related how similar the tragedy was to the real world.

<H3>Anti-Gang Banner</H3>

<p>A special banner was  designed so that the students of Thomas Jefferson could express their Anti-Gang thoughts.  It was then hung up in the school cafeteria for the students to view.  The banner expressed unity and hope for a better Anti-Gang community.  It contained several stick people holding hands and asking the question What do you think about Gangs?

<H3>Anti-Gang Guest Speaker</H3>

<p>The San Antonio Independent School District Gang Unit visited selected classes and gave a short seminar and showed a video.  Afterward, there was a question and answer session.  Many students and teachers asked pertinent questions.

<H3>Scavenger Hunt</H3>

<p>The scavenger hunt was an activity done after school.  It consisted of five teams.  Each team had ten students from different clubs and organizations that were tied up together.  In order to win, the teams had to answer questions correctly and work as a group.  If they answered incorrectly, a physical challenge was taken.  This activity required team work and effort, along with the knowledge of gang facts that had been taught during the week.  The teachers had fun watching the students run all over the school and asked if we could come up with a Hunt for the faculty and staff.

<H3>Anti-Gang Delegates</H3>

<p>Anti-Gang Delegates were selected by each organizations sponsor to help spread Anti-Gang messages to their peers and to the students at the feeder schools.  Each organization participated, cooperatively by selecting a student, sending him/her to the meetings, and by participating in the activities held throughout the year.

<H3>Outside Marquee</H3>

<p>The outside marquee helped get the information to the community about upcoming events.  For example, Anti-Gang Week and the graffiti painting activities were publicized to the community so that they could help.

<H3>Painting Over Gang Graffiti</H3>

<p>The painting over graffiti occurs approximately once a month.  A group of students, teachers, parents, and other volunteers from the community paint over gang or any other type of graffiti on public places.  Each time we have painted we have had a large amount of participation and everyone has had fun.  The graffiti has also decreased.

<H3>Elementary School Presentations</H3>

<p>The Program for Maverick Elementary was an enjoyable experience for all that participated.  The Anti-Gang Delegates played an important role in this by writing an Anti-Gang skit to present to the elementary students.  The PRIDE Group also played a vital role by helping present the skit.  The program for the students also contained information and a short game about Saving the Earth presented by our Energy Awareness group.



</DOC>
