<H2>HUNTSVILLE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
441 FM 2821 EAST. HUNTSVILLE, TX  77340

<h3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Teen Summit:  The Fourth R - Responsibility</H3>

<h3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>To increase student participation in school and community activities in an effort to build self-esteem and an increased awareness of our world and the problems facing society.  It was councils intent to let our students know they were important not only to the well-being of our school, but that they were important to the well-being of society in general; and that each of us can make a difference.

<h3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>Modeling after President Bushs Economic Summit which was held in Houston last summer, the H.H.S. Student Council planned, financed, and executed a teenage summit in our high school early in the 1990-91 school year.  One entire Saturday was devoted to showing students how they could become an active and important part of the school, the community, and ultimately the world.  By inviting a wide variety of community leaders, educators and guest speakers to conduct workshops and seminars, opportunities were provided for students to find areas of interest in which they could make a difference.  Our activities included the following:<OL>
<LI>1.  Council wanted to open the summit to 500 students who could represent a cross-section of interests and grade levels.  (Our auditorium only holds 500.)  It was important that if everyone was to feel welcome, the summit needed to be free and open to the first 500 to register.  To that end, an academic seal was designed and ordered and then sold to faculty, parents, community leaders, and local merchants.  As a result of this project, the $4,000 cost of the summit was paid by our council.

<LI>While teams of council members were selling academic stickers, others were contacting faculty members in our high school and the local college, Sam Houston State University, to present workshops in a variety of interest areas that touched on academics, leadership, community involvement, substance abuse, the Middle East crisis, international student exchanges, safety, spirit, the environment, law, AIDS, UNICEF, and the 1990 state governors race.  Where appropriate, students acted as panel members and facilitators in the various workshops.

<LI>Two guest speakers provided inspiration at the beginning of the morning and afternoon sessions.  The speakers were Jeff Rash, past president of the National FFA, and Miles McCall, an instructor at Stephen F. Austin.

<LI>During lunch (catered by the local Feed Store) a D.J. provided music for dancing.

<LI>It must be noted that each workshop session was given the task of making resolutions that they believed could be accomplished during the 1990-91 school year that would not only address current issues but provide a way for students to work toward solutions and thus make a difference in the school, community, nation and world.

<LI>These resolutions were all read during the closing session and a commitment was made by the teen summit participants to work toward making them a reality.  At the end of March, the following resolutions had been successfully addressed:</OL>
<UL>
<LI>During Desert Shield and Desert Storm, the high school participated in a variety of school and community events to show support for the armed forces.  Yellow ribbons were tied to the trees on campus, and a list of our graduates, friends, and family members was kept on a special bulletin board.  Many students and faculty members corresponded with service men that they knew and many that they did not know but whose names were provided because the soldiers were not receiving mail from home.  Once the ground war began, council provided white papers each Wednesday on information concerning the history of the problem, religions of the Middle East, world leaders, and facts and figures concerning the coalition.

<LI>A school-wide recycling program was put in place and collection points provided for soda cans and recyclable paper.

<LI>School-wide participation in the state and community Red Ribbon Campaign along with other reinforcements for drug awareness i.e., pencils, posters, etc.

<LI>Renewed emphasis was placed on conserving energy at school by doing classroom surveys on ways to reduce consumption.  Posters, handouts, etc., were provided to teachers as well as students, and a large display was placed in the library along with the planting of trees on the school grounds.  Members of council also participated in a free distribution of young trees to the community.

<LI>The entire school was behind our students as they took TEAMS/TAAS this year.  Posters were placed in the halls and announcements were made encouraging them to do their best.

<LI>A mock political debate and election were held just prior to the election of a new governor in Texas.  This debate was in response to the National Student Parent Mock Election sponsored by Time Magazine, the Congressional Quarterly, and the American Association of School Administrators to increase voter awareness and reduce apathy among the general population.  This was a wonderful activity that included registering 18 year olds, getting out the vote among parents and the community at large, and providing an opportunity for students to participate in a mock debate, rally and election patterned after national conventions.  The council office acted as a command center for the school district and all of the schools participated.  As a result of our many and varied activities, Huntsville I.S.D. was one of 5 school districts in the nation to be recognized at the AASA Convention in New Orleans.

<LI>At the summit, the participants signed a petition sent to UNICEF in response to the United Nations Convention on the Right of the Child.  One of the resolutions signed by all was to encourage the United Nations to improve the plight of all children.

<LI>Because of the hard work put forth by the student council, Huntsville High School was able to make a difference this year for the students, community, and hopefully, for the future of the state and nation.  While what we did may seem slight, it has helped students to realize that we are one student body, yet we are also a part of something much larger -- the community, state, nation and world.  The problems we discuss today must have solutions if the world is going to be a better place.  As we struggled this year to make a difference, community leaders, local news media, parents, and faculty were right there with us.  Many students who often do not get involved found a niche for themselves this year.  School pride increased and a real sense of togetherness seemed to exist. Students asked to get involved.  Club memberships have not only increased but the clubs seem more active.  The real pay-off from the Teen Summit:  The Fourth R - Responsibility has been in the classroom where teachers say students are working harder than ever and seem to be having more fun being a Huntsville Hornet.


</DOC>
