<heading>public relations</heading>
<H2>JEFFERSON HIGH SCHOOL, JEFFERSON</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Gold Card Program</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>  To involve senior citizens in the schools and to help them realize that they are getting a return on tax money spent on schools.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>Our school district has a club called Gold Card.  Senior citizens may sign up annually for a card that entitles them to free admission to school activities and other benefits.  I December, an invitation is included in a newsletter that announces a Christmas Program put on by the choir and hosted by the Student Council.  On the Friday or Saturday before the program, Student Council members meet and prepare a fruit basket for each Gold Card holder.  The basket contains one apple, one orange, one grapefruit, a handful of mixed nuts, a few starlight mints, and a customized Jefferson High School Student Council calendar for the coming year.  On the day of the program, selected council members help direct the parking of cars and act as ushers seating the seniors as they arrive.  The senior are welcomed by the Student Council President and the Superintendent of Schools, after which the choir presents its Christmas program.

<p>At the conclusion of the choir program, the Principal invites the senior citizens to get in line and eat a meal prepared by the cafeteria staff.  This is the same meal the students will be eating that day.  The seniors go through the line in the same manner as the students, except the Student Council members accompany each one and carry the trays to the tables for the Gold Card holders.  As the seniors are eating, Student Council members begin passing out the fruit baskets to the guests while visiting and answering questions.  The seniors are also invited to stay for guided tours led by the Council members.

<p>The response from the senior citizens is wonderful.  After the inaugural program last year, they began asking about this year's program in July and August.  In December 1989 there were 140 Gold Card members.  On December 13, approximately 70 seniors braved below-freezing temperatures to attend the JHS Student Council presentation.


</DOC>
<DOC>
