<H2>BURKBURNETT JUNIOR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Adopt-A-Nursing Home</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>Our purpose in adopting a nursing home was to develop and sustain a positive relationship between a group of senior citizens and teenagers in our community.  Our objectives centered around this involvement between the two groups.  We wanted to get students involved with people they didn't know in the community and create interaction between the two age groups to foster a better understanding and appreciation of each other.  Adopt-a-Nursing Home helped brighten the lives of those senior citizens who never had a chance to be around young people or those who have hew or no visitors.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>We began each of our nursing home visits by having a committee meeting to determine an appropriate time to visit, who would go, and activities we wanted to do at the nursing home.  We scheduled our first visit on Halloween.  Since StuCo had sponsored a "costume day," we went to the manor dressed up to "treat, not trick."  We made potpourri bags after school and gave one to each person residing at the home.  We were aware that some of the residents had restricted diets and chose to distribute the potpourri bags so no one would be left out of the fun.  StuCo also purchased pumpkin stickers that members put on the collars of the senior citizens.  This served as an icebreaker since some members were a little unsure of what to say.  StuCo purchased regular and sugar free candy which was put on the food trays of those who could have it.

<p>Our first visit was so successful that we had many more students wanting to go on our Christmas visit.  The residents enjoyed hearing  Twas the Night Before Christmas and Gift of the Magi read by two of our members.  We handed out Santa stickers and lots of Hugs.

<p>On Valentine's Day, each resident received a valentine signed by Burkburnett Junior High School StuCo.

<H3>INVOLVEMENT</H3>
<p>There were over 85 members of StuCo along with some members of the History Club, Pep Club, and cheerleaders who took part in the visits.  As word of the fun began to spread, many more students wanted to participate.  However, since the visits were made during school hours there were transportation limitations.  Only two other faculty member and the two student council sponsors were able to go with us during their conference periods.  Community participation involved over 55 patients and 20 staff members at the nursing home.



</DOC>
