<H2>SOUTH GRAND PRAIRIE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  1 year, 5 months and 4 days in the life of Mr. Wendal</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>This project was inspired by the song Mr. Wendal, performed by Arrested Development.  Mr. Wendal is a homeless person befriended by a young man--a person who has a great deal to offer.  The homeless of today do have much to offer, and it was our goal throughout this project to provide for the homeless and to educate both ourselves and others about the forgotten people of our world.

<p>While carrying out this project, Mr. Wendal came to represent the homeless men, women, and children that we came to know and love.  It was our goal to inform students of the importance that education holds while trying to better the lives of our fellow man.  Not many students had encountered a Mr. Wendal.  Not many students knew what he (they) had to offer, but after their experience, the young men and women of SGPHS have become attached to our Wendal family.

<H3>DESCRIPTION</H3>
<p>Our project began in the summer with a tremendous amount of planning and preparation.  Many projects were included in the overall project, as a great deal was needed to accomplish the goals that were set.
	
<p>Nov.19--Our Student council organized and carried out the second annual Scavenger Hunt to gather items that could be taken to the streets of Dallas to be handed out.  Over 5,000 items of food, clothing, and hygiene products were collected.  

<p>Dec. 7--A parents' meeting was held at SGPHS to inform our council's parents of our upcoming plans.

<p>Jan. 29--After receiving approval, our student council set out to experience the homeless for the first time.  On Thursday of that week, the group went grocery shopping for our trip.  Friday rolled around, and the group met at a member's home to prepare 195 sack lunches and 50 bags of hygiene products to be dispersed.  On Saturday around 10:00 a.m., we set out for Dallas, handed out our goods, and conversed with the homeless.

<p>Feb. 6--The sophomores collected money with collection buckets, and stopped on the way to our District Convention to give their 275 lunches, 80 hygiene bags, and many blankets and pillows.

<p>Feb. 13--The executive board, once again gathered money throughout school from students to purchase food, and other things to be handed out.  The same sequence was followed, and the outing was, again, a success.

<p>Feb. 16--Barbara Goodspeed, a homeless citizen of Dallas, came to speak to SGPHS for an assembly of our students to speak on the homeless, and the value of education.  We set up an appointment with a local optometrist in return for the visit.

<p>Feb. 27--The Senior class officers were given the chance to organize a trip to Dallas The officers collected money through pizza sales, and bought enough food to produce 205 sack lunches and purchased 20 blankets to give away.  A local dentist was called upon for a donation of toothbrushes which were also given away.
	
<p>Feb. 27--The Freshman collected money through various bake sales, and collection buckets.  These students shopped at Sam's to purchase things for over 200 lunches, and also held a clothing drive to collect numerous articles of clothing and shoes.  The freshmen received donations from two area dentists, and prepared bags with toothbrushes and toothpaste to be handed out.
	
<p>April 3--The Junior class is preparing to go on their trip to Dallas, and have collected a great deal through candy sales and collection buckets.

<P>April 16--The classes that make up our council have prepared to take their left-over money, and arrange a group project in Dallas. 
<p>April 23--Various clubs within school are preparing to organize things for the Student Council to distribute.  One the preceding Friday night, students from various clubs will experience homelessness for a night outside of our school with a "sleep-out."  

<p>May 11--A banquet has been organized to present all that we have done as a council to the community and school officials.

<H3>INVOLVEMENT:</H3>
<p>All effort was made to involve people and a very nice job was done in the way of involving others.
<p>A) Student Council Members--All members were given the chance to experience the homeless and their environment.  Those that could not attend the trips to the streets of Dallas were included in that they could take part in the preparation and purchase of supplies.  These students were involved in the Scavenger Hunt that provided many of the clothing items and other things.
<p>B) Other Students--The students of SGPHS were included in our project because they were the suppliers of most of the funds.  The students experienced the speech of a woman from the streets that had a great deal to say, and they were invited to participate in the preparation at all times.
<p>C) Organizations--We relied on other organizations to supply us with much-need supplies.  Almost every group within school had a drive of some sort to provide things that were needed.
<p>D) Faculty--Teachers were allowed to sign up to go and experience the homeless.  Each and every time we had a abundance of people sign up.  Many teachers brought items from home, and involved their families to a great extent.  Administrators went along each time, and central administrators even attended some events.
<p>E) Community--The community was a huge part of our project.  Donations came from all over the city through our Scavenger Hunt, and many local dentists and other places of business were included.  Discounts were given by local stores, and everyone has been invited to our end-of-the-year banquet.
<p>Groups from all over the city and metroplex were called upon to aid in the progress of this project.  No project in the history of our school has touched as many lives.  It is our many Mr. Wendals that we have to thank for the education, life skills, and love that we all experienced.

</DOC>
