<H2>SOUTH HOUSTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  House Renovations: Rebuilding Trust and Spirit in Community</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3><OL>
	<LI>Trojan Council wanted to reach into the hearts and homes of the community, 	as well as of the students and staff members of South Houston High.  We rebuilt 	not only houses, but the trust and spirit in our local community.
	<LI>We set out to do a project that we had never heard of before--something 	original.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>In April, we sacrificed our Easter holiday to scrape our knuckles, repaint long-neglected walls, and landscape destitute ground.  Our house renovations took place on two homes in the city of South Houston.  We worked on both houses simultaneously and divided up the work according to specialty or experience.
<p>At the first location we scraped the external walls, painted them, rebuilt a front and back porch, and replaced all of the window screens.  At the second location we scraped and repainted the interior walls, worked on the sheet rock, replaced counter tops, replaced plumbing, and landscaped the entire yard.  Although the work was long, hard, and tedious, the rewards were well worth the effort.  Through the pounding of nails and the stench of freshly caulked windows, we put smiles on the faces of two elderly ladies as well as those of the students who had never worked before with their bare hands.

<H3>INVOLVEMENT AND PARTICIPATION</H3>
<p>The entire student council cooperated to gather the supplies necessary to begin this project, and dedicated their holidays to give the labor needed to complete the project.  Fund-raising for the project was planned well in advance.  We were able to raise approximately $450 from a car wash and $2500 from candy sales.  Donations were received from the Associated Builders and Contractors of Greater Houston.  They generously gave paint brushes, paint, dry wall, and many other useful supplies.
<p>Through association with family businesses, we obtained the desperately needed window screens and plumbing supplies.  Through the help and connections of many faculty members, we were able to gain more help and supplies.  
<p>One faculty member who helped was Mr. Boudry, the wood shop instructor.  He involved several of his top students who unselfishly devoted time to rebuild the porches.  Our school cheerleaders volunteered their organization to participate in this heart warming event.  Others included the South Houston volunteer firemen, who repaired the electric poach lights.
<p>Most of all, we received the cooperation and help from many neighbors of the houses we repaired.  When we needed extra outlets and extension cords, they were pleased to oblige.  Even Mayor Dennis Cordray of South Houston enjoyed working on one of the houses.  Public relations was supplied by the news departments of local TV channels 2, 11, 13, 26, and 39.  The Houston Chronicle and Pasadena Citizen joined with Houston area radio stations as they showed appreciation to us for being such helpful citizens in our community.

<H3>EVALUATION</H3>
<p>Our total expenses were about $4000, but because of our tremendous fund-raising efforts, we never went in the hole.  More importantly, we patched up two old building and painted the world a brighter place.  The Student Body Vice President recapped the experience by saying, ....the time we spent working will always be remembered.  In conclusion, the resident of one of the repaired homes said, ....it amazed and thrilled me that children do care about the elderly and their environment so much.

</DOC>
