<H2>MARTIN HIGH SCHOOL, ARLINGTON</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Dare to Share</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>The intent of this service project was to provide relief to the Midwest flood victims through a district-wide supplies and money drive.  The area that we choose to help was Orchard Farms, a small school district in St. Charles, Missouri.  This area was in particularly poor circumstances even after flood water had receded in other parts of the state.  Out of 100 square miles of territory, 90 square miles were still under water in Orchard Farms.  Many of their students had been displaced and were living in shelters.  The total enrollment for the district, which included one high school, one junior high and two elementary schools, was 1,450 students.  Martin High felt that we, with a school district of over 50,000 students, could truly make a difference if we worked together and gave to those suffering from this devastating disaster.

<H3>DESCRIPTION</H3>
<p>After receiving approval from the Superintendent, the student council contacted the other four area high schools in Arlington.  We held a meeting before school to discuss the approach that we would take in including all the schools in our district.  At this meeting, each high school took the responsibility of contacting all of their junior high and elementary feeder schools and explaining the project.  It was also decided that the high schools would sponsor a monetary drive during their homeroom classes, and the junior high and elementary schools would hold a supply drive with a suggested supplies list provided to them.  Our drive was to be conducted between August 26 and September 2.  Next, we began the publicity strategy which included using all the schools' marquees and making posters, flyers, announcements, parent notes and banners.  We also performed a skit at the elementary schools to inform the younger children of the devastating impact of a natural disaster and the importance of helping out others when they have great need.  
<p>After publicizing our project, our collection began.  The student council collected, counted, and rolled the money from each homeroom each day of the drive.  The total dollar count was approximately $1,500 from Martin High School and the overall dollar amount was close to $4,000.  Also, each day after school, Martin student council members went to pick up the supplies collected at our eight feeder schools.  (All the other high schools completed this same task which involved collecting from over fifty schools.)  After the collection drive was completed, our student council boxed all of the supplies so they could be loaded onto an 18-wheeler headed for Missouri.  Then, one full day was spent by all of the students councils from all the high schools loading the truck.  We went caravan-style from high school to high school and helped each other to complete this task.  The amazing part of this story is that all our five area high schools had great success in competing this project; so much so, that we had to rent an additional U-Haul truck to haul to cargo to Missouri.  This particular project received media attention in both the Fort Worth Star Telegram and the Dallas Morning News.

<H3>INVOLVEMENT</H3>
<p>The student council members organized the project and publicized it to the schools and community, collected the money and supplies and loaded the trucks.  All 50,000 students in the Arlington ISD were involved in this project.  The relief drive crossed all organizations and clubs within the Arlington ISD.  All the faculty in Arlington ISD was involved in the collection process; neighbors and parents contributed goods and supplies; and the media kept the community informed of the drive.

</DOC>
<DOC>
