<H2>SNYDER HIGH SCHOOL, SNYDER</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:   A.F.S. Jamboree</H3>

<p>The purpose of this project is to bring as many American Field Service students together as possible that are staying in Texas this school year.  This would enable our students and the people of our community to acquaint themselves with students from other countries and discuss cultural and educational differences.  Equally important is the fact that attention would be directed to our high school and the Student Council.

<p>Activities scheduled during the weekend are centered around the heritage of our community.  Many of the AFS students are living in large cities and never get to see the Texas they heard about.  We also plan for the visiting students to be exposed to as many students and citizens of our community as possible.

<p>Students arrive in Snyder Thursday evening and spend that evening getting acquainted with their host student and his or her parents.

<p>On Friday the students attend classes with their host student and interaction with our students is encouraged.  This is the time most of the student body has an opportunity to visit with our guests.  Schools, culture, governments, and other topics are invariably discussed at that time.  At three o'clock the host students and their guests attend a private swimming party at the campus of Western Texas College.  This time allows the AFS students to discuss their stay in the United States with each other.  A rodeo sampler with bareback and saddleback bronc riding, roping, and bull riding is then held at the rodeo arena with the Western Texas College and SHS Rodeo Club providing the demonstrations and spills.  The AFS students then are allowed to participate in a ribbon-roping contest with male and female winners receiving a trophy.  After the rodeo sampler students then ride horses provided by various people.

<p>A dance is held Friday night for all guests and students of SHS

<p>The local AFS chapter hosts a brunch on Saturday morning.  We then give a tour of our city and the surrounding area.  Included are museums, local historical points, local gas plant, oil drilling rig, oil pulling unit, and a cotton gin.

<p>Formal activities conclude Saturday night with a western barbecue at a nearby ranch.  Song and dance follows the meal with each student telling something about their county and often providing entertainment in the form of piano playing, singing, or playing other musical instruments.

<p>Students return to their AFS homes Sunday.

<p>All Student Council members are involved in planning, organization, serving on various committees, and some keep visiting students in their homes for the weekend.  The administration, many local citizens, WTC faculty and students, SHS teachers and students, Snyder Chamber of Commerce, and the news media are all necessary to successfully complete the project.  We estimate that well over 150 students, teachers, and local citizens were directly involved in this project, not counting the hundreds of students that visited with the AFS students at school and at the dance.

<p>The 1983 Jamboree was held March 17-20 and 12 students came from all areas of Texas.  A total of 11 countries were represented.


</DOC>
