<H2>ATHENS HIGH SCHOOL, ATHENS</H2>

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  The Sting is Back</H3>

<H3>OBJECTIVES:</H3>
<p>To promote school unity and involvement;  to improve the attitude of students and faculty;  to encourage class competition, to emphasize the various forms of victories;  to show support for the football team.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>Various activities were selected for the first two weeks in October to build on the school's pride, commitment, involvement, and spirit.  Students were asked to submit spirit slogans during the spirit emphasis.  Winning slogans would be displayed in the case in the main hall.

<p>Class competition was promoted through the building of a spirit chain.  Each class was given a specific color.  Designated students from each class collected money during the week for links in the chain at 5 cents each.  After school several students would meet to count the money and construct the chains.  Each chain was assembled be members of all classes to eliminate claims of unfairness.  Numbers of links for each class were announced daily.  Friday night during pre-game activities, the chains were unveiled, and the winners were announced.  The freshman class won with over 3200 links, and they were given an early dismissal for lunch as a reward.  More than $500 was raised through this activity.  The money went to help with the expenses of Homecoming.

<p>Operation Boom Boom was organized by the Student Council to promote school spirit.  The plan was to beat a drum continuously from Thursday morning at 8:00 to the 7:30 kick-off at the game that Friday night.  An old drum was donated by the band for the activity.  The students body was informed of the plan and procedure during an assembly.  At that time, the coach promised a victory if the students beat the drum continuously.  Sign-up sheets were posted in the main hall.  The pep rally for that game was held at the football field where the drum was being beaten.  By kick-off time Friday night, the drum had been beaten to  pieces, had had the head replaced and was moved, but not one beat was missed.

<p>The Student Council representatives sold maroon and white Horrible Hankies that had on them the theme of the spirit emphasis, The Sting is Back.  Friday everyone was urged to wear their hankie as a bandanna with the emphasis in Banding up the Tigers who were the Hornets' opponents that week.  Each week thereafter, hankies were worn on Fridays to show unity and support for the football team as well as to identify the students as a member of the Athens Hornets.  A spirit dance was held after the football game.

<H3>INVOLVEMENT:</H3>
<p>Almost every student was involved in this activity at some time or another.  Spirit spread to the faculty which ordered Hornet jerseys to wear for the pep rallies, as well as making banners to carry at the outdoor pep rally.  The newspaper sent a photographer out to get a picture of the drum being beaten.  Students who had never expressed any interest in school activities were participating in some part of the spirit emphasis.

<H3>EVALUATION:</H3>
<p>Response was tremendous!  Over $500 was raised through the spirit chain.  Time schedules for the drum were filled within one hour after the assembly.  Spirit had not been higher in several years, and this was from students that had not won a game.  However, the students were able to see that not all victories are seen on the scoreboard.  The Hornets had been outscored, not out-done.  Pride and unity had been accomplished during these spirit activities, and it was obvious that "The Sting is Back."


</DOC>
