<heading>student attitude</heading>

<H2>SAM HOUSTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2000 Sam Houston Drive, Arlington, TX  76014

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Take a Closer Look:  Self Esteem Week</h3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>To encourage students to improve their self esteem and evaluate themselves as an individual and as a part of society.

<h3>DESCRIPTION:</h3>
<p>The emphasis was to showcase the positive characteristics each student possesses and the importance that a healthy self esteem can have on their personal responsibilities, family, friends, and their view of drugs and alcohol.

<p>The project began in January for the student council with the development of themes, seeking outside donations, seeking media coverage, and involving the community and other organizations.  Publicity was also put into full force with informative posters displayed in the hallways, flyers for every teacher to post, and P.A. announcements.  Mirrors with positive notes around them were placed in the offices allowing students to be reminded that they are unique and special.

<p>Monday was declared Take a Closer Look at Your Personal Responsibilities.  We gave yellow ribbons to every student to tie around their fingers to remember to be responsible for themselves and their actions.  Also, You Make the Call posters were put in the halls to challenge students to make right decisions.  The students were confronted with issues such as grades, values and their future plans.

<p>Take a Closer Look at You and Your Family was Wednesdays theme.  A blank note was given to each student.  During the announcements, they were encouraged to write a letter of appreciation to their parent or guardian.  Facts were also given about the lack of time children and parents spend together communicating.

<p>Thursday was a busy day.  The theme was Take a Closer Look at You and Your Friends.  Friends were encouraged to dress alike, Twin-kies.  If they participated they received a set of twinkies from the Twinkie Booth.  Also a school-wide assembly was held with Darren Turner as the speaker.  Darren was up-front and honest with the important issues facing adolescents today.  He challenged the students to make the right decisions and to remember they are unique.  Upon leaving the assembly every student received a Say No to Drugs pencil and helpful literature.  The day was a great success.  We had over 100 Twinkies given away and an excellent response to the assembly.

<p>The project culminated on Friday with Take a Closer Look at You and Drugs and Alcohol.  The morning started off with a mock disaster.  The Arlington Emergency Services provided firemen, police, paramedics and the careflight team.  The crowd watched eagerly as the unharmed drunk driver was taken off by the police but his passenger and the other cars passengers were not as lucky.  The motto for the day was Wipe Out Drugs and Alcohol.  The students were asked to wear beach attire. Sixty students wore various signs that displayed sayings such as I drank, I drove, I died.  A note about the effect of drugs and alcohol was put on every car window before school let out for spring break.

<p>The week was very successful.  All 2,300 students at Sam Houston High School were effected through handouts, the special assembly and the public address announcements.  Not only were the students of Sam Houston affected but also the community was involved.  Parents saw their children wearing I Am Loved pins, receiving appreciation notes, wearing yellow ribbons on their fingers and dressing up differently for school.  If one member of the school community was positively changed then all the planning and hard work by the Sam Houston student congress was well worth the effort.
</DOC>
