<H2>ALIEF-HASTINGS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
BOX 68, ALIEF, TX  77411-0068

<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:  Project W.I.N.</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</h3><OL>
	<LI>To defuse a problem of racial unrest in our high school.
	<LI>To make the student body aware of the implications in a name.
	<LI>To make students aware of their own prejudices.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>In the fall of 1989, Alief-Hastings surged with talk of an anti-black group forming among members of the student body.  Members of the administration were outraged and took disciplinary action against the students involved.  Racial unrest, however, continued to grow, and staff and students alike could feel the impact of the problem.  Council members decided that although we probably couldnt change attitudes overnight, if we could just make out students aware of prejudice and racism in themselves, we could be making a great step toward unity in our school.

<p>Project W.I.N.s name comes from the question Whats In a Name?  It was decided that the program would consist of an introduction, presentation of a student-produced video containing realistic situations, an in-depth discussion of these gut-level issues, and a closing.  In the introduction, students are asked, What comes to mind when I say Polak?  What comes to mind when I say Mexican or Black?

<p>Auditions for the video were open to any member of the student body, and we made the students aware of the upcoming auditions by sending a representative to selected classes.  We involved the Drama Department and the Speech Department in the audition process.  Once selected, the cast met after school to rehearse and film the 13-minute video.  The film was written, directed, and produced by Hastings students.

<p>To target the entire student body of 3,600 was unrealistic, so we instead decided on one class per English teacher.  The 35 English teachers each chose at least one class, bringing our target number to 1,050, at 30 students per class (approximately 1/3 of our school population).  The remaining 2/3 would be reached through word of mouth, by posters advertising the event and advocating our message, and by coverage in our school newspaper.  We also involved the community through coverage in our area newspaper and through coverage on Channel 2 (local NBC affiliate).

<p>As part of the introduction activities, we divided the room into three sections -- Strongly Agree on one side of the room, Strongly Disagree on the other and Undecided in between.  We then presented the participants with statements to react to and move to the side of the room which represented their opinion, such as Girls are smarter than boys to start off.  We moved gradually to more touchy statements such as, Blacks should sit in their own section of the cafeteria or Interracial dating is acceptable at Hastings.  After each statement, we invited the students to discuss their reactions to the statements.  This warm-up activity got the group involved, excited, and thinking about their own generalizations and prejudices.

<p>We then asked them to return to their seats and watch the video.  The video included scenarios about interracial dating, racial jokes, generalizations, and also evidence of white discrimination.  The students enjoyed watching their own friends and teachers in the film.

<p>After the video, we devoted 20 or so minutes to group discussion of the film.  The scenarios of the film were used as a basis for more personal issues and ideas to come up in group discussion.  The participants discussed each subject thoroughly, and in every session the general conclusion was that there is, indeed, a problem with prejudice and racism in our society and in our school.  The session ended with a discussion of the question, What can we do about this?  What can we as students of Hastings do to combat prejudice?
</DOC>
<DOC>
