<heading>student attitude</heading>

<H2>LA PRYOR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>

<H3>NAME OF THE PROJECT:  Puppy Relays</H3>

<H3>PURPOSE:</H3>
<p>One of the major goals of the La Pryor Student Council is to provide activities that improve student attitude and involve as many students as possible.  The Puppy Relays are designed to get the high school students involved with our elementary students on a positive learning basis.  Student Council members assist the younger children and encourage them to compete in physical activities.  The elementary children excel in fun activities and develop a feeling of accomplishment in themselves and pride in their class and school as a whole.

<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
<p>The Bulldog is the mascot of La Pryor High School, so we call the elementary students Puppies.  The Puppy Relays is one day of simple athletic field events for students in grades Kindergarten through Six.  Our last races were held from 8:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. on Friday at the football field behind the school.

<p>Notices are sent to all the elementary teachers describing the project and the races that the children can participate in.  The teachers are asked to encourage all of their students to participate in at least one event.  The different grade levels are divided into three categories with races as follows:<UL>

	<LI>DIVISION I - Grades K-2
	<LI>Sack Race Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>50 M Dash - Individual
	<LI>Standing Long Jump - Individual
	<LI>Potato Race Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>Balloon Race Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>DIVISION II - Grades 3 & 4
	<LI>Sack Race Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>3-legged Race - one boy, one girl teams
	<LI>Standing Long Jump - Individual
	<LI>Shuttle Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>Balloon Race - Four member teams
	<LI>100 M Dash - Individual
	<LI>DIVISION III - Grades 5 & 6
	<LI>Sack Race Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>Shuttle Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>Wheelbarrow Race - Two member Teams
	<LI>Broad Jump - Individual
	<LI>880 Relay - Four member teams
	<LI>100 M Dash - Individual
</UL>
<p>All teams are heated into events according to their divisions.  Each event (excluding the 880 Relay) has preliminary races (for elimination) and the first two teams of each heat were awarded green finalists ribbons.  These green ribbon holders race in the finals of each event for Division Champions.  The Division Winners are awarded First, Second, and Third Place ribbons respective of the place they finished.

<p>The heating of races, identifying students, and documentation of results takes a lot of organization.  The council members not only kept up with all of this, but also have to serve as coaches and judges.  It takes a three member committee a month to get everything together so that the day will run smoothly.  The Puppy Relay Committee has the following responsibilities:<UL>
	<LI>Order enough ribbons for all events (early March)
	<LI>Inform the teachers and students of rules and procedures of the races.(first 	of April)
	<LI>Collect all equipment and materials necessary for each event.  (second week 	of April)
	<LI>Heat each event by class.  (third week in April)
	<LI>Schedule races.  (last week in April)
	<LI>Assign eight high school students to each event and a Race Chairperson.  	As many as three events can be going on at one time.  (first of May)
	<LI>Assign runners for results of races.  (Relay Day)
	<LI>Heat final events by divisions.  (Relay Day)
	<LI>Announce the races and winners to the audience (Relay Day)
	<LI>Present ribbons to winners.  (Relay Day)

<H3>INVOLVEMENT:</H3>
<p>250 students participated in the Puppy Relays.  This figure includes our two students in special education.  Of the 250 students only 40 did not receive a green, blue, red, or white ribbon.  These students were presented with purple ribbons labeled Participant.  The number of ribbons awarded were green 295, blue 50, and white 50.  The student council presented a total of 445 ribbons.

<p>Our student council membership was ten last year.  We recruited 20 more students from among the student body to help run the races.

<p>The Puppy Relays surprisingly went beyond the boundaries of the school.  When parents found out about the project, they quickly became involved.  They offered to help out in any way they could; many simply became sideline coaches and cheerleaders.  Friends and relatives supplied some of the race equipment.  A small crowd of community people came out to enjoy the day.

<H3>EVALUATION:</H3>
<p>The student council was surprised at the tremendous success of the project.  The teachers were delighted with the activities and asked that the Puppy Relays become an annual event.  Parents and community leaders as well expressed their excitement and also offered their assistance in the next Puppy Relays.  They also encouraged the council to invite the La Pryor community so that they could also enjoy the activities and offer their support.

<p>As for the students, the elementary children loved it.  They practiced for two weeks before the relays and talked about it for a month afterwards.  The high school students enjoyed it, though they were exhausted by the end of the day.  They were surprised with the conclusions they reached.  They all felt that teaching elementary children is a very difficult task for special people.  It involves a lot of work, dedication, patience, and love, and the kids are worth it.


</DOC>
