<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Top Ten Projects - 1989</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image115.gif" WIDTH="319" HEIGHT="82" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><IMG SRC="../image118.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" 
ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><IMG SRC="../image204.gif" WIDTH="199"
HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<H2><BR>
BRYAN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
3401 East 29th Street, Bryan, Tx 77802 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Arena Scheduling/Office Aide Project PURPOSE:</H3>
To be of service to the staff, adminstrator, teachers and the school during
the opening of the school year. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The Bryan High School TAFE chapter gave over 70 hours of volunteer service
in August 1998 to help in the preparation of the school year. The students
spent time in the main office and in the counselor's office collating and
inserting pages in the bryan independent School District Handbook and the
Bryan High School Teacher Handbook. They stuffed inserts in student handbooks;
collated and stuffed teacher packets for In-Service; counted out and distributed
various forms to teachers mailboxes, xeroxed copies of birth certificates
and social security cards for students' permanent records; and acted as
office aides in both the main office and the counselor's office. The TAFE
members also served as hall monitors and photography aides and runners.
In addition to the clerical jobs, the students also prepared over 400 sandwiches.
The sandwiches, chips, cookies, pickles, candy, lemonade, iced tea and coffee
were served by the members each day during arena scheduling. Many teachers
could not leave their assigned area during the scheduling, so the students,
acting as hosts and hostesses, brought the food to each teacher. The TAFE
club members served approximately 500 people in the two days of arena scheduling.
<H2>CANYON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1510 IH 35 East, New Braunfels, Tx 78130-2897 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Spirit Chain Class Competition PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To enhance school-wide recognition of the Canyon High School TAFE Chapter.
<LI>To raise funds for TAFE activities. 
<LI>To stimulate school spirit and promote interest in class spirit. 
<LI>To contribute funds to each class activity fund. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Spirit Chain links were made and sold by all club members. The links were
sold two for a quarter during lunch. However, money was collected constantly.
Each class had its chain displayed in a showcase at school. As the chains
grew, so did the class competition and interest. As the cut-off deadline
drew near, TAFE received cash donations in the name of various classes from
businessmen, parents, teachers and class sponsors. Everybody got involved.
Things went wild on the last three days. TAFE called on the Pep Squad, Cheerleaders,
Vocational Education students and anyone willing to work to help cut and
attach links to each class's spirit chain. The last link was attached just
in time for the pep rally. The Cheerleaders unrolled the chains to the roar
and delight of the school and the winner was announced. Each class received
money from its chain. The winners got $125, the second, third and fourth
place winners received $75.$50, and $25. The TAFE club made over $500 profit.
All chains were taken to the football game and draped around the stadium.
<H2>CY-FAIR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Route 12, Box 8B, Houston, Tx 77040 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: What's Cooking with TAFE? Cookbook PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To unify the group. 
<LI>To promote good student/teacher relations. 
<LI>To use as a potential fund raiser. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The creation of the cookbook required group participation in that everyone
was asked to bring recipes. After the recipes were gathered, we sorted them
into these categories: appetizers, soups and salads, vegetable, main dishes,
and desserts. We then enlarged all the recipes to enhance readability. To
help with the assembly we had an all night work party at our sponsor's house.
We wanted this cookbook to help teachers with their busy schedule. Therefore,
we were careful to choose recipes that were short and easy to prepare. The
creation and promotion of this cookbook required the participation of all
TAFE members. This book is dedicated to Carlos Watkins, our principal, who
is retiring this year. A complimentary book was given to each of the teachers
at Cy-Fair High School. A copy was also given to the Carlton Cafe to aid
their vocational program in food preparation. This cookbook will also be
used to raise funds for TAFE and thus is available to the general public.
<H2>DEL VALLE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2709 Shapard Lane, Del Valle, Tx 78617 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Narrator PURPOSE:</H3>
To be of service to the Recording for the Blind Studio 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Narrator is a program whereby TAFE students read and record textbooks for
blind students. The program began with an orientation session at the Recording
for the Blind Studio in Austin, Texas. At that time the students were familiarized
with the history of the program, its policies and procedures, and the recording
equipment. The students then began attending sessions on a voluntary basis.
During the first few sesions, students were required to monitor other experienced
readers. When the students felt comfortable, they progressed to actually
running the recording equipment. The students must work up to reading and
interpreting textbooks. To provide positive reinforcement, the TAFE members
received a merit point for each visitation. If the TAFE members read for
a total of fifty hours, TAFE will have its name engraved on a plaque that
hangs in the recording studio. 
<H2>KILLEEN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
500 North 38th Street, Killeen, Tx 76543 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Adopt a Family for Christmas PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To be involved in a Christmas service project to help the less fortunate
in our community. 
<LI>To allow TAFE members a chance to participate in a worthy cause. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The club, in association with the United Methodist Church of Harker Heights,
Texas, decided to adopt a family in the community who could not afford a
Christmas for themselves. The club met with the pastor and the project director
of the church and devised a plan of action. TAFE accepted any donations
of money and food itmes from other clubs and students of Killeen High School.
The club also raised money by having candied apple sales. TAFE members collected
$341.21 and over 1200 food items from seven clubs and many individual students.
Because there was so much money and food, it was decided that the project
could take on more than one family. Therefore, two more families were added.
In all, a total of three families consisting of five adults and eleven children
were involved. Club members bought toys an clothing for the children and
the food items were distributed as follows: 
<UL>
<LI>300 items to the Killeen Food Center to help families in the community
<LI>200 items to Families in Crisis 
<LI>700 food items, broken down into three units, to the Adopt a Family
groups. 
</UL>
The club members wrapped all the toys and clothing items. They then delivered
the food and gifts to the church. When they arrived, they were met by the
pastor, district superintendent and several church members. The church delivered
the food and gifts to the tree selected families. 
<H2>LAKE WORTH HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4210 Boat Club Road, Fort Worth, Tx 76135 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Bread Basket PURPOSE:</H3>
To collect food for the Bread Basket Ministries of Fort Worth 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The Bread Basket feeds families throughout Tarrant County. This organization
helps families who are trying to make it on their own without having to
depend on welfare. Our goal was to collect food to help during the Christmas
season. To be able to collect more cans of food, TAFE challenged the other
organizations on campus to a Canned Food Duel. The organization that collected
the most cans would be treated to a Coke Party compliments of TAFE. A tally
sheet was posted in the hall to encourage competition. Daily updates were
announced over the loud speaker. Ten campus organizations were involved
in the canned food drive. They included: Fellowship of Christian Athletes,
Future Homemakers, National Honor Society, TAFE, Annual Staff, Band Choir,
the UIL Teac, DECA, and the Fellowship for Christian Students. It was heart
warming to see all the competition that took place during the drive. At
one point during the drive, the Bread Basket informed us that our cans came
in handy when the stock they had on hand was only three cans. The school
newspaper helped with weekly articles on the progress and results of the
canned food drive. The local newspaper also ran an article. 
<H2>MACARTHUR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4400 Aldine Mail Route, Houston, Tx 77039 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Teams Up PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help teachers fill out student grid sheets. 
<LI>To promote a positive teacher attitude toward TEAMS through help, treats,
and pencils during TEAMS week. 
<LI>To promote an awareness of the importance of TEAMS throughout our school
by passing out TEAMS ribbons. 
<LI>To reward students by giving candy after the completion of the test.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
When the teachers had their meeting about the TEAMS test, the TAFE members
attended. In this meeting, the members learned how to fill out the grid
sheets. Each member was assigned to a teacher. The TAFE TEAMSTER then took
the grid sheets home and brought them back completed. The TAFE TEAMSTERS
also provided their teachers with sharpened pencils and candy for the students.
On the last day of the test, each student was given a ribbon that said I
survived TEAMS. Teachers were given ribbons that said, TAFE TEAMS UP. TAFE
also put up banners in all the testing rooms that said Good Luck on TEAMS!
<H2>MANSFIELD HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1520 Walnut Creek Drive, Mansfield, Tx 76063 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: School Supply Train PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide school supplies to needy children throughout the Mansfield
Independent School District. 
<LI>To encourage cooperation among district schools in obtaining supplies.
<LI>To provide a sense of social responsibility and values in helping the
underprivileged. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE students and sponsor initiated a community project which involved all
nine schools in the district. This project entailed collecting school supplies
which ranged from pencils, paper, glue, folders, and erasers all the way
up to backpacks for carrying books. The high school was quite instrumental
in collecting the majority of supplies. Each 2nd period teacher encouraged
his or her class to bring in school supplies. The class which brought in
the most supplies in proportion to the number of students was given a catered
pizza party. Competition was stiff among the classes, but the winning class
had a 50 to 1 ratio (50 school supply items per student). The two faculty
sponsors stored the materials until TAFE members were able to divide the
materials equally. A majority of TAFE members were involved in the project
by personally distributing school supplies to the various schools. The project
received praise from faculty members, principals, and the community at large
and was publicized in the local paper. 
<H2>SPRING HILL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Route 8, Box 33, Longview, Tx 75605 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Welcome Back to the Combat Zone PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To disseminate necessary information to parents and students prior to
the start of the school year. 
<LI>To demonstrate appreciation of Spring Hill ISD teachers, adminstrators
and staff 
<LI>To provide assistance to the local chapter of the Association of Professional
Educators in the Spring Hill Independent School District. 
<LI>To participate in the Student Council's Freshmen Orientation and supply
first year students with information about our organization, its purposes,
and its recognition. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Before school started, our chapter was asked by the principal to man the
Back-to School Booth held annually at the local mall. To catch the attention
of the mall-shoppers, we decorated our booth with a military theme: Welcome
Back to the Combat Zone. The outpost received extensive media coverage by
the Longview Journal and local television stations KLMG and KLTV. The booth
material, obtained form the elementary, middle school, junior high and high
school campuses, included school calendars, medical information and supply
lists. Decked in our army outfits, we manned the combat headquarters from
8:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m.. TAFE distributed Welcome Back to the Combat Zone
bags to the entire Spring Hill ISD staff at their first faculty meeting
to show appreciation for their hard work. These bags contained items from
paper-weights to notepads. The prizes TAFE secured ranged from jewelry to
dinner for two at various restaurants in the Longview area. The president
of ATPE (Association of Texas Professional Educators) invited us to attend
their meeting to assist with refreshments and drawings. While there, we
gave a brief overview of our organization and our goals for the year. When
the Student Council asked us to participate in their Freshmen Orientation,
we jumped at the chance in hopes of increasing our organization. Since the
Combat Booth worked so well at the Mall, we decided to use it again. Our
main objective was to inform the newcomers of our club and how much fun
they too could have if they joined. Our scrapbook was prominently displayed
along with our awards from the years past. When the day was done, approximately
43 people signed an I am interested list. To ease the transition for new
students, we prepared a New Student Survival Kit. A reception was prepared
for the arivals. There they received their Survival Kits and met TAFE members.
The new students therefore were able to get a foothold on a new life in
the Spring Hill Combat Zone. To encourage the other clubs to get off to
a good and rapid strat, and to continue our theme Welcome Back to the Combat
Zone, TAFE sponsored a poster contest. In early September, we distributed
the rules and regulations of the contest to all the school organizations.
The participants ranged from both boys and girls athletics to the National
Honor Society, the final winner of the contest. In review, this first project
was to set the tone of our chapter. Not only did we establish better relations
with the school and community, but also with the other organizations on
campus. Compliments on the project have been received from many teachers
and students. We are pleased with the results and are looking forward to
repeating this successful project again next year. 
<H2>TASCOSA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
3921 Westlawn, Amarillo, Tx 79102 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Olympics PURPOSE:</H3>
To serve as a fund raise and a way to get other clubs involved in a fun
activity for the entire school to enjoy. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE Olympics is an annual event at Tascosa High School and a major fund
raise for the Tascosa TAFE Chapter. The project involves 100 people from
various groups or organziations at Tascosa. Ten people from each groups
form a team. The ten teams compete in various activities such as the penny
carry, ring pass, thre-legged race, crab crawl, and many other fun relays.
The teams are given points according to how well they perform each relay.
This is where the TAFE members come in. Two TAFE members are assigned to
a team. One keeps score and the other thells the teams how to do each relay
to make sure they follow the rules properly. The Olympics are held one day
a year during homeroom. Each student must pay to see the Olympics before
he can leave homeroom. The vent is one that attracts the majority of the
students at Tascosa High School. It also attracts the teachers because they
usually have a team compete. This year the TAFE Chapter invited the Excellence
Council, which consists of parents and other Tascosa fans, to attend. Each
year the TAFE Chapter awards trophies & ribbons to the teams with the most
points and to the most spirited team. Every participating team receives
a ribbon for taking part in the TAFE Olympics as a keepsake for the club
and as a token of appreciation from the TAFE Chapter. TAFE made $450 while
involving the whole school in a fun activity. It will continue to be an
annual event at Tascosa High School. 
