<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image115.gif" WIDTH="319" HEIGHT="82" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image87.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="../image205.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><BR>
</CENTER>
<H2>KILLEEN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
500 N. 38th Street, Killeen, Tx 76543 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: A T.A.F.E. Christmas<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To perform a service project for the less fortunate in Killeen 
<LI>To allow Killeen High School and members of T.A.F.E. to be involved
in a beneficial project. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The club decided to have our 1989 Christmas project involve several needy
organizations. A $500 cash donation and 2,000 food item donations were set
as their goals. They began collection from the student body and teachers
in the first week of December and the actual drive lasted for two weeks.
The club raised money by having a candy apple and bake sale. At the end
of the two week period, the members had collected $805 and over 4,000 food
items. The club's goals were surpassed. The club members used the money
to buy clothing for selected families and other types of perishable foods.
<H3>The club gave to the following:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Families in Crises - Three families of 3 adults and 11 children. 
<LI>Mission Food Kitchen (Feed meals to the needy every day) - 1500 food
items and several turkeys. 
<LI>Harker Heights United Methodist Church - 750 canned goods for food pantry.
<LI>Harker Heights Church (sponsored a family) - food, clothing and toys.
</OL>
The club members wrapped the presents and then delivered these items to
Families in Crisis, The Soup Kitchen, and to the Harker Heights Methodist
Church. <BR>
<BR>
This project involved all the twenty-one members of the club. The club spent
approximately 200 work hours on this project. Many people had a T.A.F.E.
Christmas due to the efforts of our organization and the students and teachers
of KHS. 
<H2>L.D. BELL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1601 Brown Trail, Hurst, Tx 76054 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Child Lures<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To provide third and fourth grade students in the H-E-B School District
with awareness of the lures and devices child molesters use to entice children
away from their familiar surroundings. The project was originated in response
to an increased number of reported child abuse cases in our area. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE students, in conjunction with the SWAT (Students Working All Together)
officers, studied Dr. Ken Wooden's Video (purchased by our district): about
the eleven most common lures that child molesters use to entice children.
Our TAFE/SWAT students wrote a script for eleven brief skits, added props,
trained about sixty students from our high schools, and then performed the
skits numerous times in scheduled classrooms throughout the district. Fifteen
to twenty TAFE trainers participated as well as any other TAFE/SWAT student
who would give up two Sunday afternoons to be trained to perform the eleven
skits. <BR>
<BR>
The elementary school teachers were ecstatic about having such positive
role models in their classrooms. (They also appreciated the extra grading
time.) Before visiting the elementary schools, TAFE and SWAT trainers performed
the skits for interested parents in the Bell High cafeteria and then answered
questions and made changes in the script based on parents' suggestions.
The wording of the scripts had to be appropriate and sensitive to students'
ages. <BR>
<BR>
Our TAFE and SWAT trainers were filmed by the news teams of three local
news stations, and articles and pictures of the project were in the Mid-Cities
Daily News, the Star-Telegram, the Dallas Morning News, and the Dallas Times
Herald as well as on our local cable channel, Cable 28. The Today show has
expressed an interest in doing a 3-minute segment using our Cable 28 film.
Apparently, we're the only school district in the nation with an organized
Child Lures effort. The TAFE/SWAT trainers had a feeling of satisfaction
at having participated in a project which could actually save lives. 
<H2>MACARTHUR SENIOR HIGH</H2>
4400 Aldine Mail Route, Houson, Tx 77039 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Welcomes 32 New Apples to our Teaching Tree<BR>
PURPOSE</H3>
To help the numerous new teachers to feel more comfortable at MacArthur,
to introuce these faculty members to the returning staff and to familiarize
the new members of the faculty with TAFE. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
On the new teachers' inservice day, our president came to MacArthur and
took pictures of all the new faculty members. We then mounted the pictures
on apples and wrote the teachers' name at the bottom. The bulletin board
in the Teachers' Lounge was decorated with a tree and the apples were attached
to the tree. We called it our Teaching Tree. Then, buttons were made for
the new teachers with their names on them. At the general meeting with the
entire faculty we introduced the new teachers and gave them a cup filled
with teacher goodies such as red pens, paper clips, staples, etc. The board
was left in the lounge for about a month. <BR>
<BR>
The teachers who were not new to the building really liked having the names
and pictures of the new staff members visible for them to get to know. The
new teachers thanked us for making then feel more welcome. 
<H2>JOHN JAY HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
7611 Marbach, San Antonio, Tx 78227 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Teaches!<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide real teaching experiences upon which interested students
might base their choice for a career in teaching. 
<LI>To familiarize prospective teachers with the intent and value of the
Texas Teacher Appraisal System. 
<LI>To develop an awareness of the personal, academic and professional requirements
involved in teaching. 
<LI>To provide a service to the school and faculty. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
T.A.F.E. members observed classes, prepared lesson plans and taught classes
under the supervision of teachers at John Jay High School, Passmore Elementary,
and Meadow Village Elementary School. The duration of the period of observation
and teaching depended upon factors such as scheduling, aptitude, previous
experience, subject matter, class make-up and preference of the student
or supervising teacher. The average period of assignment was about one week.
<BR>
<BR>
Administrators and teachers at the schools involved were informed of the
intent and mechanics of the project by T.A.F.E. sponsors and asked permission
to proceed. Collection and coordination of teachers and students schedules,
subject area and grade level preferences was taken care of by the T.A.F.E.
chapter president, Sandra Trujillo. After organizing this, Sandra met individually
with each student to explain the program in detail, answer questions and
to provide each with a letter of introduction to the supervising teacher.
She also provided each with several copies of the Student Teacher Observation
Form. This form, prepared by sponsors, is based on the TTAS instrument and
is intended to direct the student in both his/her observation of the training
teacher and in planning his/her own lessons. <BR>
<BR>
The faculty members involved gained both short and long term benefits. The
immediate benefits were that they had the assistance of highly motivated
future teachers. Also, they were awarded appreciation badges and apples.
The long term benefit will come as a result of their having helped advance
their profession by beginning the training of future teachers. <BR>
<BR>
The students who did not get a chance to do the actual teaching in a large
class were teachers to students preparing for the TEAMS test. There were
many TAFE members involved in this project, including a student teaching
at the pre-kinder level, one teaching biology to freshmen and one teaching
pre-algebra to upper level high school students. 
<H2>MARTIN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4501 W. Pleasant Ridge, Arlington, Tx 76016 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Martin/Corey Study-Buddy Project</H3>
</H3>PURPOSE:</H3> 
<OL>
<LI>To benefit the elementary &quot;At-Risk&quot; students and thereby slow
down the ever rising number of dropouts. 
<LI>To provide a free tutorial program in which Martin students go to Corey
to tutor Corey students for 30 minutes, once a week. 
<LI>To set up a system in which Martin students would help the elementary
students by telephone on days they did not meet for tutoring. 
<LI>To organize social functions several times throughout the year so that
the Corey parents and Martin students could get better acquainted. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Roughly eighty percent of our TAFE chapter is involved in the program. The
other students involved are the forty Corey students benefiting from this
free tutorial program. All of the Corey faculty are involved in this project
in that they select the At-Risk students to participate and continually
provide the tutors with material in which the Corey student is weak. In
this way, the Martin tutor can help strengthen his Study-Buddy in that area.
<BR>
<BR>
As a result of newspaper and television coverage, many Corey parents have
called their school, requesting that their children be included in the Study-Buddy
project. The project has become so popular that some Martin students have
more than one elementary student to tutor. Martin students have shown remarkable
maturity and commitment to these children. 
<H2>SPRING HILL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Route 8, Box 33, Longview, Tx 75605 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Loblolly Jubilee<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To encourage the development and display of school spirit. 
<LI>To put forth a positive image in the community. 
<LI>To inform the community about Spring Hill's TAFE chapter. 
<LI>To meet needs in the community for student volunteers. 
<LI>To develop leadership skills in participating members. 
<LI>To enhance the image of Gregg County by serving as hosts to tourists.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The Longview Chamber of Commerce had invited two large area schools to provide
student volunteers for the first annual Gregg County Loblolly Jubilee. At
the last minute (literally) one school informed the Chamber that they could
not provide the 22 students needed to serve as hosts at the Jubilee. Spring
Hill Superintendent, Mike Crossland, offered our TAFE chapter the opportunity
to meet this need in the community. Within 45 minutes we had committed 22
students plus 4 alternates to serve as hosts. <BR>
<BR>
One of our students served as a hostess at a street dance the very night
we signed up students to work. Another student represented TAFE, Spring
Hill High School, Longview and Gregg County by serving as Loblolly Jubilee
mascot, Lolly, and by meeting celebrity Kimberly Simms, star of Guiding
Light at the Longview airport. <BR>
<BR>
Throughout the Loblolly Jubilee, the Spring Hill TAFE members served as
gracious hosts representing the best of our community. Students wore mascot
uniforms and passed out information, directed tourists to various exhibits
and entertained children. Twenty-six members were directly involved in this
project. As a result of our service and ability to serve on short notice,
we have been promised a prominent part in all future Jubilees. 
<H2>SPRING HILL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Route 8, Box 33, Longview, Tx 75605 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Leaders of the Pack<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To encourage high attendance by the Spring Hill High School student
body during the average daily attendance month of October. 
<LI>To obtain the optimum amount of funds available from the state for our
school's use. 
<LI>To obtain prizes from the Greater Longview area for those students with
perfect weekly attendance and grand prizes for those with perfect monthly
attendance. 
<LI>To promote businesses in the Lonview area through their donations to
an education-related project while supporting school attendance and development
of student leadership. 
<LI>To develop leadership in outstanding Spring Hill students. 
<LI>To acquaint community leaders with our Spring Hill TAFE chapter. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Based on the average daily attendance of students taken during the month
of October, the state decide how much financial support a school will receive.
To give our school the highest daily attendance, as well as the highest
possible revenue, we decided to sponsor a project to help decrease the number
of student absences. <BR>
<BR>
An attendance contest was held during the accounting period of October.
At the end of each week, the names of students who had perfect attendance
were entered in a drawing for prizes donated by area merchants. During the
final week of the contest, the names of those with perfect attendance for
the entire month were entered in a drawing for several grand prizes. The
prizes were obtained by TAFE members and displayed in a glass-enclosed room
at the entrance of our school for all to see. The prizes ranged from jewelry,
pizzas, and movie passes to cash prizes. Homecoming at our school fell during
this accounting period and many ex-students visited the high school and
saw the display. We feel this was a great way to advertise the area business
in Longview, while supporting public education. <BR>
<BR>
For an extra incentive, TAFE selected students from those with perfect monthly
attendance to be Lonview City Officials for a Day. The offices included
those of City Manager, Gregg County Sheriff, Police Chief, Fire chief, District
Attorney and Mayor of Longview. The students who received these honors were
selected by a panel consisting of a TAFE officer, the TAFE sponsor, the
school principal, a counselor and three teachers. The panel's job was to
select six students they thought exhibited leadership, citizenship, and
academic excellence. Academic excellence was interpreted as meaning that
the student was working to fulfill his or her academic potential. In fact,
the student chosen to serve as Sheriff of Gregg County was a former drop-out!
This project was used by our administrators as part of their at-risk program
to prevent students from dropping out of school. <BR>
<BR>
The students spent the day with their city or county official and learned
of the many duties and responsibilities that accompany these jobs. While
there, the students actually ran the office. When the day was done, the
students came back with a wealth of information and memories to last a lifetime.
The project was such a success that the city officials have requested that
it become an annual event. The principal commended us for the project and
for the large amount of work that was put forth by the TAFE members. We
also received media attention for it. There was a front page picture, as
well as a story in the Campus Corner section for the Longview Journal. Two
local television stations also reported the event. <BR>
<BR>
Because of this project, we experienced the lowest rate of absences in years.
The faculty helped to advertise the project and were relieved at the limited
amount of make-up work they had to supervise during October. 
<H2>MANSFIELD HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1520 Walnut Creek Drive, Mansfiled, Tx 76063 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: School Supply Drive<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To collect supplies for needy children of the Mansfield Independent School
District and to collect enough for the entire year in hopes of outfitting
the needy children on all of the campuses in our district. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
To achieve our goals, our president gave a special presentation, explaining
about our idea to the school board. After this presentation, we gained approval
and a special blessing form the Superintendent of Mansfield Schools. <BR>
<BR>
We then informed the entire Mansfield community of our efforts to gather
supplies through the use of media coverage and notes sent home with every
student intended to inform parents of our purpose. <BR>
<BR>
Each TAFE officer coordinated the collection of supplies for his/her jurisdiction.
Everyone was responsible for a campus in the district and acted as liaison
for the campus. We successfully collected over 6,000 items during a two
week period. 
<H2>CANYON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1510 IH 35, New Braunfels, Tx 78130-2897 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Financial Aid for Education Majors<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To find the scholarships, grants and loans available to college students
majoring in education. To inform TAFE members at the state conference of
money available for education majors. To develop planning and work skills
necessary to carry out a year long project. To develop materials, visual
aids and team work necessary for a presentation of findings. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE graduates have found that college expenses are tremendous. Many found
out too late that there were scholarships, grants and loans developed especially
for students majoring in education. A committee was formed to contact all
colleges in Texas as well as U.S. senators and respresentatives and State
senators and representatives, asking about financial aid for Education majors.
Letters to senators were used in government classes to show how government
can help students. The school counselors asked for a copy of information
received to use in updating their files and the academic booster club (
a parent group) asked for information to be presented at one of their meetings
concerning our findings. <BR>
<BR>
Work was divided into three major categories: 1. Seeking, 2. Cataloging,
and 3. Presenting information on financial aid. <BR>
<BR>
The Seekers wrote, typed, copied, folded and stuffed envelopes. Approximately
75 letters were mailed to colleges in Texas. <BR>
<BR>
The Catalogers developed a notebook and recorded all information received.
These students had to read through all responses and determine which met
TAFE needs. A file of all material received was developed and given to the
high school counselor as well as to the academic booster club. <BR>
<BR>
The Presenters developed a 30 minute presentation to be give at the State
TAFE Conference in March. This group had to develop a presentation with
visual aids and handouts that would inform without boring the audience.
The same presentation was made at the academic booster club meeting. <BR>
<BR>
As a result of this project, TAFE members are aware of financial aid available
for college. They also developed skills necessary to work as a team on a
year long activity. 
<H2>NATALIA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Box 548, Natalia, Tx 78058 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Form a Student Council TAFE Style<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
It was the strong feeling of Natalia's TAFE chapter that educators should
form their priorities around the educational needs of students. At Natalia
there was a strong need for a student leadership program. The TAFE members
felt that a good student leadership program should include a more active
student council than the current council. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The TAFE chapter began its project in April by taking three potential student
council leaders for 1989-90 to the Texas Association of Student Councils
(TASC) State convention in Austin where they learned how active student
councils from other schools operated. Over the summer the TAFE chapter developed
a plan for a student council for 1989-90 with the approval of the new student
council sponsor. Next the TAFE chapter raised money and saw to it that the
school for the first time became a member of TASC, the Alamo Association
of Student Councils(AASC), the National Association of Student Councils
and the National School Safety Program by paying the appropriate dues. After
summer workshops, student were recruited to the first meeting in 1989 of
the AASC, which took place September 28th at Lackland High School, so that
they could get a better picture of the TASC and AASC projects. Later in
the fall, new council members were taken to other AASC leadership workshops.
<BR>
<BR>
As a result of this TAFE sponsored leadership development, an active student
council began to function at N.H.S. For the first time in the schools history,
sportmanship activities such as inter-school gift exchanges and friendship
presentations began taking place at football games. For the first time in
any recent history at NHS visiting schools found their own sides decorated
in their own school colors by the Student Council. The NHS Council also
entered the TASC competitions for Outstanding Safety, SMILE and NEED School.
A number of
</DOC>
