<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../image115.gif" WIDTH="319" HEIGHT="82" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="../image87.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="../image206.gif" WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></CENTER>
<H2><BR>
CHILDRESS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
800 Avenue J N.W., Childress Tx 79201 Rita Evans, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To honor and recognize the graduating seniors. 
<LI>To encourage positive interaction an goodwill among all students. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
For a two-week period, TAFE members distributed - at no cost - blank senior
goodbye message forms throughout the school. Students and teachers completed
the notes filled with best wishes, congratulations and personal notes of
friendship. <BR>
<BR>
The complete notes were returned to TAFE members. The project committee
made a special envelope for each senior and enclosed their notes inside.
On TAFE Senior Day, all seniors were dismissed early to eat together in
the cafeteria which was decorated in the cafeteria. <BR>
<BR>
This project was extremely successful. Over 2,000 notes were distributed.
Teachers found time to say goodbye to their students, and friends wrote
the seniors notes of best wishes. The seniors were touched by the encouraging
words and recollections of fond memories of their school days. The seniors
expressed appreciation to TAFE for their &quot;keepsakes&quot;. The entire
school joined in this project to wish success to the Class of 1990. 
<H2>SAM RAYBURN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2121 Cherrybrook, Pasadena, Tx 77502-4198 Katherine Nassar, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Kid Care - Food and Book Drive<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this project was to help feed hungry children in our area
who do not receive proper nourishment. Proper nourishment is vital to learning.
We also supplied books for the less fortunate children who do not have access
to many books outside of school. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
During the months of December and January, TAFE members collected donated
food and books for KID CARE. KID CARE is a non-profit organization run by
Hurt and Carol Porter who keep the food pantry in their house and run the
KID CARE operation out of their home. The Porters feed hundreds of hungry
children every day. <BR>
<BR>
Our main reason for getting involved was that we felt that a child who does
not receive proper nourishment will not be able to be successful in the
classroom. Donations were received from local grocery stores, teachers and
citizens of our community. The books were donated by the school district
textbook custodian. The TAFE members had to sort the books at the textbook
warehouse during the Christmas holidays. <BR>
<BR>
The food and books were delivered to Mrs.Porter during January. She was
very excited that we had gotten involved. We were the first high school
oganization to take an interest in the program. Mrs. Porter asked TAFE if
we would like to help in the organization of KID CARE clubs across the state.
Our chapter accepted the challenge and plans to help lay the gound work
for developing the new clubs. 
<H2>CHRISTOVAL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Box 162, Christoval, Tx 76935 Jenny Mize, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Books for Ballinger:<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide the teachers at Ballinger Junior High School with needed
teaching materials and books after a fire destroyed their facilities. 
<LI>To provide insight into emergency intervention under crisis circumstances.
<LI>To demonstrate the effectiveness of committee action and team work.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
On December 3, 1990, Ballinger Junior High School was burned down by arsonists.
In response to this tragic event, the Christoval TAFE chapter organzied
a committee to begin soliciting for teaching materials and unused books
to present to Ballinger to help the teachers cope with the situation. Our
committee immediately began calling various school districts and seeking
contributions. Area teachers responded eagerly and members began collecting
the materials. The majority of the materials were brought to the district
TAFE convention in Bronte. Afterwards, the committee arranged for these
supplies to be transported to Ballinger. <BR>
<BR>
The faculty at Christoval High School was supportive, allowing the TAFE
members to use the counselor's office and phones as a base of operations.
Although it was sometimes difficult to locate a person at other school districts
to organize a collection, committee members were persistent. This persistence,
along with assistance from our sponsor and faculty allowed us to make an
important contribution to the school, teachers, and students of Ballinger
Junior High School after the loss of their facilities. 
<H2>CANYON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1510 IH 35, New Braunfels, Tx 78130, Merle Kaderli, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Remembrance Tree<BR>
PURPOSE: To increase the awareness of the students, faculty, staff and community
concerning people serving in the Middle East. To provide a way to recognize
and honor the service men and women serving in the Middle East. To proved
an outlet for patriotism for school and community. </OL>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
A large paper tree was placed in the main hall of the high school with clouds
that stated Cougars Support Our Troops. Students, staff and faculty were
asked to turn in names of friends, relatives and former students who were
serving in the Middle East. As names were received they were placed on a
yellow strip of paper with an American flag, stars and yellow ribbons. These
strips were then added to the tree. A dedication ceremony was held in which
the school band and choir performed the national anthem and America. A patriotic
poem was read and each name from the tree was read. A second tree had to
be added to accommodate additional names. <BR>
<BR>
Many TAFE members were involved in making the tree and the decorated strips
with the names on them. All students, faculty, staff and community members
were encouraged to turn in names of servicemen and women. The project grew
to be so massive that it required TAFE to join hands with the Student Council
and the counselor's office. The student body president and the TAFE president
hosted the ceremony and read each name that was on the tree. The entir gathering
remained totally silent thoughout the reading. The program ended with a
moment of silence and the band and choir performing America. The tree remained
in the main hall until the war ended. It was a way for each of us to stay
in touch with the real meaning of freedom. 
<H2>NIMITZ HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2005 W.W. Thorne, Houston, Tx 77073-3498,Leslie Rowney, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Cougar Spirit Face Painting<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To introduce the Nimitz Chapter of the Texas Association of Future Educators
to the student body and community. 
<LI>To enhance school spirit during the 1990 football season. 
<LI>To raise funds for the operation of the chapter. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Members of TAFE painted student and faculty faces with spirit symbols during
lunch periods on game days for the varsity football team. They also set
up a booth at the home varsity football games and painted faces with spirit
symbols for the public. The cost was fifty cents ($.50) per person. A total
of $486.00 was raised. All members of the chapter participated in the project
by painting faces and by having their faces painted. 
<H2>GILMER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Drawer 40, Gilmer, Tx 75644 Suzanne Bardwell, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Making a Difference with T.A.F.E.<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide Christmas gifts for an Upshur County foster child (sole source
for Christmas items - Gilmer TAFE) 
<LI>To collect coats and warm clothing for needy children of Upshur County.
<LI>To encourage a sense of civic spirit on the part of TAFE members. 
<LI>To encourage leadership skills on the part of TAFE members (organizational
skills, motivational skills, commitment to supplying the coats and money
necessary to make the project successful). 
<LI>To teach TAFE members the rewards and joy of giving to those less fortunate.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE members chose to raise money to sponsor an Uphur County foster child
for Christmas. Due to the depressed economy of East Texas, the Department
of Human Resources was having a difficult time securing sponsors for foster
childrens' Christmas gifts. Gilmer TAFE members generously rose to the occasion.
Member collected the money and purchased gifts on the list of a county child.
At the same time, the Upshur County Sheriff's Department was sponsoring
a coat drive for underprivileged children. Gilmer TAFE supplied over 65
coats for infants to teenagers in a county-wide drive that netted a total
of 200 coats. <BR>
<BR>
Almost the entire membership (75 members) participated enthusiastically
in this project. Faculty and staff members of Gilmer High School also supported
and participated in this project through donations. The Sheriff's Department,
Department of Human Resources staf and Foster Parents' Association of Upshur
County were very appreciative and proud of the efforts of the Gilmer TAFE
chapter. 
<H2>MANSFIELD HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1520 Walnut Creek Drive, Mansfield, Tx 76063 Linda Williams, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: School Supply Collection<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help students who could not afford to buy school supplies. 
<LI>To promote school spirit by creating competition between classes. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Our local TAFE chapter conducted a district-wide school supply collection.
In August, during the week of inservice for teachers, our president, Jennifer
Dyer, requested that she be placed on the agenda to speak to the principals
and administrators at their initial meeting for the school year. She presented
our idea for a service project, the school supply drive. Each of the principals
gave his/her support for the project. <BR>
<BR>
Various members were assigned to act as liaison representatives with the
nine schools in our district. The Mansfield Association of Texas Professional
Educators (ATPE) building representatives helped the TAFE members coordinate
the materials needed for the campus collections. Our high school vocational
printing classes printed 6,000 notes that were distributed on each campus
for the students to take home t0 their parents. These notes explained our
project and urged each student to donate new school supplies. We also had
an article announcing our collection placed in the city newspaper and posters
were made for each of our nine campuses. <BR>
<BR>
After about two weeks, we collected the supplies from each campus, sorted
the items and redistributed them. The principals were given the items to
distribute on each campus as they deemed fit. Our high school campus held
a class competition. Each 3rd period class brought supplies and we counted
them for the rations of items to the number of students in each class. The
winning class brought 137 items per person. The prize for the winning class
was a pizza and coke party. The total number of items collected was nearly
3000. 
<H2>MARTIN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4501 West Pleasant Ridge, Arlington, Tx 76016 Teri Foster and Dixie Porcher,
Sponsors 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: How to Have a Happy Halloween<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this project was to educate the elementary school students
on how to have a safe Halloween. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The Martin High School TAFE chapter wanted to have a service project that
would involve working with the elementary school children so we decided
to put on a skit that would teach the younger students some basic safety
rules that would help them have a safe and happy Halloween. <BR>
<BR>
The TAFE students started by listing the safety tips that they wanted to
include in the skit and then wrote the skit to include those tips. We enlisted
the support of the principal of Corey Elementary School who said that we
were welcome to present the skit to the students. The teachers and their
students were very receptive to our play and the TAFE students felt that
it was an extremely worthwhile project. It made us feel good that we were
a part of helping the younger students have an enjoyable and safe Halloween.
<H2>REAGAN COUNTY HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1111 12th Street, Big Lake, Tx 76932-3599,Kathleen Gray, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFFY<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To provide a means of communication for sharing ideas and information among
the three campuses in the Reagan County ISD. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFFY is a newsletter for the faculty and staff of Reagan County Independent
School District. The staff of the newsletter consists of a mommittee of
nine TAFE members, two TAFE sponsors, three faculty members - one from each
campus - who serve as reporters, the campus principals, and the superintendent
who servs as a columnist. <BR>
<BR>
TAFFY is published approximately twice per month. The staff meets to decide
on articles, the Teacher of the Month and other current topics. Articles
and interviews are assigned. The faculty members and administrators contribute
articles, letters, professional information, calendar of events and even
birthdays. The newsletter is published and distributed to approximately
160 RCISD employees and board members. 
<H2>BREWER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1000 South Cherry Lane, Fort Worth, Tx 76108 -3298 Nancy Wright and Carolyn
Dickinson, Sponsors 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Puppets, Books and Smiles<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help elementary students develop good listening skills. 
<LI>To aid the teacher in laying a foundation for reading enjoyment. 
<LI>To be of service to elementary teachers by providing listening and reading
aides for students. 
<LI>To allow TAFE members the opportunity to get classroom experience with
younger students. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE members who participated in the project bought a Golden Book of their
choice. They then chose a main character in the story to illustrate by making
a hand puppet representing that character. Each hand puppet was identical
in dress and color to the main character in the story. Members purchased
felt squares which they cut out and decorated in a special meeting. Members
then took the unassembled puppets home and sewed them together on a sewing
machine. Later, when all the puppets were finished, the sponsors contacted
an elementary school to arrange a time for the students to go. <BR>
<BR>
The members were invited to the kindergarten pod where they read stories
to the children using the puppets as narrator. When the stories were finished,
the kindergarteners were encouraged to play with the puppets and to tell
what they like best about the story. <BR>
<BR>
This project was so successful that we have decided to make puppets for
all kindergarten or first grade pods in the elementary schools in this district.
</BODY>
