<H2>GILMER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 40, Gilmer, Tx 75644 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Gilmer TAFE's Most Spirited Adventure!<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To boost school spirit 
<LI>To encourage students and community members to actively support the
Buckeye football team 
<LI>To recognize the efforts of groups within the school tht often go unrecognized
<LI>To illustrate to TAFE members, other students, faculty and community
the rewards of enthusiastically participating in support of the school 
<LI>To raise funds to sponsor an Upshur County foster child for Christmas
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE members decided to see if they could contribute toward school pride
and enthusiasm by boosting spirit amoung the high school student body, faculty,
elementary school and community. TAFE made spirit posters and balloons for
the football team and placed them on the fence of the stadium at home games.
We also made ghost cookies for them when they played our arch rival Gladwater
on Halloween and made a huge locker room poster that said: Gladwater doesn't
have a ghost of a chance. As we moved toward the play-offs, TAFE began making
hundreds of spirit rags (one foot orange squares) which were sold at games
for 25 cents each. We also made special black and orange spirit rags for
the football team and cheerleaders. As we advanced in the play-offs it was
amazing to see the impact of a little square of orange cloth! The community
Buckeye fans went wild over them and it was an awesome sight to see the
Gilmer stands awash in a sea of orange flags while fans of all ages performed
the tomahawk yell. The coaches and team were amazed and inspired by the
support generated among fans which had a reputation for just sitting and
watching. The players would even turn and start the yell quite often. TAFE
felt it had a part in the Buckeyes going all the way to Regionals in the
state play-offs! TAFE easily raised the money to sponsor an Upshur County
foster child for Christmas. TAFE members also painted faces at the elementary
school and high school on Fridays generating a lot of enthusiasm and excitement!
Our first customer was the high school principal. <BR>
<BR>
TAFE also made spirit posters and cookies for out Special Olympics athletes,
cross-country team, FFA members and band prior to their various competitions.
The response was wonderful! 
<H2>HUNTINGTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 328, Huntington, Tx 75949 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Collect a Book, Give a Book<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Parents will be made aware of the importance of reading to younger children.
<LI>Kindergarten students will be more interested in reading. 
<LI>TAFE members will be made aware fo the less fortunate children with
little encouragement at home. 
<LI>Elementary will be aware of the help available through TAFE 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
During the months of October and November, the TAFE members collected childrens
books. Some books were brought in from their own homes, some were collected
at the school, and in the community. <BR>
<BR>
After the books were collected, the students spent two weeks getting the
books in good condition to give to the students. They pasted an insert in
each book with each child's name written on that insert. It stated, &quot;This
book is presented to (child's name) by Texas Association of Future Educators
Parents, please read to your children every night.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
This project was quite successful. The local television station came to
film the event. Many kindergarten students were overjoyed at receiving their
-first very own book. The TAFE members stayed in the classes for about an
hour reading to the students. 
<H2>MARTIN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
4501 West Pleasant Ridge Road, Arlington, Tx 76016 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAAS Test Buster Pep Rally<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this project is to improve student attitudes toward any test
and to teach useful test-taking strategies. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Over 100 people participated in this Pep Rally, including the cheerleaders
and drill teams from Mary Moore Elementary Corey Elementary, and Martin
High School. Others involved included the staff of the previously mentioned
schools. <BR>
<BR>
The TAAS Test Buster Pep Rally was a motivational half-hour assembly program
that improves student performance on standardized achievement test. This
program included fun and informative skits, cheers form cheerleaders, a
dance performed by the drill teams and songs that encourage students to
do their best on tests. All of the elementary students really enjoyed and
learned from the Pep Rally. This performance helped boost the elementary
students' confidence along with helping Martin students deal with test anxiety.
<BR>
<BR>
Here is an example of a Test Buster Cheer:
<UL>
<LI>If I eat a good breakfast and get my rest, 
<LI>I'll be ready for that test! 
<LI>If I try to relax and get rid of stress 
<LI>I'll be ready to bust that test! 
<LI>I can do it, I can do It, I can beat that test! 
<LI>If I don't know an answer, I will guess, 
<LI>I'll never give up, just do my best. 
</UL>
<H2>CHILDRESS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
800 Avenue J, N.W., Childress, Texas 79201 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT Paint the New Year Drug and Alcohol Free<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide a healthy fun alternative for high school and college-age
students on New Year's Eve. 
<LI>To increase students' awareness that a party does not have to include
drugs. 
<LI>To prevent drug and alcohol use on New Year's Eve. 
<LI>To promote a drug-free school environment. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE hosted a Drug and Alcohol Free New Year's Eve Party and Dance on December
31, 1991. The event was held in the CHS cafeteria. This event was totally
free! There was no admittance charge, and the food and games were free.
Guests were given a wrist band showing they were a part of TAFE's Drug and
Alcohol Free New Year's Eve. This party/dance was a part of our school's
drug free plan. TAFE members were totally involved in this project from
the planning through the decorating of the cafeteria with big paint cans,
confetti, streamers, and balloons. Publicity, food, and decorating commitees
actively set in motion an evening that will always be remembered by CHS
students. KQ106 provided the music, lights, and countdown to 1992. The arrangement
of our building allowed us to plan one side for dancing and the other for
the party. The party included movies on a big screen telelvision, ping,
pong, Nintendo and computer games and food! Over 200 students were on hand
for this celebration at midnight with traditional noise makers and hats.
Everyone welcomed in the 1992 drug and alcohol free as 300 balloons dropped
from the ceiling! 
<H2>BANDERA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 727, Bandera, Tx 78003 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: T.A.F.E. Teach-In<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide an opportunity for interested students, faculty, and patrons
of Bandera ISD to learn about World War II through a sharing of oral history.
<LI>To honor and recognize area World War II veterans for their service
to our country in conjunction with the fifty year anniversary of our entry
into the war. 
<LI>To encourage leadership skills among TAFE members. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Bandera area World War II veterans were contacted through the American Legion,
Veterans of Foreign Wars and Disabled American Veterans and invited to attend
a reception in their honor. The reception was open to all interested students,
faculty, and patrons of the district and was promoted through circulars,
the local newspaper, and the bank marquee in town. There was a high degree
of involvement among TAFE members by aiding in advertising, providing and
serving refreshments and/or attending the Teach-In. Other faculty members
were in attendance, including our principal who gave a brief speech. The
majority in attendance were community members. Eleven World War II veterams
attended and visited with the group. Many of them brought memorabilia from
the war. The children's Bell Choir (primary and elementary age) from a local
church performed the song, America, for the group. Several parents of students
and spouses of veterans were present as well. <BR>
<BR>
Our chapter parliamentarian opened the program with the Pledge of Allegiance,
followed by a welcome by our president. The veterans were then introduced
individually to speak. As they described places and battles, the locations
were flagged on a large world map on display. Their experiences were fascinating
- representing almost every major theater of the war. After all of the veterans
had spoken and our principal had expressed his gratitude, the chapter vice-president
closed the program and invited everyone to stay for refreshments and to
visit informally. An unexpected highlight of the program was a presentation
to the TAFE chapter by the local American Legion chapter of a book which
had been commissioned by the Bandera County Historical Society -Bandera
County Veterans in All Wars. 
<H2>CALVERT HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 7, Calvert, Tx 77837 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Grandparent Adoption of Nursing Home Residents<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To initiate students to the fact that some day we all grow old and that
we need to make our older generation realize that they are still needed
and to make students aware that they can and should play a big part in community
service. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The Calvert TAFE chapter chose to look at several topics before selecting
one that all felt comfortable with. After visiting the local nursing home,
the students held a quick meeting and advised me that they wanted to adopt
all of the residents, as they did not want to leave anyone out. They then
set up a meeting with the Administrator and the Director of Recreation and
after the meeting and with full approval of the Administrator they set to
work. <BR>
<BR>
The first thing the chapter did was to design and make an Adoption Certificate
for each grandparent and frame it. Next we gathered at the nursing home
and the students presented each grandparent with their certificate. There
were so many smiles, hugs and tears, it made you want to do something outstanding
for these grandparents every week. <BR>
<BR>
Every Wednesday after school, they all assemble at the nursing home where
they immediately check with the staff to see what they need to do for their
adopted grandparents. They either visit, read, gives shaves to the gentlemen
and manicures to the ladies, take someone from their room to the recreation
area or just whatever is needed. They have helped with a 90+ birthday party
held for the residents who were 90 or over. They are looking forward to
the helping with the Christmas Party and have already begun making small
gifts for each resident. So much love has been generated by these visits,
it makes you feel warm inside and the students really look forward to Wednesday.
<BR>
<BR>
The chapter has voted to continue this project year round. They feel that
if they discontinue it at the end of school that their adopted grandparents
would feel deserted. They have already decided that the may choose another
project for next year, but they will continue with this one also. 
<H2>STOVALL JUNIOR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
11201 Airline Drive, Houston, Tx 77037 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Project Reach-Out<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Reach-Out will motivate children to appreciate and read good literature.
<LI>Reach-Out will improve the reading skills of elementary students and
the language proficiency of ESOL students. 
<LI>Reach-Out will equip ESOL students with skills which will improve their
scores on standardized tests. 
<LI>Reach-Out will raise the confidence an self-esteem of junior high students
and entice them to consider a career in teaching. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Stovall Junior High TAFE Reach-Out program is carried out by girls and boys
in the sixth, seventh and eighth grade. The program consists of three main
activities: reading to small groups of pre-k and kindergarten children,
listening to first graders read their own book, and tutoring ESOL fourth
graders with reading comprehension activities. <BR>
<BR>
The group of students reading aloud to small groups serves nearby thompson
Elementary School. Elementary schools start about 45 minutes before junior
high. this enables our readers to go every thursday morning from about 8:00
to 8:40 to read a great story. Each week the group consist of about 15 enthusiastic
students who have parcticed their read-aloud and are ready to share. <BR>
<BR>
Our group of students who listen to first graders or tutor fourth graders
also participate once a week. Twelve tutors and about eight reading partners
serve nearby Black Elementary School from about 8:00 to 8:45 each Thursday.
Reading partners listen one on one to first graders read a favorite story.
Tutors and their partners keep track of completed lessons on a special book
marker created by each ESOL student. <BR>
<BR>
Since Reach-Out has begun, TAFE sponsors have seen numerous signs of its
benefits. Shy junior high students are becoming more expressive because
of their reading or tutoring experiences, and the students are inquiring
more frequently about the teaching profession. The elementary students are
writing us thank-you notes and talking about their favorite read-aloud books.
<H2>EISENHOWER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
7920 Antoine, Houston, Tx 77088-4398 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE TAAS up IKE<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To increase the awareness of students and staff concerning the TAAS
test. 
<LI>To help students prepare for the TAAS Test. 
<LI>To promote a positive attitude toward the test. 
<LI>To develop leadership skills and promote teamwork on the part of TAFE
members. 
<LI>To make TAFE visible throughout the school. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
For the six weeks prior to the TAAS test, TAFE members painted large signs
with examples of math problems on them. We targeted nine TAAS objectives.
Each week we hung three to six signs. Each sign had a certain objective
displayed. These were hung throughout the hall of our school. On the Friday
before the TAAS was given we passed out approximately 1500 TAAS booklet.
These booklets had helpful hints about math fact in them. These booklets
were given to all 9th and 11th graders. <BR>
<BR>
Many TAFE members were involved in putting the information together for
the booklets. Members spent time dring their study labs and after school
painting and hanging the posters. In all there were 30 posters hung. The
officers of our club took different objectives to be responsible for. Our
school, Eisenhower, had the best TAAS scores in our district. We would like
to think we contributed tho these results. 
<H2>ROCKDALE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Box 632, Rockdale, Tx 76567 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Under the Christmas Tree<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this project was to get TAFE members involved in a leadership
and community service project that would include our school, local churches,
and the community. Our objective in the project was to provide Christmas
for five needy families in the Rockdale area. The goal was to obtain enough
food items and gifts for these families and make Christmas a reality for
each family. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The idea for this project was brought up at a regular meeting of the Chapter
in its October meeting. The sponsors agreed that they thought this would
be an excellent community service project. This project would involve every
member, all the students at the high school, the faculty and staff, several
school organizations and local churches in the community. <BR>
<BR>
On the weekend of November 16-17, several members of TAFE met to make posters,
signs, decorations, and other material to support this project. On November
the 18th, the chapter members set up a Christmas tree in the entrance hall
to the high school. When students brought goods or gifts to put under the
tree, they would print their name on a small star and hang it on the tree.
Thus, the tree would be decorated by the student gift givers. The club also
held a fund raiser along with the Christmas project. It was called the &quot;Pauper
Pencil Sale&quot;, which raised $106.71 to buy five hams for the families.
<BR>
<BR>
Announcements were made daily about the project and everyone knew that TAFE
and the school were sponsoring Christmas for five families in the community.
Three lcoal churches submitted the families that received the donations.
The five families included five mothers and fifteen children. None of the
families had a father at home. <BR>
<BR>
Club members spent many hours putting this project together. Not to mention
all of the hours spent gathering, sorting boxes, wrapping and delivering
all of the gifts and food items to the churches. A total of over 1400 food
items and 55 gifts were received for this project. So much food came in
(over 500 extra items) that we gave it to the local Christmas project called
&quot;Round-Up.&quot; This project also gives food to needy families in
the community. <BR>
<BR>
Even though the chapter members and students at Rockdale never knew who
the families were, they all felt the Christmas spirit from the project known
as &quot;Under the Christmas Tree.&quot; 
<H2>NIMITZ HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2005 W.W. Thorne, Houston, Tx 77073 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAAS Test Video Tips<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To promote improved academic performance of students taking the TAAS
exam. 
<LI>To provide an opportunity for all members of the chapter to participate
in an educational activity benefitting Nimitz High School. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE TAAS Test Video Tips was a leadership/educational project undertaken
by the Nimitz High School chapter of the Texas Association of future Educators.
The concept of utilizing student produced videos to spotlight mathematical
principles included in the math section of the TAAS originated with the
Nimitz Second Period Effective Schools Math Committee. Nimitz TAFE immediately
volunteered to create and produce the video skits. The videos were designed
to focus attention on specific math skills necessary for success on the
TAAS test. <BR>
<BR>
Eleven videos were created, produced, and aired by the Nimitz TAFE highlighting
the following principles: 
<UL>
<LI>Sept. 3 Addition 
<LI>Sept. 5 Subtraction 
<LI>Sept. 10 Multiplication 
<LI>Sept. 12 Division 
<LI>Sept. 17 Cross-Multiplication 
<LI>Sept. 19 Probability & Statistics 
<LI>Sept. 24 Scientific Notation 
<LI>Sept. 26 Mean, Median & Mode, Greatest Precision 
<LI>Oct. 1 Transformation & Symmetry 
<LI>Oct. 3 TAAS Test Taking Hints 
</UL>
The completed videos were broadcast over the Nimitz Channel One system during
each study hall. A specific math concept was featured in each day's video
and accomanying study sheet. All study hall teachers were requested to tune
in to Channel One for the broadcast and encourage their students to view
the study sheet provided. The study sheets were then collected and Nimitz
TAFE awarded a prize to the first correct study sheet drawn from the entries.
</BODY>
