"3"></CENTER>
<H2>CHILDRESS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
800 Ave. J., N.W. Childress, Tx 79201 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Teach-A-Day<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To encourage members to consider teaching as a career. 
<LI>To involve TAFE members in an actual classroom teaching experience.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE Teach-A-Day is a project that was conducted at our Childress Elementary
School. Our project is designed to provide as closely as possible A Day
in the Life of the Classroom Teacher. <BR>
<BR>
Every teacher at our elementary school requested a TAFE Teacher. All 625
elementary students received instruction during the day from the TAFE teachers.
Thirty seven TAFE members participated in this project. <BR>
<BR>
It began with an after-school visit each TAFE member had with their assigned
classroom teacher. A week later TAFE members were allowed to observe their
teacher for three hours during the teacher's busy morning routine. This
observation time proved valuable. The following week all elementary school
children were taught by TAFE teachers for the complete school day. <BR>
<BR>
Members wrote lesson plans, prepared name tags for their students, studied
to make the best presentation possible, and learned a great deal about a
day in the life of a teacher. They performed all duties assigned to their
teacher for the day. <BR>
<BR>
The elementary teachers evaluated their student teachers after the close
of the day. The evaluation given to each teacher provided positive feedback
on their performance with suggestions for improvement. The teachers also
provided the sponsor with a separate evaluation form of the student and
the project overall. <BR>
<BR>
The benefits to the TAFE members were tremendous. The seniors were even
more anxious to become teachers. They were able to work with teachers whom
they had admired for years. They were given encouragement to pursue their
goals and dreams of becoming an educator. 
<H2>EISENHOWER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
7922 Antoine Drive, Houston, Texas 77088-4398 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: BREAK to end the 6weeks, FAST<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To encourage interaction among TAFE and Student Council members. 
<LI>To appreciate and honor the teachers at Eisenhower for their hard work
each six weeks. 
<LI>To improve the moral among teachers throughout the year. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
On the last day of every six weeks the teachers are treated to a breakfast.
TAFE and Student Council take turns on what is brought. We, TAFE, are responsible
for the coffee and juice. One six weeks we brought bagels and cream cheese.
The next six weeks Student Council brought fruit. Student Council and TAFE
share in the reminder memos. This year we made a big sign that all we have
to do is change the date on. We put our sign up a couple days before the
breakfast and put the invitations in the teachers' boxes also. <BR>
<BR>
This has been a joint effort between TAFE and Student Council. The Student
Council representative and our Parliamentarian communicate two or three
times during the six weeks to coordinate the Breakfast. The students work
well together to ensure that we have enough food, coffee, juice, cups, napkins,
plates, sugar, and cream. It is very rewarding for the students to see the
teachers in a non-classroom setting. The librarians are very cooperative
also. We would not be able to have this without their help. <BR>
<BR>
On the day of the Breakfast our Parliamentarian and three or four members
went to Eisenhower at 6:00 a.m. to get the coffee going and set up the counter.
Both groups of members helped the teachers get their goodies. The teachers
really liked this and the members really worked well together. With everyone,
helping the cleanup is fast and students are given passes to get their first
period classes. 
<H2>GILMER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: New Teacher Survival Kits & Welcome<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To welcome new teachers to Gilmer ISD 
<LI>To introduce TAFE to new teachers and make ourselves available for help
in the future 
<LI>To provide a motivational skit to new teachers as their first experience
with Gilmer students and TAFE 
<LI>To provide New Teacher Survival Kits (supplies, information sheets,
local maps, community information, etc.) 
<LI>To provide door prizes for luncheon hosted by superintendent and school
board at new teacher orientation 
<LI>To provide catalogs and discount coupons to local educational supply
businesses 
<LI>To ensure a positive first impression of Gilmer ISD and its students
<LI>To start the new school year with a major project focusing on the value
of teachers and teaching as a career 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
New faculty members of Gilmer ISD are required to attend a new teachers
orientation the day before the general work day or in-service. Obviously,
many of the new staff members have had no contact with the school or its
students body. Many of the new employees are first year teachers. This fun
introduction to the system and some of its students is a relaxing and motivational
way to start their job with GISD. Their day is filled with meetings and
more serious activities, this opening by TAFE has come to be relied on by
the administration as a way to put new teachers at ease and extend a warm
welcome. <BR>
<BR>
Two weeks before school starts the officers call on chapter members to solicit
door prizes from area merchants. This is an excellent way to hit the ground
running when the school year starts and gets members active before the first
day of school. Officers call on local educational supply stores requesting
catalogs and discount coupons. Members are also asked to solicit desk and
office supplies from various sources such as banks, hospitals and local
businesses. The week before the new teacher orientation, members meet and
make New Teacher Survival Kits. Bags are decorated and labeled as New Teacher
Survival Kits on the front with our TAFE logo and annual theme on the back.
The bags are then stuffed with pens, pencils, clips, coupon, notepad, keychains,
erasers, candy, and motivational handouts, etc. Also included are are maps,
a listing of local churches and organizations with addresses and phone numbers,
an informational sheet about TAFE and an invitation to call upon TAFE for
help with projects or needs regardless of the campus the new teachers work
at. From this invitation we will be starting a pen pal project at the intermediate
school this spring. <BR>
<BR>
New teachers were met at the entrance to the high school and escorted by
TAFE members to their meeting room. Each teacher was given a kit and supply
catalog upon entrance. They were then invited to sign up for door prizes
which were given at the luncheon hosted by the superintendent and school
board later that day. After a welcome to the system by our superintendent
and curriculum director, TAFE members performed a motivational skit entitled:
A Not-So-Typical Day in the Life of a Teacher. The skit was both humorous
and motivational. At the end of the skit, one of the members read an inspirational
poem about the responsibilities of being a teacher. One of the TAFE sponsors
then gave a short speech on the joys and frustrations of being a teacher.
The response by the new teachers was very positive to say the least. Administrators
from all the campuses were present as well and they too, were most appreciative.
<H2>HUNTINGTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 328, Huntington, Tx 75949 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Teaching Experience<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
This program is designed to allow students interested in the teaching profession
the opportunity to actively participate in a classroom setting. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
One of the most important aspects of the Huntington TAFE chapter is to motivate
young students to pursue a teaching career. As an incentive to learn more
about teaching, the chapter provides an elective class where students can
participate in actually teaching, grading and all the fun and vigorous aspects
of teaching. <BR>
<BR>
These classes are organized to help students observe and interact in the
classroom environment. Students receive a half credit per semester (TEA
- approved.) Presently, 31 students of our TAFE group are actively involved
in this program. In May, a $1000 scholarship will be awarded to an Outstanding
TAFE Member. The scholarship money has been given by the T.L.L. Temple Foundation.
<BR>
<BR>
Chapter members serve as teachers in the classroom. Other students are included
because they learn in these classrooms. Teachers get the help in the classroom
and also students learn what is required of a teacher. 
<H2>LUFKIN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
900 East Denman, Lufkin, Tx 75901 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Adopt A Class<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To adopt a class of students that might not otherwise be remembered at special
times in the year by their families. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
In December, members of our TAFE chapter went to Kurth Elementary School.
We were extremely excited and had been looking forward to this for several
months. We gave books to each child, read to them and autographed the book
with both the childs name and the name of a TAFE member. The kids were so
excited to have their very own book that they in turn read to their TAFE
buddy from one of their big books. This was really an unexpected treat.
<BR>
<BR>
We brought Christmas cupcakes an punch for the children, and they served
us Christmas cookies and drinks. While we ate, we had a chance to talk with
the children and take pictures. Later we gave each child a candy train that
we made from a roll of lifesavers, Hershey kisses, and peppermints. To our
surprise, each child had made a Christmas tree ornament with their school
picture on it for their TAFE buddy. When it came time to leave, it was hard
to say good-bye. <BR>
<BR>
This was such a great success that we plan to go back to this class around
Easter. We all learned a lot about kids and ourselves. We benefited from
this project and hope to do it every year. 
<H2>MANSFIELD HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
1520 Walnut Creek Drive, Mansfield, Tx 76063 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: School Supply Collection<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To increase the awareness of students, their parents and school staff
concerning the needs of the less privileged in our district. 
<LI>To develop leadership skills and promote teamwork on the part of TAFE
members. 
<LI>To make TAFE visible throughout the school and community. 
<LI>To provide an opportunity for all members of the chapter to play a leadership
role in their classes. 
<LI>To collect supplies for the needy children of the Mansfield ISD 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Our purpose was to collect school supplies for the needy children of our
district. The project was to collect school supplies in quantities sufficient
to supply all the students on all the campuses of our system. We spent one
week notifying the public of our collection. Announcements were made daily
to the classes. A class competition was held on the high school campus.
Each 4th period class brought supplies which were counted for the ratio
of items per student in the classes. We hosted a coke and pizza party for
the winning class. <BR>
<BR>
The collection lasted one week. Upon the completion of the collection, the
items were sorted and redistributed to the principals of each campus for
distribution as they deemed fit. <BR>
<BR>
In the beginning, our president was responsible for presenting the plan
for our collection to the principals and gaining their approval. Each of
our members were responsible for the explanation and promotion of the collection
in each of their classes. Our officers were responsible for the oral announcements,
also. <BR>
<BR>
The local newspaper announced our collection to the city and placed an article
and picture of the collected supplies in an issue upon the completion of
the drive. The drive was a success and around 2000 items were collected.
<H2>NIMITZ HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2005 W.W. Thorne, Houston, Texas 77073 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Toy Shop<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To provide TAFE members an opportunity to interact one on one with elementary
students. 
<LI>To cooperate with another organization in an educational project. 
<LI>To receive training in storytelling. 
<LI>To receive training in communication skills. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Toy Shop was an interactive dramatic production presented jointly by Nimitz
TAFE and the Nimitz High School drama department. The Toy Shop is a story
about a toymaker who finishes toys just in time for Christmas only to have
the toys broken by vandals. With no time left to rebuild the toys, the toys
rebuild themselves the night before they are to be delivered. <BR>
<BR>
The Toy Shop was presented to kindergarten and first grade students from
two elementary schools in the Aldine School District. As part of the production,
TAFE members broke into small groups with the elementary students and re-enacted
the play with the students performing the parts of the toys. This required
the members to learn how to speak to elementary students. They learned that
body language was as important, if not more important, than the words they
used in instructing the students. Members learned how to tell a story and
make it exciting to the students. They learned to call on students to involve
the students in the story and entertain the students. Afterwards, as closure
to the production, the students drew pictures of the toys that they had
portrayed. <BR>
<BR>
Sixteen members participated in the actual production of the play. Additional
members assisted in the construction of props. The play was presented to
over 200 elementary students. Fifteen students from the drama department
were involved with the project. 
<H2>REFUGIO HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
250 West Vance St., Refugio, Tx 78377 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Its Up To Me<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<UL>
<LI>To reduce the number of at-risk students in RISD by: improving the self-concept
of elementary students and by providing positive role models. 
<LI>To provide TAFE members the opportunity to participate in a classroom
teaching experience. 
<LI>To encourage the development of the leadership skills of TAFE members.
</UL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Monica Flores, Texas 4-H council member and TAFE member proposed a joint
project using the curriculum, Its Up To Me. The Refugio County Home Extension
Service agreed to provide the curriculum and copies of all printed materals
needed. TAFE agreed to provide the materials used to teach the lessons.
The Extension agent and TAFE sponsor agreed to jointly provide the supervision
and guidance for the project. <BR>
<BR>
Ten students volunteered to participate in the project for one semester.
Weekly meetings were held after school to choose lesson activites for first
and second grade classrooms. After discussing the activities, the TAFE teachers
participated in role playing the lesson to be taught. Each student was responsible
for completing a lesson plan and preparing the needed materials. One lesson
was taught each week during the high school's academic enrichment period.
Following the teaching experience, each TAFE teacher was to complete a self-evaluation
of the lesson and submit it to the TAFE sponsor. <BR>
<BR>
At the end of the first semester, the primary school teachers were requested
to complete written evaluations with suggestions for improvements that could
be made. These ideas were used in changes made for the second semester.
<BR>
<BR>
Two students wished to participate for the second semester. They were named
as grade level leaders. Their responsibilities included leading the training
sessions and communicating weekly with the classroom teachers to inform
then in advance of the lesson content to be covered for the week. New students
were recruited so that each classroom would have two students assigned on
a regular basis. This has helped improve continuity in case of absences
of the teacher. <BR>
<BR>
The primary school teachers felt the project has shown many positive effects.
It has been included in their campus improvement plan as an activity to
be continued. The high school principal and faculty have supported the participants
with verbal encouragement and praise. 
<H2>ROCKDALE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 632, Rockdale, Tx 76567 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: A Merry Christmas to All<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
Our objective was to provide a Christmas of gifts and food for eight needy
families in the area of the Rockdale Independent School District. The goal
was to give the best Christmas possible for each of these families and to
increase the number of families from five last year to eight this year.
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The chapter began work on this project at its regular meeting in November.
Since this was the second year for this project, we knew it was going to
involve a lot of work. The project would be set up to include all the club
members, the student body and faculty at the high school, some school organizations
and the local community. <BR>
<BR>
The 19 members of the club met on Monday evening of November 30th to put
a Christmas tree in the lobby of the high school. They then made Christmas
balls. These balls would be signed and hung on the tree by students who
brought food or gifts for the project. A sign-up board was also made for
students to select the families they wanted to support. <BR>
<BR>
Announcements were made daily about the project. Every student was aware
of what the school was doing. Five local churches submitted the names of
the eight families to receive the donations. These families included 13
adults and 19 children. <BR>
<BR>
The club had a fund-raiser called the Pauper Pencil Drive to raise money
for perishable food itmes for the families. A total of $155.44 was raised
by this sale. Club members spent over 300 work hours making sure that this
project was a success. The club had to plan, gather, sort, wrap and finally
deliver the gifts and food. The students, faculty and TAFE club members
donated 108 gifts and over 2500 food items for this project. Some of the
extra food items were given to other community projects that were sent up
to help other needy families. This year's project nearly doubled last year's
project. 
<H2>SAM RAYBURN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2121 Cherrybrook Lane, Pasadena, Tx 77502 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: American Sign Language Project<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The objective of this project is to teach a selected group of Sam Rayburn
TAFE members the basics of American Sign Language and to then apply this
knowledge to the signing of childrens books for local deaf students. The
purpose of this project is to increase student awareness & appreciation
of deaf culture while at the same time introducing students to an area of
special education. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Interested students from the Sam Rayburn TAFE club began meeting at the
beginning of the school year. Instructed by the sponsor, these students
began to learn the basics of American Sign Language for the deaf. After
several weeks of learning the alphabet and basic word structures, the students
began to bring childrens books to school. They have spent the last several
months learning the signs associated with books such as The Polar Express
by Chris VanAlsburg, One Fish, Two Fish, Red Fish, Blue Fish by Dr. Suess
and The Giving Tree by Shel Silverstein. <BR>
<BR>
These books are being prepared by our students to be read at a nearby elementary
school which services hearing impaired students. TAFE members have had the
opportunity to work with the sponsor's nine year old hearing-impaired daughter.
Practicing their signs and learning new ones, students have been exposed
to an area of special education which few regular education students see.
Arrangements have been made to visit several area schools for the hearing
impaired and TAFE students continue to work on their signing skills in preparation
for these visits. <BR>
<BR>
Approximately ten to twelve TAFE members are present for each sign language
meeting. Since the size of the chapter runs at about thirty members this
has involved about one third of our membership. An unseen advantag
