<H2>ROCKDALE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P. O. Box 632, Rockdale, TX 76567, (512)446-3471, Terry Pope, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: The Spirit of Christmas<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this project was to get TAFE members involved in a community
service project during the Christmas Holiday period. The project was designed
to involve the club, school, local churches and the entire community. Our
objective was to provide a Christmas of gifts and food for five needy families
in the area of the Rockdale Independent School District. The goal was to
give the best Christmas possible to each of these families. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The chapter began work on this project at its last regular meeting in November.
Since this was the third year for this project, we knew it was going to
involve a lot of work. The project was planned to include all the club members,
the student body and faculty at the high school, some school organizations,
local churches, and the local community. <BR>
<BR>
The 33 members of the club met on Wednesday evening of November 24th to
put a Christmas tree in the lobby of the high school, and make Christmas
balls. These balls would be signed and hung on the tree by students who
brought food or gifts for the project. A sign-up board was also made for
students to select the families they wanted to support with their gifts.
<BR>
<BR>
Announcements were made daily about the project. Every student was aware
of what the school was doing. Four local churches submitted the names of
the five families to receive the donations. These families included 6 adults
and 20 children. <BR>
<BR>
The club had a fund-raiser called the Pauper Pencil Sale to raise money
for perishable food items for the families. A total of $170.47 was raised
by this sale. 
<H2>JAMES E. TAYLOR HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
20700 Kingsland Blvd., Katy, TX 77450, Linda Atkinson, Rhonda Demel, Jennifer
Gillespie, and Linda Nugent, Sponsors 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Get-to-Know-You Social<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
At the beginning of each school year, our TAFE chapter holds a Get-to-Know-You
Social so that old members and new members can get acquainted with each
other. In addition, this gathering serves as a community service. <BR>
<BR>
Upon entering the social, each person was given a name tag with the name
of a famous person on it. This tag was placed on the person's back so that
he was forced to ask fellow members and sponsors yes/no questions about
the identity of their famous character. This game enabled members to relax
and talk to people they may not have known before. <BR>
<BR>
Once everyone discovered their character's identity, members were divided
into groups. Each group consisted of old and new members. The groups were
teams for a scavenger hunt. Each group was given an identical list of non-perishable
food items that were later donated to Katy Christian Ministries. The team
to collect the greatest number of items, within a certain amount of time,
was declared the winner. <BR>
<BR>
After school one day, a large group of TAFE members joined together to deliver
the goods to Katy Christian Ministries. They were very thankful for our
contribution, and a picture of us delivering food was featured in our local
newspaper. 
<H2>NIMITZ HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2005 W. W. Thorne, Houston, TX 77073, (713)443-7480, Leslie Rowney, Sponsor
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Proud to be Me<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To offer TAFE members an opportunity to provide instruction. 
<LI>To improve the self-esteem of elementary students. 
<LI>To provide an opportunity for TAFE members to coordinate with another
school organization. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
On December 9 and 10, 1993, Nimitz TAFE traveled to four elementary schools
in the Aldine Independent School District to present an interactive dramatic
production entitled, Proud to be Me. <BR>
<BR>
Proud to be Me is a collection of stories dealing with self-esteem presented
to the elementary students through drama. After the dramatic presentation,
TAFE members broke into small groups with students and re-enacted the stories,
discussed being proud of oneself, and discussed the immportance of not giving
in to peer pressure. This required the members to learn how to speak to
elementary students. They learned that body language was as important, if
not more important, as the words they used to instruct the students. Members
learned how to tell a story and what makes it exciting to the students.
They also learned to call upon students to involve the students in the story
and entertain the students at the same time. Afterwards, as closure to the
production, the students decorated hats which the TAFE members had previously
constructed. <BR>
<BR>
Twenty four TAFE members teamed with fifteen students from Nimitz High School
drama department to present the program to approxiomately 1,000 elementary
students. They participated in all aspects of the project, including acting
in the play, building the set pieces and hats used in the production, and
teaching the children in the classroom. 
<H2>BRYAN HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
3401 East 29th Street, Bryan, TX 77802, Brenda Johnson, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Shots Across the Brazos Valley<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help serve the community by helping to provide free flu shots. 
<LI>To provide members an opportunity to become involved in a service- oriented
project. 
<LI>To help the school advertise and prepare for the event thoroughly 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
On November 10, 1993, seventeen hundred members of the community attended
<STRONG>Shots Across the Brazos Valley</STRONG> and received free flu shots.
For a month preceding this date, The Bryan High TAFE Chapter had been preparing
for the event. TAFE did not receive any monetary reward for their work,
or even the smile of a child, but still, members felt happy to help provide
such an important service for the community. <BR>
<BR>
The first few weeks of preparation for Shots Across the Brazos Valley entailed
preparing a list of students in TAFE willing to attend the event. Eleven
members signed up to help. The next service that was required of the chapter
was helping the school's secretarial staff address mailers to people county-wide.
Seven hundred to a thousand mailers were prepared. TAFE officers covered
the neighborhood, putting up posters advertising the event. <BR>
<BR>
Finally, the day of the clinic came. Members gave up their early-release
day afternoon to help community members fill out the required applications
for the shots. Many members were asked to hold the hands of friends and
strangers while shots were given. <BR>
<BR>
Six hundred and seventy-two people received shots at Bryan High School.
Besides the four Bryan Independent School District clinics, shots were given
at local malls and grocery stores throughout the month of November. Not
only did the Bryan TAFE chapter participate, but other clubs such as the
Language Club, future Farmers of America, and National Honor Society provided
students to help work on the day of the clinic. Many local businesses helped
sponsor and advertise the event. Also, the television, radio and newspaper
advertised the event. The Bryan High School clinic involved people from
all over the community. <BR>
<BR>
The Bryan TAFE Chapter worked hard to help make Shots Across the Brazos
Valley a success and is pleased with the response from the community. We
hope that next year we can help make the clinic an even bigger success.
<H2>ALIEF HASTINGS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 68, Alief, Texas 77411 Teri Fleming, Sponsor 
<H3>PROJECT NAME: Appreciation Banquet<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of the end-of-year banquet of appreciation is to honor and give
thanks to those special teachers that are forming the teachers of tomorrow.
the objective was to give a formal setting in which those thanks could be
expressed and that admiration honored. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
It is always traditional to end the school year with a banquet, but last
year we as a chapter decided that we should host a banquet for the teachers.
The banquet would consist of the chapter members and the teacher that had
most influenced each of their young lives. The beauty of the project was
that it was all top secret. The first step was that each member that was
willing to go to the banquet chose their teacher of choice. That teacher
was then notified of the banquet and that they had been choosen to be honored,
but by whom they did not know. The banquet was held at a local community
club house and after dinner each student was given a few moments to stand
and honor their invited teacher. Each teacher was presented with a gift
of appreciation and a hug. <BR>
<BR>
The chapter members were the backbone of this project. The banquet committee,
consisting of about fifteen students, planned all invitations, handled all
RSVPs, secured the banquet hall, planned a menu and decorated the hall.
<BR>
<BR>
The faculty and student body were a small but important part of the banquet.
They kept all known information that may have leaked out a secret from the
faculty members that were involved. The community once again backed our
project with energy and enthusiasm They served as our chefs and provided
us with an off-campus place to hold the banquet. 
<H2>CHILDRESS HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
800 Avenue J, NW, Childress, Tx 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Bobcat's Spirit<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To encourage each member of the student body to get actively involved
in showing support for our football team. 
<LI>To demonstrate leadership skills in our school 
<LI>To make TAFE further known throughout our community 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE wanted the entire student body to become more involved in demonstrating
school spirit. With the beginning of the school year we wanted the school
and community to recognize TAFE as a leader in our high school. <BR>
<BR>
At the first home football game TAFE was in charge of all pre-game activities.
One TAFE member gave the welcome to packed home and visitor stands. Another
member offered a prayer for the evening's game and travel. Three more members
raised the flag prior to the kickoff. The announcer let the packed stands
know what TAFE represents and the active role it takes in leadership at
Childress High School. <BR>
<BR>
We continued our school spirit drive with locker signs. We made Road Kill
Cafe signs and put them on the lockers to get everyone's attention and build
interest in the upcoming pep rally and game. TAFE furthered their school
spirit awarenes by decorating the gym for a pep rally. We used blue and
white crepe paper and balloons to really get everyone fired up to cheer
louder at the pep rally and to let the players know that TAFE is involved
in school spirit. The cheerleaders awarded TAFE the spirit stick at the
pep rally. We wanted the spirit to carry over to the game and it did! 
<H2>ROYAL HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 469, Pattison, Tx 77466 Christine Wyatt, Marcia Schomburg, Sponsors
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Student of the Month Project<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To highlight the positive things happening in our school. 
<LI>To encourage scholastic achievement and personal best in the classroom.
<LI>To give teachers a chance to recognize and reward some of their most
outstanding students. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
With the primary goal of recognizing academic excellence, the Royal TAFE
organized a <STRONG>Student of the Month</STRONG> program. Each month, throughout
the school year, two to three departments were asked to nominate outstanding
students in their classes. The selected students were given a certificate
suitable for framing, their pictures were taken for publication in the local
newspaper, their names were featured on a brightly colored banner that hung
in the main office, and the principal announced their names on the public
address system. <BR>
<BR>
As several months passed, students began to ask what department would be
highlighted next, so they could work toward being recognized as that Student
of the Month. The interest began to grow and students seemed to be competing
for the award. <BR>
<BR>
Since all departments are featured at least once during the year, all students
have a chance to be honored. So many times our schools seem to focus on
the negative. Royal's TAFE strives to focus on the positive. Students who
excel academically are recognized as positive role models. 
<H2>BANDERA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 727, Bandera, Tx 78003 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Coats for Kids<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose and objectives of the project were as follows: 
<OL>
<LI>To provide TAFE members with an opportunity to participate in a service
project. 
<LI>To encourage the development of leadership skills among TAFE members.
<LI>To encourage the development of communication skills among TAFE members.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Members of the Bandera High School TAFE chapter, together with Debate Team
members,conducted a Coats for Kids drive during the month of October. Flyers
(sample attached) were designed by TAFE members and then distributed throughout
the community. Coats were collected throughout the month of October. <BR>
<BR>
At the end of the month, the coats were then taken to the tree cleaners
in town. The businesses had graciously offered to clean the coats at no
charge. When the coats had been cleaned, they were then taken to the elementary
and middle school nurses for distribution to children who may have needed
one. Follow-up thank you letters were sent to the cleaners. By the time
the project was finished, all of the chapter membership of twenty had been
involved in at least one aspect of Coats for Kids - from planning, to publicity,
to collection, to distribution and follow-up. <BR>
<BR>
The project involved community, faculty and staff, and students other than
TAFE members who donated coats as well. We were well pleased with the degree
of success and plan to make it an annual drive. 
<H2>EISENHOWER HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Lock-In<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help bind club members together and create a good TAFE unit. 
<LI>To help promote friendship, loyality, and a sense of belong among our
members. 
<LI>To learn about leadership qualities 
<LI>To see the need for following the directions given by the officers of
our club. 
<LI>To get ideas for a skit to be performed at the District convention when
we run for Vice-President. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The officers and sponsor meet to agree on a date, time, and list of activities.
During the month of September the officers spent lunches and after school
putting together a wonderful agenda. <BR>
<BR>
We started the evening off at 11:00 p.m. by having a short meeting, issuing
folders, and money due notes to members. The members were given name tags
and divided up into groups. We then played mixer games in their groups so
the members would get to know each other better. After the members got familiar
with their group they started to creat a hat and song for their group. We
then had a hat and song show. Around 1:30 a.m. we decided it was time for
some more food items and tooks time to discuss the skit for district. At
2:00 we had group relays. The members had so much fun playing those silly
games. The groups got points for where they placed in each event. We then
moved on to a leadership activity where each group created an animal out
of newspaper and tape. They then had to state what leadership characteristics
their animal showed. The sponsors voted on the best animal. We then moved
on to the TAFE scramble. Each group unscrambled clues to find something.
They then went as a group to find their whatever. In this case they were
to find a cup of candy. The members then worked on the stress pads we were
making for the teachers for the end of the first six weeks. We all were
ready to relax for a while so we watched Aladdin. Breakfast was cooked on
Coleman stoves. We had pancakes and orange juice. Then it was time to clean
up and announce the first, second and third place awards. Everyone had a
great time. 
</BODY>
