<H2>ARLINGTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
818 West Park Row, Arlington, Texas 76013 Troy Collins, Gail Howard,Sponsors
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Colt TAFE Book Drive</H3>
<H4>DESCRIPTION:</H4>
As a community service project, the AHS Colt TAFE sponsored a two week book
drive that benefited the Mission Arlington, a homeless shelter, and the
Alpha Project, a day care center for the homeless shelter children and children
of the Women's Shelter, a place for battered women. <BR>
<BR>
Our project began with a meeting of the executive board planning a strategy.
It was decided that the week before and after Thanksgiving would be a great
time to remind people that we have much to be thankful for. That reminder
included a reference to those less fortunate, with an emphasis that reading
and books are gifts that last a lifetime. The book drive proved to be a
huge success with teachers, students and parents donating books. We collected
over five hundred books ranging from encyclopedias to children's picture
books. It was a fulfilling experience to see so many rally around such a
worth cause. <BR>
<BR>
After the books were collected, TAFE members volunteered their time to deliver
the children's books to the Alpha Project. While there, we divided up and
spent several hours reading and sharing the books with the children of the
shelters. This was obviously a mututally rewarding experience for TAFE members
and the children. The other 300 plus books were delivered to Mission Arlington
where they were added to their library. <BR>
<BR>
The experience of visiting those two locations made our TAFE Colts aware
of an unending need to share time with those children who so desperately
need attention and nurturing. Several of our members now volunteer weekly
to read to the children of the shelter and the daycare. <BR>
<BR>
This was a rewarding experience and a welcome addition to our COLT KIDS
Program! 
<H2>GANADO HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
Drawer D, Ganado, Texas 77962 Loneta Koop, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Halloween Writing Project</H3>
<H4>DESCRIPTION:</H4>
One of the most outstanding projects this year was our Halloween Writing
contest. This project involved many people including students in elementary
high school and elementary principals and we let the community know about
the project we did by placing a picture of the winners in the paper. Our
main goal was to help the students in grades two through four develop their
writing skills while having fun. Each student was given a paper with a topic
to write about. The club chose what the theme for the stories would be.
With that topic, they created their own original Halloween story. They were
also given a picture to color and illustrate their story with. The students
could be as creative as they wanted to be. <BR>
<BR>
Three winners from each grade were selected and they were given a book as
their prize. The newspaper came to the school and they took a picture of
the winners with the principals. This appeared in the paper along with an
article describing our project. This project was fun for the students and
for the members of our club. Everyone enjoyed putting this project together
and involving the school and the community. 
<H2>GRAPEVINE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
3233 Mustang Drive, 76051-5998, Cathy Evans, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Aids Awareness<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
To educate the students about the meaning of December 1 and wearing the
special ribbon and to educate students about the dangers of AIDS with many
facts from the computer. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
First we compiled information from the computer. We then read through many
pages about AIDS and gathered many facts for teachers to tell their students.
A few TAFE members made the ribbons for every teacher to wear. Then a few
more TAFE members went to every teacher and passed out the sheets and ribbons.
With left-over ribbons, we passd them out to the students. All this was
prepared for Friday, December 1. <BR>
<BR>
The AIDS awareness project was put together and organized by the members
of TAFE. We had received approximately 98% participation from students and
100% participation was received from the teachers. Our mission was to have
the teachers and students wear the ribbons not only in school but outside
of school on this day to make the community aware of this special day and
the meaning of the ribbon. We had much support from other organizations.
Student council had corresponded with us by having the AIDS quilt hanging
in the front office. This project had met but also exceeded our expectations.
The teachers cooperated better than we expected and appreciated our efforts.
Students welcomed the opportunity to express their feelings about AIDS by
wearing the ribbon. The overall success of our project was better than we
imagined! 
<H2>LA JOYA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box Drawer J, La Joya, Texas 78560 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: TAFE Promoting Reading<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
Students will encourage children to appreciate and enjoy reading by creating
their own children's books and reading them aloud to the children. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
In preparation for National Book Week in November, TAFE members worked in
pairs to write their own children's books. They were to create the story
line and the illustrations. All books were reviewed by the sponsor and other
teachers before presentation. <BR>
<BR>
On the third week of November, TAFE visited the campus of E.B. Reyna Elementary
School in La Joya and each pair read their book aloud. The readings were
aired via Channel One so that children in each classroom were able to enjoy
the books. The elementary school library kept the books on display in the
library and even tagged them so that elementary students could check out
their favorite TAFE written book. <BR>
<BR>
TAFE students were impressed by the immediate response to their books. While
the readings were being aired, teachers were coming in, asking to see particular
books. TAFE members were invited to certain classrooms for a more personalized
reading. Teachers reported that their students wanted to check out particular
books and many students started writing and illustrating their own books.
<BR>
<BR>
This project was so successful that principals at both schools were complimented.
It involved two campuses in their effort to promote reading. 
<H2>LA JOYA HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box Drawer J, La Joya, Texas 78560 Ana Gandara, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Hire a Future Educator<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
Members will assist teachers with their end of semester tasks. This will
expose students to the variety of responsibilities that are involved with
teaching, while teachers get help in finishing their work. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
At the end of the semester, teachers are given one work day to complete
their work for the semester and to prepare for the next semester. For the
past two years in La Joya, TAFE members have given up their day off to come
in and help teachers get their work done. <BR>
<BR>
Two weeks before the end of the semester teachers are notified of the viability
of the students and asked to sign up if they need help. A week before, students
are assigned to prospective teachers and are sent to introduce themselves
and verify the assignment. On the work day, students report to their assigned
teacher. <BR>
<BR>
Students have been exposed to grading papers, arranging bulletin boards,
cleaning closets, checking attendance rosters, typing worksheets and much
more. This is a fantastic opportunity for our future educators to be exposed
to all the behind the scenes that is involved with the teaching profession.
Many have expressed a new apreciation for their teachers and an enlightened
awareness of all that is involved with each classroom lesson. <BR>
<BR>
The faculty at La Joya has expressed their appreciation of the project.
They are impressed by the student's enthusiasm as well as their energy in
completing tasks that for them seem tedious. Many teachers have taken the
opportunity to get to know their TAFE members and encourage than to pursue
the career. <BR>
<BR>
TAFE asked for a $5.00 donation for each half day of assistance and raised
about $200.00. During Teacher Appreciation Week in May, TAFE members offer
the same project, but do not accept donations. This is their gift to the
teachers. 
<H2>M.B. SMILEY HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
10725 Mesa Drive, Houston, Texas 77028, Helen Shields & Brenda Wyatt, Sponsors
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Home Away From Home On Campus<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To help promote school pride. 
<LI>To instill in the minds of the students the importance of keeping the
restroom facilities they use sanitary. 
<LI>To encourage other organizations and schools to take part in our schoolwide
project. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
For the past few years, our school has been having problems with keeping
the restroom facilities clean and intact due to graffiti and other forms
of defacement caused by our student body. Club TAFE decided to change this
obviously destructive pattern. We took it upon ourselves to start a new
and unique practice; we helped our school by adopting restrooms. We adopted
a set of student restrooms and a set in the teacher's lounge. <BR>
<BR>
First of all, club TAFE cleaned all the writing and graffiti off the restroom
walls. Then we used contact paper to cover the doors to each of the restroom
stalls. We mounted hand towel racks and placed colored hand towels, soft
skin lotions, soft soap, kleenex tissues and a bouquet of flowers on the
vanity so that the students would feel right at home when they came to use
the restroom. For each seasonal holiday, we made and placed large cutouts
for that season on the walls. In the faculty restrooms of the teachers'
lounge, the club placed decorative bathroom wallpaper border all around
the wall edges of those restrooms. We provided lotion, soft soap, decorative
hand towels and even plush bathroom floor mats for our teachers. <BR>
<BR>
Sure enough, the faculty and student body bought into our school wide prject
and now they take great pride in being able to use and help keep clean the
restroom facilities they need and use. Both students and teachers appreciated
the fact that TAFE club members came before school, during lunch, during
homeroom and after school to try to create our own form of pleasant amenities
for everyone's satisfaction. In addition, other clubs have followed in our
footsteps. They too have chosen to clean and decorate other sets of restrooms
on our campus. While on the same note, other schools in our district have
also adopted our project of promoting school pride. Now when parents and
other visitors come to our campus and have to use our facilities, we are
not ashamed! Club TAFE is glad that we inspired others to take part in our
successful endeavor. We continue to receive acknowledgements from everyone
here at school for our efforts and we are excited about this because it
shows that we did reach our goal. It also goes to show that together we
can make a difference. 
<H2>MORTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
500 Champion Drive, Morton, Texas 79346, Peggy Silhan, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Thanksgiving Food Drive<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To give members the opportunity to become involved in a service- oriented
project. 
<LI>To give members the opportunity to work together with other clubs, students,
teachers, and community groups. 
<LI>To provide deserving families in the community with a nice dinner for
Thanksgiving. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The TAFE members at Morton High School sponsored a food drive at Thanksgiving.
They made posters to announce the drive to the school since they wanted
to involve everyone. They put notices in the teachers' boxes about the drive,
also. The TAFE president talked with the sponsor of Student Council to see
if that organization would like to work with TAFE on the project. They did.
Boxes were made and set at collection points around the school. Three medium-sized
laundry baskets were purchased to put the food in for delivery. TAFE members
contacted the Minsterial Alliance and asked them to locate three families
to receive the baskets. TAFE bought two turkeys and had one donated to finish
out the baskets. The food was delivered two days before Thanksgiving. <BR>
<BR>
The Thanksgiving Food Drive was organized by TAFE with the Student Council
helping with the collection. We had 100% participation from the membership
of TAFE and better than average participation from teachers and other students.
The Ministerial Alliance was totally cooperative. The project was very successful.
With only 10 TAFE members and a high school enrollment of about 160 - three
baskets of food is significant. 
<H2>ROCKDALE HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
P.O. Box 632. Rockdale, Texas 76567, Terry Pope, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Happy Thanksgiving and Merry Christmas<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
The purpose of this dual project was to get TAFE members involved in community
services projects. The project was set up to involve the TAFE organization,
school, local churches and the entire community. We wanted to provide needed
food items for our local food shelter during the Thanksgiving season and
to provide Christmas for several needy families in our community. 
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
The chapter began planning and working on this project during September.
The project would be set up to begin in October and end when we began our
Christmas holiday break. The idea was to involve every club member, every
student and teacher at the high school, several other school organizations
(student council and FFA) and local churches in the community. <BR>
<BR>
The food drive began in the first week of October with several TAFE members
assigned to each 1st period classroom. Their job was to try to get students
and teachers to bring as much food as possible till the middle of November.
Announcements were made daily about the project. The result was over 2000
food items given to the Rockdale Christian Food Shelter on the week before
Thanksgiving. <BR>
<BR>
The club then turned their attention to the needy families in the community.
Seven churches gave up families they wanted us to support with food and
gifts for Christmas. These families included 15 adults and 28 children.
<BR>
<BR>
Club members spend many, many hours making sure this project was a success.
The club had to plan, gather, sort, wrap and finally deliver the gifts and
food. The students, faculty, clubs and TAFE Club members donated 124 gifts
and over 2000 food items for this project. 
<H2>MORTON HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
500 Champion Drive, Morton, Texas 79346, Peggy Silhan, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Teacher Sacks<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To improve morale among the teachers during the year. 
<LI>To show appreciation for the things teachers do. 
<LI>To do something for the teachers without expecting anything in return.
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
TAFE members get brown paper sacks (next to smallest size) and decorate
them according to the season or holiday that is happening each month. Each
member takes a turn bringing either candy, pencils, pens, stickers, ornaments,
note pads, etc. to put inside each sacks. There are always four or five
items in each sack each month. Members help fill all of the sacks the day
before delivery. On the designated delivery day, there is a called meeting
of TAFE. Each member takes three sacks with teacher names already on them
and delivers them personally before school starts. <BR>
<BR>
TAFE members originated the idea of doing the sacks for the teachers. We
have had 100% participation from the membership for this project. The members
really enjoy delivering the sacks, especially if they get to deliver to
their favorite teachers! The teachers are very appreciative of the thoughtfulness
of the TAFE members. Many write thank you notes and others verbally tell
the students and/or sponsors how nice it is to be remembered in such a neat
way. 
<H2>NIMITZ HIGH SCHOOL</H2>
2005 W.W. Thorne, Houston, Texas 77073, Leslie Rowney, Sponsor 
<H3>NAME OF PROJECT: Androcles and the Lion<BR>
PURPOSE:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To offer TAFE members an opportunity to provide instruction. 
<LI>To promote friendship among elementary students. 
<LI>To provide an opportunity to TAFE members to coordinate with another
school organization. 
</OL>
<H3>DESCRIPTION:</H3>
Nimitz TAFE joined with the Nimitz Drama Department to present an interactive
dramatic production of the classic children's fable, Androcles and the Lion.
<BR>
<BR>
Androcles and the Lion is the story of how a slave boy befriends a lion.
After the dramatic production, TAFE members broke into small groups with
the students, re-enacted the story, discussed the moral of the story and
completed worksheets. This required the members to learn how to speak to
elementary students. They learned that body language was as important, if
not more important, than the words they used in instructing the students.
Members learned how to tell a story and make it exciting to the students.
They also learned to call upon students to involve students in the story
and entertain the students at the same time. <BR>
<BR>
Twenty TAFE members teamed up with the drama department to present the program
to approximately 1000 elementary students. 
