<HTML>
<H1><CENTER>What is TASC?</CENTER>
</H1>
The <STRONG>Texas Association of Student Councils</STRONG> is a non profit
organization officially sponsored by the <A HREF="SSP.html">Texas Association
of Secondary School Principals</A>. Its goals as defined by the <A HREF="#Constit">TASC
constitution </A>are to &quot;instill American ideals, to develop citizenship
and to encourage student councils in the secondary schools&quot; of the
state.<BR>
<BR>
Over 1,400 high schools and junior high or middle schools have organized
Student Councils that participate in TASC activities. (Click here for <A HREF="#WhatSC">What
is a Student Council?</A>) By voluntarily joining together to support one
another through the state association, these schools offer themselves a
multitude of services. The Association's 60 year history is a tribute to
sponsors and students of past member schools who provided such a strong
heritage of service and support. The work of TASC is accomplished not just
through the state office in Austin, but through the work of thousands of
youth and adults in the schools of the state.<BR>
<H4>ANNUAL CONFERENCE for High Schools<BR>
</H4>
The Texas Association of Student Councils holds its Annual Conference during
the spring (last week of April or first week of May) of each year. The conference
begins Thursday evening and concludes Saturday afternoon. Typical attendance
is about 4,200 students and sponsors, representing over 380 Texas schools.<BR>
<BR>
The general format for the conference includes general sessions, discussion
groups/problem clinics, concurrent sessions, a political rally and social
activities. Commercial exhibitors with educational purposes/ties are also
invited to participate. Schools attending must be members of TASC and a
sponsor must accompany the delegates from each school. A registration fee
is required from each sponsor and delegate in attendance. For current year
registration information<A HREF="#Ann%20Conf"> click here.</A> <BR>
<H4>ANNUAL CONFERENCE for Junior High/Middle Schools<BR>
</H4>
Similar to the High School conference, but with more limited scope and duration,
this conference is held in November each year, and includes similar elements
to the high schools conference. For current year registration information<A HREF="#Ann%20Conf">
click here.</A> <BR>
<H4>SUMMER LEADERSHIP WORKSHOPS<BR>
</H4>
The Texas Association of Student Councils holds a number of basic Student
Council Leadership Workshops for Student Council officers and representatives.
The workshops are staffed and operated by Texas educators, and are designated
for either middle level or high school level students. (For current year
registration information<A HREF="#SumWkShp"> click here.</A>) Summer Workshops
are held at College campuses throughout the state beginning in early June
and ending in late July. The primary purpose of the summer workshops is
to teach the fundamental concepts of Student Council operation and leadership
techniques.<BR>
<H4>ADVANCED WORKSHOPS<BR>
</H4>
The two annual Advanced Leadership Workshops are usually held in late January,
and mid February, at Lakeview Conference Center near Palestine and at MO-Ranch
near Kerrville. These are open only to students who have participated in
a summer workshop or equivalent experience. For current year registration
information<A HREF="#Ann%20Conf"> click here.</A> <BR>
<H4>TASC NEWSLETTER StuCo Review<BR>
</H4>
Published 5 times each school year, the newletter provides members with
current information about what the association offers. It includes registration
information for all TASC activities listed above, plus news from TASC Districts
and member schools.<A HREF="#Nsltr.html"> To Search previous issues click
here.</A><BR>
<H4>TASC SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM<BR>
</H4>
Several Outstanding senior students are recognized each year with $500 scholarships
in honor of their achievements and contributions to Student Council.<A HREF="#SCSCH">Click
for more details.</A><BR>
<H4>RECOGNITION PROGRAMS FOR LOCAL COUNCILS<BR>
</H4>
TASC recognizes hundreds of high schools and middle schools in Texas each
year for their work in Health and Safety, Energy and the Environment, Alcohol
Abuse, Pride and Patriotism, and for overall Outstanding Student Council
Programs. For more information and a copy of hear of the report forms, <A HREF="ftp.aus.computize.com/tassp/forms">click
here.</A><BR>
<H4>LEADERSHIP COURSE CURRICULUM<BR>
</H4>
TASC is committed to providing leadership opportunities and training for
as many students as possible. With the summer workshops, district conferences,
state conferences and other &quot;meeting&quot; formats, TASC reaches in
excess of 10,000 students each year. To broaden and strengthen the opportunities
available to Texas students, the Association with the support of TASSP,
has arranged for an experimental course curriculum to be available to Texas
High Schools during 1996 - 97. For additional information, <A HREF="mailto:bgreen@tassp.org">contact
the TASC office.</A> <BR>
<H4>DISTRICT ORGANIZATION</H4>
The state is divided geographically into 19 TASC Districts. <A HREF="#DistMap">See
District Map.</A>Each district is governed by a District Executive Committee
and provides services to its member schools. Districts conduct elections
for District offices, screen and report District schools to be recognized
in TASC Recognition programs, and offer a structure of support for newly
organized councils, new Student Council advisors, and Principals.<BR>
<H4>TASC INSIGNIA</H4>
Attractive lapel pins, patches, guards depicting the TASC Star Insignia
are available from <A HREF="mailto:jostens@info.net">Josten's.</A> See their
site for pictures and order forms. <A NAME="SCSCH"></A>
<H2><CENTER>1996 TASC SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>CRITERIA AND RULES FOR APPLICANT</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT+5<B>I<FONT>n recognition of the enormous contributions of many students
to the Student Council programs, the Texas Association of Student Councils
will recognize four to ten outstanding graduating seniors with college scholarships.
The amount of each scholarship will be from $200 - $500 as determined by
the scholarship committee, with total funds of $3,000 committed by the Board
of Directors, $1,000 of which was donated by <A HREF="mailto:/">Argus Communications.
</A>Local councils may nominate no more than 10% of the total senior membership
on the council. For example, for 1 - 14 senior members, the council may
nominate one scholarship applicant. For 15 - 24 senior members, 2 nominees
may be submitted, etc. Student(s) nominated by local councils must meet
the following criteria to be considered:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>must be a senior member of the student council, with a minimum of two
consecutive years on the council. 
<LI>must have a cumulative grade average of 85 for seven semesters through
February 1. 
<LI>must enroll in the summer or fall following graduation in an accredited
institution of higher education. 
<LI>must fully complete the official application and submit it with transcript
and required attachments no later than March 1, 1996 to the TASC office.
<LI>must have certification from both schools regarding student council
involvement if transferred from another school. 
</OL>
All applications received will be judged by the State Scholarship Committee
on a point system. Winners will be recognized at the TASC Annual Conference,
with payment of the scholarship deferred until proof of enrollment in college
is submitted to TASC. Scholarships will be paid directly to the winning
students. No fewer than four scholarships will be given in 1996, and no
more than ten. <BR>
<BR>
Send the application to TASC Scholarship, 1833 So. IH 35, Austin, Texas
78741. Deadline for applications is March 1, 1996.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="WhatSC"></A>
<H2>What is a Student Council?</H2>
The role of student council varies from school to school. There is very
little that is absolute about what a student council <STRONG>must</STRONG>
be. The individual school's faculty and administrative attitudes, along
with the needs of the student body will determine in large measure what
the local student council <STRONG>IS</STRONG>.<BR>
<BR>
Elements though, of most definitions would include: 
<UL>
<LI>A group of student 
<LI>Elected by students 
<LI>Organized 
<LI>To promote school activities 
<LI>To plan programs and activities 
<LI>To represent the interests of students 
<LI>To represent the interests of faculty and administration 
</UL>
In order to be effective and viable within the school, a good student council
should 
<OL>
<LI>Fairly and equitably represent the student body 
<LI>Perform worthwhile functions within the school 
<LI>Be based on democratic principles 
<LI>Maintain open communication with the students, faculty and administration.
</OL>
<P><CENTER><TABLE border> <TD><BR>
<STRONG><FONTSIZE=+2>Student Councils were not meant to be all things to
all people; <BR>
rather they were meant to help all people be all the things they would like
to be.<BR>
<BR>
</STRONG></TABLE><BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
