<HTML>"Around the State"<p>
by various authors<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 29-30<p>
<p>
Formed six years ago, the Texas Business and Education Coalition (TBEC) provides a meeting place where business and education leaders regularly come together to discuss concerns and provide recommendations. TBEC has been structured so that its members can simultaneously influence both the direction of state education policy and support community-based school improvement efforts. <br>
John Stevens,<br>
Executive Director, TBEC<p>
The following partnerships represent great education opportunities happening across the state because of this strategic link:<p>
<p>
<strong>Around the State:</strong><p>
<strong>Lamar County Business Education Coalition</strong><p>
by Bonnie Woodfin<p>
<p>
Lamar County, Texas is a rural area located on the Texas/Oklahoma border, approxi-mately 100 miles northeast of Dallas. The economy is driven by a 50/50 combination of agriculture and industry. The nucleus of the business and industrial community is comprised of five Fortune 500 companies. This fact, along with a rich educational heritage and a commitment to the youth of the county provides a perfect climate for a merger between education, business and industry.<p>
Through the activities of the Education Committee and a broad cross-section of county citizens, in October 1991, the Lamar County Coalition of Education, Business and Industry was formed as a separate entity whose purpose is to encourage cooperation between the five independent school districts, the junior college and the business community, to assure that the students of the county are successful graduates and fully prepared to enter the workforce and/or higher education.<p>
Among the many tangible results of the Coalition's efforts are:<p>
1.The implementation of the Texas Scholars Program in all five county school districts.<br>
2.Industrial tours provided initially to teachers to familiarize them with the real world situations which will confront their students. The tours have been expanded to include students as well.<br>
3.Production of a video library detailing job descriptions, qualifications and required training for available positions in local companies. This information is presented by employees who actually hold these positions.<br>
4.Introduction of the Junior Achievement Program into all the school districts of the county. Volunteers from the business community are currently in the classrooms one day a week teaching Applied Economics to seniors across the county.<br>
5.Development of the Lamar County Alternate School.<br>
6.Initiation of the Head Start Program in the county.<br>
7.Introduction of the Baby-Think-It-Over Teen pregnancy prevention program and the Parent-To-Parent Drug Awareness Prevention program.<br>
8.Development of customized training for the major industries by Paris Junior College, specifically, the Electro-Magnetic Technology course developed collaboratively between Paris Junior College, Kimberly-Clark and Campbell Soup Company.<p>
This is only a partial list of Coalition projects. Our board of directors is composed of an equal number of business representatives and educators. Several projects have allowed for the direct involvement and input of the business community into the development of policies and procedures within the school districts. The long-term, consistent support from business and industry is unprecedented. The Coalition was honored in USA Today as one of seven national winners of outstanding grass roots programs for improving educational opportunities.<p>
<p>
<p>
<strong>Around the State:</strong><p>
<strong>The Katy Business Promise</strong><p>
by Michelle Hughes<p>
<p>
<p>
The Katy Business Promise is a community coalition of the Katy Chamber of Commerce, West Houston Association and the Katy school district. The Promise was kicked off at a recent luncheon with Governor George W. Bush with 1,000 people in attendance. Businesses that participate in the program communicate to employees their commitment to quality education by encouraging employees to be actively involved in their children's education. They provide information about workforce needs and assure students opportunities to interview for available jobs. They increase student awareness of job opportunities and provide information about entry-level job requirements. They also support the development, retention and recognition of high quality teachers and encourage employees to pursue educational opportunities. Students are encouraged to pursue challenging courses of study that enhance their post-high school opportunities.<p>
<p>
<p>
<strong>Around the State:</strong><p>
<strong>The JOGS Program</strong><p>
by Mary Grace Rodgers<p>
<p>
GLOBE (Greater Longview Organization for Business and Education) has designed and implemented a program to give positive reinforcement to students who pursue becoming GLOBE Scholars.<p>
In the JOGS (Job Opportunities for GLOBE Scholars) program, local business people give "job interviews" at the school campus to students on the path to being Scholars. The primary purpose of the interview is to give students experience in job interviews. And, although businesses are asked to participate even if they do not have job openings, many Scholars-to-be obtain summer jobs through the interviews.<p>
It had been found that interviews for students didn't often include questions about critical issues such as grades and attendance. Employers participating in the JOGS program interviews ask those types of questions; they also critique the interviews so the teenagers can do better on future interviews. <p>
The employers also provide feedback to the students on their appearance, their application and their presentation.<p>
Since its inception, a wide range of employment opportunities have been represented during interviews. That range, and the number of employers participating has continued to grow as employers throughout the area learn more about JOGS, GLOBE and the emphasis these programs place on a solid education.</html>

</DOC>
