<HTML>"Businesses Want to Invest in Kids for the Future"<p>
by Amy Jones<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 3-4<p>
<p>
A strong public school system is essential to the prosperity of any community. More and more businesses are beginning to realize how much the success of their future depends on the quality of local schools. As a result, many companies are enthusiastically entering into partnership programs with schools, and these partnerships are providing much more than traditional corporate contributions. Today's most visible school volunteers are often local business people who are participating in school/business partnership programs. <p>
Investing in partnerships can result in tremendous payoffs for schools. These collaborations can result in enriched curriculum, awareness of career opportunities, improved campus morale, recognition for student and school achievement, professional development opportunities, access to technological advances and equipment, and additional resources not provided in district budgets.<p>
<strong>Partnership Payoffs</strong><p>
The Austin Adopt-A-School relationship between Johnston High School in the Austin Independent School District (AISD) and Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) is a shining example of partnership success. Contributions made by AMD during the 1994-95 school year resulted in a significant improvement in the overall school climate and academic achievement at the school. More than 200 AMD volunteers served as mentors, tutors and guest speakers at Johnston. People power is the greatest contribution a partner can make as role models from the business community provide an important link to the world of work. As a result of these efforts, AMD was named Austin Adopt-A-School 1995 Adopter of the Year.<p>
This winning partnership also provided Johnston with calendars/planners for 1,700 students, a teacher appreciation luncheon, on-site management courses for Johnston faculty and special tutoring sessions for seniors prior to the TAAS exam. When the school implemented a closed campus policy, AMD provided tremendous support to the campus beautification project. Trees and thousands of dollars worth of courtyard furniture provided much needed relief for an overcrowded cafeteria.<p>
School/business partnerships offer benefits to the corporate partner as well. When AMD realized they were facing a decreasing pool of qualified hi-tech workers to meet the demands of their growing company, they worked with their Austin-area adopted schools to develop and fund a career pathway in electronics for students at Johnston and Del Valle High Schools. The result is the Accelerated Careers in Electronics (ACE) Program. ACE consists of a two-year, tech-prep curriculum focused on electronics. High school students successfully completing the program can receive up to 16 hours credit toward an electronics degree at Austin Community College. AMD is also providing six-weeks of paid summer internships for participating students. Under the guidance of an AMD mentor, interns receive hands-on experience in addition to classroom instruction on personal computers, time management and presentation skills. <p>
"Exposing these students to a business environment helps them to become accustomed to the unique business world culture, as well as developing the skills necessary to be productive in their respective jobs," said Steve Layman, a Test 25 Operations Facilitator and AMD mentor.<p>
Some companies maximize their contributions by joining in a collaborative effort with other businesses. Last year, Frost Bank developed a Teacher of the Month program to recognize teachers in AISD. The program awards a $1,000 cash prize each month during the school year to a teacher whose name is randomly drawn from student or parent nominations. The selected teacher is also recognized with a quarter-page ad in the Austin American-Statesman and an interview on KLBJ-AM radio. The nominating student's class receives a Pizza Hut pizza party. This program brought together several businesses, each making an in-kind contribution in an effort to promote the teaching profession. "This program is just one small way that Frost Bank can say 'thank you' to our teachers," said Frost Bank President Bob Huthnance. <p>
The service industry is another resource for school support. The Hyatt Regency Austin has been working with Bowie High School for several years to prepare students for work in the hotel industry. The Hyatt provides on-site skills training and management intern positions to students from their adopted schools.<p>
Taco Bell of Austin implemented several programs to invest in kids at Mendez Middle School. Taco Bell created the Accelerated Achievement Academy to help students earn credits for failed classes. They developed and sponsored a program that provided back-to-school supplies for every student, teacher and administrator at Mendez. They implemented a program to provide employment opportunities to parents and Taco Bell employees have become personally involved with Mendez students through a mentoring and pen pal program. "Taco Bell's adoption affects all 1,188 students at Mendez," said Principal Mike Perez.<p>
<strong>Getting Started</strong><p>
Partnership programs can provide numerous benefits to a school and its business partners. However, developing and maintaining an effective partnership program requires hard work and commitment. The first steps in developing a campus or district partnership program include studying the campus improvement plan and school goals. A school must know what its needs are before asking for community support. <p>
Schools should select a campus contact or coordinating committee. Business contacts should not be called by any teacher or administrator needing event volunteers or financial support. Instead, requests should be channeled through a main contact who will develop a relationship with the business contact.<p>
 Develop a campus "wish list" and distribute it to likely partners. Remember to include volunteer support, in-kind contributions and financial requests on the list. Always provide information as to how cash donations will be used. If specific items are to be bought with cash donations, attach an order form to the wish list. When developing and distributing a wish list, be sure to address the following questions:<p>
What are the school's goals and objectives?<br>
Where are improved resources needed?<br>
Where could volunteers assist?<br>
What community businesses are already helping?<br>
Who are your corporate neighbors?<br>
Where do your students' parents work?<p>
<strong>Tools for Success</strong><p>
What makes a great partnership? Direct personal involvement and communication are key to the success of any partnership. The school contact must inform the business partner of opportunities for involvement and campus needs. Regular communication and recognition through monthly or quarterly partnership meetings are a must.<p>
Partnership programs must have strong support from the top. The school principal should know its business partners. The principal should communicate with partners at least once during the year. Principals and other campus administrators need to make every effort to attend partnership meetings and luncheons to show their appreciation. All school personnel need to be informed of campus contributions and be enthusiastic about working with volunteers from the business community.<p>
Other factors contributing to partnership success include planning and organization, the proximity of partners to the school and a good mix of partners. An organized program can easily find ways for new partners to become involved. Businesses located near the school are more likely to send volunteers to the campus for weekly mentoring or tutoring assignments. A variety of partners will work together, each providing their own talent and expertise, to assist your school in meeting its goals.<p>
"Quality schools are a cornerstone of our success in economic development," said Glenn West, President of the Greater Austin Chamber of Commerce. Today's business community is willing and able to assist schools in investing in kids for the future. Cooperative efforts can strengthen and enhance the quality of education at your school. Consider the many benefits that partnerships can provide your campus and start developing your program today!<p>
<p>
Amy Jones is the Director of Austin Adopt-A-School (AAS), an official partnership program  between the Austin Independent School District and the Greater Austin Chamber of Commerce. Austin Adopt-A-School supports over 2,000 partnerships with more than 100 AISD schools and programs. During the 1994-95 school year, Austin Adopt-A-School contributed over $4.8 million in volunteer hours, in-kind contributions and cash donations to AISD. For more information contact Amy Jones, Greater Austin Chamber of Commerce, at 512-322-5628 or Elaine Naleski, Austin Independent School District, at 512-414-3991.</html>

