<HTML>"Caulking the Cracks in the Classroom"<p>
by Stephen Lindsey<p>
<p>
Topic: Examining teaching styles v. learning styles<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 34-38, 40<p>
<p>
"I said sit down and get quiet!" the teacher barked as the students scattered to take a seat in one of the nicely arranged and straightened rows. "Now that I have your attention, I want you to open your texts to page 25 and follow along as I write on the blackboard, and remember, no talking"! For the next twenty or thirty minutes this junior high school math teacher works problems directly out of the text while his class supposedly follows along.<p>
"Are there any questions over what I just showed you?", he asks as he places the smoking piece of chalk on the holder at the base of the blackboard. The students, fearful of others thinking that they are not so bright, respond with dazed looks and a shaking of heads indicating no. <p>
"Good; now I want all of you to look at the bottom of page 28, and begin working the set of problems under the section entitled Practice. I will come around and help you if you get stuck. If you don't finish before the bell rings, these are for homework." The class continues with students hurrying to finish their assignments before the bell rings.<p>
Upon hearing the bell, the students gather their belongings and rush out of the door into the hallway teaming with friendly faces. "I don't know if I can take much more of that guy", one student says to another. "Yeah, I know what you mean; pretty dry stuff," responds the classmate. "It's guys like that who give teachers a bad name," another student adds. "Oh well, just eight more months. I think I'm going to die!!!" <p>
<p>
We've all been in or seen classes that are managed like the one described above, and we all survived it. If you didn't, you probably wouldn't be reading this article right now. OK, so if people like us made it, then with a little application and hard work, anyone can make it, right? I don't think so, and in the paragraphs that follow, I shall attempt to describe the implications and need for addressing this problem.<p>
<strong>Lessons From The Closet</strong><p>
My wife and I recently renovated part of our attic in order to add more closet space to our bedroom upstairs. This was a first-time carpentry project for us, and we admittedly were learning as we went along. The heat from the attic area of our home was intense as we worked in the unfinished area that would eventually be our new closet. We found that no matter how accurately we tried to measure and cut the wood for the closet walls, there were always cracks, some larger than others, where the walls met each other, or met the ceiling and floor. Thank God for caulk and trim board! For without them, the energy efficiency of our home, as well as the appearance of the finished product would have been less than desirable. How's the energy efficiency of the classrooms with which you are familiar? Are the finished products less than desirable? Just what is the caulk and trim board of the educational process? Well, keep reading and hopefully with a little patience I will begin to make sense.<p>
<strong>The Cracks</strong><p>
How many times have you heard that there are too many kids falling through the cracks in the public school system? If I had a grain of wheat for every time I've heard it, I'd be able to compete with Mrs. Baird! Just what are these cracks that everyone keeps talking about? Well, most of us are familiar with the statistics on at-risk youth and the state of society in general. These social problems are what most people focus on when they mention the "cracks." Although I believe that these social issues cannot be ignored by the public schools, I also feel that they cannot and should not become the entire focus. The "cracks" of which I speak are the different ways in which people are "cut". Just as the pieces of plywood in my closet were all cut differently ( no matter how hard I tried to cut them the same), so are the students "cut" in our public school system. Due to these individual differences, "cracks" were formed in our closet as my wife and I attempted to interface the plywood with each other, as well as with the existing system of studs and joists in our attic . It required quite a bit of caulk and trim board to seal all the cracks adequately. You see, by utilizing the proper tools and materials we were able to deal with the differences in the "cuts" of our lumber. We'll probably never have our own show on PBS, but when all was said and done, we had a reasonably energy efficient, eye-pleasing addition to our bedroom.<p>
<strong>Individual Differences</strong><p>
 Children, from all walks of life, come to the public school system with different abilities, personalities and ways of processing information; yet most of us as educators insist on dealing with students in a more or less generic fashion. This is not a good thing! For you see, when these unique individuals attempt to interact with each other as well as with the existing system of public education, some serious cracks are formed through which many students are lost or at a minimum neglected with respect to their learning needs. The differences in culture, learning style and personality of each student must be recognized, valued and utilized to enhance the academic growth of the individual. In my opinion, by ignoring such differences, the school system is neither energy efficient nor capable of producing desirable products for society. We, in public education, tend to stifle individuality at every turn for the sake of being in our own "comfort zone." When it comes to the instructional process, educators must find a way to overcome this practice and address the needs of our children in ways that better suit them rather than the institution. In essence, we need to contract for an extensive remodeling job in most of the classrooms across this vast land.<p>
<strong>Caulk & Trim Board </strong><p>
The caulk and trim board of the instructional process is simply a repertoire of teaching strategies and practices that allows an instructor to deal with those students whose culture, personality and learning style calls for a different approach to instruction. These strategies, practices and approaches to instruction expand the educational process, thus sealing up the cracks making it more efficient and capable of producing quality products. The more knowledge of different cultures, learning styles and personality styles an individual has, along with the strategies necessary to deal with the innumerable variations in any given classroom, the better he or she will be able to meet the instructional needs of a diverse population of learners. In order for an instructor to deal with these individual differences, he or she must first recognize the differences when they exist and then categorize the difference in order to select an appropriate instructional strategy that effectively deals with the detected difference. Only by abandoning the traditional generic approach to instruction can the "cracks" be sealed. <p>
<strong>Learning Style Preference</strong><p>
Everyone has a preference of style when it comes to learning. Some students learn better when instruction is delivered in an auditory mode, while others need to have a visual demonstration in order to master the same material. Still others need manipulatives (tactile) or movement activities (kinesthetic) in order to truly process and internalize the presented information. In addition to these delivery modes, some students work better alone and some work better in small well-organized groups. According to Dunn, Beaudry, and Klavas (1989), <p>
Most children can master the same content; how they master it is determined by their individual styles, and those who suggest that children should learn to adapt to their teachers' styles disregard the biological nature of style. (p. 53) <p>
If we truly want all students to be successful, it is the school that needs to adapt to the learning style preferences of the student.<p>
Therefore, it is of the utmost importance that our classroom leaders have the ability to present information in a variety of ways and utilize numerous strategies in doing so. Zuehlke (1994) writes that,<p>
A communication gap exists between their teaching style and the students indigenous learning style. Therefore what is a valuable and valid communication process under one cognitive style becomes a deformed example of cognitive linguistic deficits under another. Teachers need to be careful that their teaching style does not  become a 'teaching style straight jacket' because they can be flexible and learn to teach in a variety of ways (p. 14).<p>
In many instances teachers simply need to become aware that this discrepancy exists, and that it can be overcome with training, patience, and practice. This "teaching-style straight jacket," however, continues to restrain far too many teachers in our public schools. The unpardonable sin in this analogy is that the "men in the white suits" will not come for the true culprit, but will instead apprehend the students who are incapable of coping due to educational neglect, leaving behind "straight-jacketed" teachers to inflict more damage upon the unwary masses that ultimately will comprise our future.<p>
Another component of one's learning style that has direct implications in the classroom is hemisphericity. We are all familiar with the old right-brained, left-brained research on the ways in which humans process information. With respect to hemisphericity, Marshall and Johns of the Center for Success in Learning (CSL) in Dallas, Texas categorize students as either Analytic (left-brained) or Global (right-brained). CSL makes the following distinctions.<p>
Analytic students are students who process thought logically, think from part to whole, approach tasks sequentially and tend to excel in language centered activity. Global students, on the other hand, think from the "big picture" to the small detail, from whole to part, in patterns and relationships rather than linear outlines and in pictures rather than in words and symbols. ( p. 1)<p>
The determination is therefore that students process information in different ways according to the dominant hemisphere of their brains. The implications for instruction should be quite clear. Information needs to be presented to our students in a way that they can best process it, not in a way that is necessarily comfortable to the instructor. Dunn, et. al. (1989) state, "Identifying learning styles as a basis for providing responsive instruction has never been more important than now, as teachers meet the needs of a diverse student population." (p. 50) Diverse populations require diverse strategies in order to meet the needs of all the students in the system. Being comfortable feels nice, but seeing kids learn feels even better!<p>
<strong>Personality Styles</strong><p>
Have you ever had a teacher in your school want a particular student in his or her class moved to another teacher's class due to a personality conflict? Or better yet, have you ever had a student request to be moved from a class for the same reason? Sounds pretty silly doesn't it? Well, it's sad but true; it happens all the time in schools all over the nation. It seems to me that a little understanding of each others' personality style would save an awful lot of grief as well as schedule change forms. It is necessary to understand that students have different personality traits that affect the way they learn. Teachers have different personality traits that affect the way they teach. When the two don't match something has to give. Unfortunately, it's the student who usually ends up giving the most, when in fact it is the student who needs to receive the most. <p>
Dr. Darrell Townsend (1995) has described four distinct personality groups. He has labeled these groups by assigning each a color. The groups he has established are Green, Gold, Blue and Orange. <strong>(see lists at end of article)</strong> <p>
Given this description of how the various personality styles influence learning and learning activities, one can soon see the problems that could arise in a classroom in which the instructor was either unaware of or unwilling to address the different personalities and learning needs of the students who are within his or her classroom. Dr. Townsend also lists teaching preferences of educators that fall into each of the four personality groups.<p>
From these lists of learning and teaching preferences, one can easily predict what would happen in a classroom filled with "Orange" students led by a "Gold" instructor. The underlying principle behind Dr. Townsend's work is that everyone has a dominant personality type and falls into one of the four categories. It is not possible for someone to change his or her color; however, it is possible to become familiar with the other colors, understand them and "DO" them when appropriate. For example, if there are a large number of "Orange" learners in a teacher's classroom, then he or she, regardless of his or her color, should work some less structured, competitive activities into the lesson plan in order to address the personality style characteristics of these students. Therefore, it is the teachers in our public institutions who must take the responsibility for adapting to the style of the student, not the other way around. By doing this, I propose that our students would see school as a much more pleasant place to be; learning and teaching would become much more fun for the participants. Teachers as well as students would experience much greater success. <p>
<strong>Cultural Differences</strong><p>
The recognition of cultural diversity and multicultural education in general have recently become the targets of much criticism and controversy. This criticism, although possibly well-intentioned is misguided, and at times flies in the face of logic. True, we are all Americans, but to assume that this fact, by virtue of its very existence, indicates that there should be no recognition, much less affirmation of the various cultures from which our students come is absurd. Recognition and knowledge of the diverse cultures that are present in our schools should not be seen as controversial, but rather as a powerful means by which to meet the needs of our students. Cummings (1994) states that,<p>
Recognizing the power of culture in the teaching and learning environments of classrooms and schools is vital to the expectation of an education for all children that is excellent, equitable and legitimate. When combined with other elements such as language, age and individual considerations, culture has the potential to build a bridge between home and school and student and teacher. When educators are successful in providing these bridging  opportunities, the dynamic potential for school reform, improved student achievement and a renewed connection of the community and school are within reach. (p. 13)<p>
It is the institution then, that must accept the responsibility to incorporate the recognition and affirmation of diverse cultures into not only the structure, but the very fiber of this intricate, dynamic social system we call a school. This is only necessary if we are indeed sincere about our pledge to meet the needs of all students.<p>
Are we sincere, or are we merely giving lip service at the appropriate times to the appropriate people in order to create the illusion of a school system dedicated to excellence and equity for all? Educators who ignore a student's cultural heritage, which is possibly the most significant motivating factor in his or her life, are not dedicated to the proposition to teach all students in the most effective way possible, but rather dedicated to the proposition of teaching in a way that is less effective, but much more comfortable. Cummings (1994) writes that, <p>
although some educators emphasize the age and individual differences of the developmentally appropriate construct, other equally powerful discussions have focused on the potential for improving student achievement through student-centered education that includes strong cultural components provided through Afro-centric, Euro-centric and Hispanic-centered curriculum and instructional tenets. (p.14) <p>
Motivating students to pursue maximum levels of academic achievement is our business. Therefore, a student's culture and knowledge thereof is just one of the many vehicles that can carry us toward our ultimate destination of success for all students. To refuse to utilize this mode of transportation is, in essence, an admission that we don't really care if some of our kids are left at the bus stop. Another benefit that is reaped by utilizing the motivational power of culture is that of linkage formation between students and teachers as well as between schools and homes. Delpit (1992) states that, by examining who our students really are and where they come from, we can build bridges that will span the existing gaps. He writes,<p>
We foster the notion that students are clients of professionals who are met in the office of the classroom where their deficiencies are remediated and their intellectual illnesses healed. Nowhere do we foster inquiry into who our students really are or encourage teachers to develop links to the often rich home lives of students, yet teachers cannot hope to begin to understand who sits before them unless they can connect with the families and communities from which their students come. (p.14)<p>
A lack of cultural knowledge and expertise oftentimes comes across as insensitivity on the part of the teacher and /or the school. Although possibly unintentional, this appearance of insensitivity is not excusable. If the school is to be accountable to all children and their families regardless of their cultural background, then the school should, and rather quickly, begin to equip, inform and train personnel in a multicultural platform.<p>
<strong>Role of Staff Development</strong><p>
Of course, we can't expect teachers to become proficient in appropriately addressing the various cultural, learning, and personality needs of all their students overnight. As in any worthwhile endeavor, an investment of time and resources is necessary to bring about effective change in the status quo. This investment must begin with the school district's philosophy of budgeting and staff development. <p>
An appropriate amount of money must be set aside to properly train all district instructional personnel in the assessment and implementation of a variety of teaching styles, principles and practices that will adequately address the needs of the diverse population in our schools. Without this support from the board of trustees, the superintendent and other key district personnel, significant change will never occur. The result of neglect on the part of a district in the area of budgeting and staff development will result in teachers that are as effective as the proverbial screen door on a submarine. <p>
I truly believe that all teachers want to do a good job. I have yet to meet one that I feel wakes up in the morning and says, "I think I really want to stink-up the classroom today." It is up to the district to give its teachers the support and training necessary to become effective facilitators of learning. Unless this philosophy is the prevailing one in the district, look for mediocrity to become the norm, leaders to become complacent, and ultimately children to suffer.<p>
<strong>Conclusions</strong><p>
What a powerful aspect of the educational process to neglect! Unless these connections between students and teachers, teachers and parents, schools and communities are made, schools will continue to slip in their effectiveness and their products will continue to be shoddy. A remodeling job is in order for most of the classrooms in our public institutions. <p>
The need to address the individual differences in the culture, learning style and personality of our students has never been more urgent. It seems like the "cracks" keep getting larger and greater in number. Unless the system of public education in America begins to equip its teachers with "caulk and trim board", the "cracks" will never get filled, the closet will never get finished, and our student population as a whole will be left injured and dying along society's highway. As students enter our schools, they must not, be exposed to situations that will hinder their educational experience. For crying out loud, we're supposed to help! <p>
However, due to our own ignorance and unwillingness to change, many times we do more harm than good. This does not have to be the case. We need to reexamine our commitment to the children that come through our doors, and pledge to help them all regardless of our comfort and convenience levels. We have a moral responsibility to the next generation to pave the way to a brighter future. Bennet (1993) in his Book of Virtues includes a poem by William Allen Dromgoole, entitled The Bridge Builder, that puts this responsibility into perspective. This poem reads,<p>
An old man going a lone highway,<br>
Came, at the evening, cold and gray,<br>
To a chasm, vast, and deep, and wide,<br>
Through which was flowing a sullen tide.<br>
The old man crossed in the twilight dim;<br>
The sullen stream had no fears for him;<br>
But he turned, when safe on the other side,<br>
And built a bridge to span the tide.<br>
Old man," said a fellow pilgrim, near,<br>
"You are wasting strength with building here;<br>
Your journey will end with the ending day;<br>
You never again must pass this way;<br>
You have crossed the chasm, deep and wide - <br>
Why build you the bridge at eventide?"<br>
The builder lifted his old, gray head:<br>
"Good friend, in the path I have come," he said,<br>
"There followeth after me today<br>
A youth, whose feet must pass this way.<br>
This chasm, that has been naught to me,<br>
To that fair-haired youth may a pitfall be.<br>
He, too, must cross in the twilight dim;<br>
Good friend, I am building the bridge for him."<br>
(223).<p>
<strong>Learning Preferences</strong><br>
<br>
<strong>Orange</strong><br>
Noisy environments<br>
Real-life applications<br>
Immediate payoffs<br>
Competitive situations<br>
High-energy activities<br>
Variety in lessons<br>
Physical involvement<br>
Entertaining teachers<br>
<br>
<strong>Blue</strong><br>
Harmonious environments<br>
Cooperative learning<br>
Open discussions<br>
"Feeling Perspectives"<br>
Artistic applications<br>
Non-pressured situations<br>
Imaginative activities<br>
Caring teachers<br>
<br>
<strong>Gold</strong><br>
Structured environments<br>
Traditional learning activities<br>
Clear expectations<br>
Specific goals and objectives<br>
Established routines<br>
Rewards for achievement<br>
Task-oriented groups<br>
Organized teachers<br>
<br>
<strong>Green</strong><br>
Quiet environments<br>
Cognitive challenges<br>
Non-linear learning<br>
Hypothetical analyses<br>
Independent learning<br>
Sufficient time<br>
Experimentation<br>
Competent teachers. (p.16)<p><br>
<p><br>
<br>
<strong>Teaching Preferences</strong><br>
<br>
<strong>Orange</strong><br>
Informal environments<br>
Entertaining presentations<br>
Spontaneous formats<br>
