<HTML>"Dare to Dream: Graduation Really Achieves Dreams"<p>
by Emily Cole & Jim Ketelsen<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 11-13<p>
<p>
Martha was a student in the tenth grade when I met her. She told me she was interested in a medical career. I saw the determination in her bright eyes at the same time a deep ache appeared in my stomach. How could I tell her our limited curriculum was not preparing her for success in a medical field?<p>
That scenario occurred eight years ago at Jefferson Davis High School, an inner-city school situated a mile north of the Houston Downtown district. To build an academically competitive school was the challenge, and it took an educational collaborative of partners to lay the first cornerstone. <p>
The Jefferson Davis High School Education Collaborative was launched in the spring of 1989 by Tenneco Inc., the University of Houston-Downtown and Houston Independent School District. At that time a freshman class of about six hundred students only graduated two hundred students. About twenty students would enroll in college and less than five students earned a degree. The goal of the 1989 collaborative was to substantially reduce the dropout rate and to significantly increase the rate of college attendance and success at Davis High School.<p>
The successes of Jefferson Davis High School's student body in the years since 1989 are proof that the collaborative and other initiatives it has spawned are achieving their purpose. The centerpiece of the program is the Tenneco Presidential Scholarship. Tenneco Inc. committed to provide each Davis student a $1,000.00 a year college scholarship for four years provided they met the set criteria:<p>
(1) to graduate on time with their class, <br>
(2) to maintain a 2.5 grade point average in core academic subjects, <br>
(3) to complete the mathematics sequence through Algebra II, and <br>
(4) to participate in two  summer academic institutes offered by UH-Downtown. <p>
The scholarship could be used to attend any accredited university or college in the United States. With this commitment in place an instructional program began to take place. Partners were recruited to assist. The Metropolitan Organization (TMO) assisted with the parent-community component to ensure parent and community support for the instructional changes that would take place. They assisted with organizing the annual Walk for Success (a visit to the homes of all 9th grade students). The Communities in Schools (CIS) program provided the students with emotional support and guidance. CIS also managed the summer work program for these students.<p>
The Jesse H. Jones Summer Academic Institute, sponsored by Houston Endowment, Inc. and implemented by the University of Houston-Downtown, consists of a four-week intensive academic experience focusing on leadership skills, developmental reading, study skills, time management, critical thinking and analytical skills. Specific advanced preparation in mathematics and the natural sciences also is provided for those who qualify. <p>
Participation has expanded dramatically since the inception of the first summer institute in 1990. The first recipients of the scholarship were members of the class of 1992. Out of 199 graduates, 101 received the scholarship (51%). The results to date can be seen in Figures 1 and 2 (see page 12).<p>
The Jeff Davis Collaborative has successfully proven that low-income, minority inner-city students with adequate support can be motivated toward higher goals, standards and achievements. The majority of the students who stay in school are now college bound. Clearly the culture of this school has been totally changed.<p>
Although the Davis program had increased the school's college-bound rate from ten percent in 1989 to sixty-nine percent last year, it was obvious that more had to be done in the elementary schools and middle school to prepare the students for a more rigorous academic curriculum. The dropout rate was decreasing, but ever so slowly and painfully. A closer look at the phenomena of the causes needed to be investigated.<p>
In the fall of 1993, an innovative idea led by Jim Ketelsen, retired C.E.O. of Tenneco, Inc., began to take form. The program, named Project G.R.A.D. (Graduation Really Achieves Dreams), focuses resources, new curriculum and intensive teacher training on the seven elementary schools and one middle school whose students feed into Davis High School. The instructional programs are all proven and tested and are currently being used in some Texas schools. The long-term objectives of the Project GRAD initiative are to capture the hearts and minds of the students at the beginning of their career before too many have been turn-ed off or fall behind. Specifically, the objective is to increase test scores of students above national norms and reduce the dropout rate to acceptable levels. Details of the four components of the program follow.<p>
<strong>Community and Parental Involvement</strong><p>
Project GRAD has engaged the service of Communities in Schools-Houston (CISH), a non-profit, year-round dropout prevention program to provide service in the seven elementary schools. CISH was already engaged at the high school and middle school. CISH places staff members at schools across the city and then augments this team with parents, volunteers and public and private agencies to help as therapists, tutors, mentors and class aides. CISH also offers extensive assistance to at-risk students.<p>
Under Project GRAD, a staff member from CISH has been added to each elementary school. The primary emphasis of this social service professional will be to coordinate community services and expand parental support. Providing CIS support throughout the feeder system will allow a broader development of community and parental support than has been possible to date.<p>
<strong>Classroom Management</strong><p>
Teachers are being trained in a new classroom management model, called Consistency Management, used to create a supportive, but firm and orderly classroom environment by emphasizing prevention of classroom problems. The University of Houston is the coordinator for this important component.<p>
Consistency Management encourages teachers to challenge students beyond the typical classroom lessons to improve the flow of classroom instruction and reduce student boredom. Teachers are urged to hold high expectations for students' behavior and management and to implement strategies that will help students succeed academically and achieve self-discipline. The model focuses on student participation in classroom and school governance to heighten students' sense of ownership and school pride.<p>
<strong>Math</strong><p>
The University of Houston-Victoria has trained teachers in its innovative Move It Math program. Move It Math balances skills and concepts and teaches thought processes that make huge amounts of mathematics understandable. It is a computerized curriculum database that correlates lessons from more than 250 teacher resource materials compatible with the National Council of Teachers of Mathematics Standards and support the Texas Essential Elements for Mathematics. Move It Math has elevated scores on standardized exams, improved students' attitudes toward math and aided at-risk students in meeting grade level expectations.<p>
<strong>Reading and Language Skills</strong><p>
A hallmark in public education, Success for All, is a nationally proven model for teaching reading, writing and language skills to children. Designed by Johns Hopkins University and the Baltimore Public Schools, this model stresses one-to-one tutoring by certified teachers with experience teaching special education and/or primary reading.<p>
Students also participate in reading programs that emphasize development of sound and letter recognition and basic language skills. The model stresses teacher training and a family support team consisting of social workers, parent liaisons, counselors and other professionals to provide parental education and encourage their involvement.<p>
Since the inception of these programs, over 40,000 hours of teacher training have been provided to teachers in the feeder system covering Consistency Management, Move It Math , and Success for All. Extensive support was provided for all curriculum with each school receiving in excess of $75,000.00 of support materials - manipulatives for math, integrated computer-indexed math libraries, extensive new reading materials, text, support materials, etc.<p>
The full impact of the program will only be measurable in the longer term, when the Pre-K and kindergarten classes of the 1995-1996 school year, the first classes to receive all parts of the program, reach the testing years of third, fourth and fifth grade and again when those same children progress through middle and high school. However, the results of our first full year of teaching Move It Math in 1994-95 were very encouraging. Third grade, where almost all teachers were trained prior to the beginning of the year, showed exciting results. The percentage of students meeting minimum expectations in math for the feeder system on the TAAS test (the official achievement measurement for the state of Texas) taken in May 1995, increased 50% from 34% to 51%.<p>
Strong follow-up, direction, and support of all four components of the programs must be maintained over the next several years. Each of the three classroom components have teacher facilitators in each school.<p>
The work being done in the feeder pattern has attracted additional support. Work is going forward with the YMCA and Serve Houston to provide an after-school program at each of the seven elementary schools. We are hopeful that by the 1996-1997 school year, all elementary schools will have a complete after-school program emphasizing both recreational and remedial work.<p>
Health needs of all the children are now being addressed. Harris County Hospital System, in cooperation with the Harris County Hospital Association and with TMO leadership, has established a clinic at Sherman Elementary which also serves two additional nearby elementary schools. Community Partners has a medical van which provides transportation to their nearby clinic from the other six schools in the feeder system. Community Partners also runs a nursery/day care facility at Davis High School for thirty-plus children of Marshall Middle and Davis High School students, allowing these students to complete high school.<p>
Beginning in the summer of 1996, St. John's School, an outstanding private K-12 school in Houston, will offer a summer "Bridge" program to approximately forty fifth graders who will be attending Marshall Middle School in the 1996-1997 year. This national program at an exemplary school will provide a tremendous 14-month program of support and acceleration for these students.<p>
In addition to the Tenneco Scholarship showing signs of success and Project G.R.A.D. building embryonic talent, another full partnership has evolved with the University of Texas Health Science Center. This partnership will build on the math and science component of the curriculum. A brighter path to the medical field is now made possible through the Main Street Project.<p>
Clearly, the success of the original Tenneco/Jeff Davis High School Partnership has led to substantial involvement by many other members of the community. At this point, six universities (University of Houston-Downtown, University of Houston-Victoria, University of Houston-Main Campus, Rice University, Johns Hopkins University and University of Texas Health Science Center) have programs aimed at improving the academic results of the Jeff Davis Feeder System. Corporations such as Tenneco and Shell are providing mentoring and tutoring support as well as significant dollars. Funding has been obtained to support the programs from additional corporations and major foundations in Houston. Organizations such as The Metropolitan Organization, Communities in Schools, the YMCA, Harris County Hospital System and the community have a commitment to do what it takes to provide the support necessary to allow these at-risk children to succeed.<p>
The collaborative has won numerous national and regional awards. It was cited as exemplary by the President's Forum on Teaching as a Profession, the National Association for Industry-Education Cooperative and the National Association of Partners in Education. It has been Houston Independent School District's most enduring business school project.<p>
The momentum and motivation provided by the original partnership, because of its success and clearly demonstrated results, has attracted additional support from many facets of the community. This program shows that it is possible to generate a great deal of support from the community if they can be shown that demonstrable results can be achieved.<p>
By the way, Graduation Really does Achieve Dreams. Martha is now a medical student at University of Texas Medical School-Galveston. </html>

</DOC>
