</DOCHDR>
<HTML>"From Conflict to Consensus Through Parent Involvment"<p>
by Carole Greisdorf<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 8-10<p>
<p>
Today, every decision from the most mundane to the most esoteric is subject to intense scrutiny and conflict, demanding broad participation in the decision-making process. Whether the subject is dress-code, attendance boundaries, discipline, grade alignments, or how spelling is taught, parents will want to be involved and, generally, whether we desire it or not, they will be involved. Whether schools and boards become involved in rancorous conflicts or whether they solve problems in a manner most satisfactory to all depends on their skill at conflict resolution and consensus-building. This often depends on the level of trust that has been established between the local school and its constituents. <p>
There are no easy answers as educators around the nation seek a variety of strategies to improve the quality of education. Complex problems demand varied and creative solutions. They also demand flexible leaders willing to explore new paradigms. One thing seems certain: no matter the socio-economic background of the students or where the school is located, when parents are involved in their children's education, the students do better. And isn't that what we all want?<p>
The importance of family participation has been recognized at the federal level. National Education Goal #8 states that "By the year 2000, every school will promote partnerships that will increase parental involvement and participation in promoting the social, emotional, and academic growth of children." And the National PTA, quoted in the Texas PTA Parent Involvement Manual, says, "Parental Involvement is the participation of parents in every facet of the education and development of children from birth to adulthood, recognizing that parents are the primary influence in their children's lives. Parent involvement takes many forms, including the parents' shared responsibilities in decisions about children's education, health and well-being, as well as the parents' participation in organizations that reflect the community's collaborative aspirations for all children." Research shows that "when parents are involved, children do better in school, and they go to better schools." (Henderson, Anne, 1987, The Evidence Continues to Grow).<p>
Successful parent involvement happens when principals and other educators create opportunities, work to develop understanding among participants, and accommodate differences based on ethnicity, background and education. That involvement may not look the same in all schools, but creative planning can result in an increased level of support and participation from a diverse parent body.<p>
According to Carl Marburger in his book One School At a Time, "As more control is given to the school and community, public confidence in the schools increases, problem identification and solution become more timely and accurate, and the needs of individual students are more likely to be met."<p>
The concept of parent involvement is changing. For years, educators built symbolic moats around their schools. The drawbridge was lowered when money was needed for special projects, when advertisements were needed for the football program, or when chaperones were required for field trips or dances, and then it was raised to keep out unsolicited parental involvement or input. <p>
"High School students don't want to see their parents at school"..."Parents want to participate in elementary school activities, but once their children move to middle school, we just don't see their parents"... "Secondary teachers don't need volunteers."<p>
These and other similar excuses have been given for years as to why parental involvement slacks off dramatically after elementary school. Today, those reasons are hollow and unacceptable. Administrators at all grade levels must take positive action. We must demonstrate a commitment to an organized program of involvement by opening our schools to the community and making certain that our actions are responsive to community and parental demands.<p>
According to Archie McAfee, principal of Plano East Sr. High School, a Blue Ribbon School of Excellence, "Parent involvement makes our school stronger. It shows a spirit of support that our teachers appreciate, and strengthens the morale of our staff." <p>
When Plano East was only a dream for the district, meetings with parents set the stage for a change in perspective at that school which continues today, 13 years later. Lengthy discussions among all stakeholders in the school resulted in the formation of Panthers Incorporated, an umbrella organization for all school booster clubs. The Panthers' Incorporated Board, working closely with the school administration, now coordinates all fund-raising, volunteer activities, student events and parent participation at the school.<p>
Like many schools in Texas, Plano East's school-based improvement committee plays an essential role in the development of the school's mission and strategic planning. At Plano East, the SBIC meets for a full day retreat at least once a year, and meets regularly throughout the year to help implement the committee's action plan.<p>
Plano East, according to Principal McAfee, makes communication with parents a high priority. The school uses varied techniques: School newsletters, cable television, booster club meetings, open house activities, key communicators, counselors' newsletters, parenting education classes, automatic calling system for absentees, and a FAX system which can send information to parents. Additionally, McAfee and his team of administrators are readily available and responsive to parents.<p>
McAfee says, "Successful parent involvement is not a function of a school's wealth. It takes time and work, but is certainly worth the investment. We've adopted the same philosophy as hospitals. Years ago, you could only visit during pre-set hours, and the only place to wait was the lobby. Hospitals learned that families had to be a part of the healing process. Schools similarly have learned that families must be invited and included as part of the learning process, and it must be continuous."<p>
Plano ISD, a rapidly growing district of 38,500 students, has long been dedicated to making parent and community involvement an integral part of its planning and decision-making process. The district's involvement program is multi-faceted and includes: <p>
The district's policies, strategic plan and goals which emphasize a commitment to parental and community involvement. <br>
A parent teacher organization at every one of the district's 45 schools.<br>
A volunteer/partnership coordinator whose responsibilities include recruiting and training business representatives and parents to serve as mentors to at-risk students. <br>
A comprehensive information program which includes district and school newsletters and other alternative communication methods including a Fax network and soon, we hope, a WEB-site.<br>
Trained school-based improvement committees where actual strategic planning and activities take place based on the recommendations of the committee. <br>
The Practical Parent Education program which helps teach parents how to be more actively involved in their children's education and promotes parenting skills. <br>
The district's 12 advisory committees and numerous ad hoc committees all of which include parent involvement.<br>
The Presidents' Council, a districtwide committee consisting of the presidents of every parent organization, which meets monthly with a district administrator.<br>
A group of key communicators consisting of a minimum of three parent representatives from every school which meets quarterly with the superintendent and staff to share information and concerns. <br>
Customer relations and communications training which is provided to employees. <p>
Additionally, Plano seeks to involve those parents who have traditionally felt unwelcome in public schools. For example, a Hispanic parent educator provides translation and support. Meetings have been held, in conjunction with the Plano Council of PTAs, with Hispanic parents to encourage their involvement as volunteers. Also, brochures citing the advantages of parent involvement have been published in different languages by the PTA Council. Finally, parent centers are being established in schools which will provide materials in a variety of languages to meet the needs of diverse constituencies.<p>
Constant nurturing, refining and plain hard work are essential for successful parent involvement programs. In summary, parent involvement must be: <p>
Planned - it doesn't just happen. Planning for successful parent involvement includes a needs assessment of the school, participation by teachers, parents and other staff members in how parent involvement will be structured, research into other successful programs, substantive activities for all participants, and evaluation mechanisms.<p>
Genuinely desired - everyone must believe in the concept and be dedicated to making it work. The principal sets the tone and creates a team approach to parental and community involvement. <p>
Comprehensive - all stakeholders in the school community must participate in a variety of roles. This includes training for teachers and other school staff members on how to make their schools "family-friendly."<p>
Individualized - there is no recipe or blueprint for the "perfect" partnership school. Involvement must focus on how student learning can be enhanced, and how teachers can be supported in their efforts.<p>
Public schools have many battles to fight if we are going to succeed in our mission. We should, however, be able to declare peace on one battlefront by becoming strong allies with our parents; by making them soldiers along with educators in combating negativity and apathy; by enlisting their support on the legislative front and in the media; and by enjoining them to help us prepare our students for a successful future. <p>
<strong>Research</strong><p>
Henderson, Anne T., Marburger, Carl L. and Ooms, Theodora, (1986) Beyond the Bake Sale: An Educator's Guide to Working With Parents, Columbia, MD: The National Committee for Citizens in Education.<p>
Carl L. Marburger, One School At A Time, (1985), The National Committee for Citizens in Education.<p>
<p>
Carole S. Greisdorf has served as Special Assistant to the Superintendent of Schools for Plano ISD for the past three and a half years. She oversees all aspects of communications including community relations, grants, volunteer and partnership programs, policies, elections, media relations, publications and facility usage. Carole formerly headed the Communications Department in the Volusia County, Florida, School District, a district of approximately 50,000 students. </html>

</DOC>
