http://jukebox18.computize.com:80/texstu/social.htm 199.1.196.87 19970216205211 text/html 20168
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Sun, 16 Feb 1997 20:55:41 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.1
Last-modified: Tue, 18 Jun 1996 19:43:17 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 19984
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>"An Alternative for the Social Promotion of Over-Aged Middle School Students"<p>
by Larry Sutton<p>
<p>
Topic: Alternative programs at the middle level<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 31-33, 40<p>
<p>
Tricia, a fifteen year old seventh grade student, recently transferred to our school from a nearby metropolitan school district. Her parents moved purposely to our smaller community because Tricia had been heavily involved in Hispanic street gangs since the age of eleven. Although she had been a good student through the fifth grade, she had been truant from school a majority of the time the previous two or three years, hanging out with members of her gang rather than attending school. As a result of excessive absences for two of the last three school years she was unable to meet attendance and grade requirements for promotion.<p>
Recently, in dealing with Tricia for a discipline related matter involving gang tagging of school property, we became aware of how committed Tricia is to her gang and to gang-type activity. One of the first antisocial acts of young gang members involves the territorial marking of either public or private property. Using spray paint or permanent markers, they write their gang name or tag in a distinctive graffiti style. As we talked with Tricia about this, we became aware that she is very capable of doing quality school work and that she has some very good organizational skills. She expressed a great deal of frustration with being in the seventh grade (most seventh graders are twelve or thirteen years old) when she knew that she should be in the ninth grade according to her age. Some type of intervention is necessary to assist students like Tricia in being more successful in school.<p>
Tricia's story demonstrates the need for middle schools to provide promotion alternatives for students who do not fit into special programs such as those for students who are learning disabled, migrant or have English as a second language. For students in these programs, promotion decisions can be made through the deliberations of the Language Proficiency Advisory Committees (LPACs) for ESL students and the Admission, Review and Dismissal (ARD) Committees for learning disabled students in special education. In addition, migrant and special education students are eligible for a multitude of social and educational services. However, in the past, over-aged students such as Tricia who were not in these programs were sometimes able to advance only through social promotion. Reacting to a strong expression of concern for the practice of social promotion of over-aged students, legislation passed in the early 1980s in Texas (House Bill 72) limited this type of promotion/placement. The impact of this legislation for students such as Tricia created the possibility that a student could be two years behind his or her peers by middle school.<p>
Educators continue to search for ways to help a student who has stumbled academically to regain his/her feet through an alternative placement program. One theoretical approach being discussed provides opportunity for the over-aged student to move through three years of middle school in two years by providing an instructional program and a support system based on acceleration rather than remediation. Usually at a slower pace and at a lower level, a remediation program attempts to reteach and reaccomplish previously attempted work. The proposed accelerated program takes students where they are academically and enthusiastically guides them through a program covering only those essential areas that will bring them to the basic level of their age-appropriate peers. Such an accelerated program would definitely benefit a student like Tricia.<p>
<strong>An Acceleration Model for Over-Aged Students </strong><p>
In developing an Accelerated Placement Program that would address the needs of over-aged middle school students, perhaps it would be beneficial to identify those elements which have proven to be effective in dropout prevention programs. Successful programs often: <p>
Offer alternative curricula to interest the students.<br>
Provide a supportive environment to meet the holistic needs of the student.<br>
 Emphasize self-awareness, interpersonal skill building and developing responsibility for one's behavior. <br>
Provide academic and other experiences which lead to early and frequent success. (Florida Center for Dropout Prevention, 1986) <p>
In addition, the staff has a major impact upon the success of any program. When staff members of dropout prevention programs were surveyed about factors for program success, the most frequent response, by far, was "the person(s) responsible for the program". The qualities of the staff were identified as follows: <p>
Genuinely interested in the students. <br>
Able to work cooperatively with other school staff. <br>
Eager to work in the program.<br>
 (Peck, Law and Mills, 1989)<p>
Our proposed Accelerated Placement Program is a voluntary school-within-a-school model. It emphasizes the uniqueness of each student with an effort to accommodate students' different styles and rates of learning. A small pupil/teacher ratio makes this approach feasible. The curriculum for the program focuses on the specific skills required to master the objectives measured by the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills tests at each grade level and successful mastery of subject area skills which at various points would be determined by end-of the-year tests. End-of-the-year tests have been developed for each middle school subject in order to accommodate the advanced placement option provided for in the Texas education reform legislation of the 1980s (House Bill 72). <p>
In addition to the academic component, a social skills curriculum would also be delivered to these students to increase their interpersonal skills and enhance self esteem and responsible decision-making. Students who enter the sixth grade as an over-aged student (two or more years beyond the normal age for the grade) would have a special group of teachers dedicated to delivery of the functional academic and social skills curricula with the goal of accelerating the student through a year and a half per year of instruction. An option would be available for students who do extremely well in terms of acceleration to move from the program at the end of the first year into regular eighth grade classes if they were able to successfully complete the end-of-the-year tests for the seventh grade courses. <p>
<strong>The Promotion/Retention Debate</strong><p>
As a middle school administrator attempting to provide for a population of over-aged students, I have encountered some degree of opposition to plans to accelerate the educational experience of these students. It may be surprising to some that the strongest opposition comes from teachers. They raise questions of fairness to the students in placing them in a program that allows them to circumvent the standard promotion requirements. Their primary concern is that by allowing an unprepared student to advance without demonstrating mastery of required skills, the student will have an inadequate basis for future learning. Is it fair for the school to allow a student to advance into a situation of potential failure? Alexander, Entwisle and Dauber discussed Smith and Shepards study of kindergarten teachers' attitudes about retention in which they found that most teachers subscribe to an achievement ideology: "Teachers believe... the pupil's career should be driven by competence or readiness rather than by social promotion and . . . for the most part, they act according to their beliefs." (Alexander, Entwisle and Dauber, 1994) <p>
The debate over retention and promotion of unprepared students is not new. Since the early 1900s, at least fifty studies have attempted to end the debate over promotion and retention of unsuccessful students. Results due to flawed designs of the studies are so mixed that it is difficult to draw meaningful conclusions. (Lindelow, 1985) However, John Lindelow points out that "For the majority of retained students, what didn't work the first time doesn't work the second time either, and most of these unfortunate students continue to meet with failure wherever they are placed." Doug Chafe, in an article written in 1984, analyzed various studies determining that <p>
retained students are likely to show improvement when measured against the norms of the grade they are repeating, and decline when measured against the performance of similarly skilled students who were promoted. A more meaningful finding is that gains made by retained students relative to new younger classmates tend to disappear in later years. Retention alone does not teach the child how to become a better student, so gains are not likely to be permanent.<br>
(Chafe, 1984)<p>
Alexander, Entwisle and Dauber concluded that none of the reviews of retention research "favors retention as a strategy for helping poor performing students do better,". (Alexander, Entwisle and Dauber,1994) Smith and Shepard made the following statement in their 1987 Phi Delta Kappan article: <p>
The evidence is quite clear and nearly unequivocal that the achievement and adjustment of retained children are no better -  and in most instances are worse than those of comparable children who are promoted. Retention is one part of the current reform packages that does not work. (Emphasis in original)<br>
 (Smith and Shepard, 1987, p. 134)<p>
William L. Callison's Dropout Prevention Handbook reviewed a Los Angeles Unified School District Dropout Prevention/Recovery Committee's 1985 report that indicated that dropouts are retained five times more often than are other graduates. A student who is retained in either first or second grade, has a 20 percent chance of graduating. (Callison, 1994) Despite the overwhelming evidence against retention, this practice is still one of the strong components of the educational reforms initiated in the 1980s. Obviously, there are over-aged middle school students because they have been retained at least once. Because this practice has been in place for so long, we will need programs to assist these over-aged students at least through this decade.<p>
<strong>The Need for Accelerated Programs and Placement Alternatives</strong><p>
The need to accelerate over-aged students at the middle school level is critical. In addition to the fact that retention seems to be ineffective and in many cases detrimental to students, the presence of over-aged students may be a problem for their younger classmates. Over-aged students usually have matured physically and socially due to their chronological age beyond the level of their age appropriate classmates. Parents of age appropriate students are often concerned when there are over-aged, under-achieving students in classes with their children. They are concerned with the behavior problems and the negative influences they envision having an impact on their children. Parents may fear that the teacher may have to adopt a slower pace for the class due to the limitations of the retained students and that there may be more classroom management problems. <p>
<strong>Adapting Previous Alternative Placement Options</strong><p>
At Taylor Middle School and other area middle schools, the need for alternative placement options was addressed during the past eight to ten years with programs that produced marginal success for some of the participating students. Taylor Middle School's Alternative Placement Program, which will accommodate over-aged students until a more effective accelerated placement model is implemented, provides a method for advancement without a support system to insure that the academic and social skills are acquired. An over-aged student entering the Alternative Placement Program makes a contractual agreement with the school administration and his/her parent(s) to: <p>
(1) Remain in the current grade placement for one semester with the expectation that the student will be successful enough to meet the regular promotion requirements at that grade level, remain free of major discipline referrals and meet the attendance requirements. <br>
(2) Advance to the next grade level at the beginning of the second semester with the same expectations that the student will be successful in terms of passing academic classes, having no major behavior problems and meeting attendance requirements.<br>
(3) Attend and successfully complete the regular summer school program for those students who are required to attend for promotion/placement. <br>
 (Taylor I.S.D. Administrative Regulations)<p>
The proposed Accelerated Placement Program attempts to continue the effective practices of the present Alternative Placement Program, eliminate those aspects that are not functional and implement practices that will produce successful students. For example, in the Alternative Placement Program a student is able to advance through two grades in one year and one summer. The program has allowed students who have matured enough to be responsible about their assignments and behavior to succeed. However, they receive no more support than any other student. There is no organized support system to assist the student attempting the challenge of moving from one grade level to the next in the middle of the term. The most difficult phase of this program occurs during the Spring semester. At this point the student enters the next grade without having covered the material classmates covered during the Fall semester. The proposed Accelerated Placement Program addresses the support issue by providing a team of teachers specifically assigned to the students in this program. These teachers will provide instruction at an accelerated pace and a social skills curriculum in addition to the academic curricula. This provides the opportunity for students to work on the development of attitudes and habits that are a basis for success. <p>
Perhaps the most effective aspect of the Alternative Placement Program has been the summer school component. The Summer Learning Camp has components of both remediation and acceleration. In small classes, students are provided a rather innovative multi-level (non-graded) environment where instruction is thematic and interdisciplinary. Teachers utilize motivating strategies and a number of field trips to integrate field experiences with classroom work. Although Summer Learning Camp teachers are committed to the concept of making the experience relevant and interesting, it does not mean that everything flows smoothly. Often the teachers express frustration at being able to get a student who is so near completion of the program to make the final efforts necessary to complete required assignments and projects. The Summer Learning Camp should also become a valuable part of the Accelerated Placement Program functioning in much the same manner as it has in the Alternative Placement Program. Some of the instructional strategies already being utilized in the Summer Learning Camp would be appropriate for the Accelerated Placement Program classes during the regular school year. <p>
Realizing the limitations of the current Alternative Placement Program in terms of not having a specific staff dedicated to the delivery of an academic and a social skills curriculum and an inadequate support system for the transitions the student must make from one grade to the next, there is a definite need for the improvements of the Accelerated Placement Program to help students like Tricia to become successful students. Students in the program will benefit from instruction based on the end-of-year course tests at each grade level and the opportunity for advancement as skills are mastered. <p>
<strong>Implementation Concerns and Limitations </strong><p>
In order to implement an accelerated placement program, the following considerations would need to be addressed: funding for personnel, classroom space, curriculum materials including computer software and equipment, recruitment and training of appropriate personnel, design of both academic and social skills curricula, planning for instruction and the securing and funding of testing materials. Since this is a school-within-a-school program, the students involved in the Accelerated Placement Program would only be in classes dedicated to the program for a part of their school day. Physical education and elective classes, especially those pre-vocational electives, would be taken with students in the regular program. Personnel dedicated to the Accelerated Placement Program would fluctuate with the number of over-aged student assigned to the regular program. The second year of implementation would perhaps double the cost in terms of staff in order to provide for both first and second year students in the program. Even though there are some definite costs related to the implementation of an accelerated program for over-aged students, the benefits for the students and the decrease in the dropout rate that should result from such a program are certainly worth the initial expenditure.<p>
Are there any negative aspects to the Accelerated Placement Program? With such a program are there some concerns for the school and for students like Tricia? Some of the concerns that are present with any program dedicated to any at-risk student population may be inherent in the Accelerated Placement Program. Primarily, having the students who are over-aged and usually somewhat unmotivated placed in classes with students who are very similar provides some concerns. Discipline management and the limited number of successful peer role models are potential problems. Another major concern has to do with staffing. It is my experience that inadequate and inappropriate staffing along with inadequate training has certainly limited the effectiveness of many programs with otherwise effective designs. If acceleration is to be accomplished in this proposed placement program, the teachers must be well trained and uniquely capable of dealing with under-achieving students. <p>
Recognizing the fact that retention has such a negative impact upon students and that there are many Tricias in our schools, there needs to be a way to provide for our over-aged students. The Accelerated Placement Program may provide a method for these students to successfully re-establish themselves as students and help them to develop better feelings about themselves. Without a tremendous cost to establish the program initially, the Accelerated Placement Program should pay for itself in terms of dropout prevention and increased revenue from state funding based on attendance. In terms of helping students become more successful in life, the program is certainly cost effective for our society.<p>
<strong>References</strong><p>
Alexander, Karl L., Doris R. Entwisle and Susan L. Dauber (1994), On the Success of Failure: A Reassessment of the Effects of Retention in the Primary Grades, New York: Cambridge University Press.<p>
Callison, William L., (1994), Dropout Prevention Handbook: Apprenticeships and Other Solutions, Lancaster, PA: Technomic Publishing Co., Inc.<p>
Chafe, Doug, (1984), "Retention: Research, Policies and Decision Making" Prepared by Research, Evaluation and Accreditation Committee of the San Mateo County Office of Education, May 1984.<p>
Lindelow, John, (1985), "The Grade Retention/Social Promotion Debate", National Association of Elementary School Principals, Vol. 2, No. 1, November 1985.<p>
Smith, M. L., and L. A. Shepard, "What Doesn't Work: Explaining Policies of Retention in the Early Grades", Phi Delta Kappan, 66 (1987): 129-134.<p>
Smith, M. L., and L. A. Shepard, "Kindergarten Readiness and Retention: A Qualitative Study of Teachers' Beliefs and Practices", American Educational Research Journal, 25 (1988): 307-33.</html>
</DOC>
