<HTML>"No Money, Please! Community partnerships that build understanding - not activity funds"<p>
by Shana McKay & David Lusk<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 17-19<p>
<p>
The ability to build meaningful partnerships between the community and schools begins with a foundation of solid relationships.<p>
Relationships begin at many levels and in a variety of forums, but in the Conroe Independent School District, we are fortunate to have a non-profit organization called the Education for Tomorrow Alliance (ETA), which focuses on bringing together businesses and education to interact and work together as a team.<p>
The current programs facilitated by the ETA are COMPAQ SCI://TECH, CHOICES, Teacher Enrichment Program, Student Internships Program and the School-Based Partnership Program.<p>
<strong>COMPAQ SCI://TECH</strong><p>
Underwritten by Compaq Computer Corporation, this is an annual super science/technology exposition that brings together over 3,500 people representing businesses, the science and technology community, educators, students, volunteers and the general public. With more than 1,000 students K-12 participating in projects and more than 200 awards given totaling in excess of $32,000, this program is rapidly developing into one of the finest science and technology competitions in the state. Many high school students who research major projects for the competition say the work and exposure has helped their skills and selection of their chosen field of study in college.<p>
<strong>CHOICES</strong><p>
CHOICES is sponsored by Entergy/Gulf States Utilities and is a proven, cost-effective way to increase high school graduation rates. The program is presented annually to ninth graders in CISD by business people volunteering two days of their time to demonstrate that students can gain control of their futures by becoming responsible for their educational choices today. Presentations center on getting students to focus on staying in school, selecting courses wisely and emphasizing how studies directly impact job opportunities and employability in a real dollars and cents way.<p>
<strong>Student Internship Program</strong><p>
The Student Internship Program matches sophomores and juniors with mentors from a diverse group of businesses, industries and other entities to give them an inside look at potential careers. During the month-long, non-paid experience, students work closely with professionals who give advice on how to set and reach their goals, help them explore options and assist them in making a stronger connection between their current education and their future work experience. This program is brought to the community by Columbia Conroe Regional Medical Center Hospital.<p>
<strong>Teacher Enrichment Program</strong><p>
The most significant component of the Teacher Enrichment Program is conducted during the summer when teachers are placed in paid positions in the business community. This experience helps to augment teaching skills by providing current real world practice and application in the fields related to the educator's instructional area. <p>
<strong>School-Based Business and Education Partnership Program</strong><p>
The CISD's School-Based Business and Education Partnership Program, however,  is the most far-reaching program because it touches every school in a unique way. Although school-business partnerships and adopt-a-school programs are not unique, CISD's approach is.<p>
Developing the program was one of 10 improvement goals outlined through the CISD's Visioning and Strategic Planning Process in 1993. The goals were based on a community-wide needs assessment that was conducted in late 1992 and the early part of 1993. The planning process itself involved hundreds of people and got many focused on education as more of a "team" endeavor.<p>
The management team, with representatives from central administration (including the superintendent), schools and businesses/chambers of commerce, was established to implement the school-based partnership program and research programs across the country considered to be the best. The strongest tenets that surfaced and became the basis for the program were the following:<p>
Target a business for each school that would become a primary and significant partner and bring them on line;<br>
Invite the chief executive officer by letter to learn more about the program and then follow up with a call and visit by the Superintendent, the ETA Executive Director and the Education Committee Chairs from the chambers of commerce. The initial discussions must be by the decision makers - CEO's talking to CEO's;<br>
Let the businesses know up front that their commitment would be one of human resources - time, energy, expertise. (Money was never, and is still not, an issue);<br>
Clearly discuss and outline the mutually beneficial aspects of businesses being involved directly in the schools;<br>
Provide a road map for planning and suggested activities to get started. It is important to facilitate the brainstorming of needs, resources and activities that can bring the two together. The sharing of ideas is very important in the early stages of the program, as is the designation of the "coordination team" from both the school and the business and the time to get to know each other and create understanding;<br>
Develop procedures so that when a business partner has been matched with a school, other schools will no longer approach that business for assistance/fund-raising, etc.;<br>
When all schools have a significant partnership that is solid and running smoothly, begin to encourage the inclusion of secondary partners that can compliment and supplement the resources of the primary partner. In addition, begin to explore ways to encourage partners to share their human resources/expertise with other schools with similar needs if those resources are abundant and available;<br>
Recognize efforts through celebrations, newsletters, brochures, etc. No business or activity is too great or too small to make a difference. Understanding each other's role in the community can be as important as reading in the classroom, displaying art and student works or tutoring students. It is very important for young people to know that people in the community care about them.<p>
Matthew Thomas, former Education Committee Chair for the South Montgomery County/Woodlands Chamber of Commerce, management team member and liaison between Entergy/GSU and its partner Conroe High School, has been a strong proponent of education and the partnership program since day one.<p>
"It reminds me of the old Fram Oil filter ads - 'you can pay me now or you can pay me later,'" he says. "I believe the benefits to the businesses are obvious - it makes 'cents' and in the long run it will save dollars." Thomas believes there are four major factors that should convince any business to get involved in this type of educational partnership: <p>
1) it will cost less to help educate students now, than to retrain them later when they hit the workforce; <br>
2) it will enhance the company's image - this type of investment in the community will help make a difference in the lives of young people - better than any dollar invested in advertising; <br>
3) economic development - families and businesses want to be located in communities where there are excellent schools; <br>
4) the company will ultimately develop better products because the employees will be of a higher quality.<p>
"In today's market there is no such thing as unskilled labor - you are either skilled or unemployed," he adds.<p>
<strong>Partnerships That Work Both Ways</strong><p>
Thomas has stepped out and been a leader in many ways. He has chaired the fund-raising/scholarship committee for the COMPAQ SCI://TECH 96 and will be chairing the entire event next year. He is also the first to take his company into schools outside his "partner" school - the CHOICES program is moving into every ninth grade class in the school district. Entergy/GSU has donated computers to CHS for the business classes and has also taken advantage of the resources at Conroe High School.<p>
"When we needed customer information translated into Spanish, we immediately contacted our CHS partner and tapped into the Spanish instructional program to match their resources and expertise to our need," Thomas says.<p>
And Alan Veach, principal at Conroe High School says he likes this approach to partnering better than any with which he has been previously involved.<p>
"Having one significant partner provides the opportunity to get to know them and to work as a team to enhance what is going on in the schools," Veach says. "It is very rewarding for all those involved and fosters a healthy respect for the schools and the businesses."<p>
Don Stockton, principal of Knox Junior High School in The Woodlands, says the reciprocal nature of the partnership is novel. While partnering with Allstate Insurance, Stockton did staff development for the employees and there wasn't a week that the company didn't take advantage of the large group instruction room or the gymnasium. Some of the partnership activities Stockton highlighted included career talks, pen pals for students needing extra adult contact, and even some specific assistance to staff, i.e. financial planning tips.<p>
Chris Kattner, principal of Peet Junior High School in Conroe, says the response by the school's dual partner - Montgomery County Government and Sadler Clinic - has been great. <p>
"Community people are in our building every day teaching in social studies classes," Kattner says. " I believe we need people from the community in our schools every day - it is a powerful tool for building community support and it gives people first-hand knowledge of kids and what's going on in schools today."<p>
Alan B. "Barb" Sadler, Montgomery County Judge, agrees.<p>
"Districts should not rule out other governmental entities and agencies when they are looking for school partners," Sadler said. "I was a little shocked when first approached, but it truly makes sense. As citizens and leaders, we are collaborating on more and more projects that influence the overall good of the communities we serve. What has more of an impact on our future, our quality of life, our economic development than the fulfillment and success of our young people?"<p>
<p>
Shana McKay has been the Director of Communication in the Conroe ISD for almost seven years. In the four years prior to that, she was a newspaper reporter with a background in education issues reporting. Ms. McKay is an Executive Board Member of the Texas School Public Relations Association (TSPRA) and is a graduate of Texas A&M University.<p>
<p>
David L. Lusk has been a Superintendent for 18 of his 27 years in education, the past four being in the Conroe ISD. He has been a Superintendent in Kansas City and in Covington, Kentucky, and has been an Assistant Superintendent in Roanoke, Virginia and in Jacksonville, Florida. Dr. Lusk - who received his doctorate from Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University - has received the National "Break the Mold" Award from U.S. Secretary of Education Lamar Alexander, an award of excellence from the International Society of Educational Planning and the F.L. Dupree Award for Creative Leadership. He has been named one of the 100 best school administrators in North America by the Executive Educator and was chosen by the Bush Administration as a consultant for the New American Schools Development Corporation.</html>

</DOC>
