<HTML>"The EDIT Project: A partnership to encourage minorities to enter teaching"<p>
by Grant Simpson<p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p>
<p>
from <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong>; Spring 1996; Vol. V, No. 2; pp. 14-16<p>
<p>
Under-representation of African Americans and Hispanics in the teaching profession is a problem at both state and national levels. In the 1993-94 school year, while 15.8% of the national student body was African American, only 7.4% of the teachers were. Similarly, Hispanics comprised 12.7% of the preK-12 population, but only 4.2% of the teacher work force. This is even more apparent in high density states. For example, California and Texas are home to 58.3% of all Hispanics in the United States. California's student body is 36.1% Hispanic, but only 8.3% of teachers are. Texas schools are 33.1% Hispanic, but only 12.9% of the teachers are; 14% of Texas students are African American, but only 8% of the teachers are. Nationally less than 10% of students seeking teacher certification are members of any non-European group, and education degrees earned by minorities are on the decline.<p>
For years recruitment and retention of under-represented groups have been focal points for Texas public universities. In return, there are significant increases in both African American and Hispanic students who are declared education majors. At my own institution (Southwest Texas State University with a student body of over 21,000), the concerted efforts at minority recruitment from 1986 to 1995 have more than doubled the percentage of under-represented groups to a total of 26.4% of the undergraduate population. School of Education figures mirror this progress. <p>
However, even in this encouraging data, there are disturbing trends. For example, statewide, of the 1,887 Hispanic education majors (1992-93, The Higher Education Coordinating Board), only 139 (7.4%) are seeking certification in bilingual/bicultural education. This is very bad news for a state with literally thousands of unfilled positions in bilingual education and a growing need which is almost exponential. Texas is growing annually by 80,000 students (preK-12). Almost 70% of these will be Hispanic or African-American. Of the 46,000 new Hispanic students annually, 75% will qualify for LEP (Limited English Proficiency) identification. In California, the numbers are significantly higher with over one million students identified as LEP and over 18,000 teacher vacancies in bilingual education.<p>
Likewise, the Texas Preliminary Consolidated State Plan (1995) cites critical teacher shortages in bilingual education, special education, science and math. The State Plan indicates that teacher training programs and school districts will have to document efforts to promote greater access and participation of historically under-represented groups in these disciplines. Again, current data magnify the scope of the problem. In the 92-93 survey of majors previously cited, 8 of 1,887 Hispanic education majors (0.4%) and only 1 of the 401 African-American majors (0.2%) declared a math or science focus. <p>
Summarily, not only do Hispanics and African-Americans continue to be under-represented in the teaching population, they are also not "in the pipeline" in numbers appropriate to the need. Thus, well-intended recruitment budgets for school district personnel departments may be efforts with very little return possible. <p>
<strong>If Not the Pipeline, Then Where?</strong><p>
Increasingly, school districts are beginning to acknowledge the potential of their own para-educator population as a source for increasing representation in the professional ranks. Para-educators are hired to assist with programs aimed at populations with special needs (e.g. bilingual, Chapter 1, migrant, special education). These teacher assistants are frequently minority females who may be lifelong residents of the community and graduates of the school system for which they work. Some have acquired college hours along the way; some only dream of it. Nationwide, a recent survey identified more than 150 programs in 30 states which identify and support para-educators on the pathway to teaching. <p>
Entrance requirements between states are a noteworthy distinction. In heavily unionized states, an associate degree or 60 credit hours are routine for entrance into para-educator ranks. In "right to work" Texas, only a high school diploma or the equivalent is required. Uniformly, these programs are geared to increase diversity in the teaching population and also to respond to high need categories. Almost half of programs surveyed have a special education focus; almost two-fifths are aimed at preparing bilingual teachers. <p>
<strong>The Partnership</strong><p>
 In the spring of 1991, the Tomas Rivera Foundation provided seed funding for the Enhancing Diversity in Teaching (EDIT) Project which was designed to increase the participation of under-represented groups in teacher education. This is a collaborative effort between a local school district and the school of education at Southwest Texas State University. The district identified para-educators as candidates who were then paired with successful, minority education majors in a mutual mentoring process. Para-educators are teacher aids who work "in the field." Oftentimes, para-educators only have a G.E.D. The college juniors, substituted in the workplace, allowed the para-educators to attend college classes while remaining full time employees with the school district. While the juniors provided nuts and bolts on university survival, the para-educators coached the juniors on the "real world" issues of public school. This arrangement provided a relevant field placement for the juniors and gave the cooperating school district early access for recruiting talented minority students nearing degree completion. The total group assembled for weekly seminars which developed topics for professional growth and nurtured their evolvement into a learning community.<p>
<strong>Expansion</strong><p>
The Texas Education Agency has refunded both expansion and continuance of the EDIT Project. In 1993 EDIT expanded from one district to five. As project director, I beat the bushes talking to nearby superintendents and their administrators, under the assumption that they would jump at the chance to grow their own professionals. Their responses did not disappoint. In one district, 100 para-educators turned out to hear about the program, and over 40 applied for consideration. The cooperating school districts had to establish an application, screening and selection process. Most also chose to secure board approval and public recognition for this "Grow Your Own Professional" effort. Because the fiscal year ended on 8/31, I did not get my renewal budget until early August. With registration two short weeks away, I literally had to hand walk eighteen new para-educators' applications through admissions and registration, breaking innumerable bureaucratic rules along the way. Identifying appropriate coursework, orienting the new students to campus, matching each para-educator with an available junior and building all of them into a supportive community of learners were just some of the challenges of expansion. But the view was worth the climb!<p>
In the last two years, the teacher preparation program at SWT has been restructured to include much earlier entry and intense experiences in the field. This made our junior "mentors" unavailable to participate in pairing with para-educators. To support the release time for para-educators, EDIT now reimburses the school districts for substitute fees incurred during the semester. Para-educators are encouraged to concentrate their schedules on afternoon and evening course offerings. Substitute reimbursement for a semester ranges from ($125 to $500) per participant. With pre-registration months in advance, the para-educators can plan their schedules and help with procuring a permanent substitute. This advance planning helps promote stability for all parties concerned:<p>
the para-educator whose job and family life is disrupted;<br>
the teacher and students whom she supports; <br>
the local administration. <p>
<strong>Results!</strong><p>
We now have 27 para-educators from 7 cooperating school districts. While participating in EDIT, they have earned an average of 26.4 credit hours and a 2.68 GPA. Eliminating 4 students currently on academic probation, the remaining 23 have an average GPA of 2.93. The cumulative records (all college work) reflect an average of 58.2 credits hours at a 2.61 GPA. Beside passing a state proficiency exam, the school of education requires a cumulative GPA of 2.5. These data clearly support the premise that the para-educators identified by their school districts are viable candidates for certification.<p>
<strong>Living Proof</strong><p>
Picture it - a small, rural town in Texas with two deeply rooted heritages. One, the founding German settlers who immigrated, farmed and prospered. Two, the Mexican residents who preceded the Germans and have a rich cultural heritage spanning centuries. The town mirrors the history of political, economic and cultural conflicts associated with Anglos and Hispanics throughout the southwest.<p>
Now imagine the parish hall of the local Catholic church, festively decorated with crepe paper, posters, and banners reading "Congratulations, Maria." The marquee sign of the local Mexican restaurant touts "Closed for Maria's Graduation." The hall is filled with a happy crowd from both cultures who fill the tables, enjoy the barbecue, toast the honoree and cheer as she unwraps each package in a dazzling array of presents filling three cafeteria tables. The town has gathered to celebrate one of its own, one who has worked at the elementary school for 20 years as a bilingual aide, one who has plugged away at earning college credits since 1976, one who in the last three years has amassed 79 hours at a 3.62 GPA, one who graduated today and starts work on Monday, not as the para-educator, but as a certified, bilingual, kindergarten teacher. <p>
Within fifteen minutes of meeting Maria, you know that you are in the presence of a survivor and a success seeker. She is distinctive in many ways. Her outgoing manner, challenging questions and infectious laugh make her a standout in any setting. Clearly, she made a degree and teacher certification her highest priority, but her path to success would have been significantly longer without the assistance of a special program. Maria worked in another school district "down the road," but heard about the EDIT project through the grapevine. Seeing this as an opportunity to accelerate her coursework, she then talked both her school district and the project director into allowing her to participate. Her school district freed Maria to attend class without a student substitute and permitted her to have a flexible schedule. EDIT paid for tuition, books, and fees which enabled her enrollment in both semesters and both summer sessions. As she grew closer and closer to her goals, the district gave her even more freedom in coming to class for up to nine hours a semester. EDIT supported these efforts by providing funds for a substitute. Three years later, Maria's tenacity combined with the university/school district partnership paid off. <p>
<strong>The Future</strong><p>
Maria is one of the first three graduates of the EDIT Project, all of whom had signed contracts before graduation. The shortages exist; demographics indicate little relief in the near future. So instead of passive acceptance, a proactive recruitment from within seems timely, expedient and profitable. The good news for skeptical business managers is that the average expenditure per participant per year is about $1,500. The public relations value of this kind of investment in employees surely warrants district consideration of such efforts even without external funding. In a nutshell, the EDIT program has a waiting list of school districts and prospective participants. It could grow exponentially with seed monies to sponsor the collaboration. With each step towards success and each graduation, the data grows for institutionalizing the process. The message from Maria is: "I can do it!" The message to universities, school districts and their communities is: "This works!" </html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT18-B21-91</DOCNO>
