<HTML>"San Antonio administrator named as NASSP/McDonald's State Assistant Principal of the Year"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Principal Awards<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 2, 13<p><p>
<p><p>
When hearing people speak about Donald Pinson, one frequently hears the words "dynamic," "firm" and "kind." Indeed, if one were to listen to his bosses, peers and his students' parents, one would come to see this mildly-countenanced vice principal at San Antonio's John Marshall High School as one of those people who is the lifeblood of the institution: a  major piece of the school's infrastructure, if you will. <p>
Connie Madla, parent of four John Marshall students, first met Pinson through Band Booster activities. One of Pinson's functions is to serve as the liaison administrator to oversee all Booster and band activities. The job requires his attendance at every band function, whether in-town or out-of-town. "It was during these times," said Madla, "that I observed that he... had a tremendous rapport with both parents and students. His untiring patience and dedication to the JMHS Band have earned him a very special place in the lives of many Band students... The man never loses his 'cool.'"<p>
But being the liaison administrator is only one of Pinson's duties. He is also responsible for the Special Education and Mathematics departments. In fact, he enjoyed his 17 years of teaching so much that he volunteered to teach a pre-calculus class when John Marshall opened its night school. Additionally, Pinson is directly responsible for the development of the master schedule of classes.<p>
Mike Watts, the former principal at JMHS, described Pinson's job regarding master schedule development: "Mr. Pinson is more than an effective scheduler. He uses many creative techniques to lower the number of teachers and periods required for "floating" teachers. He builds room arrangements to benefit staff while allowing no negative impact on the instructional process. Taken for granted by many individuals, the master schedule at Marshall is a work of art."<p>
After the Assistant Principal of the Year interview process, Pinson said he commented to his wife, "'You know, I gave some really stupid answers.' Then, when the guy called (Robert Madding, the chair of the TASSP Principal's Image Committee) to say I won, I'm not sure, but I think I said, 'You're kidding!' But I hope I didn't say that."<p>
All of the NASSP/McDonald's Assistant Principal winners from across the country will attend a special assistant principal workshop at McDonald's Hamburger University, April 27 through May 1. Pinson was also invited to be a guest of NASSP at the 1996 NASSP Annual Conference. However, this year's conference in San Francisco from February 23 through 27 conflicts with another important time in Pinson's life. His son, a senior at John Marshall, will be attending the state championships of the Academic Decathlon.<p>
"I really wanted to go to the NASSP conference," said Pinson, his voice positively glowing with pride as he speaks of his son's accomplishment, "but you gotta put family first." Mr. Pinson, if all parents were as dedicated to their family and jobs as you are, the world would be a better place. Congratulations from TASSP!</html>

</DOC>
