<HTML>"ASK A LAWYER . . .   Answers to principals' legal questions"<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 10, 17<p><p>
<p><p>
John S. Aldridge, an attorney with Walsh, Anderson, Underwood, Schulze, and Aldridge, P.C., answers questions from principals in this column, which is a regular TASSP feature. If you have questions, please pass them on to the TASSP staff. This column is not intended to constitute legal advice or to substitute for a principal's need to consult his or her school district's own attorney regarding legal questions.  <p>
<p>
DEAR JOHN: Under site-based management, in a spirit of "openness" I generally have my campus committee interview prospective teachers and other employees for vacant campus positions. However, I make the ultimate decision on who is assigned to my campus based on my professional judgment. Can the superintendent override my recommendation and accept the recommendation of the committee, if my superintendent doesn't agree with the individual I select? <p>
I assume that you are politically astute enough to avoid avoidable  confrontations with your superintendent. However, what's good  for the goose is good for the gander. The Texas Attorney General recently ruled that a school board could not hire an employee recommended by an "interview committee" appointed by the superintendent, over the objections of the superintendent. Tex. Atty. Gen. Op. No. 95-068 (1995). Under Senate Bill 1, the superintendent has the sole authority to make recommendations to the board regarding the selection of all personnel for hiring. Texas Education Code sec. 11.163(a)(1).<p>
The same rule  --  for principals  --  applies to local campus hiring decisions. You are the Queen (or King) of your campus domain. With one exception, Texas Education Code sec. 11.202(b)(1) gives the principal the sole authority to "approve all teacher and staff appointments for that principal's campus from a pool of applicants selected by the district or of applicants who meet the hiring criteria developed by the principal after informal consultation with the faculty." The superintendent has final placement authority only for a teacher transferred because of enrollment shifts or program changes in the district. Texas Education Code sec. 11.202(d). So, rule long and prosper!<p>
DEAR JOHN: Is there any way around the 7-day disqualification period imposed by TEA for the period after a student has made a passing grade and requalifies for participation in extracurricular activities? Can principals allow students to participate in extracurricular activities immediately on achieving a passing grade at the mid-3-week stage, or must they follow the 7-day disqualification rule mandated by TEA for UIL activities?<p>
For UIL activities, UIL has adopted a written rule that students  remain disqualified for seven days following the date on which  they receive grade reports or mid-six week notices of passing grades in classes which they previously were failing. No such written rule has been issued by TEA for other types of school-sponsored extracurricular activities (such as FFA stock shows, cheerleader activities, FHA events, etc.), and principals legitimately have asked whether the same "7-day disqualification" rule applies to non-UIL student events. Senate Bill 1 mandates "at least three weeks" suspension of a student from UIL and extracurricular activities after a grade evaluation period in which a student receives a grade lower than 70 in an academic class. Texas Education Code sec. 33.081(c).<p>
To insure that a student is suspended, in fact, for the full three weeks, the same 7-day rule should be adopted for all school-sponsored or sanctioned extracurricular events. Three weeks really means three weeks. The TEA rule allows for seven days of grace, but also requires seven days of disqualification. Because TEA grants students a 7-day "grace period" for the week immediately after a student receives a failing grade (during which period they can continue to participate, even though they have received a grade lower than 70), to guarantee a three week no-pass, no-play suspension, a corresponding 7-day disqualification period must be added to the other end after a student is shown to be passing at the mid-six-weeks stage. If not, a student's suspension would only be effective for two weeks, which would violate the statute. Principals should comply with that common-sense rule to avoid violating no-pass, no-play, and to avoid possible TEA accreditation sanctions.<p>
DEAR JOHN: I'm requiring all persons who enter onto my campus to leave their firearms at home (except for peace officers), regardless of whether they have one of these new "concealed handgun" permits from the State. Some teachers have objected, saying it's their "right," it's "legal," and they'll pack their heat anyplace they choose. After all, this is Texas! What should I do?<p>
The Attorney General has issued two recent opinions relating to  the new "concealed weapon" law and its effect upon school  districts. The first reviewed the new concealed handgun law, Senate Bill 60, and its application to activities of educational institutions. The concealed handgun law generally permits a person who obtains a license from the Department of Public Safety to carry a concealed handgun. However, Senate Bill 60 amends sec. 49.03 of the Penal Code to prohibit even license holders from carrying concealed handguns in certain places including: the physical premises of a school or educational institution, any grounds or building on which an activity sponsored by a school or educational institution is being conducted, or a passenger transportation vehicle of a school or educational institution, whether the school or educational institution is public or private, unless pursuant to written regulations or written authorization of the institution.<p>
Thus, teachers and visitors need to leave their handguns at home. However, a different rule applies for attendance at sites where high school or collegiate sporting events or interscholastic events are taking place. Senate Bill 60 also added sec. 46.035 to the Penal Code, which provides that a license holder commits an offense if he or she intentionally, knowingly, or recklessly carries a handgun "on the premises where a high school, collegiate... sporting event or interscholastic event is taking place, unless the license holder is a participant in the event and a handgun is used in the event." However, the statutory definition in Texas Penal Code sec. 46.035 of "premises" applicable to Senate Bill 60 is defined narrowly only to mean a building or portion of a building. Thus, the Attorney General concluded that a license holder is not prohibited from carrying a concealed handgun in the driveway, street, sidewalk or walkway, parking lot or parking garage where a collegiate sporting event or interscholastic event is held  -- because those locations are not "buildings or portions of buildings!" Tex. Atty. Gen. Op. No. DM-363 (1995).<p>
DEAR JOHN: Does that mean you can keep a firearm in a car parked in the school parking lot?<p>
Not unless the individual is in attendance at a high school or  collegiate sporting event or interscholastic event. Plus, there is a  solution even for attendance at sporting/UIL events. While the Attorney General concluded that a license holder is not prohibited from carrying a concealed handgun in the driveway, street, sidewalk or walkway, parking lot, or parking garage where a collegiate sporting event or interscholastic event is held, in the same opinion, the Attorney General noted that schools and businesses are authorized under other laws to post trespass notices to exclude people who are not authorized to enter onto specific property. Tex. Atty. Gen. Op. No. DM-363 (1995). In the same opinion, the Attorney General determined that Senate Bill 60 permits private business owners, who post the notice required by the criminal trespass statute, to exclude from their premises any persons carrying concealed handguns. In a subsequent letter opinion, General Morales determined that governmental entities, including school districts, similarly may prohibit persons carrying concealed handguns from entering or remaining on premises of which the governmental entity is the "owner," as that term is defined in the Penal Code. Tex. Atty. Gen. Op. LO-95-058 (1995).<p>
Regardless of such legal nit-picking, it remains a criminal offense for any person, including a license holder, to take a concealed handgun to a school board meeting. Section 46.035 provides that a license holder commits a class A misdemeanor if he or she intentionally, knowingly, or recklessly carries a handgun at any meeting of a governmental body. <p>
DEAR JOHN: I occasionally get requests from parents for student records of other students (usually those involved in discipline incidents with their children). Under the federal Family Education Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), I know I am not generally supposed to release identifiable student record information regarding another student. After all, this is pretty settled law. However, do I have still to submit those records to the Attorney General for permission not to withhold them, or can I just use my own judgment and withhold them?<p>
The Texas Attorney General's long-held view has been that a  governmental entity seeking to withhold records must request the Attorney General's determination to "approve" such withholding of records. In most cases, the Attorney General requires that the disputed records be provided to its office (together with a legal brief stating the legal bases to justify their being withheld). After the records are reviewed, the Attorney General then issues an opinion either directing that they be released or authorizing that they be withheld under one of the exceptions to the Open Records Act. <p>
However, under a new Texas Attorney General's decision, schools are not required to submit student FERPA record requests to the Attorney General for permission to withhold, if the reason for withholding them relates to the FERPA exception. Tex. Atty. Gen. ORD-634 (1995). Under that new decision, a school district may, without making a submission of the records to, and without seeking a determination from, the Attorney General, withhold records that qualify as "education records" under FERPA. You still will want to check with your school district's attorney on a case-by-case basis to insure that some other type of open records rule doesn't apply.<p>
Since the issuance of that decision, the Attorney General has been shipping back to the schools who had submitted them, all records that accompanied requests for Open Records Decisions in which the FERPA "student record" exception was claimed, without making a review or ruling on the records at issue. For student records requests, the Attorney General is telling schools that they should look them over. If the records are really FERPA-qualified, schools are being told to keep them under the authority of ORD-634, and don't bother the Attorney General further. </html>

