<HTML>Book Reviews<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 7<p><p>
<p><p>
"The Manufactured Crisis: Myths, Fraud, and the Attack on America's Public Schools"<p>
by David C. Berliner and Bruce J. Biddle.<br>
Reading, Mass.: Addison Wesley, 1995.<br>
Reviewed by Gerald Bracey<p>
On November 5, 1990, the Denver Post changed my life profoundly and forever, although neither it nor I knew it at the time. On that date, the Post reprinted an earlier Washington Post essay, "Johnny's Miserable SATs," by syndicated columnist Richard Cohen. That column led me to ask how miserable they really were, once you factored out the many demographic changes in who had been taking the SAT over the years.<p>
After all, the standards on the SAT had been set on 10,654 students in the Northeast. Ninety-eight percent of them were white, 60 percent were male and 40 percent had attended private preparatory high schools. By 1990, though, the group was 29 percent minority, 52 percent female, spread across the nation, and 31 percent reported family incomes under $30,000 a year. My own factoring produced an Education Week article entitled "SATs: Miserable or Miraculous?"<p>
With the appearance of that article, a number of researchers called my attention to other indicators also showing that the schools were doing better than people thought. Most significantly, engineers from Sandia National Laboratories in Albuquerque visited me in my Denver office and presented their report. I showed them the data I had gathered and suggested we put it all together and publish it. They informed me that politics prevented them from going public. "You bury this, or I'll bury you," was then-Deputy Secretary of Education David Kearns' reaction to their report. The Bush administration did not revel in good news about schools.<p>
The Sandia engineers then said that since almost all the data were already in the public domain, I should simply go it alone (much of their data emanated from the U.S. Department of Education). I did, first with unsuccessful approaches to the popular media, and then to Phi Delta Kappan with a piece called "Why Can't They Be Like We Were?," the refrain of a song in the 1960 Broadway musical, Bye Bye Birdie, and a title designed to debunk the prevalent nostalgia about how good schools had once been: "Why can't they be like we were, perfect in every way? Oh, what's the matter with kids today?"<p>
Just after I signed off on that essay, I hied off to the annual convention of the American Psychological Association. While sitting in the audience at one symposium, I suddenly had the odd sensation of hearing myself speaking from the podium. The actual speaker was David Berliner of Arizona State University. At the time, Berliner knew nothing of my article-to-be. Skeptical about the harsh verdicts handed down on U.S. schools, he had perused the same data I had come across and reached the same conclusions. <p>
Few things are more gratifying to a researcher than to have one's conclusions independently confirmed, especially when those conclusions run strongly against the prevailing wisdom and especially when the confirmer is a well-respected researcher.<p>
Since then, as I have produced the various editions of the annual "Bracey Report" in Kappan and Berliner has produced various articles in various venues, he and I have exchanged data as well as commiseration over the inattention granted those data by the media and policy-makers.<p>
All the while, Bruce Biddle of the University of Missouri was telling students, and Berliner, of the enormous distortions of data appearing in the media. Now Berliner and Biddle have put everything in one place in a book entitled The Manufactured Crisis. It is an important book to which educators must attend. If only the news media and the public would as well.<p>
This is no mere rehash of earlier articles. Even those who have read all five editions of the "Bracey Report on the Condition of Public Education" will find enormous amounts of new information freshly presented. Indeed, the most important parts of Crisis are not those that present the data, important as that function is, but those that undertake the more difficult tasks of trying both to identify the true problems of U.S. education and to prescribe what we can do about them. Berliner and Biddle contend that if you don't know what the real problems are, your "solutions" won't work. Makes sense.<p>
Early on, they attack the myths concerning the intelligence and achievement of U.S. students. In a separate chapter they debunk associated myths, showing that we don't spend more money on schools than other countries (most computations show us about average); that money is related to school achievement; that costs have not skyrocketed; that U.S. schools produce technically competent workers who then become the most productive in the world; that Americans are generally pleased with the schools their children attend; and that students in public schools out-perform those in private schools in some curriculum areas.<p>
Of course, if the prevailing views of U.S. schools are based on myths, then the proposals for school reform are perforce misguided. Berliner and Biddle take one chapter to explain why so many of the reform proposals put forward to date have not succeeded and cannot succeed. This chapter leads naturally to one analyzing the real problems of U.S. education  --  and U.S. society -- and what we can do about them:<p>
We have reviewed nine problems in American society that create distress for American schools... Each poses serious difficulties... Unfortunately, many people who propose reforms for education seem to be unaware of these problems, and as a result their proposals are unrealistic. Effective reforms must begin by taking these problems seriously (p. 240).<p>
This passage is as compelling as it is depressing: I see nothing on the horizon currently to suggest that anyone with the means to do anything about these societal problems is of a mind to do so. As Robert Samuelson put it in the Washington Post, "The war on poverty is over. The poor lost."<p>
Undaunted by this savage reality, Berliner and Biddle close with a chapter on improving education, dealing with such conditions as funding, school size, the curriculum, teaching methods, heterogeneous student populations, community involvement and the professionalization of education. None of this sounds sexy, only solid. Each area of improvement is undergirded by a principal extracted from research. <p>
The Manufactured Crisis opens with "This book is written in outrage." And so it is. And the reader is the better for it. Nothing may so concentrate the mind as the thought of imminent death, but anger works well, also. Berliner and Biddle are mad, and this translates into pungent prose that rivets the reader's attention. <p>
This book is a must for anyone in education. It provides the weapons for repudiating misinformed critics. It provides a good starting base for reform. The bonus is that it is also a wonderful read.<p>
References<p>
Berliner, David. "Educational Reform in an Era of Disinformation." Presented to the American Association of Colleges of Teacher Education, San Antonio, Texas, February 1992.<p>
Bracey, G. W. "SATs: Miserable or Miraculous?" Education Week, November 21, 1990, p. 28.<p>
 --  --  -- . "The Bracey Report on the Condition of Public Education." Phi Delta Kappan, October 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995.<p>
Samuelson, Robert J. "RIP: The War on Poverty." Washington Post, October 4, 1995, P. A25.<p>
<p>
Reviewed by Gerald W. Bracey, executive director of the Alliance for Curriculum Reform, a consortium of 31 educational organizations; author of the annual "Bracey Report on the Condition of Public Education"; and, most recently, Final Examination: A Study of the Perpetual Scrutiny of American Public Education, published by the Agency for Instructional Technology.<p>
<p>
Reprinted with permission from the NASSP Bulletin, Vol. 80, No. 576, January 1996, pp. 119-121. NASSP Bulletin is a publication of NASSP.</html>

