<HTML>Community Connections<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 11<p><p>
<p><p>
"The National "Back to School" Campaign Has a Role for You"<p>
Editor's note: The Family Involvement Partnership for Learning is leading a vigorous grassroots back-to-school effort called "America Goes Back to School: A Place for Families and the Community." U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley officially launched this initiative in September when he asked all Americans to rally around their local schools and make a commitment to support education improvement throughout the year. Secretary Riley was joined in this effort by the National Coalition for Parent Involvement in Education (NCPIE), a group of educational and community organizations that includes parent, principal, teacher, and school board associations.<p>
The following is an excerpt from a resource guide designed to support "America Goes Back to School," suggesting ways to get involved in children's learning. For a copy of the complete guide, write to the GOALS 2000 Information Resource Center, U.S. Department of Education, Room 2421, 600 Independence Ave., S.W., Washington, D.C., 20202.<p>
1. Improve the basics and core academics. <br>
Families: Read and write together, use TV wisely, encourage your children to do their best, and help develop school-family compacts. <br>
Schools: Rigorously teach the basics and encourage family involvement in teaching and learning the basics, and develop school-family compacts with parents. <br>
Community, religious, and business groups: Provide tutors as well as adult literacy training.<p>
2. Create safe and drug-free school environments.<br>
Families: Organize and participate in "parent patrols" or "security dads and moms."<br>
Schools: Require firm, fair rules, and keep in touch with families before problems arise.<br>
Community and religious groups: Make safe neighborhoods and safe passage to school a priority.<p>
3. Make college more accessible. <br>
Families: Make sure your children enroll in courses that prepare them for college and/or careers. <br>
Schools: Offer college-prep classes, be sure all students know about them in time to plan their academic program, and build local partnerships with colleges, universities, and community colleges.<br>
Colleges: Bring high school students and their families on campus to build connections and share information about the existence of financial aid.<p>
4. Get technology and computers into the classroom as fast as possible.<br>
Families: Work in partnership with the schools to get computers in schools and homes.<br>
Schools: Make the use of technology and computers a learning priority.<br>
Community and religious groups: Establish computer labs in neighborhood centers.<br>
Business: Assist schools directly by supplying computers and computer training.<p>
5. Raise standards of achievement and discipline.<br>
Families: Enroll children in tougher courses and keep in contact with teachers to ensure children are getting what they need.<br>
Schools: Raise academic standards and encourage students to work hard to meet them.<br>
Community, religious and business groups: Offer mentoring programs and homework centers.<br>
Business: Adopt flexible employee leave policies that accommodate school visits/volunteering.<br>
Colleges: Visit K-12 schools to advise students of entrance requirements and to share resources with the faculty.<p>
6. Connect schools and families with community resources and school-to-work opportunities.<br>
Families: Take advantage of learning opportunities in the community and support service programs.<br>
Schools: Forge new partnerships with community groups to expand learning opportunities, especially for tech-prep, in evenings, week- ends and summer; enrich daily instruction; and provide students with service experiences.<br>
Community and religious groups: Offer affordable, quality after-school and summer learning opportunities.<br>
Businesses: Provide apprenticeships, internships, and training opportunities for students and teachers.<p>
Reprinted from Community Update, No. 27, August 1995. Community Update is a publication of the U.S. Department of Education.<p>
<p>
"What's New in School?"<p>
Most parents and other adult members of your community remember schools as places where they sat at desks in rows. They weren't supposed to talk unless they were called on, and schoolwork consisted primarily of memorizing information from a textbook. Times have changed, and many people believe schools should too. But sometimes efforts to help schools adapt to a rapidly changing world can confuse and alienate people in your community. That's where ASCD's What's New in School, a four-part video series can help.<p>
What's New in School explains why today's high-tech workplace demands that schools teach and develop new skills and abilities. This award-winning program features interviews with people in a variety of businesses who describe how new technologies and changing economic conditions are altering the job market. Scenes from various workplaces highlight the growing need for students to have strong communication, problem-solving and cooperation skills.<p>
Plus, What's New in School explains how recent research on how learning takes place has helped educators expand opportunities for learning in the classroom and develop new ways to ensure that all students are active participants in learning.<p>
What's New in School describes three of the most promising practices in education today: cooperative learning, curriculum integration and performance assessment. Parents hear a clear rationale for why schools are using these innovative approaches. And interviews with parents, students and educators explain how young people benefit by learning new skills and by seeing more clearly how classwork relates to life outside school.<p>
If you are interested in ordering What's New in School, you may contact ASCD at 1250 North Pitt Street, Alexandria, VA 22314-1453, (703) 549-9110 or FAX (703) 549-3891.<p>
<p>
"For Parents Only"<p>
The Bureau for At-Risk Youth announces publication of a new series of 12 booklets for parents.<p>
For Parents Only  are easy-to-read booklets full of expert advice on the topics that interest today's parents most. Each booklet contains reader-friendly text, humorous illustrations, self-tests, checklists and activities.<p>
Topics include:<p>
*Building Your Child's Self-Esteem<br>
*Building Positive Parent/Child Communication<br>
*Teaching Your Child To Make Smart Choices<br>
*Keeping Your Child Drug-Free<br>
*Teaching Your Child To Appreciate Diversity<br>
*Teaching Conflict Resolution Skills<p>
For more information or to receive the free 72-page buyer's guide, write to The Bureau For At-Risk Youth, 645 New York Ave., Huntington, NY 11743 or call (800) 99-YOUTH.<p>
Reprinted from <i>The High School Magazine</i>, Vol. 2, No. 3, March 1995, p. 51. <i>The High School Magazine</i> is a publication of NASSP.</html>

