<HTML>"From the desk of the Executive Director -- Julian Shaddix"<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 3<p><p>
<p><p>
Several years ago TASSP adopted its motto, "Above all, students first." As time passes it is becoming increasingly evident that this motto is more than a pious-sounding phrase with no real thought of meaning. The TASSP Directors meeting on January 24th provided additional evidence that Texas principals are truly the champions of their students.<p>
At the Directors' meeting, President Jan Aragon proposed to the Board that it consider awarding a $500 unrestricted scholarship to each of the twenty regional academic excellence winners. Even though this proposal would cost TASSP $10,000 per year, it was received positively and unanimously adopted by the Board. This action further strengthens our belief that principals truly care about students and are often willing to sacrifice time and resources in the best interest of those they serve.<p>
As I thought about this unselfish action I was reminded of many other things that TASSP does in support of students. Many people are unaware that TASSP sponsors and supports the largest state student council organization in the world. The Texas Student Council is the envy of all such other organizations across our country. In addition to Student Council, TASSP also sponsors and supports the Texas Association of Future Educators. This student organization, almost 200 chapters strong, has as its focus the recruitment of top notch young people into the teaching profession. Many of these will eventually become teachers and principals.<p>
As I pursued the thought of "students first" I found more and more of TASSP's resources focused on things that either directly or indirectly benefited the students in our schools. All of these activities speak out strongly about the character and integrity of campus administrators. All of these thoughts make me proud to be associated with TASSP and all of those who give so willingly because they care about students.</html>

