<HTML>Middle Level Page & High School Page<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Alternative Scheduling<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 4-5, 17<p><p>
<p><p>
This joint section of alternative scheduling at the HS & MS levels is presented here at the request of our members. <p>
<i>Editor's note: In response to your inquiries about scheduling alternatives which create a variety of options for greater student achievement, the following successful strategies at the middle and high school levels are offered. Please note that each example has been tailored to meet the needs of its unique campus community.</i><p>
<strong>"The Power of the Flexible-Block Team"</strong><p>
by Tom Leyden, Schimelpfenig Middle School, Plano<p>
Most public schools have maintained an artificially contrived schedule that causes students to change classes every 45-55 minutes six or seven times during their school day. This schedule may or may not have much to do with the way "real" life operates. If seventy-two minutes are needed for a science focus, the teacher is forced to abandon the project at the end of the 45-55 minute class period and hopefully complete the project the next day with time to spare.<p>
Some schools have discovered a flexible block schedule that puts a core group of learners with a core group of teachers for a block of time. The teachers determine the time to be spent on some instructional activity based on the needed amount of time. Thus, class lengths are discussed and scheduled by the professionals based on curricular needs, not the master schedule's routine cycle. The teachers can group and re-group students based on what is the best learning grouping for each student without interfering with other classes outside the block.<p>
An example of the flexibility can be seen when English, math, history, and reading instruction can be delivered in a way that makes sense to the learners. Middle school students need to understand the skill of reading charts and graphs. This skill can be taught by using a graph delineating a historical event, such as the progressive increase in the number of immigrants entering America over a fifty year period. The math teacher can use the same graph to show percentages and increases. The reading teacher can reinforce the study of charts or graphs from a reading skill view and the history teacher teaches the content and dynamics of history found in the chart. Student learners have learned a skill, used the skill and had the skill reinforced from multiple perspectives.<p>
Another example of the power of the flexible team is that teachers who have the same kids in common tend to be better able to challenge those students because the team of teachers get to know the students very well. The strength of the relationship with students comes from the relationship that the teachers have with each other. English, math, history, science and reading teachers who have the same students talk about those students and make plans to help and challenge each one. Since the student's teachers know him or her well, and they all have the same expectations, the student is better able to meet those consistent expectations.<p>
Some people think that if students are grouped under the supervision of an integrated team of math, English, science, history, and reading teachers that the students have all they need. This type of teaming does provide coordination and communication that is much stronger than having teachers who are departmentalized and have no idea who a particular student has for other subjects. However, unless there is control given to the team so that when the "team" is in session all teachers and all learners are in session, the true power of the block is gone. All team members (teachers and students) must be in session at the same time; none can be in an elective unless that elective is a part of that core team.<p>
In conclusion, the power of the flexible block is that professionals are given charge over their resources. These resources include the following: common group of students, ability to change groupings, ability to control and reschedule within the block of time based on curricular appropriateness, ability to integrate curriculum and the ability to know the students well. It is imperative that the team be given a common planning time daily so that each of these resources can be managed and monitored regularly. From the power of the flexible block comes the ability to do something that has been needed by students for years. It allows educators to put the learning environment together so it does reflect the way real life operates. It is that order that makes sense to professionals and to learners, and that is a refreshing common ground upon which to build a dynamic student-teacher relationship for challenging learning.<p>
<p>
<strong>"The MS Accelerated Block Schedule"</strong><p>
by Bob Caudle, Principal, Goodnight Junior High, San Marcos<p>
Goodnight Junior High School in San Marcos has developed an accelerated block schedule which was modified from an alternating A/B block schedule.  The reasons for incorporating this schedule were to extend language arts and mathematics to ninety minutes a day classes, to build smaller, more efficient academic teams, and to gain flexibility in meeting individual student needs.  Goodnight has a diverse population with over 60% of the students identified as at-risk.<p>
At Goodnight, students take three academic classes each semester.  A student might take language arts, Algebra I and U.S. History in the fall semester and then a Reading Workshop, Algebra I and Science II in the spring.  (Students stay with the same mathematics teacher all year long.) Students meet with each of these classes ninety minutes every school day. They also have at least two electives which meet every other day for ninety minutes. Approximately 120 eighth grade students have earned the privilege of a third elective based on their grades if they have mastered all of the TAAS reading objectives the previous year. These students still take Reading Workshop (based on Nancy Atwell's model) but since they have strong reading skills, they only go to reading every other day which allows them to take a third elective class.  There are also approximately 50 students who attend a tutorial class in lieu of one of their electives in order to keep up with their class work. These students can be placed in the tutorial for a period of time (as little as three weeks) and then returned to their elective class if they maintain a passing average in their classes. Most of these students prefer staying in the tutorial the whole semester.  One full-time teacher runs the tutorial program.<p>
Our academic teams each consist of three teachers (example: language arts, Algebra Readiness and U.S. History) who have a common group of approximately 60-70 students.  The students are split into three clusters which meet with each of the three teachers each day for ninety to ninety-five minutes.<p>
The advantages of this schedule include: lowering the number of classes each student has during a given period (the average student has five total classes, three academic and two elective); lowering the number of students and classes the academic teachers teach during a given grade period (each academic teacher teaches 60-70 students in three ninety-minute classes each day); having smaller teams which allows the teachers to keep up with their students; and extending the number of minutes each academic teacher has students while still having them every school day and not every other day. The extended time allows the staff to do more relevant, hands-on learning activities while avoiding "habit learning" which comes from an over reliance on traditional lecture/discussion and pencil-and-paper tasks.  Teachers require more in-depth writing assignments when the teachers have half as many papers to grade and more time to work with the students.<p>
The consensus of the staff is that this schedule allows them to keep up with students' needs and helps them hold the students responsible for completing more relevant assignments.  It is the belief of the staff that the accelerated block schedule helps them by simplifying the system and allowing them to better serve each student's needs.<p>
<p>
<strong>"A/B Block Scheduling"</strong><p>
by Alan Veach, Principal, Conroe High School<p>
Due to the increased credit demands placed on students as well as an interest in changing instructional delivery, the traditional six or seven period schedule found in most high schools is undergoing revisions. According to Robert Canady and Michael Rettig, there are at least three problems with the traditional schedule:<p>
1. fragmentation of instructional time, with little opportunity for in-depth study,<br>
2. disciplinary problems due to the amount of time that students are in the hallways; depersonalizing school due to teachers having so many students on a daily basis that the teachers do not get to know their students; and<br>
3. little allowance for flexibility for students who need more time to learn.<p>
[Canady, R.L., and M.D. Rettig. (November, 1995) "The Power of Innovative Scheduling," Educational Leadership: 4-10.]<p>
Due to these concerns, several modifications of block scheduling are emerging at the secondary level. One of those is the alternate block, commonly called the A/B block schedule. The A/B block schedule consists of 8 periods with days of the week alternating as A or B. Four courses meet on A days, and the other four courses meet on B days. Teachers teach three classes and have a 90-minute conference each day. Many teachers teach only five core courses, with their sixth class being a study hall, advisory period or an elective.<p>
Block scheduling creates a longer time period for classes that allows for a greater diversity of activities such as field trips, lab experiments, longer class discussions and speakers. It enables teachers to more fully develop issues and concepts and to be more creative and innovative and use more variety of teaching methods. It also allows for more extensive use of the library. Instructional time is actually gained due to less "start-up" and "closing" of class instruction (checking roll, etc.) and less time changing classes. Students must attend and prepare for a maximum of four classes each day, and with teachers, there are never more than three preparations daily. A/B blocking reduces the number of student contact hours a teacher has each day. Thus teachers have more effective student contact time with fewer students on a daily basis. Since the students have two days between classes, homework assignments can be more meaningful and of better quality. In addition, there are financial and instructional benefits for vocational education programs in the A/B block schedule. On A days, vocational students can participate in their vocational programs, and on B days participate in their core academic subjects. This works well for students having to attend a vocational school at another location.<p>
One of the advantages of the A/B block schedule is that students are in an academic class for the entire school year. Student learning and retention is increased. This is important for students who take the TAAS test in March and those students who take the advanced placement tests in May. Building a master schedule and balancing classes is easier in an A/B block schedule because you are working with eight periods. Students have a greater variety of classes to choose from at any given time. The A/B block schedule allows students to take athletics, music and certain other courses every day, and still have room for other course selections.<p>
The A/B block schedule also allows for the implementation of academic teaming at the ninth and tenth grade, a program that is very difficult, if not impossible, to implement in other types of block scheduling. Academic team teachers are able to have a common planning period on one of the block days. Another advantage of the A/B block is that accelerated classes can be placed into an A/B schedule.<p>
According to teachers and students, the pace of the school day using an A/B block schedule is more relaxed. There does not seem to be a "race to finish" as in a traditional six period day. The A/B schedule, as with other block schedules, demands greater creativity from teachers to vary their classroom experiences.<p>
Whatever type of alternative schedule is used, school administrators and teachers are capable of being creative and making a schedule to fit their own school's needs, escaping the traditional six to seven period school day.<p>
<p>
<strong>"Trimester: Pre-Owned Scheduling Vehicle"</strong><p>
by Bill Lawson, Principal, Temple High School<p>
The question still remains as to the real impetus for Temple High School's 1994-95 implementation of its trimester approach scheduling.  Although we did have our own 1990 site-based objective of restructuring our school day to better meet the needs of our 2,100 students, many feel the final push came with the Commissioner's Recommended High School Graduation Plan.  In either case, a long Sunday afternoon meeting in December, 1993, was set for any THS staff member who wanted final input on a move to some type of non-traditional schedule. After over a year of meetings, out-of-district visits and various kinds of study and research, we knew we could not continue to maintain current programs and meet new demands for many of our students without a major restructuring effort. The outcome of our December meeting was totally unanticipated.  Rather than create additional block periods, or try an alternating day (A/B) block or move to an accelerated/compressed block approach, a completely remodeled version of the old Texas quarter system was proposed and quickly accepted by the staff as a viable option to address many of our needs.<p>
Basically, the trimester consists of three twelve-week "semesters," with five 70 minute classes daily.  At the end of each term, students passing a course will receive .5 credit with a regular schedule potentially generating 7.5 credits every year and 30 credits in four years.  With the state's minimal graduation credit count remaining at 21, additional state and local credits can supplement a student's graduation plan (now locally set at 26 credits for the class of 1998 and beyond).  Numerous opportunities have emerged for many students.  All THS students (including the many AP/International Baccalaureate students) can complete their four-year plans without giving up their fine arts, career, athletic or competitive academic pursuits.  Additionally, THS math students are required to take a full year (three terms) of Algebra I and Geometry, providing more time for much needed math instruction and TAAS review (helping foster a 13-point increase in the building's Exit Math score in 1995).  Students who fail a course will find the same term (A or B) of that course available for immediate retake.  For example, a THS student knows he/she will not advance to the B-term of English I until he/she passes the A-term (and counselors will reschedule that student accordingly for the next immediate trimester).<p>
The trimester system brought with it several anticipated pitfalls and, during the first year of operation, a few unforeseen concerns had to be addressed.  The total amount of semester instructional time decreased (although not as much as with the 90-minute based block schedule), and teachers and students felt somewhat stressed to "get it all in."  The master schedule, of course, was more tedious in its building although counselors found it more flexible when trying to accommodate many unique students needs.  AP/IB teachers found time restraints to be limiting to their required curriculum demands.  We have found, however, that spring term AP/IB review courses are generating very positive results as students prepare for their May exams.  The foreign language teachers are continuing to work on the sequencing of their courses, not wanting students to leave 12-week instructional voids in their graduation plans.  Another "must" in the readjustment to the trimester is placing a workday into the school's calendar between terms.  All the traditional semester transition demands, along with the need to immediately reschedule all students who fail one or more classes, remain with the trimester plan.<p>
The single greatest need that has been generated by the move to a non-traditional schedule revolves around curriculum and instruction.  After two summers of extended workshops focusing on nothing but complete rebuilding of curriculums and revamping of instructional approaches (we have found Bernice McCarthy's 4-MAT a very practical model), the THS staff is much more comfortable with and in control of the extended teaching periods and compressed semesters.  Extensive staff development is essential to the success of any major structural change.<p>
As a final thought, I would like to suggest that any rebuilding of a school's schedule becomes a customized matching of school and community demands to time and personnel resources in each particular school district.  The trimester scheduling approach happens to meet those needs peculiar to Temple High School.  To suggest that the trimester is "the answer" to all districts' need would be inappropriate  --  and an invitation to disaster for many.  But sharing Temple's success and setbacks with many districts over the past 18 months has been valuable to us at the high school, and we are certainly available to anyone who might want to consider the trimester plan as a viable response to the new scheduling demands we are all facing in Texas. <p>
<p>
<strong>"HS Accelerated Block: The Process of Change"</strong><p>
by Lorenzo Garcia, Principal, Spring Woods Senior High School, Houston<p>
Spring Woods High School is currently in the second year of its structural change to the accelerated block schedule. Although extremely positive, the results of the first year cannot solely be attributed to the schedule we have implemented. We feel that the site-based process, which has been successfully implemented in Spring Branch I.S.D., greatly facilitated and supported a positive change. In addition, attention to staff development, especially in the areas of curriculum and instructional practices, ensured a smooth transition. This synergistic approach to school improvement has fostered positive attitudes towards the changes we have made.<p>
The Spring Woods High School staff initially expressed interest in alternatives to the traditional six-period day during the 1992-93 school year. This interest again emerged during the 1993-94 school year. The involvement in scheduling alternatives was driven in part by the State Board of Education's twenty-four recommended proficiencies and also by a desire to determine how schedules for students and teachers could be improved. To that end, a group known as the "Restructuring Committee" was formed. The purpose of this group was to examine several scheduling alternatives from a variety of perspectives, to compare and contrast their advantages and disadvantages with our current schedule and to make a recommendation to the Campus Advisory Team as to the scheduling alternative that would best meet our needs.<p>
The Restructuring Committee embarked on a study process beginning in October of 1993. Several subcommittees were created to study different aspects of proposed scheduling options including: bell schedules, electives, travel, survey, mobility, extra-curricular activities, staff development and the calendar.<p>
The Restructuring Committee and its subcommittees consisted of parents, teachers, administrators and community members. At every juncture in the process, input was sought and ideas were expressed by all facets to our community. This was not a top-down mandate, but a grass-roots effort. Changes were made through group effort, open dialogue and consensus. After each subcommittee met and reached their respective decisions, reports were prepared and forwarded to the full committee as well as presented at faculty meetings. At the conclusion of this team effort, the faculty participated in a straw vote in which both the A/B Block and Accelerated Block options received support for further study by the Restructuring Committee. Explanations of the new scheduling approach were presented to students both in classes and assemblies. Information concerning block scheduling and the process being undertaken were presented to local newspapers for publication. Parents, having learned of the proposed changes through several P.T.A. newsletters and bulletins, were invited to a community meeting that was specifically tailored to address both the need and our plan for change. Students, faculty and parents were provided the opportunity to vote on the option they preferred. The Accelerated Block Schedule received overwhelming support from all groups.<p>
To further assist the Campus Advisory Team in the decision-making process, a study of the history of educational reform was undertaken. Though not our original intent, our study reaffirmed the existence of the strong mandate in this country for graduates who should be better prepared for demands of the 21st century. Previous reports such as Scans 2000 and One Student at a Time called for improvements. These previous findings in conjunction with the State Accountability System made it clear that change was not only needed, but essential.<p>
Furthermore, the Spring Woods administrators and Campus Advisory Team understood the wave of educational reform initiated by A Nation at Risk. This movement initiated and brought such educational reforms as House Bill 72 and Chapter 75. Though sound in theory, these reforms were too sweeping in nature and were not successful in bringing about systematic change. To be successful, any proposed reform must take into account the variations that exist in each community and educational setting. This is the nature of a grass roots effort. When a reform program factors in community variation, socio-economic or otherwise, it creates and fosters a versatility that offsets the rigidity that caused other reforms, such as House Bill 72, to lose the momentum that is necessary for success. Our program sought to and did focus on confronting the problems of teaching by engaging the actual teachers in the decision making process. Our restructuring effort focused not only on structure, but also included curriculum and teaching practices.<p>
In the early spring when the decision to move to the Accelerated Block had been made, we began the implementation process.  Throughout the entire process, we analyzed all aspects of the change: structure, curriculum, and teaching practice. Each department was instructed to organize a plan for how content and pedagogy would be addressed by the teachers. As was our goal, the increased teacher participation created a better focus on students and promoted ways to involve those students more effectively in learning. We hoped not only to create a new structure, but also to shift from a teacher-centered environment.<p>
The actual structure that we would come to employ emerged from several of the Restructuring Committee's subcommittees.  Out of respective proposals advanced by each subcommittee, we developed the structure that would best fit our needs by asking and answering a series of questions.  A sample of such questions included these:<p>
1. How will Spring Woods fit our calendar into the district's calendar?<br>
2. How will our lunch be structured?<br>
3. How often will grades be reported?<br>
4. Will early graduation be permitted?<br>
5. Do we change credit requirements for advancement and graduation?<br>
6. Will we allow early dismissal and/or late arrival?<br>
7. When will we have staff development?<br>
8. How we handle transfer students?<br>
9. How about extra-curricular activities?<br>
10. Do all subjects fit into block schedule? (This arose due to our specific concerns regarding foreign language, math, and advanced placement classes.) <br>
11. What modifications will be needed in vocational education programs?<br>
12. How will we deal with student absences?<br>
13. How and when will we evaluate the success of the block schedule?<p>
With these questions addressed and answered, we developed a system that has best met the needs of Spring Woods High School.  One of our greatest, if not the most significant, advantage of restructuring is the ability to tailor the program to meet the needs of a specific school and satisfy the primary objective of education, to create an environment in which the students will succeed.<p>
Dialogue with all members of the team is paramount to developing the changes that will best benefit each individual school.  The challenges that today's educator faces are to make the needed changes and produce the student who will be successful in the 21st century.  Each of us must find the system for our community and school that meets this challenge.</html>

</DOC>
