<HTML>Research & Development page<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 6<p><p>
<p><p>
"Assessment & Development: Everyone Wins"<p>
by Raymond E. Lemley, Ph.D., Executive Director, the Texas Principals Leadership Initiative<p>
<i>Editor's Note: Dr. Ray Lemley is the Executive Director of the Texas Principals Leadership Initiative (TPLI), a professional growth initiative for principals made possible through funding from the Texas Commissioner of Education.</i><p>
Clearly, assessment and development are good for principals and assistant principals. There really is no down side when one works to improve one's performance. Here are some things we know: those who have trained as assessors improve their performance; those who get assessed get "better"; those who work as assessors gain new insights from the experience; those who take part in developmental activities improve professional performance. No doubt about it. Principals and assistant principals who pursue effective staff development activities improve on lots of levels. It may be difficult getting building administrators to training sites and persuading them that participation in assessment and development activities is a good thing. It may be even more difficult to persuade the assistant superintendents and the superintendents that there are systemic gains made by letting site administrators get involved in intensive assessor work. But here's a fact and one needs no chi squares to prove this one: Assessment and development, in most forms, improves participants on many levels.<p>
Getting to the point where administrators participate in assessment and development activities, however, requires a personal commitment to changing behavior; assessment and development activities may even require changes in one's attitude. Behavioral changes accompanied by attitudinal changes involve mild forms of danger and peril. Truly, some of the activities associated with assessment and development may disrupt one's status quo, one's professional balance. No doubt, the nature of assessment and development requires professionals often to question long standing patterns of administrative behavior. After all, it is not easy to realize that some long-standing behaviors were not and are not as effective as one believed they were. The other important issue is that all of us need to get well beyond the issues of using assessment as a form of evaluation. Assessment is best used for development. It was never intended to replace formative and summative evaluation models. Anyone wanting to evaluate principals' effectiveness should use procedures beyond assessment. Assessment is used most effectively to allow participants to chart a developmental course. In fact, there may not be any form of instrumentation that better supports developmental planning. <p>
The practice of assessment has well defined and established the results of assessment. Any process that survives more than a decade's scrutiny certainly has stood the test. Quality assessment has been used by several businesses long before educational assessment programs were introduced. Those who know assessment tell us that effective assessment activities are marked by:<p>
Incredibly Powerful Feedback. Without feedback anchored in specific language, one merely has generalized comments that rest upon unsupported information. <p>
Behavioral Indicators of Performance. Despite the push for warm language couched in forms of analytical generalizations, the most powerful indicators of performance rest in behavioral descriptions. One either is sensitive or is not; one communicates well orally or one does not. Almost may count in some quarters, but language that suggests "almost" does not meet the needs of individuals working to improve. Interestingly, assessment avoids mind reading, something that educators try doing too often in describing why someone does a particular thing rather than what someone does. Assessment does not engage in reasons; it simply delineates the behaviors.<p>
Descriptors Anchored in Job Alike Contexts. The powerful and specific feedback that comes from assessment is rooted in activities that look very much like the activities principals and assistant principals actually perform. Assessment activities spring from the "stuff" that school is made of  --  the episodes, incidents, and events that define schools.<p>
Specific Developmental Suggestions Stemming from Performance. Real world and real time recommendations are probably the most valued recommendations one can receive. When feedback is posited in a specific behavior grounded in a specific context, then one thinks and talks in terms of taking or not taking actions meeting a defined need. "You need to be a better decision maker" really says nothing about performance. It sort of sounds like, "Fight team, fight." What does all that mean? What does it tell me to do? Very little.<p>
High Levels of Direct Benefit. Talk with anyone who has participated in assessment and development activities. Participants never leave one of these activities without talking about the direct benefit to job-related performance. Everyone talks about how participation had an impact upon behaviors the very day one returned to the campus. Pretty powerful stuff.<p>
New Ways to Process the Work. Go to an assessment center, train as an assessor, take part in an intense developmental activity and one then does one's things differently. And here "differently" means "better." Principals who engage in assessment and development talk about new behaviors, new insights, new perspective. And new is better!<p>
All good assessment anticipates gaining insights into one's performance. Reflective practice is becoming more and more a reality of the principal's job. Assessment thus encourages principals to engage in evaluation of and reflection upon present performance. Practitioners often feel they do their jobs as well as the complexities of school administration allow. They often feel that the mandates directed at improving performance are meddlesome and silly. Experienced principals may well have adopted an attitude that no one truly understands the principal's job. The real issue is whether the principal truly understands his or her job in the context of excessive demands. Forward thinking and forward looking principals welcome opportunities to better understand their performance. Assessment certainly leads to understanding; understanding defines realistic improvement goals. The joining of assessment with development creates a synergy leading to enhanced performance. Regardless of mandates and directives, principals on a sound developmental path produce results that certainly benefit students.<p>
Assessment and development lead to stronger leadership. Set the mandates and requirements aside; a commitment to personal and professional assessment and development holds interesting prospects for improvement. Quite simply, it makes sense for principals to improve. No argument there. Principals can counter lots of the current criticism by demonstrating a willingness to take charge of their growth and their renewal. Active participation in programs that create a fresh way to examine behaviors and performance is an answer. Effective leaders must demand excellent development programs derived from assessment. The discussion about professional growth is a win-win discussion. The stakeholders are quite correct in insisting that administrators take control of the assessment and development programs. The cadre of leaders charged with the growth and development of students has the capacity to assume responsibility for their own growth. Good assessment and development are tools that support and build exciting growth opportunities.<p>
The benefits of quality assessment that leads to effective development are too significant to waste time talking about the efficacy of assessment. We know it works. We know it leads to positive changes. We know that assessment helps define effectiveness. We must know that we need to engage with assessment programs so that principals and assistant principals can become empowered to define and to achieve their own developmental goals.</html>

</DOC>
