<HTML>State Board of Education Report & other related articles<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; pp. 18-19<p><p>
<p><p>
<strong>"State Board Report"</strong><p>
Six Open-Enrollment Charters Approved by SBOE<p>
SB 1 grants the State Board of Education the authority to establish up to twenty open-enrollment charter schools to eligible entities.  While remianing a part of the state public school system, this type of charter school is free from many state laws and regulations.   Guidelines for this type of charter were approved by the SBOE in October, 1995, and distributed throughout the state.  The guidelines included provisions for the application and selection of an open-enrollment charter school as well as the processes for modifying, revoking, or placing an open-enrollment charter school on probation.<p>
Eight applications were received in time for review and evaluation by the State Board of Education in February.  The following six charters were approved:<br>
* Renaissance Charter School, Irving - (grades 7-12)  an academic and career-focused education including apprenticeship;<br>
* West Houston Charter School, Houston - (grades 7-9) academic program based on individual learning styles;<br>
* SER-NINOS Charter School, Houston - (grades PreK-4) educational program targeted at low-income, at-risk children;<br>
* American Institute of Learning, Austin - (ages 16-21) dropout recovery program leading to a certificate of mastery;<br>
* Cypress Lodge Charter School, Jefferson - (ages 15-17) educational program including environmental research job training for adjudicated youth;<br>
* Medical Center Charter School, Houston - (grades K-5) academic program featuring integrated technology and Montessori instruction serving employees of the Texas Medical Center.<p>
ESC Alternative Teacher Certification Given High Marks<p>
The State Board of Education has received a summary of the 1994-95 Final Evaluation Report of the Education Service Center Alternative Certification Program Consortium.  Evaluation study results revealed a strong level of satisfaction among interns, mentors and campus administrators with the performance of program interns and the quality of training received in the program.  Almost 59% of those surveyed gave the program a grade of A, while 34% rated it a B, with only about 6% assigning a grade of C.  Almost half of the interns surveyed indicated that they would not have chosen to pursue a teaching career through a traditional college or university if alternative certification did not exist.<p>
Four broad themes emerged from the comment section of the survey:<br>
* concern regarding the rigor of the program and the heavy burden placed on alternative certification program interns who must  juggle the demands of a first year teaching assignment with the numerous requirements of the alternative certification program;<br>
* the importance of the intern-mentor relationship and the match of certification areas with campus assignment;<br>
* the need for detailed information regarding program requirements, meeting dates and other expectations and events to be provided by all stakeholders; and<br>
* a strong interest expressed from the mentors and campus administrators to meet with the alternative certification program personnel.<p>
Sunset Process for SBOE Rules Continues<p>
The new Texas Education Code, 7.102, requires the State Board of Education to conduct a sunset review of TEA rules currently in the Texas Administrative Code (with the exception of the essential elements in Chapter 75 which are already being clarified in a revision process.)  These rules are scheduled to expire on September 1, 1996.  Before June 1996, each rule subject to the sunset review process must be repealed in a two-reading process.  The rule may be reproposed if the SBOE has been given statutory rulemaking authority in the particular area addressed by the rule.<p>
At the January/February SBOE meeting, the following actions pertinent to campuses were taken in the sunset process:<p>
19TAC Chapter 68, Transportation was repealed in January without proposal for readoption due to lack of statutory authority. <p>
19TAC Chapter 75, Curriculum (excluding Subchapters B, C, D essential elements) - The SBOE maintains rulemaking authority in the following areas:  minimum requirements for elementary and middle school, high school graduation requirements and options for offering courses, providing for an academic achievement record, establishing criteria for awarding credit but not in terms of time requirements, providing for students with dyslexia and related disorders, and defining limits of participation in and practice for extracurricular activities.  The Board no longer has authority in the following areas:  general responsibilities of school districts, prekindergarten curriculum requirements, summer school programs, grading/promotion/retention/placement, and tutorial programs.  After a public hearing before the Board, proposed rules on curriculum (new Chapter 74) and extracurricular activities (new Chapter 76) were heard at first reading in February, 1996.  An SBOE Committee of the Whole work session on curriculum has been planned for March 26th with final adoption scheduled for April. (see opposite page for detailed report)<p>
19TAC Chapter 78, Vocational and Applied Technology Education relating to career and technology education, vocational and applied technology education, local advisory councils, vocational education for public school students by contract, integrated vocational-technical education and training delivery system for a quality workforce and fiscal agents for quality workforce planning committees was repealed at second reading in January.  However, the Board will retain responsibility for the state plan for vocational education, funding rules for career and technology federal funds, and approval of the knowledge and skills in enrichment programs.  The SBOE will also continue as the State Board of Vocational Education and is expected to work in collaboration with the new Texas Workforce Commission.<p>
19TAC Chapter 89, Adaptations for Special Populations which relates to programs provided for gifted students, students with disabilities, adult learners, persons wishing to obtain a GED certificate, and migrant students, was proposed for repeal at first reading in February.  The SBOE will retain rulemaking authority for several program areas covered by this chapter including G/T, Adult Education, GED, and Migrant Education.  The SBOE rulemaking authority for special education is retained in part.  Rules may be adopted to support students enrolled at the Texas School for the Blind and Visually Impaired and the Texas School for the Deaf, to prescribe the qualifications an instructional arrangement must meet to be funded as a particular instructional arrangement, and to govern contracts for the residential placement of students with disabilities. Authority for the remainder of the special education rules was transferred to the Commissioner of Education.  Parents and advocates generally want the special education rules to be readopted by the commissioner without change.  School districts and administrator organizations generally want a reduction of all rules, specifically rules that exceed state and federal requirements.  The agency will conduct statewide hearings on the rules in late March and early April.  <p>
19TAC Chaper 109, Budgeting, Accounting, and Auditing was readopted in February with several changes including:  1) more input on standards for budgeting, accounting, financial reporting and auditing through adequate involvement of interested stakeholders such as business managers, principals, superintendents and others, and 2) a change in the name of the TEA financial accounting manual to the Financial Accounting System Resource Guide developed by Deloitte & Touche, LLP.<p>
19TAC Chapter 133, Pupil-School Relations was proposed for repeal at first reading in February.  The SBOE has no statutory rulemaking authority for this chapter which relates to alternative education programs, expulsion, and discipline of students with handicaps.<p>
<p>
<strong>"Changes in Minimum Graduation Requirements Approved at First Reading"</strong><p>
Following a lengthy hearing prior to its February meeting, the State Board of Education approved new curriculum and extracurricular rules on first reading.  To simplify and clarify the administrative code in this area, the current rules in Chapter 75 have been divided into three separate chapters.  The new chapter 74 will provide general rules about programs, instruction, and grading; chapter 75 will contain the essential elements which will be replaced by the essential knowledge and skills next year, and chapter 76 will outline rules for extracurricular activities.<p>
Changes from current rule to the proposed new rules are outlined below.  Although there was considerable consensus in the Committee on Students on the proposed changes, the full Board has requested a review of curriculum issues.  Therefore, a special SBOE public hearing/work session  has been scheduled for March 26th, with second reading and final adoption due at the April Board meeting.  Please contact the TASSP office or the TEA Division of Curriculum, Instruction and Assessment with comments or concerns.<p>
Changes: Proposed new Chapter 74, Required Curriculum:<br>
*  would require districts to teach essential elements or essential knowledge and skills as adopted by the SBOE, except for prekindergarten essential elements which by law are now a district option.<br>
*  would require a review of the curriculum at least every five years and a linkage of changes in curriculum to adoptions of instructional materials when possible.<br>
*  would delete specific time requirements per SB 1 related to the teaching of the various subject areas at the elementary level; instead, students would have to be able to demonstrate the essential knowledge and skills in each subject of the required curriculum.  Districts would adopt their own schedules and instructional strategies for ensuring student success.<br>
*  would delete both specific time and credit requirements for subjects at the middle level.  Districts would adopt their own schedules and instructional strategies to ensure that students learn the required curriculum and are prepared for high school.<br>
*  would require a total of 22 credits in the minimum high school program. Changes include the requirement of one-half credit of speech, one credit of technology applications, and one credit of world geography. Elective credits would be reduced to five and one-half units. (Changes in this program would be effective with next year's eighth graders.)<br>
*  changes to the high school physical education requirements would include the inclusion of one-half credit of Foundations of Personal Fitness in the one and one-half credit requirement for PE; the deletion of vocational courses from the PE substitutions list; and a change in the limit of number of PE credits for state graduation credit from two to three.<br>
*  would designation dance as a fine art at the secondary level.<br>
*  would impose an SBOE passing standard of a grade which is the equivelent of 70 on a scale of 100 for high school course credit with the understanding that it will be determined whether rulemaking authority in this area was the intent of the legislature.<br>
*  would maintain Reading Improvement I, II, III as courses eligible for state graduation credit, but would rename the course so that it does not carry the implication that this is a lower-level course.<br>
*  would require Algebra I as one of the mathematics requirements for high school graduation.<br>
*  would require that science courses at the high school level include at least 40 percent hands-on laboratory investigations and field work using appropriate scientific inquiry.  Science III would be added to the list of required course offerings.<br>
*  would designate an updated list of advanced courses for the No-Pass, No-Play Rule to include all AP and IB classes, and would delete some courses currently on the list which are not considered advanced such as Physics I.<br>
*  would provide additional services to students with dyslexia and would require more training for teachers who teach students with dyslexia.<p>
Changes: Proposed new Chapter 76, Extracurricular Activities:<br>
*  defines only extracurricular activities in an effort to clear up some of the confusion in current rule concerning the difference between extracurricular and curricular/cocurricular activities.<br>
*  would allow students who attend cocurricular and curricular activities such as field trips to not have classes missed count as absences that are allowed for extracurricular activities.<br>
*  would allow a student who had been ruled ineligible and who is enrolled in a state approved course in which the essential elements require public performance to perform one time per semester.<br>
*  would include the commonly accepted definition of the school week.<br>
*  would allow a student at the state championship level of competition in UIL events to request an additional two absences if all of the previous fifteen absences had been used.<p>
<p>
<strong>"Governor Announces Reading Initiative"</strong><p>
Challenging all Texans to join him in attacking what he called a crisis, Governor Bush announced at the Commissioner's Midwinter Conference that he will rally parents, businesses and communities and direct dollars and state resources toward helping local school districts achieve, "the clearest and most profound goal (he has) for Texas:  Every child  --  each and every child  --  must learn to read."<p>
Governor Bush charged school districts with the responsibility of considering new ways to structure their schools and classrooms to exphasize reading and use the flexibility of the new education code to be creative in meeting students' needs.  He offered a pledge that he and the state will:<br>
*  target $29 million in funds from the federal Academics 2000 program to teach reading and basic skills from kindergarten through fourth grade;<br>
*  ask the Legislature to appropriate $35 million to fund intensive reading academies in schools;<br>
*  improve teacher training and direct a million dollar federal grant to fund a center for training and development to help teachers do a better job of teaching reading skills;<br>
*  make elementary reading a top priority for expenditures from the telecommunications infrastructure fund;<br>
*  develop a diagnostic reading measurement tool to help local districts identify reading problems;<br>
*  rally the private sector, business community, volunteers and parents to do their parts to improve children's reading skills.<p>
Aditionally, the Barbara Bush Foundation has agreed to award $300,000 in grants to family literacy programs in Texas.  The First Lady of Texas, Laura Bush, will serve as honorary chair of the initiative and will appoint a volunteer council to help implement the program.<p>
<p>
<strong>"State Board for Educator Certification Holds Organizational Meeting"</strong><p>
The thirteen members appointed by Governor Bush met in Austin on February 20th for an organizational meeting.  Jim Nelson, a lawyer from Odessa, was elected chair.  Preferences for committee assignments were taken and plans for hiring an executive director and staff were discussed.  The next meeting of the Board is scheduled for March 22-23.  Public comment is invited.<p>
Established by SB 1, this Board was established to recognize public school educators as professionals and to grant educators the authority to govern the standards of their profession.  They will oversee educator certification, ensure compliance with continuing education requirements and establish the standards of conduct for public school educators.<p>
Board members and their term expirations are listed below.<p>
James Harris, secondary teacher, Lubbock ISD (1997); Mary Denton, secondary teacher, Forney ISD (2001); Peggy O'Neill DeRouen, elementary teacher, Ricardo ISD (1999); Cynthia Tassos Phillips, elementary teacher, Eanes ISD, Austin (2001); Andrew Jackson, businessman, Missouri City (1999); Art Lacy, businessman, McKinney (1997); Jim Nelson, lawyer, Odessa (2001); James Price, businessman, Cooper (1997); Joe Ramos, businessman, San Antonio (2001); Virginia Collier, superintendent, Brenham ISD (1999); Keith Sockwell, assistant superintendent, Plano ISD (1997); Mary Margaret Rucker, guidance counselor, La Marque ISD (1997); Arturo Pacheco, dean, UTEP College of Education, El Paso (1999); *Glenda Barron, assistant to the Commissioner of Higher Education; *Felipe Alanis, Deputy Commissioner for Programs and Instruction, TEA; <p>
*non-voting members designated by the Commissioners of Higher Education and Texas Education Commissioner respectively.</html>

