<HTML>"TASSP/TASC Web Site"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Technology<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 12<p><p>
<p><p>
The TASSP Board of Directors appropriated funds to develop a homepage and related sites for the Associations on the World Wide Web.  Our goal is to have the site on line by the end of April, 1996.  The site will include: <p>
*access to TASSP publications (Newsletters and Texas Studies),<br>
* a searchable indexed membership roster with e-mail addresses if members wish to provide them,<br>
* conference bulletin boards for sharing administrative knowledge, suggestions, questions,<br>
* principals' positions available will be updated daily, and e-mailed to subscribers who sign up for the service,<br>
* e-mail access to the TASSP office and individual staff members,<br>
* electronic registration for TASSP conferences and workshops, <br>
* on-line membership subscription,<br>
* regional information: meetings, deadlines for nominations, etc. and<br>
* TASC Information including membership rosters, searchable project reports, all report forms, and StuCo advisor/student bulletin boards.<p>
Equally important, the site will link to other powerful, useful sites that Principals can use immediately:<p>
*the entire text of Senate Bill 1, with a search feature to find key words/terms (TEA Web Site),<br>
*an excellent list of links provided by Texas teachers to curriculum areas, teaching techniques, etc.  (Tenet Web Site),<br>
*ERIC  Database, with search feature to find current research in the field of education,<br>
*listings of school home pages in Texas and around the world (Web66 and Texas Web: Education),<br>
*curricular links in all subject areas as well as the ASCD web site,<br>
*a couple of sites including Adventures in Education (see Jan newsletter) and College Board Online that provide comprehensive college/career planning tools,<br>
*the NASSP web site and<br>
*other state Principals' sites as they become available.<p>
What do you need to access the site?<p>
1.Mac or PC with at least 8 meg RAM, 250 - 500 meg hard drive preferred but not essential.<p>
2.a.Modem and available telephone line with subscription to an internet provider.  (Tenet is an internet provider available to school personnel for $5/ year.  Tenet will convert to the SLIP access in the near future to allow use of the graphical browsers now available) -OR-<br>
2.b.direct connection to ISD network that is connected to the internet.<p>
3.Netscape or other web browser (Netscape is free to schools and teachers).<p>
4.Other programs such as graphic converters, an irc client (if desired), perhaps a newsgroup reader.  These are available free or for a minimal shareware fee directly over the internet.<p>
In cooperation with Computize, TASSP will try to assist schools in establishing their own homepages. Computize will be providing details about a school web site package in the near future.</html>

</DOC>
