<HTML>"A somewhat personal appeal for Technology NOW"<p><p>
<p><p>
by Eddie G. Bull, TASSP Assistant Executive Director<p>
<p>
Topic: Technology<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; March 1996; Vol. 35, No. 4; p. 12-13<p><p>
<p><p>
Many of you are well into this era of technology, using e-mail routinely, surfin' the World Wide Web, even constructing home-pages for yourselves or your school.  You download from ftp sites or newsgroups, you post messages for colleagues on Tenet, you even irc a bit on Saturday nights!! And while these uses are fun and entertaining for some, there is a sizeable group of professional educators who don't want anything to do with the computer, and another sizeable group who just don't think about it because they have NO access to any of these applications.  <p>
As an older than average guy, a fiscal and social conservative, and yes, some might even say, "a reactionary," I've been a little reluctant myself to take up this new fad. But last summer I was sort of on "vacation" for a few weeks following a heart attack, and I found I had lots of indoor time on my hands. About that time, the local paper published an article on the Internet and Internet providers in town.  I had heard a little of the Internet, and primarily in some negative ways  --  it was a purveyor of filth and pornography, an electronic wasteland where geeks and nerds entertained themselves. Yet the news article seemed to say there was a lot more out there "on-line," so I rushed out and bought myself a Mac, hooked up with America Online, and in a matter of a few weeks became an Internet advocate (Not addict, though my wife might beg to differ). I did not stay with America Online, for at nearly $3/hour access charges, my Visa card rebelled after the 1st month; I found local service that was under $30/month for unlimited access,  bought a self-help book they recommended for help with the myriad of programs needed to replace the AOL software, and was up and going within a day or two.<p>
Why do I promote the Internet? No, I don't have a site where I'm trying to sell you something (although TASSP/TASC will soon have a world wide web site that you will definitely want to visit regularly!). And I don't have stock in Netscape or any other techie venture. I believe those of us with perhaps the most constant contact with the generations of the future, owe it to those kids and to ourselves to be in tune with this phenomenal communication medium. I don't know if the Internet as it exists today will survive... in fact, I'd bet against it, because new technologies will enable faster, more constant communication than this rather disorganized, helter-skelter patchwork of megacomputers.  But I'd wager almost anything that after many of us see what is possible on the Internet that we'll support it and its successors avidly and persistently.  <p>
* Can you imagine replacing long distance telephone service as we know it with low-cost (perhaps even free) video conferencing spanning the world? It can be done today with free shareware and a $100 mini cam attached to a personal computer.  <p>
* Think the US Mail is sometimes slow and unreliable? E-mail offers millions of us the opportunity to contact friends/professional associates and others almost instantly. And while there are problems associated with e-mail, it offers more reliable and faster delivery than any competing mail carriers.  And if your experience with e-mail is limited to using Pine or another non-POP server, you'll be amazed at the ease that Eudora and POP servers offer.  (Six months ago I said I didn't want anything to do with e-mail...that I had quite enough mail, thank you, through the postal service, and that I would never take the time to access an e-mail box on a regular basis.)<p>
* Instant access to what's happening in the world is possible now through structured commercial sites, like the interactive CNN news pages on the World Wide Web. But if you tend to distrust the "Media," you can tele-chat in "real-time" with a Ukrainian in Kiev or a Bosnian Serb in Sarajevo to find out first hand from an ordinary joe (or Natasha or Ivan) what's really happening! These chat channels were great conduits of information during the Iraqi war three years ago.  <p>
* Shopping opportunities abound over the internet: everything from computers and related hardware and software to airline tickets; from spices and wines to flowers and fruit baskets. A lot of hype surrounds the use of credit cards over the internet, but the incidence of computer fraud is higher on non-internet transactions than it is with online purchases.<p>
* Perhaps the most compelling reason to access the web is the almost instant access to information. Not only can you contact governmental agencies and private organizations via e-mail, you can visit some spectacular web sites to get general or specific answers to inquiries. Much (most) of this info is free, but  some commercial services, like Encyclopedia Brittanica, are available by subscription to allow users to access always current up-to-date data.  <p>
* The WWW is a canvas, unlimited in size, available to artists and artisans of words and thoughts to publish on. Even now you can visit the National Art Galleries of several countries to view Rembrandts and Degas...you can pick out a picture postcard to e-mail to a friend... you can visit thousands of individual home pages posted by men and women, boys and girls just like you and me.  <p>
The internet is only a tool  --  another way to communicate and share.  But it seems to be a huge leap forward in our progress, and we school folks need to be aware of it and using it. And we must get this access to students, and allow them the use of technology to satisfy intellectual and cultural curiosities. After surfin' for just a few months, I'm convinced that my grandchildren will routinely access world knowledge and unlimited cultural interchange simply by, in the manner of Captains Kirk and Piccard, uttering the phrase, "Computer, show me..."</html>

</DOC>
