<HTML>"16th Annual Federal Relations Conference Held in D.C."<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: 1996 NASSP Federal Relations Conference<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 16<p><p>
<p><p>
Peggy Walters, past TASSP State Coordinator and a Field Consultant for the National Association of Secondary School Principals, represented Texas at a Federal Relations Conference in Washington, D.C., February 10-14. This 16th annual conference was co-sponsored by the 66,000- member national secondary and elementary principals' organizations.<p>
More than one hundred education professionals from across the nation met with federal lawmakers to discuss ways to improve educational opportunities for all the nation's youth.<p>
Particular concerns discussed included impending cuts in education funding, proposed changes in the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act, administration of educational block grants to the states and equity and constitutional issues of vouchers for children to enroll in private schools.<p>
A number of presenters outlined issues at the federal level. Stanley E. Collender, Director of Federal Budget Policy for Price Waterhouse, brought conferees up to speed on policies and procedures in the FY 1996 and 1997 budgets with a sometimes humorous, but on-target, multi-media presentation.<p>
Representatives of the National Association of State Directors of Special Education, The Council for Exceptional Children, The American Federation of Teachers and the American Association of School Administrators presented a spirited panel discussion of important aspects of the re-authorization of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act. NASSP believes that the dual discipline system that currently exists between special education and general education students needs to be eliminated. We advocate a process of mediation before attorneys become involved in the IEP and administrative phases of IDEA.<p>
 Michael Brown, NASSP president-elect, introduced Reed Hundt, Chairman of the Federal Communications Commission. Mr. Hundt was presented the Conference's Distinguished Service Award. Mr. Hundt addressed the new Telecommunications Act and urged educators to be actively involved in the very complicated rule-making process of the act as it relates to business in education.<p>
 Patricia Sullivan, Director of Education Legislation for the National Governors' Association, shared her organization's interests in the future of public education.<p>
 Recent national polls indicate that voters are choosing education as their highest priority. This makes our involvement in issues of education policy especially important in this election year.<p>
 For more information on the status of specific bills relating to NASSP issues, contact Stephen Yurek, NASSP Legal Counsel, 1-800-253-7746. </html>

</DOC>
