 <HTML>"Ask A Lawyer"<p><p>
<p><p>
by John Aldridge<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Sex offenders and the secondary school system<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; pp. 14-15<p><p>
<p><p>
       <p>
<strong>John S. Aldridge, an attorney with Walsh, Anderson, Underwood, Schulze and Aldridge, P.C., answers questions from principals in this column, which is a regular TASSP feature. If you have questions, please pass them on to the TASSP staff. This column is not intended to constitute legal advice or to substitute for a principal's need to consult his or her school district's own attorney regarding legal questions.</strong>  <p>
<p>
DEAR JOHN: Our district has just gotten notice that a convicted sex offender has moved into one of the neighborhoods in my campus attendance zone. What am I obligated to do? <p>
Certain convicted sex offenders - once released from jail - are required to register with and file certain information with police. The police must keep all "public" information about the sex offender on a central database, and must provide the information to any person who requests it in writing.<p>
Texas Revised Civil Statute Article 6252-13c.1 requires sex offenders who have committed certain "reportable offenses" to register with the local law enforcement authority (i.e., the chief of police if within a municipality; the county sheriff if not) where the sex offender resides or intends to reside. The offender must register within seven days of arriving in the jurisdiction. The registration form requires the offender to provide the following information: a photo and complete set of finger prints, the offender's full name and any alias, date of birth, sex, race, height, weight, eye color, hair color, social security number, driver's license number, shoe size, home address, the type of offense, age of the victim, date of the conviction, the punishment received and any other information required by the law enforcement authority. <p>
DEAR JOHN: What are these types of "reportable offenses" for which offenders must register?<p>
The reportable offenses are varied, but generally relate to those criminal offenses that cause you to wrinkle your nose and call the children back into the house. The offenses are "reportable" if the individual was convicted, adjudicated delinquent or placed on deferred adjudication after September 1, 1995, for the following crimes: Indecency With A Child, Sexual Assault, Sexual Performance By A Child, Aggravated Sexual Assault, Possession Or Promotion Of Child Pornography, Aggravated Kidnapping With Intent To Violate Or Abuse The Victim Sexually, Burglary With Intent To Commit A Felony Offense, Indecent Exposure (on a second conviction), Attempted Conspiracy Or Conspiracy To Commit Solicitation and Prohibited Sexual Contact (i.e., incest). <p>
DEAR JOHN: How will I receive notice of these offenders living in my area? <p>
Your law enforcement officers have two basic duties - to inform the general public and to inform the school system. The Texas Dept. of Criminal Justice (not the local law enforcement agency) must maintain a computerized database containing all information on sex offenders' registration forms. The registration information is "public" except for an offender's (1) photograph, (2) social security number, (3) driver's license number, (4) numeric street address, (5) telephone number, or (6) fingerprints and (7) any information that would identify the victim. The law enforcement authority must release the "public" information about the offender to any person who submits a written request for the information. A person who releases the "private" information to a person other than a full-time, fully paid, employed law enforcement officer commits a class B misdemeanor. (Art. 6252-13c.1, Sec. 5). <p>
If the sex offender's victim was under the age of seventeen, the local law enforcement agency must (1) publish notice in both English and Spanish in at least one newspaper of general circulation in the county where the offender intends to reside (exception: incest), and (2) provide notice to the superintendent of the district in which any registered sex offender (whether convicted, adjudicated delinquent, or on deferred adjudication) intends to reside (no exception for incest perpetrators). <p>
The notice in the newspaper must include: (1) the offender's age, (2) the offender's gender, (3) a brief description of the offense, (4) the municipality, street name (but not address) and the zip code where the offender intends to live. <p>
The notice to the superintendent must include any information the law enforcement authority deems necessary to protect the public except the: (1) offender's social security number, (2) offender's driver's license number, (3) offender's telephone number and (4) any information identifying the victim of the offense. Thus, under the "any information the law enforcement authority deems necessary to protect the public" rule in the statute, law enforcement authorities have discretion over which information to provide to the superintendent. But the statute makes non-public to everyone the offender's social security number, driver's license number, telephone number and any information identifying the victim.<p>
DEAR JOHN: Once the notice is printed in the newspaper, or once the superintendent receives notice from the law enforcement authorities about this sex offender living in our school district, all hell is going to break lose. What are school officials supposed to do?<p>
The law provides little guidance about the school district's duty to disseminate the information received from the law enforcement authorities. The statute provides civil immunity for any "individual, agency, entity or authority" who releases "public" information. (Art. 6252-13c.1, sec. 5A). The District should release only "public" information, even though it receives non-public information as well, under the statute. As discussed below, the superintendent does not receive exactly the same information as is provided to the newspaper. Depending on the nature and disposition of the offense, the school district may get more info than what gets published in the paper. At the same time, as discussed above, in the discretion of local law enforcement authorities, the district may also get less information. Try to figure out the Legislature's thinking! Information about incest perpetrators (now known as Prohibited Sexual Contact, Penal Code 25.02) will not get published in the newspaper, but will get sent to superintendents. On the other hand, information only about convicted offenders gets published, whereas superintendents will additionally get information about offenders who have been adjudicated delinquent or placed on deferred adjudication.<p>
DEAR JOHN: Because the newspaper announcement and the superintendent's receipt of the information occur almost simultaneously, what's the superintendent's duty separately to inform parents?<p>
The superintendent has no statutory duty separately to inform parents. In general, school districts have not taken the initiative to broadcast information received from law enforcement authorities about a convicted sex offender. Your school district should confer with its own school attorney as to what should be done with this information. In most instances, each report will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Under the statute, the superintendent has no duty to send a scare memo out to all parents, to announce there's a sex offender loose on the streets or do anything else.<p>
DEAR JOHN: I have been to many legal clinics where I and other principals have been told to avoid being guilty of "deliberate indifference" to students' (or teachers') claims of sex abuse or physical injuries. Deliberate indifference seems to be the key word for determining whether we are exposed to personal liability for injuries that occur on our campuses. By doing nothing, are we inviting claims of "deliberate indifference" to the fact of a convicted child abuser living in our campus attendance zone? <p>
If the district or one of its campuses has developed a pattern of permitting known sex offenders to hang around the playground and fondle children, that's a problem. Likewise, if a particular student or group of students is known or suspected to be a target of a known sex offender's attentions at school or at school-related events, the administration should involve parents post-haste and take appropriate steps to prevent any contact at school or at school-related events. However, unless there has been some notice to you of continuing threats of which you have taken no action to correct, there is no general duty of the school to anticipate that the mere presence of a child offender in town necessarily will result in harm to your students.<p>
DEAR JOHN: Even if there's no affirmative duty to send out a separate school announcement, no doubt once the notice is posted in the newspaper either I or the superintendent will probably get specific requests. What then?<p>
The school's lawful response is no different from any Public Information Act response to any citizen's request for public information. If any member of the public (parent or not) requests information about the offender, the superintendent must release the "public" information (see roster below) about the offender to the requester. The superintendent should not release "non-public" information (see roster below) about the offender to members of the general public. If a request is made for information about the victim, if the superintendent actually knows the victim's identity and if the victim is a student in the district, just say "no." (ORD-634. 1995). But of course, if there's a proper Public Information Act IA request made for anything other than information that would tend to personally identify a student victim, the district should respond as it ordinarily would for information that it believes it should not release or doesn't want to release. <p>
DEAR JOHN: What's the worst that can happen to a principal who releases "private information"? <p>
The specific Class B misdemeanor available against persons who release the information required for registration has been re-pealed and is no longer available against school officials. (This offense was explicitly repealed by S.B. 267, Section 6 (Chp. 258, Session Laws). But in the Public Information Act (Texas' former Open Records Act), there's still the general criminalization of distribution of confidential information. Texas Government Code 552.352. <p>
DEAR JOHN: Should my school district adopt a formal board policy on this?<p>
Because the information from law enforcement by statute goes directly to superintendent (who is by statutory designation the officer for public information), the question of the desirability of a board policy is a local decision. Board policy on the subject is not legally required. The development of a consistent administrative procedure on internal release to district personnel, however, is advised.<p>
DEAR JOHN: What is the "public" information that the statute allows a principal or superintendent to release?<p>
Asuperintendent may release all "public" information that the superintendent receives from law enforcement authorities (1) to any district employee whom the superintendent deems should know it in order to protect the students' safety, and (2) to any member of the public who requests it. "Public" information includes the offender's (1) name and alias(es), (2) gender, (3) age, (4) race, (5) height and weight, (6) hair color, (7) shoe size, (8) a brief description of the offense, and (9) the municipality, street (but not house/apartment number) and zip code where the offender resides or intends to reside. <p>
DEAR JOHN: What is the "private" information that the statute allows a principal or superintendent to release to school employees?<p>
The superintendent may also release "private" information to school employees he/she receives from law enforcement authorities about a convicted sex offender. "Private" information includes: (1) any photograph of the offender, (2) the offender's numeric street address, * (3) offender's social security number, * (4) offender's driver's license number, * (5) offender's telephone number, and * (6) any information identifying the victim of the offense. [*NOTE: Only through law enforcement inadvertence would the superintendent receive the information designated by asterisk.] <p>
Information identifying the victim (if known) of the offense should not be distributed to anyone - including to school district employees. It's within the superintendent's discretion whether to disclose to selected school district employees any other "private" information. However, "private" information should not be voluntarily released to members of the general public either on the school's initiative or in response to a request. If there's a public request for "private" information, the district official within 10 days should follow the familiar open records (public information) request process that involves the attorney general.<p>
DEAR JOHN: What types of administrative procedures might be reasonable in disseminating this information among staff or parents?<p>
The statute provides little guidance about the superintendent's duty to disseminate the information received from law enforcement authorities. You should check with your school district's own attorney, but the following procedure would seem to fulfill a principal's duty to protect the safety of the students in the district while avoiding liability. The superintendent should devise a written administrative procedure regarding the dissemination to other district employees of the information received from local law enforcement authorities about a released sex offender. The procedure should state (a) what information may be released, (b) what information must be released, and (c) to whom. <p>
As a matter of administrative regulation or board policy, a decision may be made to release information to certain school district employees. Although the superintendent may release the above-mentioned "public" and "private" information to any school district employee, the conservative approach may be for the superintendent to release the information only to district employees who have a security need to know it. Such persons may include principals, school security guards, bus drivers and teachers who have playground duty. The superintendent should inform the persons individually and should instruct them not to reveal the information indiscriminately to others. The district employees should also be instructed to inform the superintendent and/or the police immediately if they suspect that the offender poses a threat of harm to any student. If any other district employee requests information about a convicted sex offender, the superintendent must release the "public" information and may release the "private" information (with the exceptions noted above) to the employee. <p>
As a matter of administrative regulation or board policy, a decision may also be made to release information (other than in response to a specific Public Information Act request) to parents in a general school announcement. Local policy or administrative regulations should outline the type and manner of that release.</html>

</DOC>
