<HTML>"Twenty-seven Texas schools win Blue Ribbon honors"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Blue Ribbon Schools - secondary<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 16<p><p>
<p><p>
This February twenty-seven Texas public middle and high schools were named Blue Ribbon Schools by the U.S. Department of Education, Texas Education Agency officials announced.<p>
The schools were selected from a field of 32 campuses nominated in March, 1995 by the Agency for the program, which recognizes outstanding public middle and high schools throughout the United States. The group includes five schools selected for the program's Developing Schools component, which recognizes schools that have challenging demographics, for their efforts to significantly reduce achievement gaps among their students.<p>
To qualify for the program, schools had to have challenging academic standards, including a rigorous curriculum for all students; a disciplined, supportive safe and drug-free environment; participatory leadership and a strong partnership among the family, school and community; excellent teaching and an environment that strengthens teacher skills and improvement; low dropout rates and documented student achievement. Schools are nominated for the program by state education agencies, the Bureau of Indian Affairs, the Department of Defense and the Council for American Private Education.<p>
All Texas school districts were invited to apply for the recognition program. Completed applications were reviewed and scored by a diverse group of professional educators, including university professors, superintendents, principals and other staff from Blue Ribbon schools and representatives from state education associations, regional education service centers and the Agency. A national review panel then selected the most promising schools for site visits by experienced educators who submitted reports on their findings. The review panel considered the reports and made recommendations on which schools should be named Blue Ribbon Schools to U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley. He announced the winners Thursday, February 8, 1996 in Washington, D.C.<p>
Commissioner of Education Mike Moses congratulated the Texas schools for winning the honor.<p>
"I congratulate the staffs, students, parents and others involved with these schools for helping them earn Blue Ribbon School status," Moses said. "They are outstanding examples of the schools that are leading Texas's efforts to improve education for all students."<p>
Texas had 84 percent of its nominated schools selected as Blue Ribbon Schools, compared to the national average of 55 percent. Representatives of the winning schools will be recognized at a national awards ceremony this May in Washington, where they will receive a special flag to fly at their schools and a plaque commemorating their selection.<p>
Established in 1982, the Blue Ribbon Schools Program honors elementary and secondary schools in alternate years and has recognized more than 3,000 schools since the program's inception. Blue Ribbon Schools are often visited by educators from throughout the country who study their success. The Education Department currently is working with state education departments to explore ways to more widely disseminate information about Blue Ribbon Schools so that other schools may benefit from their success.<p>
1994-95 Secondary USDE Blue Ribbon Schools Winners in Texas:<p>
Crockett Middle School, Amarillo ISD<br>
Carroll High School, Carroll ISD<br>
Carroll Middle School, Carroll ISD<br>
Coppell Middle School West, Coppell ISD<br>
