<HTML>"Book Reviews"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Book reviews in secondary education<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 13<p><p>
<p><p>
<p>
<strong>How to Establish an Alternative School</strong><p>
Putting experience into practice describes How to Establish an Alternative School by John Kellmayer. The author is a school administrator with 20 years of experience working in several alternative school settings, including one for emotionally disturbed teen-agers, another for chronically disruptive high school students and a school-within-a-school for "hard core  discipline cases."<p>
The book presents a detailed overview of the volume of work involved in establishing and sustaining a viable alternative education program, beginning with an explanation of the political realities that surround the creation of an alternative school.   The material explains the elements of effective alternative programs; different alternative school models, with advantages and disadvantages for each model; the planning involved in setting up an alternative program; curriculum options; school administration; student needs; choosing a faculty; and both cognitive and affective evaluation for each type of program.<p>
Kellmayer's educational and disciplinary philosophies are interwoven, delivering a personal account as well as his instructional mission. How to Establish an Alternative School  packs a lot into the proverbial nutshell. <p>
Reprinted from "Claiming all youth: three helpful views from the experts," in School Safety Update, December 1995, page 5. "Claiming all youth" was prepared by Sue Ann Meador, Associate Editor of School Safety Update. School Safety Update is published by the National School Safety Center. <p>
To order How to Establish an Alternative School, call Corwin Press at (805) 499-9774. For Hardcover, order # DB564-6257-6 ($42.95) or for Paperback, order # DB564-6258-4 ($18.95). <p>
<p>
<strong>Evaluating Your School PR Investment</strong><p>
Includes everything you need to evaluate your PR program including checklists for each of your key publics - from support staff members to the board of education, teachers to parents. You'll learn how to conduct communication audits and attitude surveys.<p>
If you aren't certain how effective your communication program is, you need Evaluating Your School PR Investment.<p>
To order Evaluating Your School PR Investment, send $17.95 plus $5.00 shipping and handling to National School Public Relations Association, 1501 Lee Highway, Suite 201, Arlington, VA 22209-1100, or call (703) 528-5840.<p>
<p>
<strong>The Internet Handbook for School Users</strong><p>
"The beauty of this handbook is that it is written in plain English and saves hours of time because it gets to the practical applications all educators need. Sophisticated Internet users are now distributing the book to staff members, saving them hours of time normally spent answering staff questions."<p>
Rich Bagin, ASPRA/APR<p>
NSPRA Executive Director<p>
Are you and your staff reaping the many benefits that the Internet can bring to your schools? Now, thanks to the leadership of the Educational Research Service (ERS), you can begin learning all that the Internet has to offer. <p>
Learn first hand how the Internet is helping educators. Here's just a sampling of what this 110-page handbook delivers:<p>
Answers to the most-asked questions by educators.<br>
Communication Tools: E-mail, mailing list, etc.<br>
Tools for accessing outline information.<br>
Guide to K-12 Internet resources.<br>
Glossary of terms and a quick reference sheet.<br>
Education Projects using Internet... and much more!<p>
To order The Internet Handbook for School Users, send $26.00 plus $6.00 shipping and handling to National School Public Relations Association, 1501 Lee Highway, Suite 201, Arlington, VA 22209-1100, or call (703) 528-5840.<p>
<p>
<strong>Helping Parents Help Their Kids</strong><p>
Parents look to administrators, principals and teachers for a concrete answer to their question: What can I do to help my child? Now, using this valuable resource from NSPRA, you can give parents the specific guidance they need.<p>
Helping Parents Help Their Kids gives you everything you need to conduct successful parent workshops:<p>
An 8-page booklet with the latest research on parents' impact on student achievement.<br>
Resource Packet containing models, research and materials from schools across the nation. <br>
Tool Kit for Parent Involvement with leader tip sheets and camera-ready parent handouts.<p>
To order Helping Parents Help Their Kids, send $55.00 plus $7.50 shipping and handling to National School Public Relations Association, 1501 Lee Highway, Suite 201, Arlington, VA 22209-1100, or call (703) 528-5840.<p>
<p>
<strong>Hidden Casualties</strong><p>
Violence, both direct and indirect, has a notable effect on children and their ability to learn, says Hidden Casualties: The Relationship Between Violence and Learning. Researchers say that consistent exposure to traumatic experiences can limit the development of cognitive ability, affect one's ability to form close attachments, and disturb physiological functioning. Children living daily with danger also develop defenses against their fears, and energy spent on these defenses is not available for learning. The report offers teachers and school leaders a strong rationale for the inclusion of violence prevention strategies across the curriculum. <p>
Single copies of Hidden Casualties can be ordered from the National Health & Education Consortium, 1001 Connecticut Ave., NW, Suite 310, Washington, D.C. 20036. ($10 plus $2 shipping and handling).<p>
<p>
<strong>Understanding How School Change Really Happens</strong><p>
If you're hungry for real-life models of school change, you'll want to read this powerful book. If you're searching for an ongoing process of positive change for your school or district, this book is for you. Here, you'll find valuable insight into and understanding of the complex task of school change.<p>
This engrossing book tells the singular story of one high school's struggle to remake itself. It is the story of the Quest Program, a teacher-designed experiment in curricular reform. The participants - teachers, administrators, students, parents and college collaborators - worked together to create an alternative class of ninth graders with the goal of promoting critical thinking and high self-esteem simultaneously.<p>
Through participant observations and extensive interviews with all involved in the change effort, Cohen's book draws you into the complex daily intrigues of high school life, vividly illustrating the impact of change on an often-resistant institution and community. She puts the change efforts in perspective, analyzing the roles and dilemmas of all of the central players - the same elements that pervade the change efforts of any school.<p>
While Cohen illuminates the pitfalls you can expect when you attempt reform, she also describes the successes that occurred during the three years of her study. Signs of progress included teachers feeling renewed and revitalized and students becoming more tolerant of one another.<p>
The author's observations and recommendations provide a guiding light for principals, administrators and other professional educators who are interested in school reform.<p>
To order Understanding How School Change Really Happens, call Corwin Press at (805) 499-9774. For Hardcover, order # DB564-6254-1 ($44.00) or for Paperback, order # DB564-6255-X ($20.00). </html>

