<HTML>"School/Community Partnership Built the Career Center"<p><p>
<p><p>
by John K. Brown & Barney E. Welch, Ector County ISD<p><p>
<p>
Topic: School/Family/Community Partnerships<p><p>
<p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; pp. 4, 17<p><p>
<p><p>
In Ector County we are experiencing an educational dream come true thanks to the hard work of committed community and school district visionaries and dedicated staff. That dream has materialized in the form of a newly constructed facility called the Career Center.<p>
Opened in August, 1995, Ector County ISD's $9 million secondary campus, dubbed first-class and innovative by Governor Bush, is state-of-the-art and anything but traditional.<p>
But, only ten months prior to its opening, the Center faced a community relations crisis.<p>
As instructional and technology designs were being mapped out, a construction site was picked in a strategically prime location near Odessa College and geographically midway between the two high schools, Odessa High School and Permian High School. While acquiring six acres from a property management company for the building was a non-event, getting another four acres for a parking lot would become a community relations nightmare.<p>
At the heart of the controversy was the district's initial intent to begin eminent domain and condemnation proceedings to acquire 18 nearby lots, all containing houses, to build the Career Center parking lot. Letters went out to the homeowners explaining that we needed the property and would offer residents fair market value for their homes. If they would not sell, we would initiate proceedings through the court.<p>
This action caused public outcry and adverse publicity. Many in the community saw the district as being bent on getting the properties immediately at the expense of the mainly low-income Hispanic residents.<p>
On October 23, 1994, it all came to a head at the center's ground breaking ceremony. Several hundred Hispanic citizens showed up in protest and turned the event into a town hall meeting.<p>
Among those present were organizers from a local Spanish radio station, KOZA, regarded by many in the Hispanic community as vanguards of minority rights. They broadcasted live from the site as local television stations, tipped in advance, covered the highly charged emotions of concerned citizens. One Hispanic leader at the event lamented that the ceremony, held in the "victims' backyards," was "salt in their wounds."<p>
The real issue raised by these citizens and their organizers was not the construction of the Career Center. Most people were behind such a facility that would greatly benefit Hispanic and other youth. It was the manner in which the district gave such short notice to residents without prior discussion and the concern over low offers for the properties. Owners, for the most part, wanted "fair compensation." Complicating matters was the fact that the homes had been carrying an appraised value much lower that what owners felt would bring enough to purchase a comparable house in a nice neighborhood.<p>
During the event school board members and district administrators listened to the concerns of the Hispanic leaders and residents. Nick Fowler, school board member, prime advocate of the Center and local business owner, reassured them that things would be set right. "It's always very important for every business to listen to its customers," said Fowler.<p>
All 18 properties were eventually sold voluntarily to ECISD after homes were reappraised and owners offered higher amounts. Construction of the center was placed on a fast-track schedule, with work still going on one week before classes started. Today, the Career Center serves 267 sophomores, and we anticipate about 430 more next fall.<p>
Also, another rather interesting twist of irony occurred. The general manager of radio station KOZA is currently the chairman of the Career Center Business Careers Advisory Committee. Talk about community support!<p>
This turn of events has resulted from our forming a strong community partnership dedicated to the school and the business community working jointly to provide relevant education to our students. We have worked with and involved business and professional leaders from all business sectors and ethnic groups within Ector County.<p>
Throughout the months leading up to the center's opening, we conducted an aggressive public relations campaign, addressing gatherings of business people and civic leaders at every opportunity and recruiting business partners for membership on advisory committees as well as to help design the curriculum. We made certain that the constant advice of the business community was both sought and heeded as we determined the curriculum and the equipment to be used. It is fair to say that the Career Center's learning objectives have been formulated primarily from the direct input of our business partners.<p>
Key to the success of the Center, business people, professionals and civic leaders are participating directly in the educational process. Over one hundred business and professional people have had direct contact with Career Center students during its first half-year of existence. They are regularly seen in classrooms conducting career-related discussions and even evaluating student presentations. Such was the case recently when television professionals judged twenty-two teams of marketing students who presented story boards of their ideas for a new thirty-second Career Center television commercial. As a result, fourteen teams were selected to work with several studios in producing concept videos.<p>
Another excellent example of business involvement happened when students were put through the paces of mock job interviews conducted at the Center by our business partners - the students' potential employers.<p>
Other activities have included numerous field trips to hospitals, a rehabilitation center, banks, television studios, car dealerships, retail and wholesale businesses and non-profit agencies. The students also shadowed city hall elected and appointed officials, and are in the process of arranging business partner shadowing days. Business and professional people have readily provided our students with opportunities to participate directly in ongoing projects. Students have designed logos, produced brochures, conducted research and participated actively on teams dedicated to accomplishment of real world projects.<p>
Although still in its first year, the Career Center is on the leading edge of new school-to-work systems being implemented in school districts across the nation. The school's motto, productive citizens through career development, reflects an alignment with the new education paradigm that sets a course for meeting the needs of industry.<p>
Our quest to graduate productive citizens is far too challenging to be accomplished by educators working alone. It is only through the joint effort of the business community and the school district that we can hope to succeed. We know that we are on the right track. What started with conflict has evolved into a joint commitment to the success of our students and ultimately the growth and prosperity of the community.<p>
John Brown was appointed to the position of Director of the new ECISD Career Center on December 5, 1994. The Career Center opened its doors to 270 tenth grade students in August 1995. A graduate of Penn State University, Dr. Brown received his masters degree in mathematics from John Carroll University in Cleveland and his Ph.D. in education from the University of Illinois. He taught high school math and was a school administrator in Ohio and Illinois for fifteen years before entering business as an executive with The Associates, a subsidiary of Ford Motor Company. After fifteen years in the business world, Dr. Brown returned to education with the intent of applying his combined background toward making education more relevant to the career goals of students.<p>
Barney Welch is currently the Career Center marketing instructor. The 1995-96 school year is his first at the secondary level. He joined the ECISD team in January, 1994 after completing a 21-year career in the United States Air Force, retiring in the rank of major. He held a variety of management positions including chief of public affairs at Air Force installations in the U.S. and abroad. During the 1990-91 Gulf War, Major Welch was assigned to U.S. Central Command in Saudi Arabia where he was a media relations officer and a spokesman for General Norman Schwarzkopf. Major Welch received his B.A. in Administration from Southwest Texas State University and his Masters in Public Administration from Troy State University. His teaching experience beyond the secondary level includes adjunct instructor of speech communication at Utica College of Syracuse University.</html>

</DOC>
