<HTML>"From the Desk of the Executive Director"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Executive Director Letter<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 3<p><p>
<p><p>
Legislative Alert! Sound Familiar? It hardly seems possible that it is time to begin preparing for the 75th Texas Legislative Session. Hopefully, there are many of you staying in touch with your state senator and state representatives and keeping them well informed concerning the needs and issues in public education. We are continually advised that the most important aspect of legislative "lobbying" takes place one on one in local communities. Please be active now in inviting your legislators to visit your campuses and experience the needs of students, teachers and administrators.<p>
During the coming months the TASSP Legislative Committee and TASSP staff will be seeking input from our membership related to issues and concerns that must be addressed in the next session. There will be issues that must be promoted and others that must be opposed. We have already become aware of a number of problems related to Senate Bill 1 that must be refined or abolished. Other concerns will surface during the coming weeks and these issues need to be discussed and refined as well. We also know that vouchers for private schools will resurface, possibly stronger than during the 74th Legislature. We must remain cognizant of any attempt to erode the authority of the principal in providing leadership on his/her campus. Increased accountability without a measure of control is an increasing concern for many of our members.<p>
One of our most important tasks is to represent our members regarding legislative issues that affect the performance of their jobs. In order to do this well we must know the issues and know how our membership feels about these issues. Please begin now to give us your input on issues you feel need to be addressed. Below are the names and phone numbers of the TASSP Legislative Committee. Please keep them informed about all of these issues. It is vital to our profession and, more importantly, to the students of Texas that principals be well represented during the 75th Texas Legislature.</html>

