<HTML>"High School Focus"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: High School Focus<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 11<p><p>
<p><p>
<strong>Personalizing the High School</strong><p>
by John A. Lammel<p>
Restructuring a high school requires educators to examine many different dimensions, including, but not limited to school environment, curriculum, instructional strategies, technology, organization and time, accountability and assessment, professional development, governance and leadership.  <p>
In all these areas, there is one common theme that surfaces - personalization of the teaching and learning experience. By providing more personal attention to each student, schools will improve.<p>
Smaller learning communities, a school-within-a school, interdisciplinary curriculum and academic teaming and/or increased student-teacher contact time through block scheduling, and advisement can personalize teaching and learning. Advisement may be the best way, however, to have the greatest impact on schooling and student success over a period of time.<p>
How advisers and advisees are organized, how frequently they meet and how the structure of the advisement programs correlates with the overall school guidance and education program may differ from place to place. The most essential goal of an advisement program, however, remains the same: to provide each student with an adult advocate who knows the student personally and will help the student examine options and make responsible choices.<p>
This program does not replace the guidance counselor; rather, it enhances the counselor's role to become an "advisement team leader" who becomes primary resource for advisers and students in a referral situation. Advisement allows the student to have a long-term one-to-one communication on a regular basis. In contrast, some school counselors may very well have 250-600 students, which seldom allows for individual student contact or communication. For many students, this means that important questions go unanswered.<p>
Adviser responsibilities also include monitoring the academic progress of each student advisee to provide reinforcement, support, intervention and help at appropriate times; helping plan programs of study that are based on the needs, interests, backgrounds and aspirations of each student; establishing a system of in-school communication wherein all professionals concerned with a student have systematic and consistent information to help the student succeed; and suggesting study techniques for improving classwork and homework. (From, Advisement Programs - A New Look at an Old Practice, by John M. Jenkins, NASSP, 1992). I encourage you to take a closer look at this document if you are interested in implementing an advisement program. I also encourage you to provide an opportunity for a team of your teachers and a counselor to visit a school with an advisement program. <p>
Things to remember:<p>
Staff development is essential to train and prepare teachers for the roles and responsibilities of advisers. <p>
Guidance counselors need to understand their role as "team leader" to the advisers and provide support and counsel to the advisers and to students when referred by the adviser. <p>
A teacher needs time to plan and prepare for his or her role as an adviser to approximately 15-20 advisees. Therefore, building leaders need to identify a schedule that allows time for advisement preparation and time to confer with the advisees and parents as needed.<p>
 I strongly encourage you to consider implementing an advisement program as you continue your efforts to improve your school and the opportunities for every student. <p>
<p>
This article was prepared by John Lammel, NASSP's Director of High School Services. Reprinted from NASSP's NewsLeader, Vol. 43, No. 4, Dec. 1995, p. 5.<p>
<p>
<strong>The TAAS Gold Card</strong><p>
by Belinda Ebert, Tuloso-Midway Student Council Sponsor<p>
The Tuloso-Midway Site-Based Team came up with the TAAS Gold Card incentive four years ago. The purpose was to encourage the students to pass all the parts to the TAAS the first time they took it. <p>
Our school already had a very good passing rate for graduation. The problem was that students were not trying as hard as they should the first time they took it because they knew they had many more chances to pass before graduation. Since the school report card for the AEIS indicators is mainly interested in students passing the first round of tests, the lack of first-round effort made our school look bad. That's when the idea came to the site-based committee to offer the TAAS Gold Card. (Our school colors are gold and maroon and the card is worth its weight in gold, so the name stuck.) <p>
The students (these are sophomores) who pass all three parts the first time they take the TAAS are sent to the library the first week of school to have a special identification card made. The card has their picture and is labeled "TAAS." This card entitles them to be admitted to any school function held on Tuloso-Midway grounds free of charge. The school club sponsors have the students show their I.D. cards and sign their names on a roster. The roster is then turned in to the bookkeeper at the high school. She distributes a check to the club that held the function to reimburse the club for the Gold Card students.<p>
The student gets to use this card during the sophomore, junior and senior years. If it is lost, it is not replaced. The card gets the student into the prom, but not his date. The date must pay unless she has her own TAAS Gold Card! Over the 3 years, the card can save a student more than $300.<p>
The first year Tuloso-Midway set aside $2500 to cover the cost of this program. The next year, $3500 was set aside. This past year a corporate sponsor, Koch Refinery, helped to offset the cost to the district by donating $3000 for this incentive. (We have 850-900 students total in our high school.) <p>
Has it helped our TAAS scores? Yes. Every year it gets to be a "bigger deal" than the previous year. It's funny to hear the students finding a date for the dances now. In the past, they used to look for the best-looking date. Today, they check to see how smart the potential date really is. It is not unusual to hear them say, "Do you have a TAAS card?" If the answer is yes, that person gets asked to the dance!<p>
If your school decides to try this, adjust it to meet your needs. Best of luck! Hope your scores go up!</html>

</DOC>
