<HTML>"Letter from the President"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Letter from the President<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 2<p><p>
<p><p>
I had a very exciting experience last month: I attended the state conference of the Texas Association of Future Educators, an organization that we sponsor. The ballroom at the Hyatt in Austin was filled with about a thousand students who were bright, eager and attentive to all the activities of the conference. The general sessions were conducted by capable officers and dedicated sponsors who serve for the love of students and our profession.<p>
As I looked at that sea of faces, I noted that at least half of them were of African-American and Hispanic origin. And I had to ask myself, "Why am I having so much trouble hiring good minority teachers if all these students are interested in education as a career?" What happens to these students along the way? Do they get discouraged and give up? Do they decide that schools are not places they like and enjoy? Are they "snatched up" by private enterprise where they can make more money?<p>
I want to challenge us as principals and assistant principals to encourage these students to persist in their desire to teach, to apply for scholarships and to come back to our districts as certified teachers. We need them as role models for our students. Take time to personally encourage students that you think have good academic and people skills to consider teaching. Sometimes a nudge from a caring adult is all it takes to move a student in the right direction. And if you are not already doing so, sponsor a TAFE chapter in your school. We need some good people to step up and take our places in the future!</html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
