<HTML>"Changes in the Middle"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Middle Level Focus<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 10<p><p>
<p><p>
Change has been the symbol of the middle school movement.  It seems appropriate then to update some of the changes that are relevant to Texas middle level educators.  The following information answers some questions about people working in new positions with middle level education at the state level.  It introduces Sue Galletti, NASSP's new Middle Level Director, announces a new date for the Texas Middle School Annual Conference for 1997, and looks briefly at some beliefs and reflections about Middle Level Education. <p>
New Names and Faces<p>
For the past year, there has been considerable concern about the future of the Texas Mentor School Network.  Recently some of the "mystery" concerning the Network began to clear as Carmen Neely, from Lubbock ISD assumed the leadership role for the State Initiatives Programs which included the Mentor Network.  Two new names and faces who have joined Carmen in this endeavor are familiar to middle level educators. <p>
Bob Brundrette assumed the role as  coordinator for the Middle Level, a role for which he is well qualified, having served as a middle school mentor principal in Santa Fe ISD.  While at Santa Fe, he was active in the movement to promote the "wellness program" as part of the of the middle school concept.  Bob's tenure there was also marked by successful implementation of a flexible block schedule. He has been an active "middle schooler" as a presenter for TASSP, a past Board member for TMSA and past president of HAMSA, The Houston Area Middle School Association. <p>
Coila Morrow joins Bob at Region 13 as a curriculum consultant working with all levels of the educational ladder.  Coila is another well known personality  to Texas middle level educators.  She has worked extensively with the Texas Middle Level Network.  She joins the staff at Region 13 Service Center after serving for a number of years in the area of curriculum and as the middle level contact at the Region 17 Service Center in Lubbock.<p>
<p>
Sue Galletti Selected as NASSP Middle Level Director <p>
Sue Galletti of Lake Stevens, Washington, has been selected as the NASSP Director of Middle Level Services.  Sue began her career in education as a teacher in California. She was selected Outstanding Teacher of the Year after her first year of teaching in an alternative middle school in Bellevue School District. <p>
While teaching, she was also very involved in student activities.  Following five years as a full time staff development specialist, where she was responsible for inservice for teachers and administrators in Bellevue School District, Sue began her seventeen years as a middle level administrator. Her administrative experience includes three years as an associate principal in Bellevue School District, seven years as a principal in Mercer Island and four years as a principal in Lake Stevens - all at the middle level.  Twice, Sue has been involved in conversions of junior high schools to middle schools. She continues to provide inservice on school-based management, tracking, the change process and effective middle schools throughout the United States. She also teaches in the administrative program at Western Washington University, where she received her master's degree in Middle Level Education.  <p>
In the next few months, Sue will be completing her Doctor of Education Degree at the University of Washington, where she is also a mentor principal in the Danforth Administrative Internship Program.  Sue has been very involved in the Association of Washington School Principals, serving as the chairperson of the Professional Growth Committee for Principals and as a board member for five years. Sue states that she will miss the students especially, as well as the energy and vitality of being in a middle level school.  But she is looking forward to working with the outstanding staff at NASSP and the creative principals and associate principals at the middle level throughout the United States. <p>
<p>
In Case You Missed It<p>
The following from TEA for 1996-1997:  "The Spring exit level testing and the Grades 4 and 8 writing testing are scheduled for administration during the last week of February.  Testing during this period in February will remove any state testing from Texas Public Schools Week, which will occur during the week of March 3 - 7, 1997, and will allow exit level students to receive their test results one week earlier."  Because of this change, the TMSA Annual Middle School Conference for 1997 has been changed to January 23 - 25, in Corpus Christi.<p>
<p>
Books 'In the Middle':<p>
This We Believe: Developmentally Responsive Middle Level Schools<p>
The National Middle School Association revisits the basic ideas and ideals of middle level education to set forth twelve characteristics of developmentally responsive middle level schools.  The characteristics put forth in the original This We Believe remain viable for middle level schools.<p>
A "true" middle school will evidence the following conditions or characteristics called essential elements:<p>
1.Educators knowledgeable about and committed to young adolescents.<br>
2.A balanced curriculum based on the needs of young adolescents.<br>
3. A range of organizational arrangements.<br>
4. Varied instructional strategies.<br>
5. A full exploratory program.<br>
6. Comprehensive advising and counseling.<br>
7. Continuous progress for students.<br>
8. Evaluation procedures compatible with the nature of young adolescents.<br>
9. Cooperative planning.<br>
10. Positive school climate.<p>
<p>
 Academic Blend From Reflections on Becoming, by Ronnie L. Sheppard and Beverly D. Stratton<p>
Schools have come to realize that a developmentally appropriate curriculum for middle level students must go beyond the traditional disciplines of math, science, social studies and language arts. In order for our youth to become what they can and to become individuals who value themselves and others, schools must realize the significance of a strong affective education program. In fact, like the books written about early adolescents, curriculum should no longer be seen as separate disciplines, each with a unique set of goals that are detached.  <p>
A curriculum that is tailored to the early adolescent blends affective and intellectual development. Schools continue to struggle with questions concerning how to address both the academic and the affective. Strong teacher-based advisory programs have made their mark. Yet what has often been overlooked  are numerous avenues to bridge the academic and the affective within the core courses. Efforts could be made to turn to additional resources through which to deepen our understanding of early adolescents.  <p>
Literature offers one avenue for this. They (young adolescents) can offer us valuable information about how to help them become continuous learners. They have a sense of what is relevant for them. (Page 92, Reflections on Becoming, National Middle School Association).</html>

</DOC>
