<HTML>"Perceptions of Students at Work"<p><p>
<p><p>
by Sharon Knotts Green<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: School to work transitions<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 5<p><p>
<p><p>
Fueled by the School-to-Work Opportunities Act of 1994, educators and industry leaders in communities across the nation have formed new partnerships to help prepare young people for viable careers. As the External Education Manager for Motorola Austin, I am frequently asked to comment on students' work performance and how educators might better prepare students for success in the workplace. This admittedly generalized summary is based on my personal observations as well as written and verbal evaluations by student supervisors. Remarks made by personnel managers, workplace mentors, and the students themselves are also included. <p>
Students lack career exploration skills including self-assessment, use of information resources and decision-making. In our fervor to help students find employment, well-meaning adults have often placed students in positions which have little relevancy to students' career interests. Consequently, students soon display their disillusionment through erratic attendance and other unacceptable behaviors. Encourage students to reflect on the kind of activities they enjoy. Make career resources available to students and set the expectation that they are to be active participants in their own development.<p>
Students do not ask enough questions. Whether it is during a job interview or after being given a task, failing to ask questions until a point is clear can have serious consequences. An interviewer may feel that the student is not interested in the position or the student may have inaccurate picture of the type of work he or she will be doing. On the job, students may make poor decisions about addressing a task because they do not understand the big picture.<p>
Students have poor attendance. When a student (or anyone for that matter) is hired into a position it is expected that those job tasks will be performed. Regardless of how great one's talents, if the person is not present to do the task, then the company does not benefit from the relationship. The result is that the student will most likely be dismissed from the job. Help students develop strategies for ensuring regular attendance and handling unexpected problems which could prevent them from getting to work on time.<p>
Students must be more resourceful and creative in problem solving. In the workplace there are few problems that have only one solution. Students tend to wait to be given all of the tools to do a task instead of researching what resources are available. Teach students to be observant of resources around them and to consult older employees who can lead them to other resources. Give assignments that allow flexibility in how to solve problems.<p>
Students fail to relate previous accomplishments with current or future projects. Although students do many assignments in school, they may not fully realize the value of what they have learned or where else they might use those same skills. Teach students to inventory skills learned in other classes or previous assignments as they seek to solve new challenges.<p>
Students lack savvy about the hiring process. It matters whether or not an application is accurate, clearly written or typed and has correct spelling. One's appearance, hygiene, posture, handshake, knowledge of the company and verbal skills do impact interviewers' perceptions of candidates. Truthfully expousing on skills and abilities during an interview is not bragging. Teach every student the basics of hiring as these same rules will apply to other selection processes such as college applications, scholarship applications or interviews for admission to special programs.<p>
Students display confrontational behaviors toward supervisors and fail to take directions. Diversity of viewpoints adds to the quality of a decision, but employees and supervisors must be able to discuss different viewpoints without extreme anger. Teach students to calmly and clearly present their opinions and explaining the rationale behind their views. Help them to understand that disagreement with a supervisor is not a license not to do the job. Failure to do a job for which one is hired is a basis for dismissal.<p>
To this point my comments have focused on the areas in which students' work readiness skills could be strengthened. However, in closing I want to also add that students have brought energy and fresh ideas to the company. Through internships and the company's tuition reimbursement program, many return as full-time employees while pursuing higher degrees. High quality partnerships between schools and business can help youth develop skills that will help them be successful on the job and in life.<p>
Sharon Knotts Green is the External Education Manager for the Semiconductor Products Sector at Motorola, Austin. Last October, she was well received by educators from across Texas as a distinguished lecturer at the 1995 National Conference of Texas. </html>

</DOC>
