<HTML>"Research & Development"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Research & development in secondary education<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 12<p><p>
<p><p>
<strong>'OLD PROBLEMS, NEW CHALLENGES:' TEACHERS EXPRESS VIEWS IN 1995 METLIFE SURVEY</strong><p>
More Than a Decade of Comparisons<p>
Dramatic differences exist with teacher satisfaction in their work environments, salaries and the recognition they receive, between suburban and rural teachers and their counterparts in urban settings, reports a nationwide survey of teachers. Teachers in rural and suburban settings believe they have increasing support from parents and community members and feel more satisfaction with their career choice. These teachers also note a decline in the number of students lacking basic skills and in teen suicides. On the other hand, urban teachers say these problems have worsened in their schools. They are least likely to say they feel respected in today's society or recognized for good performance. However, teachers in rural, suburban and urban settings are nearly twice as likely today as in 1984 to say they earn a decent salary.<p>
The Metropolitan Life Survey of the American Teacher, 1984-1995: Old Problems, New Challenges is sponsored by The Metropolitan Life Insurance Company and was conducted by Louis Harris and Associates. This is the twelfth consecutive year Met Life and Harris have teamed up to get a read on teachers' thoughts about their profession and the education students receive. This year's survey polled a nationally representative sample of more than l,000 public school teachers. Complete survey results were made available during a news conference and symposium at the National Press Club in Washington, DC, in November. The event was co-hosted by the Education Commission of the States (ECS).<p>
The Met Life survey also points out that many teachers believe aspects of the public school system have improved considerably over the past ten years. Nearly all teachers surveyed believe that a broad variety of measures would further strengthen the quality of education, including:<p>
emphasizing school discipline and safety (97%). <br>
emphasizing basic skills such as reading, writing and arithmetic (96%) .<br>
broadening the curriculum to include computer literacy and foreign languages (94%) .<br>
tightening graduation requirements (80%). <br>
establishing minimum competency tests for students at predetermined grade levels (77%).<br>
increasing the amount of homework required of students (62%).<p>
"The American teacher must stand at the center of our school reform debate. If America's public schools are sick, the American teacher must help make the diagnosis," says Harry P. Kamen, chairman and CEO, Metropolitan Life Insurance Company. "And if America's public schools are to get better, the American teacher must help write the prescription and administer the cure."<p>
"While teachers are on the front line every day in helping students learn at higher levels, they can't do it alone," says ECS President Frank Newman. "We must continue to build partnerships and provide support from political and business leaders, communities and parents. The Met Life survey helps us see more clearly where we are making progress and where there is work to be done."<p>
Complimentary copies of Old Problems, New Challenges are available by writing to: Met Life Teachers Survey, 1995, P.O. Box 807, Madison Square Station, New York, NY 10139-0807.<p>
Met Life, with over $8 billion in capital and more than $163 billion in assets under management, is one of the most secure financial services companies in the United States. It annually pays out over $30 billion to policyholders, beneficiaries and other recipients, and serves 90 of the Fortune 100 companies.<p>
The Education Commission of the States (ECS) is a nonprofit, nationwide compact formed in 1965 to help governors, state legislators, state education officials and others develop policies to improve the quality of education. Forty-nine states, the District of Columbia, American Samoa, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands are members. The ECS office is located in Denver, Colorado.<p>
<p>
<strong>Report Challenges Bigger is Better Theme in Public Education</strong><p>
Public education would do well to embrace a "smaller is better" theme as it heads into the new millennium, according to a recent study by the Texas Center for Educational Research (TCER), an independent research organization that studies major issues affecting all levels of Texas public education.<p>
The study, Sizing Up the Schools - Bigger is Better versus Small is Beautiful: Issues in the Debate over District, School and Class Size, concludes that although size cannot be examined in isolation, in smaller classes, "Students are more likely to be engaged in the life of the classroom, to develop positive relationships with their teachers and to benefit from more contact time with teachers."<p>
Recommendations from the study are aimed at three distinct levels - district, school and classroom - because the question of size has a different emphasis at each level of the educational system. In contrast, the study suggests that at the district level, districts should combine resources when feasible to take advantage of efficiencies of scale. At the campus level, the study endorses the importance of small schools. For larger schools, the report recommends creating sub-units, or schools within school, where teachers and students can come to know one another better. At the classroom level, the study notes that smaller classes improve the social environment of most schools. The Texas class size limits are an appropriate policy to help achieve this goal.<p>
The study noted that those who urge creation of bigger schools are interested in providing greater educational opportunities, i.e., a greater variety of course offerings, particularly for high school students. Advocates of smaller schools look at personal development issues, noting that students in a smaller setting are more likely to participate in the extracurricular life of the school, be known by the teachers and raise their level of achievement.<p>
Copies of Sizing Up the Schools are available for $10. Contact Claire England, TCER, P.O. Box 2947, Austin, TX 78768-2947, (512) 467-0222.<p>
<p>
<strong>NCATE Standards Approved</strong><p>
The Specialty Areas Studies Board of NCATE approved in late September new Curriculum Guidelines for Programs in Educational Leadership. The Guidelines were developed over a 22 month period by representatives of AACTE, AASA, ASCD, NAESP, NASSP, NCPEA, UCEA and NPBEA. Six drafts of the Guidelines preceded the final, approved seventh version. The fifth and sixth drafts were widely circulated to universities, state departments of education and elementary and secondary educators.<p>
Management of the Guidelines will be by a "Constituent Council" organized by four dues-paying members of NCATE, including ASCD, AASA, NAESP and NASSP. The four sponsors will underwrite the $100,000 annual cost of the Council required for training folio reviewers and conducting the folio review process. The Constituent Council office will be located initially at ASCD, and then rotate at three year intervals among the other associations. Currently a half-time person is being employed to coordinate the training and folio review processes.<p>
The new Curriculum Guidelines will become operable for the fall of 1996. Folio reviewers will come from nominations by the four sponsors of the Constituent Council and from NCPEA and UCEA. <p>
For copies of the final, approved draft of the Guidelines, contact Scott Thomson at NPBEA, 4400 University Dr., Fairfax, VA 22030-4444, (703) 993-3644, or Agnes Crawford at ASCD, 1250 North Pitt Street, Alexandria, VA 22314, (703) 549-9110.</html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT18-B21-116</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000119-B019-185</DOCOLDNO>
