<HTML>"Changes in Curriculum, Graduation Requirements Finalized by SBOE"<p>
<p><br>
Topic: State Board of Education Update<p>
<p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; pp. 18-19<p>
<p>
Following a lengthy hearing in February, a work session in March, and additional discussion in April, the State Board of Education adopted new state curriculum rules at its last meeting. To simplify and clarify the administrative code in this area, the current rules in Chapter 75 have been divided into several chapters. The new chapter 74 will provide general rules about programs, instruction and grading; chapter 76 will outline rules for extracurricular activities; and Chapter 75 will contain the essential elements until they are replaced with the clarified essential knowledge and skills next year. Each essential knowledge and skills area will be contained in a separate chapter.<p>
The Board also discussed a "recommended middle school program" to prepare students for the rigor of the Recommended and Distinguished Achievement Programs in high school. TASSP will be following the development of this proposed initiative closely to ensure that research-based middle school practices are the foundation of its development.<p>
<strong>The new Chapter 74, Required Curriculum</strong>, includes the following departures from current law:<p>
*requires districts to teach essential elements or essential knowledge and skills as adopted by the SBOE, except for prekindergarten essential elements which by law are now a district option.<br>
*requires a review of the curriculum at least every five years and a linkage of changes in curriculum to adoptions of instructional materials when possible.<br>
*effective 1996-97, deletes specific time requirements per SB 1 related to the teaching of the various subject areas at the elementary level; instead, students must demonstrate the essential knowledge and skills in each subject of the required curriculum and meet course and grade level standards; districts should adopt their own schedules and instructional strategies for ensuring student success.<br>
*effective 1996-97, deletes both specific time and credit requirements for subjects at the middle level; districts should adopt their own schedules and instructional strategies to ensure that students land meet course and grade level standards and are prepared for high school.<br>
*adds to rule conditions for approval by commissioner of PE substitutions for private or commercially sponsored programs to all graduation programs; these conditions have already been in use.<br>
*designates dance as a fine art at the secondary level.<br>
*maintains Reading Improvement I, II, III as courses eligible for state graduation credit; in addition, name of course was changed to Reading  so that it does not carry the implication that these are lower-level courses.<br>
*requires that science courses at the high school level include at least 40 percent hands-on laboratory investigations and field work using appropriate scientific inquiry; Science III is be added to the list of required course offerings.<br>
*allows for the issuance of a certificate of coursework completion for any student who completes all graduation requirements except for required exit-level assessment instruments; the student's transcript will include a notation of the date the certificate was issued, but no seal will be attached.<br>
*requires districts to provide three days during each half of the year when examinations for acceleration without prior instruction (credit by examination) will be administered at no charge; exams may be locally developed or purchased from Texas Tech or UT Austin (this section 74.24 was changed substantively at second reading, thus restricting it from final approval until July.)<br>
*allows districts to offer high school courses at earlier grade levels; graduation credit may be awarded if the student has demonstrated proficiency in the subject matter and completed course requirements.<br>
*imposes an SBOE passing standard of a grade which is the equivalent of 70 on a scale of 100 for high school course credit.<br>
*designates a revised list of advanced courses for the No-Pass, No-Play Rule to include all AP, IB and concurrent enrollment classes, deleting some course currently on the list which are not considered advanced such as Physics I.<br>
*provides for campus-based services or transportation to the place of services for students identified with dyslexia; requires appropriate training for teachers and other professionals who identify and provide support to these students.<br>
*<strong>New Minimum High School Program</strong> -  effective for incoming freshman in 1997-98 to allow for planning time with next year's eighth graders, changes to the new minimum program include the following:<p>
*requires a total of 22 credits.<br>
*requires Algebra I as one of the three credits to fulfill mathematics requirements.<br>
*requires Chemistry I, Physics I, or Biology I as one of the two credits to fulfill science requirements.<br>
*high school physical education requirements will remain at one and one half credits with a maximum of two for state credit, but will include one half credit of Foundations of Personal Fitness IA/IB in the one and one-half credit requirement for PE; the list of substitutions for all required PE credit remains the same.<br>
*requires one credit of technology applications selected from Computer Science I or II, Business Computer Applications I or II, Business Computer Programming I or II, Computer Applications, Microcomputer Applications, Business Information Processing, Computer Mathematics or Industrial Technology Computer Applications.<br>
*requires one-half credit of speech selected from Introduction to Speech Communication (may no longer count as English credit), Public Speaking, Debate, Oral Interpretation, or a new course to be developed emphasizing workplace communication skills.<br>
*six and one-half units of elective credit; one elective credit must be World Geography, World History or Science.<p>
*<strong>Recommended High School Program</strong> - effective for incoming freshman in 1997-98, changes to the recommended program include the following:<p>
*reduces the second language proficiency requirement from three credits to two.<br>
*adds one half credit of Foundation of Personal Fitness IA/IB as a requirement in one and one half credits of physical education; the list of substitutions for all required PE credit remains the same.<br>
*defines the one credit of technology applications as Computer Science I or II, Business Computer Applications I or II, Business Computer Programming I or II, Computer Applications, Microcomputer Applications, Business Information Processing, Computer Mathematics or Industrial Technology Computer Applications.<br>
*requires one-half credit of speech selected from Introduction to Speech Communication, Public Speaking, Debate, Oral Interpretation or a new course to be developed emphasizing workplace communication skills.<br>
*increases the number of elective credits in all three Options by one half credit.<p>
*<strong>Distinguished Achievement Program</strong> - effective for incoming freshmen in 1997-98, changes to the distinguished achievement program include:<p>
*adds one half credit of Foundation of Personal Fitness IA/IB as a requirement in one and one half credits of physical education; the list of substitutions for all required PE credit remains the same.<br>
*defines the one credit of technology applications as Computer Science I or II, Business Computer Applications I or II, Business Computer Programming I or II, Computer Applications, Microcomputer Applications, Business Information Processing, Computer Mathematics or Industrial Technology Computer Applications.<br>
*requires one-half credit of speech selected from Introduction to Speech Communication, Public Speaking, Debate, Oral Interpretation, or a new course to be developed emphasizing workplace communication skills.<br>
*decreases the number of elective credits in all three Options by one half credit.<p>
<strong>Extracurricular Rule Held at Second Reading</strong><br>
Following lengthy discussion, the State Board voted to postpone final action on extracurricular rules until its May meeting. Final details concerning the adopted rule will be shared at the UIL session scheduled on Friday, June 14 from 10:30-11:45 a.m. during the TASSP Summer Workshop.<br>
Proposed new Chapter 76, Extracurricular Activities includes:<p>
*defines only extracurricular activities in an effort to clear up some of the confusion in current rule concerning the difference between extracurricular and cocurricular activities.<br>
*would allow absences for cocurricular and curricular activities (such as field trips) not to be counted as absences that are allowed for extracurricular activities.<br>
*would allow a student who had been ruled ineligible and who is enrolled in a state-approved course in which the essential elements require public performance to perform one time per semester.<br>
*would include the commonly accepted definition of the school week.<br>
*would allow a student at the state championship level of competition in UIL events to request an additional two absences if all of the previous fifteen absences had been used.<p>
<strong>Advanced Placement Measure Added to AEIS</strong><p>
In June 1994, the SBOE requested that TEA staff pursue the development of an indicator of Advanced Placement participation and performance for future inclusion in the AEIS. Since that time, the College Entrance Examination Board has received permission to release AP data for Texas students to TEA on an annual basis (note statewide data in charts). The actual indicator will provide two measures. The first will report the number of examinations with a score of three or above and the second will describe the number of examinees with at least one score above three. The first measure may count a student multiple times, depending on the number of examinations with a score above three, while the second will count a student who scores a three or above only once, even if that student scores high on all examinations taken. Board members hope that the utilization of both measures will encourage broader participation in the AP examination program.<p>
Many Board members would like to see measurement of International Baccalaureate performance/participation and also participation in concurrent enrollment courses included in the AEIS. They requested that the Commissioner provide plans to include IB and concurrent enrollment in the indicator system no later than the fall of 1998, noting that these programs are viable options for advanced-level work.<p>
<strong>Ten Open-Enrollment Charters Approved by Board</strong><p>
SB 1 grants the State Board of Education the authority to establish up to twenty open-enrollment charter schools to eligible entities. While remaining a part of the state public school system, this type of charter school is free from many state laws and regulations. Guidelines for open-enrollment charters were approved by the SBOE in October, 1995 and distributed throughout the state. The guidelines include provisions for the application and selection of an open-enrollment charter school as well as the processes for modifying, revoking or placing an open-enrollment charter school on probation.<p>
Six charters were granted by the SBOE in February. Thirteen additional applications were received in time for review and evaluation by the State Board of Education in April. The following ten charters were approved:<p>
*Academy of Traditional Studies, Corpus Christi (grades 6-8, dropouts) individualized program for students at risk or who have already dropped out of school;<br>
*Dallas Can! Academy Charter, Dallas (grades 9-12) individualized, year round academic/career preparation program for predominantly minority students who are at risk of dropping out or who have dropped out of school;<br>
*Genesis Charter High School, Dallas (grades 7-12) individualized program emphasizing liberal arts and sciences, leadership and community service;<br>
*Girls and Boys Prep Academy, Houston - (grades 6-12) foreign language, math and fine arts magnet school;<br>
*George I. Sanchez Charter, Houston (grades 9-12) program aimed at retention of at-risk students and dropout recovery program;<br>
*One-Stop Multiservice Center, Mission (grades 9-12) strong academic/career preparation program for dropouts and students at risk of dropping out;<br>
*Raul Yzaguirre School for Success Charter, Houston (grades 7-8) program for students at risk of dropping out with self-contained classrooms and direct instructional methods;<br>
*Seashore Learning Center, Corpus Christi (grades pre-k-6) developmentally appropriate elementary program;<br>
*The North Hills School, Irving (grades 5-8) program based on a Middle Years Program from the International Baccalaureate Organization; and <br>
*Waco Charter School, Waco (grades K-5) academic program based on an individualized education workplan for each student.</html>

</DOC>
