<HTML>"Summer Workshop '96 to Focus on 'Dynamic Leadership for a Changing World'"<p>
<p>
Topic: TASSP Summer Workshop '96<p>
<p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 1<p>
<p>
 Scheduled June 12 through 14 at the Austin Convention Center, this year's conference activities will focus on developing dynamic leaders who can meet the challenge of personalizing education for kids in our changing world. Your entire administrative team will have the opportunity to tap into resources providing successful strategies for technology use, teacher development, alternative instructional arrangements, school safety, leadership skills and the like - today's critical issues facing middle level and high school administrators. Featured keynoters will be:<p>
<strong>Pat Williams<br>
general manager, orlando magic<br>
orlando, florida</strong><br>
More than just being the boss of Shaquille O'Neal and the GM of the 1995 NBA Eastern Conference champs, Pat Williams is bombarded each year with thousands of speaking requests, of which he accepts less than 100. He is famous for his motivational ability and sense of humor. Williams is more than qualified to speak on children: he and wife Jill have 18 children, ages 10 to 22. "Fourteen are adopted," says Pat, "but I forget which fourteen." In his spare time (no one is sure when that is), Williams has authored over a dozen books.<p>
<strong>Jennifer James<br>
cultural anthropologist<br>
seattle, washington</strong><br>
As a cultural anthropologist, Jennifer James has been able to comment on her findings in many different ways. She has been a college instructor and an assistant professor at the University of Washington in Seattle, and she has hosted her own radio and television talk shows. Currently, Dr. James is known as a lecturer, a columnist for The Seattle Times and as an advisor to the Committee for Children, a non-profit organization committed to the prevention of child abuse.<p>
<strong>Marilyn Hohmann<br>
senior associate, clsr<br>
louisville, kentucky</strong><br>
Marilyn Hohmann is a senior associate with the Center for Leadership in School Reform (CLSR) in Louisville, Kentucky, which focuses on the national high school reform agenda. In addition to having served as principal of Fairdale High School, she is a former teacher, guidance counselor and assistant vocational principal. She has been featured on NBC's "Brokaw Report" (1993), the "Today Show" (1990) and in Time magazine (June, 1990). Ms. Hohmann has served on the NASSP & Carnegie Foundation National Commission on High School Restructuring for the past two years.</html>

</DOC>
