<HTML>"'Surf's up' in Socorro ISD"<p><p>
<p><p>
by Art Shaw, principal, Montwood High School<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: Technology at the secondary level<p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 9<p><p>
<p><p>
It is no wonder executives of the Apple Corporation called Socorro ISD one of the nation's "fifteen or twenty" most innovative, progressive and technologically advanced districts at an executive briefing in San Jose. High school students at the district's two high schools, Montwood and Socorro, are already "surfin' the net" from their classrooms as part of a district technology plan which will soon feature Internet access from every classroom in the district's twenty-one campuses.<p>
In 1994 the voters of East El Paso approved a $70 million bond issue with $4.5 million of the funds earmarked for Internet access from every classroom and office in the district. As of this date, all campuses in the district have access to the Internet from their offices and library. <p>
Both high schools are fully on-line, boasting more than 150 Internet access points on each campus. Middle schools are currently being equipped, elementary campuses will follow, with the entire project completed by 1997. A unique component of this accessing process, but typical of the district's commitment to Site-Based Decision Making, is the installation of Mac or DOS platform hardware in each area, depending upon the preference of the user.<p>
A five-year district technology plan, begun in 1992 and augmented by the individual campus technology plans, calls for networking for all classrooms and offices districtwide. These programs are clear indications of the Socorro ISD's commitment to the implementation of technology access for all teachers and students in the district, which also includes teleconferencing capability at both high schools and the Ed Center. <p>
All aspects of technology, to include phone service, have been upgraded. Campuses are allotted per-capita-based technology funds which serve to replace older equipment, increase the capability of current hardware, buy new software and fund special projects at each individual school. The projects include NovaNet Labs at both high schools and the KEYS campus, CD ROM access campus-wide at some schools, multimedia configurations, CD ROM Towers in most libraries and numerous other initiatives. In addition, local cable television companies have provided cable drops to each classroom and several homebound students are part of an experimental program with Time-Warner (owner of Paragon Cable) to use the teleconferencing capabilities for learning purposes.<p>
Since everyone will eventually have access to the Internet, all users have e-mail addresses/passwords. The district office serves as a hub with T1 access to current and future sites. A district Acceptable Use Program has been developed to prevent student access to those unacceptable Internet offerings and teach students/faculty the responsibility involved in use of the Internet. Faculty are trained extensively to insure students are monitored effectively. <p>
All students/faculty must sign the agreement prior to Internet access and the issuance of a password. Any user who purposely and willingly abuses the system is banned from future access. The district and the two high school campuses carefully monitor usage and lock out known inappropriate Internet addresses once they are discovered. Isolated abuses by students have been reported, but the problem has not been widespread, largely due to careful monitoring by staff and a keen awareness of the potential for problems. The MIS department also publishes a regular bulletin for faculty describing appropriate use of the network.<p>
Needless to say, the installation of Internet and e-mail in each classroom has been hugely popular with students and faculty. Students utilize the net for research, recreation and communication with students at other schools also on the Net. Montwood and Socorro students have created attractive home pages and have shared valuable information and their excitement about technology with students from all over the world. <p>
Synergy, an integrated curriculum pilot project, is using the Internet connection to conduct in-depth research on various topics to include ongoing e-mail conversations with experts in fields of marine biology. The students are also learning how to incorporate their ideas in newsletters. Their newly acquired desktop publishing skills include using a variety of software programs including Microsoft Word, Quark Xpress, Delta Graph and Aldus Freehand.<p>
Irma Avila, 1995-96 teacher of the year, is using technology with her at-risk students. Her students are putting together Hyperstudio stacks about poets. The stacks will include pictures of the students' favorite poets, samples of the poets' works and original poems of the students.<p>
The Universal Access Lab at Montwood, which is used extensively, is moving into the Science arena. Biology students are now using the facility for dissection. The teachers and students enjoy a safer, cleaner and cheaper alternative to traditional methods. <p>
At Montwood, students can take a course in desktop publishing. This vocational course has all the materials for students to excel. Nathan Thompson, a junior at Montwood, recently competed at the state level. He won second place and will now compete nationally. Danny Martinez, also taking the course, won first place in regionals in computer aided graphics.<p>
Also in the vocational department is computer maintenance. Students repair and build computers for Montwood and other schools. This year they will have put together approximately seventy machines. Look for the label on a computer near you.<p>
Montwood has its first computer club, called The Net. The club was formed in December by a group of computer enthusiasts, some of whom had very little knowledge, but enjoyed the computer's potential. The club meets to discuss technology issues and to learn from each other. Members have taught DOS and Windows basics, html (creation of homepages), midi (music on the computer), networking basics and have looked at various new technologies appearing on the Internet. Several members have their personal homepages on the Rio Grande freenet. The club maintains its own web page on the Rio Grande Freenet at http:\\rgfrn.epcc.edu\ao256.html.<p>
There are many exciting projects occurring at Montwood in the next few months. Students will be presenting multimedia projects to parents in mid-May. The student projects will include sound, graphics, text and animation. One teacher is creating a personal homepage and many more teachers and students are using the available technology to enhance learning.<p>
Montwood is still learning how to integrate the technology into the curriculum. Recently, Montwood held a 1/2 day inservice on technology. Teachers could choose between a wide variety of topics: Multimedia, Eudora (e-mail package) and Netscape, Library Resources and NovaNet, Basics on the Macintosh and Windows machines, Gradebook program and TV-EYES Pro. With the newly-attained Microsoft Office many a teacher will be busy learning how to use the presentation tool, the word processor and the spreadsheet to aid in student learning.<p>
Parents and the community are also enjoying the fun of "surfing" the net. The district's facilities are made available to community members regularly and NovaNet ports are utilized by GED students, English classes for the non-English speaker, basic technology instruction, word processing and other adult basic education classes conducted by the district. Extensive use of the NovaNet system is employed at KEYS Academy, the district's alternative school, as well as both high schools, where students earn graduation credit through use of the technology capability provided for them by the district's commitment to technology.<p>
The possibilities are endless, and students in the Socorro ISD find ways daily to take advantage of these mind-building opportunities as a part of their technological education.</html>

</DOC>
