<HTML>"Texas Study seeks articles: Fall '96 to focus on 'a kaleidoscope of innovative practices'"<p><p>
<p><p>
Topic: <strong>Texas Study of Secondary Education</strong><p><p>
<p><p>
from <strong>TASSP News Highlights</strong>; May 1996; Vol. 35, No. 5; p. 2<p><p>
<p><p>
TASSP is preparing for the Fall 1996 edition of Texas Study of Secondary Education, TASSP's magazine for secondary education stakeholders. TASSP is looking for manuscripts to be published in the Texas Study.  Deadline for submission of articles is September 6, 1996. The effectiveness of this publication to offer useful information depends on practitioners, researchers, and other contributors who can offer timely insight into the current topics which affect secondary campus communities.<p>
Accordingly, the association is looking for manuscripts, 3-8 typed, double-spaced pages (photographs, slides and/or illustrations appreciated), for immediate consideration to publish. A second copy on IBM or Mac disk in text format would also be appreciated. All articles which are submitted will be reviewed by a committee of principals in late September. Those articles which are selected will be included in the Fall '96 issue of TSSE scheduled for publication in November.<p>
TASSP seeks articles in a magazine format which are written in a style that is both conversational and informative. Articles may emphasize this issue's focus -  A Kaleidoscope of Innovative Practices - or address policy, research, staff development or other trends relating to other pertinent topics. We hope to publish articles that can offer our members insight into a variety of topics and programs which meet the needs of students and educators in secondary education.<p>
A majority of the articles chosen for publication in this issue will relate to the Fall '96 focus on A Kaleidoscope of Innovative Practices, including ideas on how we are creatively meeting our students' needs by implementing innovative ideas in our schools. We would like to describe in print the strategies and programs that have been responsible for success at your school! Topic ideas might include but are not limited to:<p>
* Innovative curriculum/instruction/assessment programs.<br>
* Successful school safety practices.<br>
* The how-to's of effective problem-solving.<br>
* Staff development opportunities that get your staff is excited!<br>
* Creative alternative education placements<br>
*Infusion of technology<br>
*Positive utilization of diversity<p>

<strong>Additionally, we are looking for humorous or poignant short anecdotes</strong> pertaining to school, administration or something "principal-ish" in nature. Remember to also send your exact job title (Principal, Assistant Principal, Associate Principal, Resident Scapegoat, etc.) and the name of the school for which you currently work. <p>

Please address all writing attempts to Dawn Rinken, Managing Editor, Texas Study, TASSP, 1833 South IH 35, Austin, TX 78741, fax to (512) 442-3343. Or e-mail your text-formated attempt as an attachment to drinken@tassp.org. (Anecdotes need not be done as attachments.)</html>

</DOC>
