<a name="vision">
<br>
<br>

<h3><i><font color=navy>A Clear Vision of Where Our Future Lies</font></i></h3>

</center>

<br>
<table align=left hspace=20 border=0>
<tr align=center>
<td><image border=1 src="art.gif">
</tr>
<tr align=center>
<td>Arthur D. Levinson<br>
President and<br>
Chief Executive Officer<p>
</tr>
</table>

<h4><i><font color=brown>"To deliver full value to stockholders we're focusing  our efforts and resources behind our pipeline. Though this will mean modest short-term earnings, I believe the long-term benefits will justify this approach."
<p>
Arthur D. Levinson, Ph.D.<br>
President and Chief Executive Officer
</font></i></h4>

<p>
Genentech has always been about science, and about applying science to bring to market new medicines that can significantly help people. As in Genentech's early days, business realities and the promise of our pipeline compel us to put the full force of our efforts behind our science. To deliver full value to stockholders we're taking a long-term financial view and focusing our efforts and resources behind the products in our pipeline -- both our own discoveries and those of our business partners. Though this will mean modest short-term earnings, I believe the long-term benefits will 
justify this approach. 
<p>
What will drive these long-term benefits? The answer is 
at the heart of our business strategy. In Genentech's 1995 annual report I outlined a 
four-point strategy for growth, still in place: 
<p>
<ul>
<font color=navy size=+0><b>1</b></font> &nbsp;Maximize sales of marketed products
<p>
<font color=navy size=+0><b>2</b></font> &nbsp;Accelerate and expand product development
<p>
<font color=navy size=+0><b>3</b></font> &nbsp;Increase the pace of forming strategic alliances
<p>
<font color=navy size=+0><b>4</b></font> &nbsp;Improve financial returns. 
</ul>
<p>
Let's take a closer look at strategy point 2.

<h2>Accelerate and Expand Product Development</h2>

<img align=right src="body_left.gif">So far in 1996, we have made significant progress. We received FDA clearance to market Activase&reg (Alteplase, recombinant) for the treatment of acute ischemic stroke within three hours of symptom onset. One pipeline product, nerve growth factor (NGF), recently reached an important milestone with positive Phase II results in treating diabetic peripheral neuropathy. With these results, we are moving into Phase III trials with NGF. Per our 1995 arrangement with our majority stockholder Roche, Roche has exercised its option to develop NGF outside the United States. In addition, Roche has exercised its option to develop insulin-like growth factor (IGF-1) for diabetes outside the United States. Genentech is currently investigating IGF-1 for diabetes in Phase II and III clinical trials. Roche has also exercised its option to develop the IDEC-C2B8 antibody for treating non-Hodgkins B-cell lymphoma outside the United 
States: Genentech's partner IDEC Pharmaceuticals is 
currently investigating this indication in the United States in Phase III trials. Genentech 
has also resolved a dispute and obtained a business partner to develop an anti-IgE antibody. Genentech's anti-IgE antibody is currently in Phase II clinical trials for allergic asthma.
<p>
Genentech has moved two new products into clinical development and is actively preparing two more for the clinic: We are preparing IND applications for vascular endothelial growth 
factor (VEGF) for cardiovascular disorders and an anti-VEGF antibody for cancer. In addition, as part of a collaboration with XOMA Corporation, an anti-CD11a antibody for psoriasis and organ transplant rejection just entered into Phase I trials. Similarly, in collaboration with Roche, Phase I clinical trials of an anti-CD18 antibody for hemorrhagic shock were initiated.
<p>
These are just some of the many promising products in Genentech's pipeline targeting a variety of disorders, from 
cancer to asthma to diabetes. We're carefully managing this tremendous resource, with a clear eye toward the future.
<p>
<img align=left src="sig.gif">
<br clear>
<br>
<br>
<br>

<a name="ngf">
<h2><font color=brown>Pipeline Profile</font></h2>

<h3><font color=navy><i>Nerve Growth Factor Delivers Promising Phase II Results</i></font></h3>

<img align=left src="body_right.gif"><p>

Following successful Phase II results presented at the annual American Neurological Association (ANA) Meeting in October, Genentech is busily preparing nerve growth factor (NGF) for Phase III trials investigating its potential as a treatment for diabetes-related peripheral neuropathy. This common disorder among 
diabetics currently lacks effective therapy.
<p>
Nerve growth factor is one of a family of natural human factors known to stimulate the growth and survival of neurons in the 
nervous system. Preclinical data indicate NGF specifically targets small sensory neurons of the peripheral nervous system (the nerves that receive stimulation from outside the body, such as the sense 
of touch from the skin), potentially promoting their survival, growth and regeneration. These small sensory fibers are responsible 
primarily for the perception of pain and temperature.
<p>
Peripheral neuropathy is a 
disease resulting from multiple causes, including diabetes, AIDS and cancer chemotherapy. In this disorder, small sensory neurons in the feet, legs and hands are affected, resulting in spontaneous pain, numbness and other abnormal sensations, 
such as burning or tingling.
<p>
The Phase II trial of NGF in diabetic patients with peripheral neuropathy showed this protein is safe and that it improved neurological function and the sensation of cooling detection and of heat measured as pain by well-accepted neurological function tests.
<p>

A Phase III trial, currently scheduled to begin by the end of the year and conclude before the close of the decade, will seek to 
confirm and expand these results for the purpose of applying for regulatory approval in the United States. Roche will conduct pivotal trials in Europe for marketing registration there. 

<img hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right border=0 src="drugs.gif">

Genentech's Phase III trial, in approximately 1,600 diabetic patients with peripheral neuropathy, will target various endpoints. The primary endpoint will be improvement in objective tests of neurological functions, such as was seen in the Phase II results. A secondary endpoint will be a subjective measure of the patients' perception   of benefit. In addition, pharmaco-economic analysis and quality-of-life assessment will be important aspects of the Phase III 
development plan and a necessary foundation for Genentech's reimbursement strategy.

<p>
Designed in consultation with the FDA, these Phase III trials should demonstrate definitively whether NGF can improve the symptoms in diabetic patients with peripheral neuropathy. 
If so, it will represent an important first for diabetic patients and for Genentech.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>

<a name="aha">
<h2><font color=brown>Marketed Product News</font></h2>

<h3><font color=navy><i>AHA/AAN Specify Activase 
in Treatment Guidelines for Stroke</i></font></h3>

<br>

In September, the American Heart Association (AHA) and the American Academy of Neurology (AAN) issued new guidelines intended to improve patients' chances to recover from ischemic stroke -- stroke that is caused by a blood clot in an artery of the brain, about 80 percent of all strokes. The guidelines spell out the appropriate use of Activase in the treatment of acute ischemic stroke. Activase was licensed by the FDA for treating these strokes within three hours of the onset of symptoms in June 1996.
<p>
The guidelines urge that stroke be treated as a life-threatening emergency, and that eligible patients be 
treated with Activase quickly to enhance their chance of recovering with no or minimal disability. They also clearly spell out the screening required to determine who should and who should not be given Activase, so that only patients most likely to benefit and least likely to suffer side effects are treated.
<p>
Because stroke has until recently not been treatable, and therefore not been considered a time-sensitive medical emergency, these AHA/
AAN guidelines are essential to educating physicians on the urgency of evaluating and, where appropriate, treating stroke patients with Activase.
<p>
But the public also must be educated to recognize the urgency of stroke. Genentech is working with a consortium of several leading medical organizations organized by the AAN to develop a major public education campaign called START (Stroke Awareness, Response, Treatment) to educate the public to recognize the symptoms of stroke and to treat it as a medical emergency. A central theme to the campaign is viewing strokes as "brain attacks" to impart the same medical urgency that is already recognized for heart attacks.
<br>
<br>
<br>

<a name="anti"> 
<h2><font color=brown>Business Partner News</font></h2>

<h3><font color=navy><i>XOMA Prepares Genentech's Anti-CD11a Antibody for Clinical Testing in Psoriasis Patients</i></font></h3>

Just as the third quarter of 1996 came to a close, XOMA Corporation, in a collaboration with Genentech, filed an Investigational New Drug Application with the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to begin clinical testing of Genentech's anti-CD11a antibody for the treatment of psoriasis. This cleared the way for XOMA to begin Phase I clinical trials in October to test the safety of this fully humanized monoclonal antibody in patients with psoriasis. This immune disorder leaves patients with itchy, scaly, red patches on their skin, often covering large areas of the body. The anti-CD11a antibody is designed to block specifically the immune cells, called T-cells, that are over-active in psoriasis. Preclinical studies suggest the antibody also may be useful to curb these same immune cells after an organ transplant to prevent rejection of the transplant by the patient's immune system.
Per Genentech's agreement with XOMA, reached earlier in 1996, if the Phase I trials prove the safety of anti-CD11a, XOMA will take the product through Phase II clinical testing, initially for psoriasis, and also for organ transplant rejection. If Phase II trials demonstrate that the drug is both effective and safe, Genentech and/or XOMA will conduct pivotal Phase III trials to prove its effectiveness. 
Collaborations such as this one are essential to helping Genentech realize its product development goals for its large pipeline. By leveraging Genentech's technology and financial resources with partners' development and manufacturing resources, partnerships such as this one with XOMA allow Genentech to deliver more of its products to patients who need them. 
<br>
<br>
<br>

<a name="business">
<h2><font color=brown>Third Quarter Business Highlights</font></h2>

<ul>
<li> Appointed David Roche to senior vice president of Sales and Marketing and Judy Heyboer to senior vice president of Human Resources.
<p>
<li> American Heart Association and American Academy of Neurology issued guidelines for use of Activase in treatment of acute ischemic stoke.
<p>
<li> The Pulmonary-Allergy Drug Advisory Committee to the U.S. FDA recommended Pulmozyme&reg (dornase alfa) Inhalation Solution for marketing clearance for treatment of cystic fibrosis patients with advanced disease (It is currently approved for treatment of CF patients with mild to moderate disease). 
<p>
<li> With Tanox Biosystems, Inc. and Ciba-Geigy, Ltd., settled lawsuits filed against each other related to the development of anti-IgE antibodies. Also, reached an agreement in principle under which Genentech and Tanox/Ciba-Geigy will combine their existing anti-lgE antibody programs under a cross-licensing program in a cooperative development effort.
<p>
<li> Reported results of Phase II trial of nerve growth factor for peripheral neuropathies, demonstrating initial safety 
and efficacy, at an annual American Neurological Association Meeting in October. 
<p>
<li>Roche exercised its option, per Genentech's 1995 arrangement with Roche, to develop NGF outside the United States.
<p>
<li>In collaboration with XOMA Corporation, filed an Investigational New Drug Application for Genentech's anti-CD11a antibody in patients with psoriasis, and began a Phase I safety trial in October.
<p>
<li>In cooperation with Roche, filed an Investigational New Drug Application for Genentech's anti-CD18 antibody in patients with hemorrhagic shock, and began a Phase I safety trial in October.
</ul>
<br>
<br>

