<blockquote>

Click here to see the press release of <a href="http://www.gene.com/pressrelease/1996/10_21_96.html">Genentech's Third Quarter 1996 Results</a>.

<a name="managing">
<h2><font color=brown>Product Pipeline</font></h2>

<h3><font color=navy><i>Managing a Pipeline of Plenty</i></font></h3>

<center>
<blockquote>
<h4><font color=brown><i>With a pipeline as rich as Genentech's, the challenge is to prioritize the company's resources to expedite those products that are most promising -- both medically and financially.</i></font></h4>
</blockquote>
</center>

<br>
</blockquote>
<img src="pipeline.gif">
<center>
<table border=1>
<tr>
<th>Products  <th>IDEC-C2B8 Antibody	      <th>Anti-HER2 Antibody 	             
<th>Auriculin&reg 	   <th>Nerve Growth Factor	                 <th>IGF-1 	             <th>Nutropin&reg	                           <th>Nutropin 
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Disease Indications	<td>Non-Hodgkins B-Cell Lymphoma 	<td>Breast Cancer	<td>Oliguric Acute Renal Failure	<td>Diabetic Peripheral Neuropathy	<td>Diabetes 	<td>Growth Hormone Inadequacy in Adults	<td>Turner Syndrome	
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Status	<td>Phase III	<td>Phase III	<td>Phase III	<td>Phase III	<td>Phase III	<td>Preparing Regulatory Filing	<td>Awaiting Regulatory Approval

</tr>

</table>
</center>

<blockquote>

How robust is Genentech's product pipeline? When you consider factors such as the number of products in late-stage clinical development, 
the frequency of Genentech's 
interactions with the FDA, 
the regularity of scientific 
presentations about potential Genentech products at major medical meetings, and the large number of contracts Genentech generates with clinical research sites, it becomes clear that substantial clinical development is occurring. 
<p>
With a pipeline as rich as Genentech's, the challenge is to prioritize the company's resources to expedite those products that are most promising -- both medically and financially. A key to doing so is to organize efforts into therapeutic areas: cardiovascular, oncology, endocrinology,
pulmonary/allergy/immunology, neurology. This enables Genentech to focus related efforts and build a critical mass of internal and external expertise in specific therapeutic areas that each may cover several synergistic projects.
<p>
Genentech has a two-pronged effort for these therapeutic areas. First, the company is building on its existing strengths in areas where it has already had successes and built strong relationships. For example, in endocrinology, Genentech is continuing to develop new indications for growth hormone, but is now also turning that expertise to diabetes. Likewise with cardiovascular medicine, where Genentech scientists and physicians are recognized experts on thrombosis and acute coronary events, and are now focusing that expertise on vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), an oral IIbIIIa antagonist, and other, novel approaches to treating cardiovascular disease.
<p>
Second, Genentech is building strengths in promising new areas, such as oncology, where 
it has several innovative cancer treatments under development. Genentech is bringing some of the best people in the field in house, and is collaborating with academic and clinical leaders outside the company. Its Oncology Advisory Board, for example, is an essential resource in planning the development efforts for potential cancer therapies.
<p>
In all areas, relationships with external experts allow Genentech to fully leverage the talents of its people and ensure it is developing products that will be useful and usable both in theory and in the real-world, day-to-day practice of medicine.
<p>
Finally, Genentech continues to collaborate closely with the FDA. The highest likelihood for success comes when a company knows before it enters the clinic what clinical endpoints the FDA wants to see to be able to grant approval, and then designs its trials accordingly. This is how Genentech designed its clinical trials for Activase in stroke, whose timely approval is indicative of the value of this approach. And this is how Genentech approaches all its projects. 







</blockquote>
</BODY>
