<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Letter from Art Levinson</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<CENTER>

<!-- begin-gne-header -->
<a href=/cgi-bin/imagemap/about_gne>
<img border=0 src=about_gne.gif alt=About Genentech ismap></a>
<!-- end-gne-header -->
</center>

<table cellpadding=20 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10>
<tr>
<td><img border=1  src="art.gif">
<td><H2>Letter from Art Levinson</h2>
<b>President & C.E.O., Genentech, Inc.</b>
</tr>

</table>

<br clear=all>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<font size=+3>D</font>ear Internet Community:<P>
Welcome to Genentech's home page.   Genentech's business is the application of recombinant DNA technology to make medicine for treating human illness.  We are a pioneer in the field, having developed the first pharmaceutical based on DNA technology, recombinant human insulin.  We are also the first company to take a bioengineered medicine all the way from research to the market in 1985 with a recombinant form of human growth hormone called Protropin.  Like a lot of high tech pioneers, we've gotten where we are with help from the Internet.<P>
   

Founded in 1976, Genentech has grown rapidly, now employing 2,800 people.  All along we have depended heavily on scientific research.  The company spends approximately forty percent of its revenues on R&D - high by the standards of any industry.  Genentech also encourages  scientists to spend as much as twenty-five percent of their time on research of their own choosing, a policy that has led to some of Genentech's most important discoveries.<P>
  

Computing technology has always been a significant part of Genentech's research effort.  For years, the Internet has served as a hub for scientific information and communications flowing in and out of the company.  Since the early 1980s, the company's scientists have been connected to the Internet, either through the University of California at San Francisco or through our own server.  This has provided scientists -- myself included -- at Genentech with access to biological databases, scientific publications, specialized computer software resources, and convenient communication with other scientists from all over the world.<P>


With the advent of the World Wide Web, the Internet has taken the next step in its evolution.  No longer just a resource tool for science and government, it is now a meeting place for the world to exchange ideas -- both verbally and  visually.  Genentech welcomes this opportunity to show the world a little more of what we are all about -- not only to give back to the Internet community but to encourage a greater understanding of the rich, complex, and vitally important field of biotechnology.  With more knowledge, more people can benefit -- not only from the medicine itself, but in learning about how and why it is created.<P>


We are excited about our science and committed to it.  We want you to know why.
<P>
Sincerely,
<br>
<br>
<br>
Art Levinson<br>
President and Chief Executive Officer<br>
Genentech, Inc.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<!-- begin-gne-footer -->
<center><a href=/cgi-bin/imagemap/nav> <img border=0 src=../nav.gif alt=Navigation ismap></a></center>
<!-- end-gne-footer -->
</BODY>       
</HTML>
