<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Corporate Backgrounder</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFfFf">
<CENTER>

<!-- begin-gne-header -->
<a href=/cgi-bin/imagemap/about_gne>
<img border=0 src=about_gne.gif alt=About Genentech ismap></a>
<!-- end-gne-header -->

<H1>Corporate Backgrounder</H1></CENTER>

<center>
<img src=company.gif>
</center><p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+3>G</FONT>enentech, Inc. is a pioneer biotechnology company using human genetic information to discover, develop, manufacture and market pharmaceuticals that address significant unmet medical needs.  Genentech commits itself to high standards of behavior in contributing to the best interests of patients and the medical profession, and makes it products available to all patients who need them, regardless of their ability to pay.  The company has headquarters in South San Francisco and is traded on the New York and Pacific Stock exchanges under the symbol GNE.  
<P>
<HR size=5>
<UL>
<li> <a href="#overview">Overview</a>
<LI> <A HREF="#achievements">Scientific Achievements</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#pipeline">Product Pipeline</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#collaborations">Research and Development Collaborations</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#employees">Employees</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#patients">Uninsured Patients Programs</a>
</UL>
<p>
<a name=overview>
<hr size=5><P>
<h2>Overview</h2>
<font size=+3>G</font>enentech manufactures five products and markets them in the United States and Canada:  
<P>
<UL><LI><B><a href=..//Medicines/activase.html>Activase&reg;</B></a> (Alteplase, recombinant), a tissue-plasminogen activator, to dissolve blood clots in the arteries of patients with acute myocardial infarction (heart attack) and patients with acute massive pulmonary embolism (blood clots in the lungs). 
<P>
<LI><B><a href=../Medicines/actimmune.html>Actimmune&reg;</B></a> (Interferon gamma-1b) for treating chronic granulomatous disease, a rare, inherited deficiency of the immune system.
<P>
<LI><B><a href=../Medicines/pulmozyme.html>Pulmozyme&reg;</B></a> (dornase alfa) Inhalation Solution, the first new therapeutic approach for cystic fibrosis in 30 years.
<P>
<LI><B><a href=../Medicines/protropin.html>Protropin&reg;</B></a> (somatrem for injection) human growth hormone for treating children with growth hormone inadequacy (GHI).
<P>
<LI><B><a href=../Medicines/nutropin.html>Nutropin&reg;</B></a> [somatropin (rDNA origin) for injection] human growth hormone also for treating GHI in children, for treating growth failure in children due to chronic renal insufficiency, and for treating growth failure in children with Turner syndrome.  (Nutropin also comes in a liquid version, <a href="../Medicines/nutropin_aq.html">Nutropin AQ<img border=0 src=tm.gif></a>, currently approved for the former two indications).
</UL>
<P>
As a result of  a new 1995 merger arrangement with Genentech's majority stockholder, Roche Holdings Ltd., of Basel Switzerland, Genentech receives from Roche royalties on sales of its products in Canada, and on sales of Pulmozyme in Europe. Genentech receives royalties on sales of growth hormone, interferon gamma and tissue plasminogen activator outside of the United States and Canada through other licensees.  Genentech also receives worldwide royalties on five additional licensed products which originated from Genentech technology and are marketed by other companies.
<P>

<a name=achievements><P>
<HR size=5><P>

<H2>Scientific Achievements</H2>

<img align=left src=team.gif>
<font size=+3>G</font>enentech's most important asset is its science.  The company's research has led to ten -- almost half -- of biotechnology-based products on the market today.  Genentech is the only biotechnology company to have taken five of its own products from the laboratory to the marketplace.
<p>	
Genentech scientists are the most prolific in the biotechnology industry, publishing at a rate of about 250 papers per year, more than one paper for every business day.  The company is also the leader among biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies for the highest average number of citations per published scientific paper -- a peer-related measure considered to be a good indication of scientific impact.  Genentech holds more than 1,500 patents worldwide, and has more than 1,200 pending.
<p>
Science at Genentech focuses on four areas of medicine: cardiovascular, cancer, endocrinology, and pulmonary/allergy/immunology.  Nurturing quality research through a commitment to basic science, the company encourages scientists to pursue their own interests with time for discretionary research. 
<p>
Genentech was the first biotechnology company to successfully scale up protein manufacturing from small quantities used for research to the much larger quantities needed for clinical trials and marketing.  The company continues to be a world leader in the manufacture of biopharmaceuticals, producing up to 50 kilograms of many products yearly for clinical research and the marketplace, through a variety of fermentation and proprietary purification processes.
<p>
To ensure continued scientific excellence, Genentech opened the world's largest research facility devoted solely to biotechnology in October, 1992.  A 275,000-square-foot, $85 million facility, the Founders Research Center features specialized laboratories and equipment and three inter-connected buildings overlooking the San Francisco Bay.  It houses more than 400 Genentech scientists and staff members.  The Founders Research Center was dedicated to <a href="founders.html">Bob Swanson and Dr. Herbert Boyer</a> in honor of their pursuit of the promise of biotechnology when they established Genentech more than 17 years ago.
<p>
The company's investment in facilities continued in 1993 with the completion of a $37 million manufacturing expansion to manufacture Pulmozyme and in 1995 with the completion of a new $58 million Process Science Center that houses 170 employees.  The 150,000 square-foot center is used primarily as a laboratory building, with 12,000 square feet used as a pilot plant for scale-up of recovery processes.  With this new addition, Genentech occupies more than 1.7 million square feet of space in 19 buildings in South San Francisco. In 1996, Genentech began construction of a second manufacturing facility in Vacaville, California.
<P>

<A NAME ="pipeline">
<HR size=5>
<P>
<BR>
<H2>Product Pipeline</H2>
<P>
<font size=+3>W</font>ith more than $2 billion in assets and 1995 revenues of $918 million, Genentech reinvested more than 40 percent of its revenues into research and development (R&D) in 1995 -- more than twice the pharmaceutical industry average.  To balance resource use with the strongest likelihood of success, Genentech moves only the most promising of its products into clinical development.  The company chooses these products using a rigorous set of criteria that assesses scientific factors, medical need, and factors that impact market potential.  Genentech has aggressive goals to accelerate and expand its product development, moving three to four new products into development in 1996.  An example of these is an anti-CD18 monoclonal antibody, recently moved into the clinic for treating hemorrhagic shock.
<p>
Some other potential products Genentech is investigating in clinical trials are the HER2 humanized monoclonal antibody, a potential treatment for severe cases of breast and ovarian cancer; and insulin-like growth factor (IGF-1) as a possible treatment for diabetes.  Other indications targeted by the many new products in Genentech's pipeline include: other cancers, various side effects of cancer chemotherapy, asthma and a type of acute renal failure. 
<P>
Visit the <a href=../Pipeline/>Product Pipeline.</a>
<p>
<A NAME ="collaborations">
<HR size=5>
<P>
<H2>Research and Development Collaborations</H2>
<P>
<font size=+3>G</font>enentech and Roche are collaborating on several R&D projects to maximize complementary scientific strengths.  These collaborations utilize advanced technology to develop potential new pharmaceuticals for untreated medical conditions.
<p>	
Genentech also has R&D agreements with several biotechnology companies studying related technologies.  An example of these is its relationship with IDEC Pharmaceuticals to develop a monoclonal antibody, IDEC-C2B8, currently in Phase III trials for non-Hodgkin's B-cell lymphoma.  Genentech continues to seek out and develop strategic alliances with other companies when a synergistic fit exists.
<P>

<A NAME ="employees">
<HR size=5><P>
<H2>Employees</H2>
<P>
<img align=left src=lunchcrowd.gif>
<font size=+3>G</font>enentech's success is predicated on its ability to recruit and retain highly qualified and motivated people in all areas of the company.  Of the approximately 3,000 Genentech employees, more than 80 percent have college degrees and more than 25 percent hold advanced degrees including Ph.D.s and M.D.s.  Genentech demands the best from its employees and rewards them accordingly with a benefits plan which includes health care benefits that are among the best in the industry, an employee stock purchase plan, a paid sabbatical program and one of the largest corporate-sponsored day-care centers in the country.
<P>

<A NAME ="patients">
<HR size=5>
<P>

<H2>Uninsured Patients Programs</H2>
<P>
<font size=+3>A</font>lthough Genentech's products are covered by most government and private insurance, Genentech has established uninsured patients programs for each of its marketed products to make them available to qualified patients in the United States who are uninsured or underinsured.  Genentech has provided more than $170 million worth of drug to patients in need since the programs were initiated.
<p>
Genentech's goal remains singular:  to use excellent science to bring new products for significant medical needs to market.  The company's strengths -- including its excellent science, five marketed products and our strong development pipeline -- will help ensure Genentech continues to meet that goal. 
<P>
<HR size=5>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
<!-- begin-gne-footer -->
