<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Genentech Chronology</TITLE></HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFAFA">

<CENTER>

<!-- begin-gne-header -->
<a href=/cgi-bin/imagemap/about_gne>
<img border=0 src=about_gne.gif alt=About Genentech ismap></a>
<!-- end-gne-header -->


<H1>Genentech Chronology</H1></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<center>
<img src=statue.gif>
</center>

<FONT SIZE=+3>G</FONT>enentech, Inc. was founded in 1976 by venture capitalist Robert Swanson and biochemist Dr. Herbert Boyer.  In the early 1970s, Boyer and geneticist Stanley Cohen pioneered a new scientific field called recombinant DNA technology.  Excited by the breakthrough, Swanson placed a call to Boyer and requested a meeting.  Boyer agreed to give the young entrepreneur ten minutes of his time.  Swanson's enthusiasm for the technology and his faith in its commercial viability was contagious and the meeting extended from ten minutes to three hours: by its conclusion, Genentech was born.
<P>
Though Swanson and Boyer faced skepticism from both the academic and business communities, they forged ahead with their idea.  Within a few short years they proved their detractors wrong.  
<P>
<center>
<table border width=250 cellpadding=5>
<tr><th><a href=#1970>1970s</a></td>
<th><a href=#1980>1980s</a></td>
<th><a href=#1990>1990s</a></td></tr>
</table>
</center>
<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name=1970>
<HR size=15> 
<P>
<CENTER><H2>1970s</H2></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE><UL><LI><B>1976--</B> <a href=founders.html>Robert Swanson and Dr. Herbert Boyer</a> founded Genentech.<P>
<LI><B>1977--</B>	Genentech produced the first human protein (somatostatin) in a microorganism (e. coli  bacteria).<P>
<LI><B>1978--</B>	Human insulin is cloned by Genentech scientists.<P>
<LI><B>1979--</B>  Human growth hormone is cloned by Genentech scientists.
</UL><P>
<a name=1980>
<HR size=5>
<CENTER><H2>1980s</H2></CENTER>
<UL><LI><B>1980--	</B>Genentech went public and raised $35 million with an offering that leapt from $35 a share to a high of $88 after less than an hour on the market.  The event was one of the largest stock run-ups ever.<P>

<LI><B>1982--</B>	First recombinant DNA drug marketed: human insulin (licensed to Eli Lilly and Company).<P>
 
<LI><B>1984--</B>	First laboratory production of Factor VIII, a clotting factor for bleeding in hemophiliacs.  Genentech announced agreement to grant license of worldwide production and marketing of Factor VIII to Cutter Biological.<P>
 
<LI><B>1985--</B> Genentech received approval to market its first product, Protropin (somatrem for injection) human growth hormone for children with growth hormone inadequacy -- the first recombinant pharmaceutical product to be manufactured and marketed by a biotechnology company.<P>
 
<LI><B>1986--</B>	Genentech's Roferon-A alpha interferon, licensed to Hoffmann-La Roche, Inc., received FDA approval for the treatment of hairy cell leukemia.<P>
  
<DL><DT>--  Genentech instituted the Uninsured Patients Program, providing free human growth hormone for financially needy, uninsured patients.
</DL><P>

<LI><B>1987--</B>	Genentech received approval to market Activase (Alteplase, recombinant) tissue-plasminogen activator used to dissolve blood clots in heart attack patients.<P>

<LI><B>1988--</B>	Genentech's Uninsured Patients Program expanded to cover Activase.<P>
 
<LI><B>1989--</B>	Genentech opened its day-care center, Genentech's Second Generation, one of the largest corporate-sponsored day-care centers in the U.S.
</UL><P>
<a name=1990>
<HR size=5>
<CENTER><H2>1990s</H2></CENTER>
<UL><li><B>1990--</B>  Genentech received approval to market Actimmune (Interferon gamma-1b) for the treatment of chronic granulomatous disease, a rare, inherited deficiency of the immune system resulting in frequent and severe infections.  Actimmune was added to the Uninsured Patients Program.<P>

--  Activase received U.S. marketing extension for the management of acute massive pulmonary embolism (blood clots in the lungs).<P>

--  Genentech and Roche Holding Ltd. of Basel, Switzerland completed a $2.1 billion merger.<P>

--  Genentech's Hepatitis B vaccine -- licenced to SmithKline Beecham Biologicals S.A. and Mitsubishi Chemical Industries Ltd. -- received FDA approval.<P>
 
--  Genentech acquired full ownership of Genentech Canada, previously a joint venture with Boehringer Ingelheim.
<P>

<LI><B>1991--</B>  Genentech and Xenova Limited announced an agreement for a research collaboration to develop new small molecule pharmaceuticals.<P>

<LI><B>1992--</B>  Genentech and Roche announced a collaborative agreement for the development, registration and marketing of Pulmozyme 
	(dornase alfa) DNase in all major countries in Europe.<P>
  
<DL><DT>--  Genentech entered into three research and development collaborations with Roche for:
<DD>- biotechnology-based automated screening of Roche's chemical 	
 	  library to identify new small-molecule drug candidates:
<DT><DD>- a custom immunoadhesin protein based on the tumor necrosis 	
 	  factor (TNF) receptor for treating septic shock:
<DT><DD>- orally active pharmaceuticals for treating allergies and asthma based on the IgE molecule.</DL>
<P>
	
--  Genentech opened the Founders Research Center, the largest biotechnology research facility in the world.  The center was dedicated to Founders Bob Swanson and Dr. Herbert Boyer in appreciation of their vision and determination to pursue the promise of biotechnology.<P>
  
--  Genentech and DePuy Inc. announced a strategic alliance to develop 
	Transforming Growth Factor Beta (TGF-B1) in the treatment of orthopedic
	(bone related) conditions.<P>


<LI><B>1993--</B>  Genentech received approval to market Nutropin [somatropin (rDNA origin) for injection] for treating growth failure in children with chronic renal insufficiency before they undergo kidney transplantation.<P>

--  Genentech introduced the Genentech Foundation for Growth and Development, an independent non-profit organization to advance the understanding of growth and development of children and to encourage and create research opportunities for practicing physicians and nurses who often have not had such opportunity in the past.<P>
  
--  Genentech received approval to market Pulmozyme (dornase alfa) Inhalation Solution for treating cystic fibrosis (CF) from regulatory agencies in the United States, Canada, Sweden, Austria and New Zealand.<P>
 
--  Genentech entered into an agreement with GenVec Inc., a company developing gene therapy techniques, to license all of its cystic fibrosis gene therapy products in all relevant markets.<P>

--  Genentech established a wholly owned subsidiary, Genentech Europe Ltd., to coordinate development and marketing of Pulmozyme with Roche and to develop and market future Genentech products in Europe.<P>

--  Genentech's Factor VIII -- licensed to Miles Inc. in 1984 (formerly Cutter Biological) -- received FDA approval for the treatment of hemophilia-A.<P>

--  Genentech's bovine growth hormone, -- licensed to Monsanto Corporation and distributed under the name Posilac -- received FDA approval.<P>

--  The GUSTO trial (Global Utilization of Streptokinase and t-PA for Occluded Coronary Arteries) showed that front-loaded Activase t-PA combined with IV heparin reduced heart attack patient mortality by nearly 14 percent over other thrombolytic regimens studied in the 41,000 patient trial.<P>
  
--  Genentech was granted a permanent injunction against the Wellcome Foundation that prevents Wellcome from marketing t-PA in the United States until Genentech's patent expires in 2005.<P>

--  Genentech launched Access Excellence, a $10 million nationwide communications network program designed to enable high school biology teachers across the country to access their peers as well as experts.<P>
	
			

<LI><B>1994--</B>  Genentech introduced the Pulmozyme Patient Pledge to ensure that every qualified CF patient who needs Pulmozyme and its related equipment can obtain it and that Genentech's research in CF will continue at an aggressive pace.<P>
	

--  Genentech received license to market Nutropin for the treatment of children with growth failure due to inadequate levels of the natural hormone in their bodies.<P>

--  Genentech received license to market Nutropin for the treatment of growth hormone inadequacy.<P>



<LI><B>1995--</B>  Genentech entered into an agreement with Scios Nova, Inc. for the development of Scios Nova's Auriculin anaritide for the treatment of oliguric acute renal (kidney) failure.<P>

--  Genentech and Eli Lilly and Company settled all pending patent infringement, breach of contract, and related claims, ending a long-standing dispute regarding recombinant human growth hormone.<P>

--  Genentech entered into an agreement with Alkermes, Inc. to develop sustained release formulations of up to two Genentech proteins utilizing Alkermes' proprietary ProLease microencapsulation technology.<P>

--  Genentech entered into an agreement with IDEC Pharmaceuticals Corp. for the development of IDEC's anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody, IDEC-C2B8, for the treatment of non-Hodgkin's B-cell lymphomas.<P>

--  Genentech received license to market an accelerated infusion regimen of Activase (Alteplase, recombinant), a genetically engineered version of the naturally occurring tissue plasminogen activator (t-PA), for the management of acute myocardial infarction (AMI).<P>

--  Genentech announced an agreement with Roche Holding, Ltd. to extend for four years Roche's option to purchase the outstanding redeemable common stock of the company at a predetermined price that escalates quarterly up to $82 a share.
<p>

--  Genentech began receiving royalties rather than sales revenues on all European sales of Pulmozyme and all Canadian sales of all its products as Roche assumed responsibility for those sales per the new agreement with Roche.<P>

<li><b>1996--</b>  Genentech recevied approval to market Nutropin Liquid for treating growth failure in children with chronic renal insufficiency before they
undergo kidney transplantation and for the treatment of growth hormone
inadequacy.
<p>
--  Genentech submitted a supplemental Product License Agreement to the FDA for Activase in acute ischemic stroke or brain attack within three hours of symptom onset.<P>

--  Genentech began construction on a new manufacturing site in Vacaville, California. 
</ul>
<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
