<html><head><title>Corporate Responsibility</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<center>
<!-- begin-gne-header -->
<a href=/cgi-bin/imagemap/about_gne>
<img border=0 src=../about_gne.gif alt=About Genentech ismap></a>
<!-- end-gne-header -->

<h1>Corporate Responsibility</h1></center>
<center>
<img src=gne.view.gif>
</center>

<p>

<blockquote>

<font size=+3>G</font>enentech and its employees take seriously their responsibility to their community.   Many employees manifest this commitment through their direct involvement in the community, either on their own or through Genentech-sponsored programs.  Whether ensuring that patients get medicines they need or students know their DNA from their ABCs, Genentech supports a wide range of programs and efforts.
<p>
<ul>
<li><A HREF=#programs>Programs for indigent patients</a> - Genentech believes that all patients who need its medicines should receive them.  Since its first product reached the market in 1985, the company has had programs in place to help ensure this happens.
<p>
<li><A HREF=#foundations>Independent, non-profit foundations</a> - Genentech has established and funds two non-profit foundations, one for promoting research in the area of growth and development and one to support science education.
<p>
<li><A HREF=#corporate>Corporate programs</a> - Genentech has created and supports a number of programs to benefit the local or national community in a variety of ways. Click here or see below for more information.
</ul>
<p>
<A NAME=programs>
<h2>Programs For Indigent Patients</h2>
<p>
If a patient needs a medicine, he or she should be able to receive it, regardless of economic or insurance status.  Over the past ten years, Genentech has provided more $130 million worth of pharmaceuticals free-of-charge through various programs for un- or underinsured patients in the United States.
<p>
<A NAME=assistance>
<h3>Genentech Assistance Program</h3>
<p>
All of Genentech's products are covered by the Genentech Assistance Program, except for Pulmozyme (dornase alfa), which is covered by the Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis, described below.  
<p>
For consideration of eligibility for the Genentech Assistance Program, the patient must not be eligible for public or private insurance reimbursement and must meet income restrictions.  Please direct requests for applications forms and more specific information on eligibility to:
<p>
Genentech, Inc.<br>
P.O. Box 2586<br>
South San Francisco, CA 94083-2586<br>
(800) 879-4747<br>
FAX: (415) 225-1366
<p>
<A NAME=endowment>
<h3>Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis</h3>
<p>	
Genentech is aware of the numerous expenses associated with cystic fibrosis treatment, and that the complexity of the payment system can, at times, limit patients' access to needed  and important therapies.  This concern about access led Genentech to create the Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis.  The Endowment's purpose is to expand CF patients' access to Pulmozyme therapy.  The Endowment is funded by Genentech but operated through an independent board of directors with management by an outside firm.  To learn more about the Endowment and about eligibility requirements, call 1-800-297-5557.  Or write:
<p>
	The Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis<br>
	4828 Parkway Plaza Blvd., Suite 120<br>
	Charlotte, N.C. 28217-1969
<p>
<a name=foundations>
<h2>Independent Non-Profit Foundations</h2>
<p>
<h3>Genentech Foundation for Biomedical Sciences</h3>
<p>
	The Genentech Foundation for Biomedical Sciences is an independent nonprofit organization that provides funds to San Francisco Bay Area schools for science education at all levels, from grade school through  the post-graduate level.<p> 
	The Foundation receives about $500,000 annually from Genentech -- from royalties that Genentech receives on one of its patents on a basic process of biotechnology.
<p>
	The Genentech Foundation for Biomedical Sciences operates through an annual grant application process. For more information on the Genentech Foundation for Biomedical Sciences or to request a grant application, call (415) 225-2861 or send a request to:
<p>	
	Manager, Genentech Foundation for Biomedical Sciences<br>
	Genentech, Inc.<br>
	460 Point San Bruno Blvd.<br>
	South San Francisco, CA 94080
<p>
<h3>Genentech Foundation for Human Growth and Development</h3>
<p>
	The Genentech Foundation for Human Growth and Development is an independent, nonprofit organization that aims to advance the understanding of growth and development of children among health care delivery professionals such as pediatric endocrinologists, nephrologists, nurses, and others. 
<p>
	Through this foundation, funds are available for clinical research, research staff support, fellowship support, and patient and professional education. Funds are granted by an independent board of directors. The foundation encourages practicing physicians and nurses  in their research efforts. 
<p>
	Grant applications are available from the Foundation in late January or early February.  Applications undergo review quarterly beginning in March. Grant recipients must be licensed and practicing in the United States or Puerto Rico. 
<p>
	To apply for a Foundation grant, applicants should write to:
<p>
	Admiral Thomas Emery, Executive Director<br>
	1224 West Main Street, 5th Floor, Suite 503<br>
	Charlottesville, Virginia 22903 
<p>
<h3>The Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis</h3>
<p>
Genentech's concern about access to its product Pulmozyme by cystic fibrosis patients led Genentech to create the <A HREF=#endowment>Genentech Endowment for Cystic Fibrosis</a>, which is funded by Genentech but operated through an independent board of directors.  Genentech also provides a <A HREF=#assistance>Genentech Assistance Program</a> for its other products.
<p>
<A NAME=corporate>
<h2>Corporate Programs</h2>
<p>
<A HREF=about_ae.html><h3>Access Excellence</h3></a> 
<p>
 Access Excellence is a three-year program designed to assist high-school biology teachers. Funded solely by Genentech, Inc., the program was developed and launched in 1994 with the assistance of many leading national scientific and  educational organizations. To learn more about this program, visit the Access Excellence forum on the Internet. 
<p>
<h3>Corporate Contributions</h3> 
<p>
 Genentech has an active corporate contributions program that primarily funds nonprofit organizations related to areas of health care and science in which Genentech is involved. In 1994, Genentech donated more than $3 million for scientific research through medical and academic research organizations and hospital groups. Genentech also funds educational, cultural and social service organizations on a local level.  Any requests for funding should be in writing from the organization or group requesting the grant and addressed to: 
<p>
	Corporate Contributions Manager<br> 
	Genentech, Inc.<br>
	460 Point San Bruno Boulevard<br>
	South San Francisco, CA 94080-4990. 
<p>
	Please allow three to four weeks for a response. 
<p>
All requests for funding are evaluated based on the merits of the requesting organization or group and the program involved.
<p>
<a href=/rmat-bin/entry.cgi><h3>Collaborative Research Materials Program</h3></a>  Genentech makes unique experimental proteins available free-of-charge to academic researchers worldwide, thereby encouraging and supporting important medical research which might otherwise languish for lack of needed biological resources. 
<p>
</blockquote>
<p>
