<head>
<title>Guide for the Perplexed</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote>
<img src="/images/hep.gif" width=392 height=37 alt="Brown High Energy Physics">
<br>
<h1>
<img src="/images/info.xbm" width=32 height=32>
Guide to the HET computer system
</h1>

<hr>
<h2>What's New</h2>
<blockquote>
<img src="/images/pointright.xbm" width=27 height=14> 
<b>pion</b> now has 
<a href="http://sunsite.unc.edu/Dave/Dr-Fun/df9605/df960506.jpg">
<b>four</b> CPUs 
</a>
and 128MB memory. 
<br>
<img src="/images/pointright.xbm" width=27 height=14> 
The bad news is that we will soon switch it over to the
<a href="http://www.fwi.uva.nl/pub/solaris/solaris2.html"><b>Solaris 2.5</b>
operating system.</a>
Try your programs
on <b>hbar</b> or <b>barus</b>
if you want to see in advance what will break.
Since trivial tools like "finger" don't even 
work properly, <i>a priori</i> pessimism is justified.
So far, though, so good.
(If you only use e-mail, TeX and Netscape, don't worry;
the change should be about as noticeable to you as if
Denmark changed its national language to Swedish.)
<br>
<br>
<img src="/images/pointright.xbm" width=27 height=14> 
The first of two 
<b><a href="http://www.cray.com/">Cray</a></b> --- no wait ---
make that <a href="http://www.sgi.com/"><i>Silicon Graphics</i></a>
supercomputers </b>
has arrived.
</blockquote>
See <a href="machines.html">"The Machines"</a> for details.
<hr>


<h2>Our resources</h2>

When new questions arise, their answers will be put here.
So look before asking.  


<ul>
<li> <a href="machines.html">
     The machines</a>
<li> <a href="/guide/email.html">
     Electronic mail</a>
<li> <a href="/guide/computing.html">
     Serious computing</a> (under reconstruction)
<li> <a href="/guide/text.html">
     Text editing and typesetting</a>
<li> <a href="/physics/index.html">
     Physics preprints and resources</a>
<li> <a href="/guide/software.html">
     Interesting software </a>
<li> <a href="/guide/commands.html">
     Assorted commands </a>
<li> <a href="/cgi-bin/man2html"> Hypertext Unix Manual </a> 
<li> <a href="/guide/privacy.html">
     On Privacy and Security </a>
<li> <a href="/guide/UNIX-password-security.txt">
     On passwords </a>
<li> <a href="/guide/RTM.html">
     <href="http://iicm.tu-graz.ac.at:80/T0x00005fb4">
     <i>RTM</i></a>
</ul>
<p>

<h2>Help with what you're using</h2>

For help with 
<a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/Mosaic/NCSAMosaicHome.html">
Mosaic</a>
or <a href="http://home.netscape.com/">Netscape</a>
use the <b>``Help''</b> menu from the
upper right of the menu-bar.
<p>
To learn about the Web, browse it!
The 
   <a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/demo.html">
Mosaic demo document</a>
is a good place to begin.
The number of servers available is literally growing every day;
check out
   <a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/Mosaic/Docs/whats-new.html">
What's New with Mosaic</a>.
In addition to on-line information, you could read
   <a href="/guide/the_www_book.dvi">
``The WWW Book''</a>,
<p>

Technical discussions of WWW issues are in the newsgroups
<a href="news:comp.infosystems.www.misc"> comp.infosystems.www.* </a>
and 
<a href="http://gummo.stanford.edu/html/hypermail/archives.html">
cern.www.talk.</a>
For documentation servers, visit 
<a href="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/">hoohoo.</a>
<p>

<h2>More Documentation</h2>

For help with the operating system, consult the
<a href="http://www.het.brown.edu/cgi-bin/man2html"> 
unix manual pages for
Sun
</a>.
There are even some <i>paper</i> manuals in 
   <a href="/images/toon.gif">
B&H 625.</a>
<p>

<h2> Life on the internet </h2>

A compendium of 
  <a href="http://www.cis.ohio-state.edu/hypertext/faq/usenet/top.html">
USENET FAQs</a>
(<b>F</b>requently <b>A</b>sked <b>Q</b>uestion lists, with answers)
on many topics, from unix to TeX to birdwatching to pro wrestling,
 is another source of information. 
<p>
<p>

</blockquote>

