<title>
Text editing and typesetting
</title>

<h1>
<img src="/images/info.gif">
Text editing and typesetting
</h1>

For text editing, the Sun OpenLook 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?textedit">
<b>textedit</b> 
</a>
tool has a good graphical
interface and is the easiest to learn.  
It is available on <b>pion, quark,</b> and <b>lepton</b>.
For general use, including non-graphics terminals and on
other machines, 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?emacs">
<b>emacs</b> 
</a>
is recommended because it is nearly
universal.
For the purists and masochists, 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?vi">
<b>vi</b> 
</a>
is of course available.
<p>

For typesetting papers, 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?tex">
<b>TeX</b> 
</a>
is now available on <b>pion, quark and lepton</b>.
All of the common macro packages used in physics are available.
(The files are located in the directory /het/tex/macros.)
There is an old
   <a href="phyzzx.doc.dvi">
guide to the PHYZZX macros</a>
and a 
   <a href="harvsamp.dvi">
sample harvmac preprint</a>.
The <b>TeX previewer</b> is 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?xdvi">
<b>xdvi</b>.  
</a>
Learn to use it; save some trees.
xdvi runs automatically when you  double-click 
a DVI file from the 
<a href="/htbin/man2html?filemgr">
File Manager.
</a>
<p>

<b>FrameMaker</b> is also available, but it's slow and you won't 
be likely to find many people to whom you can circulate your documents
electronically.
<p>

___________________________________________________________________
</DOC>
