<title>Assorted commands</title>

<h1>
<img src="/images/info.gif">
Assorted commands
</h1>

To be a kindler, gentler user, here are a few unix commands to look into:
<ul>
<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?ps"> ps </a>
     - process list of jobs you own and how much CPU and memory
     they are using (try "ps -ux")
<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?kill"> kill </a>
     - kill processes you own by their "process ID" (PID) number
     (e.g., "kill -9 12433")
<li> punt - a local variant of kill, to wipe out all processes 
     of a given name (try "punt clock")
<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?nice"> nice,</a>
     <a href="/htbin/man2html?renice"> renice </a>
     - lower the priority on a job you are running
<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?du"> du </a>
     - show your disk usage (by directory, in kb)
<li> And don't forget the
     <a href="bdgtti/bdgtti-1.04_8.html#SEC45">
     seven UNIX commands you can't live without </a> from the
     <a href="bdgtti/"><i>The Big Dummy's Guide to the Internet</i></a>.
</ul>

Look at these pages to find out about extra features:

<ul>

<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?tcsh"> tcsh,</a> 
     <a href="/htbin/man2html?csh"> csh </a>
     - the unix shell - what you can do and set from the command line

<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?xterm"> xterm </a>
     - the standard X-windows terminal window and its features.

<li> <a href="/htbin/man2html?olwm"> olwm </a>
     - the OpenLook window manager and its features.

</ul>

</DOC>
