<title>Benjamin in Wired</title>
<h1>Benjamin in ``Wired''</h1>

<a href="../benjamin/index.html">Benjamin's home page</a>
as well as <a href="../index.html"> his Dad's</a>,
were featured in the October 1994 issue of <i>Wired</i>
magazine, much to our surprise.  Just how public
are the things you put on the World Wide Web?
What about copyright?  What about fair use?
<p>

<h2>Why We Dig ``Wired''</h2>

In case you missed it, <i>Wired</i> has kindly
given permission to repost our scrapbook clippings
from Gary Wolf's article on Mosaic and WWW
(1994 Wired Ventures Ltd.  All rights reserved.):
<ul>
<li> <a href="wired-1.jpg"> page 120 </a>
<li> <a href="wired-2.jpg"> page 121 </a>
</ul>
<p>

To set the record straight, Benjamin was actually 1-1/2
years old when I took that portrait, not three.
He is three now, and 
<a href="../benjamin/benjamin-9408-1.gif">
here is a more recent picture.
</a>

<p>

<i>Wired</i> magazine itself </a>
used to easily accessible be on-line at http://www.wired.com/, 
running a few months behind the newsstand issue; 
but now 
<a href="http://www.wired.com/">
it's an adventure to get there.
</a>

<p>


<hr>
<i>
<a href="index.html">
Paul Mende
</a>
- mende@het.brown.edu
</i>
